{Let's examine how Mamedyarov played with Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 c5 5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. Ne4 Qb6 {This line was clearly part of Mamedyarov's preparation.} 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 ({RR} 7... exf6 8. b3 d5 9. c3 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 12. e3 Ke7 13. Be2 Nc6 14. O-O-O Nxd4 15. Rxd4 Be6 16. Kb2 Rhc8 17. Rhd1 Rc5 18. Bf3 Rac8 19. Bxd5 Rxc3 20. Bc4 Bxc4 21. Kxc3 Be2+ 22. Kb2 {Le,T (2557)-Paravyan,D (2612) Chess.com INT 2023 1-0 (71)}) ({RR} 7... exf6 8. dxc5 Qxb2 9. Qd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Na6 11. Nb3 b6 12. cxb6 axb6 13. e4 Bb7 14. Kd2 O-O 15. Bd3 d5 16. Rhe1 Rfd8 17. e5 fxe5 18. Rxe5 Nc5 19. Nd4 Ra4 20. Nf3 d4 21. Be2 d3 22. Bxd3 {Woodward,A (2544)-Lin,B (2290) Chess.com INT 2025 ½-½ (76)}) 8. e4 $5 (8. c3 {is a standard move.}) 8... Nc6 $5 (8... cxd4 9. e5 (9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 $14) 9... Qb6 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 $14) 9. c3 {Now White is controlling the center quite well and should have a slight advantage.} cxd4 $146 ({RR} 9... d6 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. O-O a6 12. e5 dxe5 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Nxe5 Rd8 15. Qe2 cxd4 16. Rfd1 O-O 17. cxd4 Rd5 18. Rac1 Rfd8 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Qxa6 Rxd4 21. Rxd4 Qxd4 22. Qe2 c5 23. g3 Rb8 24. b3 {Griffa,R (2075)-Aglietti,G (2060) Robecchetto 1998 1-0 (42)}) 10. cxd4 Qf4 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $14 {This position is highly desirable for White at the top level. White controls the center, the pieces are active, and the king is ready to join the battle. In other words, White is playing for two results.} d5 $1 14. Rhc1 (14. e5 $2 Bg4 $17) (14. exd5 Nb4 $132) {The position is already quite drawish now.} 14... Rd8 15. exd5 Nb4 16. Be4 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Rxd5 18. Rc7 Bg4 19. Ke3 Bxf3 20. Kxf3 b6 21. Rxe7 Rxd4 22. Rc1 Rd3+ 23. Ke2 Rad8 24. Re8+ Rxe8+ 25. Kxd3 1/2-1/2


