{A46: 1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 e6: Torre, London and Colle Systems} 1. d4 {Richard Palliser,MH} Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {Richard Palliser,MH: 'N'} (3. c4 {Richard Palliser,MH} c5 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 (5... a6 6. g3 (6. e4 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 Be7 10. Rc1 d6 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Qd2 Rac8 14. b4 Rfe8 15. Kh1 Qb8 16. Rc2 Bd8 17. Na4 Ne5 18. Bg1 h5 19. Bf2 Ng6 20. c5 b5 {½-½ Skopec,L (2642)-Papadiamandis,E (2632) 17/482 Las Palmas 1974 (8.1)}) 6... Qc7 7. Bg2 Qxc4 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nb3 d5 10. O-O Qb4 11. e4 d4 12. Nd5 exd5 13. exd5 Ne7 14. Re1 Bg4 15. Qd3 Rd8 16. h3 Bc8 17. Rac1 g5 18. Bd2 Qd6 19. Qxd4 Nfxd5 20. Qxh8 {0-1 Adianto,U (2598)-Kasparov,G (2838) EUR-ASIA m 30' Batumi rapid 2001 (5)}) 6. Qb3 Bc5 7. Be3 b6 8. f3 Qe7 9. g3 Nc6 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Bg2 Na5 12. Qa4 Bb4 13. Bc1 Nxc4 14. O-O d5 15. Kh1 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bd7 17. Qc2 Rac8 {[%emt 0:00:12] Chapter-Games Chapter - 24 Game -}) (3. g3 {Richard Palliser,MH} c5 4. c4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qc7 6. Nd2 Bc5 (6... b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. Nb5 Qc8 9. e4 a6 10. Nc3 d6 11. O-O Be7 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Nbd7 14. Qe2 Rd8 15. Rac1 Ra7 16. g4 h6 17. f4 Nh7 18. Nf3 Nhf8 19. g5 Ng6 20. gxh6 Nxf4 21. Qd2 {1-0 Phandsupatavorn,W (2490)-Kulejewski,L (2250) Biel Master Open 2015}) 7. N2b3 Be7 8. Qd3 a6 9. Bg2 d6 10. Bd2 Bd7 11. Ba5 Qc8 12. O-O O-O 13. Rac1 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. e4 Qb8 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. h3 Rc8 {1-0 Huzman,A (2435)-Novikov,I (2480) USSR 43/36 1987}) 3... c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 ({A slightly more flexible method of development than} 5. c3 {,}) ({although with this move order, a definite case can also be made for the Jobava-Prie-like} 5. Nc3 $5 {, as we've seen before, most recently in Banh Gia Huy-Shahil, Qatar Masters Open, Doha 2023.}) 5... h6 $5 ({This has been something of a recent trend amongst strong grandmasters over the past year or so. Black threatens ...Nh5 and avoids transposing into one of the main lines with} 5... d5 6. c3 {.}) 6. Nc4 $5 ({A direct response. Instead,} 6. c3 Nh5 7. Bg3 Nxg3 8. hxg3 d5 9. Bd3 Bd6 10. Qe2 Qe7 (10... 