{E20: Nimzo-Indian: 4 g3 and 4 f3} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {It's no surprise to see this sharp line as part of Erigaisi's repertoire.} c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 $1 O-O {Maghsoodloo allows the advance of the e-pawn. 6...d6 is the main alternative.} 7. e5 (7. cxb5 exd5 8. Bd3 dxe4 9. fxe4 d5 $15) 7... Ne8 8. f4 exd5 9. cxd5 d6 10. Nf3 (10. Bxb5 dxe5 11. Nge2 Nd6 $11) 10... c4 11. a4 dxe5 $5 {This is a relatively rare choice.} (11... Nd7 {is the main line, and here Erigaisi has played} 12. axb5 $5 {:} (12. Be2 {is the most popular choice - see the notes to Firouzja,A-So,W/chess24.com 2021}) 12... dxe5 13. Bxc4 Nd6 (13... Qc7 $1) 14. Be2 Qb6 $1 (14... exf4 15. O-O $1 Bb7 {[%eval 104,20]} ({Black should play} 15... Bc5+ $14 {[%eval 36,21]} 16. Kh1 Qf6) 16. Bxf4 $16 {favoured White in Erigaisi,A-Nakamura,H/Kolkata 2022}) 15. fxe5 (15. Bd2 e4 $1 (15... Bxc3 {[%eval 41,19] 15...e5-e4 -0.32} 16. Bxc3 Ne4 17. Rf1 {Prevents Qb6-f2+.} Nxc3 18. bxc3 Qc5 {[%eval 95,21]} (18... exf4 $14 {[%eval 37,19]} 19. Qd4 Re8) 19. c4 {[%eval 39,18]} (19. fxe5 $16 {[%eval 95,21]} Qxc3+ 20. Kf2) 19... Re8 $1 $14 20. Rf2 {was better for White in Piesik,P-Kozak,A/Slovakia 2020}) 16. Ne5 $1 e3) 15... Nxe5 $1 {appears to be a critical line. For example,} 16. Nxe5 Re8 $1 17. Nd3 Ne4 18. Qc2 Nxc3 (18... Bf5 $5) 19. bxc3 Bg4 $1 20. Nf4 Rac8 $1 21. Bd2 $1 (21. Bb2 Qe3 $1 22. Qd2 Rxc3 $1) 21... Bxe2 22. Nxe2 Qxb5 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Rb5e2]} 23. O-O $1 Qxe2 24. Rae1 Qc4 25. Qf5 Bc5+ 26. Kh1 f6 {and the engine says 0.00!}) 12. fxe5 Bg4 13. axb5 {is another way to reach the game position.} (13. Be2 $1 Nd7 14. Bf4 {has been seen a few times in correspondence games, with Black holding in the complications.} Qb6 (14... Nb6 15. axb5 (15. d6 $5 {Black must now prevent 0-0.} Nxa4 16. Qd2 {is worth a look for example,. Hoping for 0-0.} f6 {And now ...f6xe5 would win.} 17. Rd1 fxe5 18. Bxe5 Nf6 {Against Qd2-d5+} 19. O-O {with good compensation for White}) 15... Nxd5 16. Bg5 Qd7 17. Bxc4 Nec7 18. O-O Bxc3 $1 19. bxc3 Nxc3 20. Qxd7 Bxd7 21. Bd2 N3xb5 22. Ng5 {[%cal Od2b4]} Ne6 23. Rad1 {[%cal Od2b4]} Rfc8 {(�-� Neubauer,R-Borwell,A/ICCF email 2012). Black equalises with accurate play, e.g.} 24. Bd5 {[%cal Of1f7]} Bc6 25. Ba2 Nbc7 26. Nxf7 {Threatens to win with Bd2-a5.} (26. Rxf7 $5 Bd5 $8 27. Bxd5 Nxd5 28. Rd7 $11) 26... Bd5 $1 $11) 15. d6 $1 {Repels Ne8-c7} bxa4 16. Kf1 $1 Be6 $1 {Otherwise Nd5 was coming.} 17. Rxa4 Bc5 {[%eval 32,19]} ({Black should try} 17... Qb7 $11 {[%eval -21,20]}) 18. Bxc4 $14 Qxb2 19. Qd2 $1 Qxd2 20. Bxd2 Bxc4+ $1 21. Rxc4 f6 $1 {Black has to break up White's impressive pawn centre.} 22. Ne4 (22. e6 $2 {[%eval -166,19] 22.Nc3-e4 0.25} Nxd6) 22... fxe5 $1 23. Nxc5 Nxc5 24. Rxc5 e4 25. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Od6d7]} exf3 26. Be7 Rf4 $1 {[%cal Oe8d6] This allows Black to contain the d-pawn with ...Rd4.} 27. gxf3 {(�-� Oikamo,T-Engelen,J/ICCF email 2021). d6-d7 would now be deadly.} (27. d7 $5 Rd4 $8 28. Rc8 Rxd7 29. Rxa8 Rd1+ 30. Kf2 Rxh1 31. Ba3 $16) 27... Nf6 28. Rg1 Kf7 29. Ke2 a5 {and Black holds comfortably.}) 13... Nd7 14. Bf4 (14. Qd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nc7 16. Bxc4 Bc5 $1 (16... Bc5 $5 17. Qf4 Nxe5 $11) 17. Qe4 Nxe5 $1 {gives Black good counterplay.}) (14. Bxc4 Bxf3 (14... Nxe5 15. Be2 $15) 15. gxf3 Qh4+ (15... Nxe5 16. Be2 $15) 16. Kf1 Qxc4+ 17. Qe2 Nxe5 $19) 14... Nc7 $1 15. Bxc4 ({RR} 15. Ra4 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Nb6 17. Rxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 Rc8 19. Qd3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Ne6 21. dxe6 Qh4+ 22. Bg3 Qxc4 23. Qxc4 Rxc4 24. exf7+ Rxf7 25. Ke2 Rxc3 26. Rd1 Rfxf3 27. Rd7 Rb3 28. Bf2 Rf8 29. Bd4 Rxb5 {Karthi,J (2206)-Marin Ferragut,P (2333) Durres 2025 0-1 (51)}) 15... Nb6 16. Be2 $146 (16. Bg5 $2 Qxg5 17. Nxg5 Bxd1 $19) (16. Bb3 Nbxd5 17. Bd2 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 Bxf3 19. Qxd8 Bxc3+ 20. bxc3 Rfxd8 21. gxf3 Nxb5 {[%eval 32764,0] 4.f3-7.e5 with 10.a4}) (16. Qd4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Ne6 18. Qe4 Qh4+ 19. Bg3 Qxe4+ 20. fxe4 Nxc4 21. dxe6 Nxb2 {[%eval 32766,0] 4.f3-7.e5 with 10.a4}) ({RR} 16. Qd4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qh4+ 18. Ke2 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Ncxd5 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Be3 Qd8 22. Rhd1 Nxe3 23. Qxd8 Rfxd8 24. Kxe3 Rdc8 25. Rd3 h5 26. Ra6 Rab8 27. Rxa7 Rxb5 28. h4 Rxe5+ 29. Kf4 Re6 30. Rad7 Rf6+ {Kornyukov,A (2452)-Ferey,A (2181) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (32)}) 16... Nbxd5 17. Bd2 Bc5 {Preventing White from castling. The opening battle has been successful for Maghsoodloo, and Black has a promising position here although it remains tremendously sharp and the assessment can change very quickly.} 18. Qa4 Qd7 19. Qc4 Bb6 20. Na4 (20. h3 {simplifies} Nxc3 21. Qxg4 Qxg4 22. hxg4 Nxe2 23. Kxe2 f6 24. exf6 Rxf6 25. Ba5) 20... Bxf3 (20... Be3 $1 {is the best move here, and after} 21. Rd1 {Bd2xe3 is the strong threat.} (21. O-O-O {[%eval -125,18] 21.Ra1-d1 -0.23 [#]} a6 $1) 21... Qf5 $1 {Black's position looks easier to play.}) 21. Bxf3 {With the idea Na4xb6.} Rae8 {[%eval 40,20]} (21... Rad8 $11 {[%eval 4,19]}) 22. O-O-O $1 $14 {After the last two moves, suddenly queenside castling looks a lot safer for White!} Rxe5 23. Rhe1 $1 ({And not} 23. Bf4 Qf5 24. Bxe5 (24. Bxd5 $2 Nxd5 25. Nxb6 Nxf4 $19) 24... Be3+ 25. Rd2 Bxd2+ (25... Qxe5 26. Rhd1 $15) 26. Kxd2 Qg5+ $17 (26... Qxe5 27. Kc1 $17) (26... Qxe5 27. Kc1 $17)) 23... Qf5 24. Rxe5 (24. g4 $5) 24... Qxe5 25. Re1 {It's now clear that White is the one who is pressing.} Qd6 26. Qc6 Rd8 27. Nxb6 axb6 28. Rd1 (28. Qxd6 Rxd6 29. Be2 Kf8 $16) 28... Ne7 {[%eval 40,22]} (28... Qe5 $1 $11 {[%eval 0,22] is superior.}) 29. Qxd6 (29. Qc4 {seems wilder.} Ncd5 30. Bb4 Qxb4 31. Qxb4 Rc8+ 32. Qc3) 29... Rxd6 30. Be3 Rxd1+ 31. Kxd1 $11 {Endgame. With a healthy pawn majority on the queenside, the bishop pair advantage would be close to decisive. As it is, White is still better, but the doubled b-pawns give Black excellent chances to hold. KBB-KNN} Ned5 32. Bf2 f5 33. Kd2 Kf7 34. Kd3 g5 35. Kc4 Ke6 36. h3 Ke5 37. Bd4+ Kd6 38. g4 {The position is equal.} f4 39. Be4 h6 40. Bf3 (40. Bg7 {[%cal Oe4d5] is critical, but. Strongly threatening Be4xd5!} Ne6 $1 41. Bxh6 Ne3+ 42. Kd3 Ke5 {gives Black dangerous counterplay. Dodges Be4-f5}) 40... Ke6 41. Bg7 Kf7 42. Bd4 {Again Maghsoodloo chooses not to take the pawn. This pair of bishops is nice.} (42. Bxh6 Ne3+ 43. Kd3 Ne6 $1 {forces White to play. aiming for ...Kf7-g6.} 44. h4 gxh4 {and Black is okay.}) ({Much worse is} 42. Bxd5+ Kxg7 43. Bc6 Kf7 $15) 42... Ke6 43. Bg7 Kf7 44. Bd4 Ke6 45. Be4 Kd6 46. Bh1 Ke6 47. Bf3 Kd6 48. b3 Ke6 49. Bg7 Kf7 50. Bd4 Ke6 51. Bg7 Kf7 52. Bd4 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.04 (flawless) /Black=0.05 (flawless)} ({Don't play} 52. Bxd5+ Kxg7 53. Bg2 (53. Bf3 Kf6 $17) 53... Kf6 $17) 1/2-1/2


