{[%evp 9,99,21,26,21,19,8,8,5,18,22,22,-10,11,7,-4,8,12,0,40,50,14,1,2,25,35,2,85,85,85,59,124,124,123,122,127,129,124,132,125,114,111,106,164,155,176,128,152,134,202,189,218,170,216,168,182,143,238,134,226,209,196,201,247,185,197,199,249,269,286,272,284,235,313,321,321,311,353,354,362,319,373,341,346,322,332,299,473,441,463,476,424,383] A07: Réti Opening: New York and Capablanca Systems} 1. Nf3 {David Cummings} d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 c6 4. h3 Bh5 5. c4 {David Cummings: '5 0-0 is more common, but the text is a move order subtlety that Parham faced as Black recently, against Anish Giri at Tata Steel (see the February 2024 Update). Instead:'} (5. O-O {David Cummings} Nd7 6. d4 e6 7. c4 {and now the following games in the PGN Archives give an overview of current theory:} Be7 {and here:} (7... Ngf6 8. cxd5 exd5 {and now:} 9. Qb3 (9. Ne5 {is best met by} Ne4 (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. Nd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Bc5 13. Rc1 Qe7 14. Kh2 O-O 15. g4 Bg6 16. f4 {gave White an edge in Nepomniachtchi-Duda}) 10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Bf4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bg6 14. Qb3 Qb6 {with balanced chances in Mikhalevski-Shirov}) 9... Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {is reviewed in Vachier-Lagrave-Bluebaum}) 8. Nc3 (8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nc3 (9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3 Nf8 {was fine for Black in Chirila-Moradiabadi}) 9... Bxf3 10. exf3 $5 {is Ju Wenjun-Goryachkina}) 8... dxc4 9. b3 cxb3 10. Qxb3 {offers White good compensation for the pawn, see Eljanov-So}) 5... e6 6. d4 $146 (6. O-O Nd7 (6... Nf6 7. d3 (7. d4 Nbd7 8. cxd5 (8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Qb3 Rb8 10. Nd2 O-O 11. e4 dxe4 12. Ndxe4 Bc7 13. Be3 Bb6 14. Rfe1 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Nf6 16. Nc5 Qe7 17. Qc3 Rfd8 18. b4 Bc7 19. a4 a6 20. Rab1 Bd6 21. b5 axb5 22. axb5 Bg6 {1-0 Warlick,J (2655)-Puccini,J (2554) 12/(156) Cande 2011 (6)}) 8... exd5 {David Cummings: 'transposes to the mainline covered in the note to White's 5th move above.'} 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nc3 {David Cummings: 'when White is ready to expand on the kingside with f2-f4 and g2-g4, although after'} Nxe5 (11... f6 {(David Cummings) Black should still get a playable position.}) 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 Bc5+ 14. e3 Nc4 15. f5 Qe7 16. Kh1 O-O-O 17. e4 d4 18. Na4 Ne3 19. Bxe3 dxe3 20. Qf3 Bd4 21. Nc3 f6 {½-½ Livaic,L (2550)-Orozbaev,E (2376) Olympiad-45 Budapest 2024 (2.27)}) 7... Be7 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Be3 Qxb3 10. axb3 a6 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ne5 Nbd7 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Rac1 Rfd8 {Meier,G (2630)-Karjakin,S (2783) chess.com (blitz) 133/(6) 2017}) 7. Qb3 (7. cxd5 exd5 8. d3 Bd6 9. Nc3 Ne7 10. Qb3 Nc5 11. Qc2 O-O 12. e3 a5 13. Ne2 Bg6 14. Rd1 h6 15. Nf4 Bh7 16. b3 Ne6 17. Bb2 Nxf4 18. exf4 Re8 19. Qc3 Nf5 20. a3 Bf8 21. Re1 Qb6 {0-1 Kampal,T (2465)-Levitina,I (2679) (m/1) 78/295 Hamilton 2000 (5)}) 7... Qb6 8. d3 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Ne5 11. Qe4 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Nf6 13. Nd2 Be7 14. Nc4 Qd8 15. Bd2 O-O 16. b4 Nd5 17. Rab1 Bg5 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. d4 Rfd8 20. Rfd1 Qe7 {½-½ Sahraoui,S (2558)-Jones,S (2555) 42/259 Nikea 1986 (9.4)}) 6... Nf6 {David Cummings: 'Black varies from the after-mentioned Giri game which saw:'} ({RR} 6... Nd7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 Ngf6 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. f4 Bg6 11. O-O Be4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qb3 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Nb6 16. Qb4 Qd5 17. b3 O-O-O 18. Be3 Qe6 19. Kh2 f6 20. Qxe4 fxe5 21. fxe5 {Giri,A (2749)-Maghsoodloo,P (2740) Wijk aan Zee 2024 ½-½ (63)}) 7. Ne5 $146 {[%mdl 4] An interesting side line. Eine interessante Nebenvariante. David Cummings: 'This early knight jumps means that White is ready to recapture with the knight should Black try ...d5xc4. There are some differences in the position now, compared to lines in the earlier notes where White prefaced the Nf3-e5 jump with c4xd5, ...e6xd5. Alternatively:'} (7. Nc3 {(David Cummings) Vrolijk,L (2568)-Bogner,S (2536) Germany 2024 1-0 (55) allows Black to grab a pawn with:} Bxf3 8. Bxf3 dxc4 {although after} 9. e3 {White gets typical compensation for this kind of structure.}) ({RR} 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 Bb4 10. O-O Bg6 11. Qb3 Qb6 12. Na4 Qxd4 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. a3 b5 15. axb4 bxa4 16. Qxa4 Qf6 17. b5 Nb6 18. Qb4 Qe7 19. Qc3 O-O 20. Be3 Nc4 21. Bd4 {1-0 (21) Vrolijk,L (2520)-Botta,M (2262) Spilimbergo 2025}) ({RR} 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Ne5 Nfd7 10. Nd3 dxc4 11. Nf4 Bg6 12. e4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qe2 b5 15. h4 h6 16. Nxg6 fxg6 17. f4 Nd3 18. e5 b4 19. Ne4 g5 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Be3 Qd7 {Sanal,V (2555)-Aslanov,U (2324) Baku 2025 1-0}) 7... Nbd7 8. Nc3 {The position is equal. David Cummings: 'By allowing the knight trade on the e5-square, White is ready to sacrifice a pawn if necessary. If:'} (8. cxd5 $6 {David Cummings} Nxe5 (8... exd5 9. Nc3 {goes back to Giri-Maghsoodloo} Bd6 {David Cummings} 10. f4 Bg6 11. O-O Be4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qb3 {gave White pressure in Giri-Maghsoodloo, which can be found in the Archives.}) 9. dxe5 Nxd5 {Black is fine.}) 8... Nxe5 {David Cummings: 'Played before White can get f2-f4 in.'} 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. cxd5 $1 cxd5 {David Cummings: 'This is a bit safer, in this case, than the alternative recapture:'} 11. O-O {David Cummings: 'Reaching a position that has only been played in a handful of games. Note that:'} (11. f4 {(David Cummings) immediately, allows} Bc5 {keeping White's king in the middle.}) 11... Bc5 $146 {David Cummings: 'Black has also taken the pawn here with:'} ({Vorgänger:} 11... Nxe5 {David Cummings: 'and now:'} 12. f4 {David Cummings: 'allowing the developing move'} (12. g4 $5 Bg6 $8 13. f4 $11) (12. Qb3 {(David Cummings) asks questions of Black. Now} Qb6 $6 {This typical queen trade works out well for White after} (12... Rc8 {is the engine recommendation} 13. Bf4 Bd6 (13... Nc6 14. Nxd5 $1 exd5 15. Rfd1 {gives White a powerful attack}) 14. Nb5 Bb8 {and now} 15. Nxa7 {regains the pawn, but Black is close to equality.}) 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. g4 Bg6 15. f4 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Nc6 17. f5 {with the initiative}) 12... Bc5+ {David Cummings: 'was less testing for Black, Mezentsev,V (2409)-Pruess,D (2400) Berkeley 2005 0-1 (73)'} 13. Kh1 {[%eval -68,20]} ({Better is} 13. Kh2 $11 {[%eval 8,20]} Nc6 14. g4 Bxg4 15. hxg4) 13... Nd7 {[%eval -13,20]} (13... Nc6 $15 {[%eval -68,20]}) 14. f5 O-O 15. Qe1 {Hoping for g3-g4.} exf5 16. Rxf5 Bg6 17. Rxd5 {Threatens to win with Qe1-d1.} Qe7 {[%eval 13,18] ;0-1 Mezentsev,V (2409)-Pruess,D (2400) Berkeley Masters op 2005 (7)} ({Black should try} 17... Qc8 $15 {[%eval -46,20]})) 12. g4 Bg6 13. e4 {David Cummings: 'Holding on to the e5-pawn with:'} (13. Bf4 {(David Cummings) Dzagnidze,N (2525)-Stefanova,A (2528) Rogaska Slatina 2011 0-1 (43), can be met effectively by} O-O {and if} 14. e4 d4 15. Na4 b6 {gives balanced chances.}) 13... dxe4 {[%eval 40,20] David Cummings: 'Varying from an earlier game which saw:'} (13... Nxe5 14. Bf4 Qf6 15. Qa4+ Kf8 16. exd5 $16) (13... d4 $11 {[%eval 0,17]} 14. Na4 b5 15. Nxc5 Nxc5) (13... O-O {David Cummings} 14. exd5 Nxe5 15. Qe2 Nd3 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Nf4 19. Rad1 Qf6 20. Rd6 Kh8 {with a complex fight ahead, Rodshtein,M (2602)-Gonda,L (2511) Czech Republic 2022 1-0 (34)}) 14. Nxe4 $14 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 {Black should prevent b2-b4.} Nxe5 16. Bf4 {David Cummings: 'White's raking bishops fully compensate for the pawn deficit. Black has to continue treading carefully.'} Ng6 17. Bg3 {[%mdl 1024] White has compensation. A strong pair of Bishops.} e5 {[%eval 85,18] David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'Black has played well so far, but this gives White a chance. This move does block the g3-bishop, but it weakens the light squares and leaves Black's king in the centre for another turn. Decent alternatives here are:'} (17... Qb6 $11 {[%eval 2,17]} 18. Qa4+ {David Cummings} Ke7 19. Rac1 Rhd8 {when Black's king is relatively safe.}) (17... O-O {(David Cummings) allows} 18. Bxb7 {although Black could now either trade queens, or go for counterplay on the dark squares with:} Rb8 19. Bxb8 Qxb8 20. Qb3 Nf4 {etc.}) 18. Qa4+ $16 {White stays focused until the end.} Qd7 19. Qc4 (19. Qxd7+ {simplifies} Kxd7 20. Rfd1+ Ke7 21. Rd5) 19... Rc8 {[%eval 124,18]} (19... Bd4 $14 {[%eval 59,19]} 20. Rad1 {(David Cummings) is also problematic for Black.}) 20. Qb3 $36 {[%cal Oa1d1][%mdl 2048] Ra1-d1! would now be deadly. Black is under strong pressure. White is more active.} (20. Bf5 $6 Bxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Rxc4 $11) 20... O-O {[#] David Cummings: 'Black finally castles, but this surrenders the exchange.'} (20... Qc7 {David Cummings} 21. Qb5+ {ensures Black's king stays in the centre. Now after} Ke7 22. Bf5 Qc6 23. Qe2 {White has too many threats, such as Bf5xc8, Ra1-c1, Bg3xe5 etc.}) 21. Bf5 $1 {[%mdl 64] Deflection} (21. Bxb7 Rb8 22. Qc4 Bxf2+ (22... Rxb7 23. Qxc5 Rxb2 24. Rad1 $17) 23. Rxf2 Qxb7 $19 (23... Rxb7 $2 24. Rc1 $17)) 21... Qe7 22. Bxc8 Rxc8 23. Rac1 {David Cummings: 'White is an exchange for pawn up but is also more active.'} Rd8 {Prevents Qb3-d5} 24. Qc4 b6 25. Rfd1 {Rd1xd8+ is the strong threat.} a5 {[%eval 164,19]} (25... Bd4 $16 {[%eval 106,18]}) 26. Rd5 h6 27. Rcd1 {[%eval 128,19]} (27. Rxd8+ $18 {[%eval 176,19]} Qxd8 28. Qe4) 27... Bd4 28. Kh2 Rxd5 {[%eval 202,19]} (28... Rf8 $16 {[%eval 134,19] David Cummings: 'keeping the rook, was more tenacious.'}) 29. Qxd5 $18 Qf6 30. Rd3 Qe7 {[%eval 216,19]} (30... Nf8 $142 {[%eval 170,20]} 31. Rd2 Qe6 32. Qxe6 Nxe6) 31. Qa8+ Kh7 32. Qe4 {[%eval 143,21] David Cummings: 'White doesn't bother defending the b2-pawn.'} (32. b3 $18 {[%eval 182,20]}) 32... Kg8 {[%eval 238,19] [#]} (32... Bxb2 $16 {[%eval 143,21]} 33. h4 Kg8) 33. h4 {[%eval 134,18] David Cummings: 'Black is pinned back, so White goes about gaining space, in order to press on both sides of the board.'} Qc5 {[%eval 226,22]} (33... Bxb2 $16 {[%eval 134,18] was worth a try.} 34. Rd2 (34. h5 Nf8 $14) 34... Bc3 (34... Ba1 {David Cummings} 35. Rc2 {and the rook enters via the c8-square.})) (33... Nxh4 {David Cummings} 34. Rxd4 {wins for White}) 34. Rd2 Nf8 35. Rc2 Qe7 36. b3 {[%cal Bb2b3,Bb3a4][%mdl 32]} Qd7 37. f3 Qb5 {[%eval 249,21]} (37... Bc5 $142 {[%eval 199,20]} 38. Qe2 (38. Qxe5 Qd1 $16) 38... f6) 38. Kg2 a4 39. bxa4 Qb1 40. Bf2 {Prevents Qb1-g1+} ({And not} 40. Bxe5 Bxe5 41. Re2 Qxe4 42. Rxe4 Bd6 $15) 40... Bxf2 41. Rxf2 {[%mdl 4096] Endgame. KQR-KQN David Cummings: 'White soon wraps up the win.'} ({Much less strong is} 41. Kxf2 Qd1 42. h5 Qd6) 41... Qd1 42. Rc2 Qd8 43. h5 (43. Qxe5 Ng6 44. Qe4 Nxh4+ 45. Kf2 Ng6 $18) 43... Qd6 44. Re2 Qd1 45. Qc2 (45. Qxe5 {(David Cummings) also works}) 45... Qd6 46. Qd2 Qc5 47. Qb2 Nd7 {[%eval 473,23]} (47... Ne6 {[%eval 299,20] was necessary.} 48. Qxe5 (48. Rxe5 Qc7 $18) 48... Qc4) 48. Rc2 {White is clearly winning.} Qd6 49. Rc8+ Nf8 50. Re8 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.16 (very precise) /Black=0.30} 1-0


