1. c4 {[%emt 0:00:03]} e5 {[%emt 0:00:20]} 2. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:07]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 3. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:05]} e4 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 4. Ng5 {[%emt 0:02:18]} c6 {[%emt 0:00:15] A high-profile outing for the Adhiban gambit.} 5. Qa4 {[%emt 0:13:28] This move has been gaining some traction recently. Hitherto, the mainline has been:} (5. Ngxe4 Nxe4 6. Nxe4 d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Ng3 h5 9. e3 h4 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. d4 {which is examined in Gines Esteo-Durarbayli, and other games in the Archives. In practice, this line has proven quite tricky for White to play, however, and Black has scored more than 50% from this position.}) 5... Qe7 {[%emt 0:00:15] The alternative:} (5... b5 6. cxb5 d5 7. bxc6 Qb6 {is covered in Hamitevici-Laurent Paoli in the Archives.}) 6. f3 $5 {[%emt 0:01:44] A rare sideline that soon leads to a complex tactical slugfest! Instead:} (6. Qc2 {aims to capture the e4-pawn under more favourable circumstances than on move 5.} b5 7. cxb5 d5 8. e3 {and now:} h6 (8... Qe5 9. f4 Qc7 10. b3 h6 11. Nh3 {when Black has tried:} Qb7 (11... a6 12. Bb2 cxb5 $2 (12... axb5 13. Nxb5 Qb7 14. Nc3 Bxh3 15. gxh3 Be7 {gives Black some compensation in view of White's broken kingside structure, but I would still pick White here.}) 13. Rc1 Bxh3 14. gxh3 Qb7 15. Ne2 Nbd7 16. Rg1 {and White had pressure on both sides of the board in De Jong, J (2408)-Grutter,T (2337) Netherlands 2023 1-0 (41)}) 12. Bb2 Be7 13. Rc1 c5 14. Na4 Bxh3 $2 15. Nxc5 $1 Qc8 16. gxh3 {left White in control, Daneshvar,B (2577)-Muradli,M (2546) Baku 2023 1-0 (55)}) 9. Nh3 c5 10. d3 exd3 11. Bxd3 {gave Black insufficient compensation in Aravindh-Adhiban, see the game in the Archives.}) ({RR} 6. Qc2 Na6 7. Ngxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Qxe4 9. Nxe4 Nb4 10. Kd1 d5 11. a3 dxe4 12. axb4 Bxb4 13. f3 Be6 14. b3 f5 15. e3 O-O 16. Ba3 a5 17. Kc2 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 f4 19. exf4 Rxf4 20. Be2 Bf5 {Abdusattorov,N (2690)-Paravyan,D (2639) Riga 2021 ½-½ (47)}) 6... exf3 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 7. Nxf3 {[%emt 0:03:18]} g6 {[%emt 0:00:51] An earlier online game had seen:} (7... d6 8. g3 (8. d4 {is preferable}) 8... Nbd7 9. Bg2 g6 10. d3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O {leaves Black for choice, thanks to White's loosened structure, Isajevsky,A (2404) -Harshavardhan,G (2413) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (40)}) 8. d4 $146 {[%emt 0:01:40]} ({RR} 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O d6 11. d3 Nbd7 12. Bd2 Nc5 13. Qc2 Ng4 14. e4 Ne5 15. Ne1 Ne6 16. Ne2 c5 17. Bc3 Bd7 18. Qd2 b5 19. b3 a5 20. Nc2 b4 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. a4 h5 {Tejaswini,G (2298)-Mohamed,A (2428) Fujairah 2025 0-1 (43)}) 8... Bg7 {[%emt 0:01:31]} 9. c5 {[%emt 0:07:57] A more accurate move order was:} O-O {[%emt 0:04:03]} (9... b6 $142 $1 {undermines White's pawn chain. After ''} 10. cxb6 d5 {Black has good compensation.}) 10. Bf4 {[%emt 0:00:44] transposing back to the game} Na6 $5 {[%emt 0:06:40] Abdusattorov offers an exchange sacrifice.} (10... b5 $5 {[%cal Rb5a4]} 11. Qa5 (11. cxb6 Ba6 $11) 11... Na6 $11) 11. Bd6 {[%emt 0:05:55]} Qe3 $6 {[%emt 0:03:19] It turns out that this pushes White's c3-knight to a better square. Instead:} (11... Qe6 $1 12. Bxf8 Bxf8 13. Qb3 Qe7 {offers Black decent play for the exchange. Black will follow up with ...b7-b6, opening up the dark squares, and White's king doesn't have a clearly safe haven on either side of the board.}) 12. Nd1 $1 {[%emt 0:05:55]} Qe6 $1 {[%emt 0:18:22]} 13. Nf2 $6 {[%emt 0:11:52] This makes it harder for White to unravel on the kingside. Instead:} (13. Bxf8 $14 {is also possible, for example} Bxf8 14. e3 (14. a3 b5 15. Qc2 {and it doesn't look like Black gets enough for the material.})) (13. e3 b5 14. Qa3 Nd5 15. Bd3 $1 {is much better for White according to Abdusattorov}) 13... Re8 {[%emt 0:08:46]} 14. h4 {[%emt 0:16:32]} (14. Be5 $15) 14... b6 $1 {[%emt 0:08:35]} 15. Ng5 {[%emt 0:06:23]} Qf5 $2 {[%emt 0:09:16] [#] [#] Giving White a tempo for kingside expansion. Here:} (15... Qd5 $17 {keeps the pressure on. keeps the pressure on. was better, and if} 16. O-O-O Qf5 $1 {(now hitting the f2-knight) with a tough fight ahead.}) 16. g4 $1 {[%emt 0:06:16]} Qd5 {[%emt 0:05:47] [#] [#] Or:} (16... Nxg4 $142 17. Nxg4 Qxg4 18. Qb3 {striking at the tender f7-square.}) 17. O-O-O $1 {[%emt 0:01:40]} bxc5 $2 {[%emt 0:01:05]} (17... Re3 $16) 18. dxc5 {[%emt 0:06:13]} Nxc5 {[%emt 0:01:10] [#]} 19. Qc2 $2 {[%emt 0:04:03] White was well on top, but after this, the tables turn completely!} ({White has to play} 19. Qa3 $1 $18 Qc4+ 20. Kb1 {leaves Black's queen very short of squares.}) 19... Qxa2 {[%emt 0:00:06] Suddenly Black has a very powerful, and probably winning attack!} 20. Bxc5 {[%emt 0:00:04]} (20. Qxc5 $2 {too greedy.} Nxg4 21. Qa3 Qxa3 22. bxa3 Nxf2 $19) 20... Rb8 {[%emt 0:00:09]} (20... Nd5 $1 {was more precise (Abdusattorov)}) 21. b4 {[%emt 0:00:16]} Qa3+ {[%emt 0:06:21]} 22. Kd2 $1 {[%emt 0:01:19] Now Black unleashes a creative and crushing sequence.} Nd5 $1 {[%emt 0:06:02]} 23. Rh3 {[%emt 0:02:27] [#]} Re3 $1 {[%emt 0:01:56] A stunning move that cuts across all of White's lines of communication.} 24. Nfe4 {[%emt 0:05:55] Or:} (24. Bxe3 {leads to mate.} Bc3+ (24... Qxb4+ 25. Kc1 Bb2+ 26. Kb1 Bc3+ {and it is mate in 2.}) 25. Kd3 Rxb4) (24. Nge4 $1 $15 Rxh3 25. Bxh3) (24. Rxe3 Nxe3 25. Qd3 Qxd3+ 26. exd3 Nxd1 27. Nxd1 d5 {and Black is much better, despite the roughly balanced material.}) 24... Rxh3 {[%emt 0:04:57]} 25. Bxh3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} h6 {[%emt 0:02:26]} 26. Nf3 $6 {[%emt 0:01:15]} (26. Nxf7 Qxh3 27. Nfd6 {is a bit more tenacious}) 26... Nxb4 {[%emt 0:01:57]} (26... d6 27. Bxd6 Nxb4 28. Bxb4 (28. Qc1 Bb2 $15) 28... Rxb4 29. Ke1 $11 (29. Qxc6 $2 {too greedy.} Rxe4 30. Qxc8+ Kh7 $19)) 27. Qc1 {[%emt 0:05:54]} (27. Rb1 {was the only defense.} Nxc2 {[%mdl 64] Discovered Attack} 28. Bxa3 Rxb1 29. Kxc2) 27... Qa5 {[%emt 0:06:17]} 28. Ke3 {[%emt 0:00:05]} d5 {[%emt 0:00:34] White's king is hopelessly exposed.} 29. Ned2 {[%emt 0:00:58]} ({Reject} 29. Nd6 Bb2 {[%mdl 64] Deflection} 30. Qxb2 Qxc5+ 31. Kd2 Qxd6 $19) 29... h5 {[%emt 0:03:12]} (29... Bb2 $142 30. Bxb4 {[%mdl 64] Remove Defender} Qxb4 31. Qxc6 Bb7) 30. Kf2 $19 {[%emt 0:00:31]} (30. gxh5 $142 Bxh3 31. hxg6 fxg6 32. Bxb4) 30... hxg4 {[%emt 0:00:15]} 31. Nb3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:00:37]} 32. Qd2 {[%emt 0:00:56]} gxf3 {[%emt 0:00:40] Winning the piece back, and leaving Black with a lot of extra pawns.} 33. Bxc8 {[%emt 0:00:05]} fxe2 {[%emt 0:00:31]} 34. Kxe2 {[%emt 0:00:52]} Qxc8 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 0-1


