1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 Re8 11. Bf4 Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 13. Nc3 $5 Bxd4 14. Nd5 d6 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bh4 Bxb2 {Parham already spent 20 minutes on this move, so clearly he should spend more time reading my updates to this column!} (16... g5 {was my recommendation for Black in the notes to Huschenbeth-Navara, and this was Niemann's choice in a game one day later in the Tata Steel Challengers!} 17. Qe4 Bxb2 18. Re1 Be5 19. f4 gxh4 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Bd3 Bf5 $5 (21... Kf8 {is the main line}) 22. Qxf5 Qxd5 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Qxh4 (24. Qh6+ {Vachier Lagrave,M (2734)-Firouzja,A (2777) Sinquefield Cup 10th 2023 (9) 1/2-1/ 2 MVL immediately forced a draw against Alireza here with Qh6-h7, which may have the game to inspire Alireza to try this line from the White side.}) (24. Re4 $5 {was my recommendation to keep the game going}) 24... Rd8 {Played quickly by Niemann, and with Black still in preparation Saleh decided to force the draw.} 25. Qh6+ Ke7 26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. Qh6+ Ke7 28. Qh7+ Kf8 $11) ({RR} 16... g5 17. Qe4 Bxb2 18. Rb1 Be5 19. f4 gxh4 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Bc4 Be6 22. Rxb7 Kh8 23. Bd3 Bg8 24. Nxc7 Nd6 25. Qxh4 Nxb7 26. Nxa8 Nc5 27. Bf5 e4 28. h3 Qd4+ 29. Kh1 Qa1+ {0-1 (29) Caruana,F (2820)-So,W (2770) Paris 2021}) ({RR} 16... g5 17. Qe4 Bxb2 18. Re1 Be5 19. f4 gxh4 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Bd3 Bf5 22. Qxf5 Qxd5 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Qh7+ Kf8 26. Qh6+ Ke7 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qh6+ Ke7 {½-½ (28) Bruzon Batista,L (2559)-Quesada Perez,Y (2566) Saint Louis 2025}) ({RR} 16... g5 17. Qe4 Bxb2 18. Re1 Be5 19. f4 gxh4 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Bd3 Bf5 22. Qxf5 Qxd5 23. Qxh7+ Kf8 24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Qh7+ Kf8 26. Qh6+ Ke7 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qh6+ {½-½ (28) Vachier Lagrave,M (2734)-Firouzja,A (2777) Saint Louis 2023}) 17. Rb1 Be5 18. f4 Be6 $146 {A mistake, but the resulting lines are instructive since most of Alireza's moves are forced but not simple to find over-the-board.} (18... c6 $1 {is the correct way, with incredible complications ensuing after} 19. fxe5 cxd5 20. exf6 Nxf6 21. Bd3 Bd7 22. Qg3 {Huschenbeth,N (2605)-Navara,D (2689) FIDE Grand Swiss 2023 (1) 1-0 as we saw in}) (18... Bd4+ {is also possible, but White can at least win back one pawn to start with:} 19. Kh1 c6 20. Ne7+ Kf8 21. Nxc8 Qxc8 22. Qe4 $1 Bb6 23. Qxh7 $14 {Black's king remains weak.}) ({RR} 18... c6 19. fxe5 cxd5 20. exf6 Nxf6 21. Bd3 Bd7 22. Qg3 Bc6 23. Rf1 Qb6+ 24. Kh1 Ne4 25. Qf4 h6 26. Qf7+ Kh8 27. Bxe4 dxe4 28. Bf6 Rg8 29. Qg6 Qe3 30. Bxg7+ {1-0 (30) Firouzja,A (2682)-Sevian,S (2666) Chess.com INT 2019}) ({RR} 18... c6 19. fxe5 cxd5 20. exf6 Nxf6 21. Bd3 Bd7 22. h3 b5 23. Bxb5 Qe8 24. Qxe8+ Bxe8 25. Ba6 Bg6 26. Bxf6 gxf6 27. Bb7 Re8 28. Bxd5+ Bf7 29. Bxf7+ Kxf7 30. Rb7+ Kg6 31. Rxa7 Rc8 32. Rd7 Rxc2 33. Rxd6 {Karjakin,S (2781)-Anand,V (2786) Stavanger 2017 ½-½ (33)}) 19. Bc4 $1 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Bf7 {Black appears to have achieved some consolidation, but there is a stunning blow which Alireza finds after 20 minutes of thought.} 21. Qe4 Bc5 (21... c6 {also needs to be considered, but White can exploit the opening of the seventh rank:} 22. Ne7+ Kf8 23. Bxf7 Qxe7 24. Qxe7+ Kxe7 25. Rxb7+ $1 Kd8 26. Bxe8 Kxe8 27. Rxg7 Kf8 28. Rxh7 Kg8 29. Rd7 $18) 22. Ne7+ $1 Kf8 23. Qxh7 $1 {Leaving everything hanging, but the tactics all work out for White.} Bxc4 (23... Kxe7 24. Re1+ Kd7 25. Bxf7 $18 {Black cannot defend the knight on e8.}) (23... d5 $1 {is the best defence, but White can keep all his material with some more geometry:} 24. Nxd5 Bxd5 25. Qh8+ Kf7 26. Qh5+ $1 g6 27. Bxd5+ Kg7 28. Qf3 Nd6 29. Rd1 $18 {Black has survived the short-term danger, but is left with no material advantage and a long-term weakness of the kingside.}) 24. Re1 $1 {The threat of Qh8-g8 forces Black to give the queen, which would be fine were the c4 bishop not also lost at the end.} Qxe7 25. Rxe7 Kxe7 26. Qe4+ $1 Be6 27. f5 Rd8 28. g4 c6 (28... d5 $1 {would have avoided White's option in the game, although admittedly after} 29. Qxe6+ Kf8 {[%cal Gd8d6]} 30. Bg3 d4 31. Kg2 $18 {the chances of holding are slim.}) 29. g5 $1 {Ultra-precise, crashing through on the kingside before capturing the e6-bishop.} (29. Qxe6+ Kf8 30. g5 Nc7 {forces the queen out, although after} 31. Qb3 $18 {of course White should still be winning.}) 29... Kf8 (29... Nc7 30. gxf6+ gxf6 31. fxe6 $18 {[%cal Ge4h7] And Qh7+ next will decide.}) 30. fxe6 Ke7 31. gxf6+ gxf6 32. Qg4 d5 33. Qg8 Bd4 34. Bg3 Be5 35. Bxe5 fxe5 36. h4 e4 37. h5 d4 38. Qf7+ Kd6 39. e7 Rc8 40. Qf4+ Kxe7 41. Qxe4+ Kd7 42. Qxd4+ Nd6 43. h6 1-0


