1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:38]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:05]} d6 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 3. d4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} cxd4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 4. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 5. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} a6 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 6. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:16]} e6 {[%emt 0:03:53]} 7. Qf3 {[%emt 0:00:14] This is one of a few ways to deviate from} (7. Qe2 {which was also played by Praggnanandhaa at Wijk.}) 7... Be7 {[%emt 0:12:54]} (7... h6 $5 {is worthy of attention, as I've mentioned on previous occasions. Indeed, the following practical tests prove that Black's position is good enough:} 8. Be3 (8. Bd2 Qc7 9. g4 b5 10. a3 Bb7 11. O-O-O Nbd7 $132 {Nepomniachtchi,I - Carlsen,M Chess. com INT 2023}) 8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O Qc7 10. Qg3 b5 11. a3 Rb8 $132 {Hakobyan,A - Sarana,A Chess.com INT 2023}) 8. O-O-O {[%emt 0:00:38]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:11:28]} (8... Qa5 $6 {is covered in Predke, A (2682)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2761) Belgrade 2022 CB10 2022 [Roiz,M]}) 9. g4 {[%emt 0:03:37]} Nbd7 {[%emt 0:04:44] B95: Sicilian Najdorf: 6 Bg5 e6, unusual White 7th moves. This natural developing move is Black's top choice, but it is actually an inaccuracy.} (9... b5 $1 {is playable, although it allows a dangerous piece sacrifice:} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Bxb5+ axb5 12. Ndxb5 {This looks extremely shaky for Black, but after} Qc6 13. Nxd6+ Ke7 14. Rhe1 Rd8 15. Nd5+ Kf8 $132 {The chances are mutual. Matsukevich,V - Hauff,A ICCF email 2021}) 10. Bd2 $1 {[%emt 0:01:53] White's initiative on the kingside is coming fast. In particular, g4-g5 is especially annoying because Black has no adequate spot for his knight's retreat.} h6 {[%emt 0:14:03]} (10... Ne5 {can be well met by} 11. Qe2 Nexg4 ({Too passive is} 11... b5 12. g5 Nfd7 13. f4 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. a3 Bb7 16. h4 $36 {Ganguly,S - Bharath,S La Plagne 2023}) 12. f4 b5 13. h3 Nh6 {Obviously, the h6-knight is clearly misplaced and it diminishes Black's control of e5.} 14. e5 b4 15. exf6 bxc3 16. fxe7 cxd2+ 17. Qxd2 $36 {Black's king came under strong pressure in Sossai,S - Migliorini,R ICCF email 2012}) ({RR} 10... Ne5 11. Qg2 b5 12. g5 Nfd7 13. f4 Nc4 14. Kb1 Bb7 15. f5 e5 16. Nb3 Rc8 17. Bd3 Ndb6 18. Rhf1 Na4 19. Bxc4 Qxc4 20. Na5 Nxc3+ 21. Bxc3 Bxe4 22. Qh3 Qc7 23. f6 Bf8 24. Qe3 Bg6 25. a3 {Zemlyanskii,I (2541)-Erdogmus,Y (2576) Chess.com INT 2024 0-1 (41)}) ({RR} 10... h5 11. g5 Ng4 12. Qg3 Nge5 13. f4 Nc4 14. Bxc4 Qxc4 15. Be3 b5 16. g6 b4 17. gxf7+ Kxf7 18. Rhg1 Bf6 19. e5 dxe5 20. Ne4 exd4 21. Nd6+ Ke7 22. Nxc4 dxe3 23. Nxe3 Nc5 24. Nc4 Bb7 25. Qe3 {Fedorov,A (2145)-Sahib,S (2376) Chess.com INT 2025 1-0 (33)}) 11. h4 $146 {[%emt 0:01:23] The most consistent. As previously, White doesn't mind giving up his g-pawn to open files against his opponent's king.} ({Even so, stronger seems} 11. a3 $1 Ne5 12. Qg2 Nc4 13. Bxc4 Qxc4 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Kb1 $36 {White has excellent attacking prospects on the kingside. Glatthaar,M - Schaefer,U ICCF email 2012}) ({RR} 11. Qh3 Nc5 12. Bg2 g6 13. f4 e5 14. Nf5 gxf5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. gxf5 O-O-O 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bf6 19. Qa3 Kb8 20. Ba5 b6 21. Bd2 Ka7 22. Kb1 Rc8 23. Rhe1 Rhe8 24. Bc3 Re7 25. Bc4 Bh4 {Klimkowski,J (2508)-Szikszai,B (2278) Prague 2024 1-0 (59)}) 11... Ne5 {[%emt 0:11:08]} 12. Qg2 {[%emt 0:19:09]} (12. Qg3 $5 {[%cal Rf1e2]}) 12... Nexg4 {[%emt 0:02:58]} (12... Nfxg4 13. f4 $16) 13. Be2 {[%emt 0:05:09]} ({Deserving of serious attention is} 13. h5 $5 Rg8 14. Rh3 {The knight loses its stability, so there are definitely issues to solve for Black.}) 13... h5 {[%emt 0:01:13]} 14. f3 {[%emt 0:06:54] The most straightforward choice.} ({After} 14. Rhg1 g6 15. f3 Ne5 16. Bg5 Bd7 17. f4 Nc6 $132 {Black had acceptable play in Gurel,E - Wartiovaara,O Cala Gonone 2022}) 14... Ne5 {[%emt 0:00:12] [#]} 15. f4 $146 {[%emt 0:00:22] A novelty. GM Praggnanandhaa reasonably decides to force matters.} (15. Qxg7 Ng6 16. Rhg1 Rh7 17. Rxg6 (17. Ncb5 $2 axb5 18. Rxg6 Rxg7 $19) 17... Rxg7 18. Rxg7 e5 $17) ({Predecessor:} 15. Kb1 Bd7 16. Qxg7 Ng6 17. Rhg1 Rh7 18. Rxg6 Rxg7 19. Rxg7 e5 {White's compensation for the queen was questionable in Pettersson, T - Behrendorf,K ICCF email 2016} 20. Nb3 Be6 21. Bc1) 15... Neg4 {[%emt 0:05:58] [#]} 16. e5 $1 {[%emt 0:01:39] No way back!} dxe5 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 17. fxe5 {[%emt 0:00:09]} Nxe5 {[%emt 0:06:36]} (17... Qxe5 {was rejected by Parham in view of} 18. Nc6 $1 {, but actually it was possible too, since} bxc6 19. Qxc6+ Nd7 20. Qxa8 O-O 21. Qg2 f5 22. Rhe1 Qd6 $132 {is very unclear: Black's passers shouldn't be underestimated!}) 18. Qg3 $1 {[%emt 0:09:50] And now Bf4 would win. The pin is extremely dangerous, but Black has sufficient defensive resources.} Nfg4 {[%emt 0:03:24]} 19. Bf4 {[%emt 0:11:57]} f6 {[%emt 0:01:34] It is essential to strengthen the e5-knight.} 20. Nf3 {[%emt 0:03:29]} ({After} 20. Ne4 Bd7 21. Qb3 O-O-O {Black manages to secure his king.}) 20... O-O {[%emt 0:04:45]} 21. Nxe5 {[%emt 0:07:23]} fxe5 {[%emt 0:00:25]} (21... Nxe5 $2 22. Bxh5 Kh8 23. Ne4 $18) 22. Bd2 {[%emt 0:00:20]} ({Somewhat more natural looks} 22. Bg5 b5 23. Bxg4 hxg4 24. Qxg4 Rf5 25. Ne4 Bb7 {with an approximate balance.}) 22... Qc6 $6 {[%emt 0:10:27] Parham leaves his queenside pieces undeveloped for too long.} ({More to the point was} 22... b5 $1 $11 {keeps the balance. '='} 23. Bxg4 hxg4 24. Qxg4 Rf5 (24... Bb7 25. Qxe6+ Rf7 26. Rhg1 Bxh4 $132)) 23. Bxg4 $6 {[%emt 0:19:23] After this move Black's decision is fully justified.} (23. Rhg1 $16 Bc5 24. Bxg4 Bxg1 25. Rxg1 hxg4 26. Qxg4) ({Much stronger was} 23. Bg5 $1 Qe8 24. Bxg4 hxg4 25. Qxg4 $36 {, and White has a free attack.}) 23... hxg4 $11 {[%emt 0:00:17]} 24. Qxg4 {[%emt 0:00:26]} Qf3 $1 {[%emt 0:00:21] Black manages to liquidate into an acceptable endgame.} 25. Qxf3 {[%emt 0:01:33]} Rxf3 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 26. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} (26. Ne4 b6 27. Bg5 Bb7 {offers White no advantage either.}) 26... Bb4 {[%emt 0:10:03]} 27. Ne4 {[%emt 0:10:09] c3 is the strong threat.} b5 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 28. Nd6 {[%emt 0:02:09] Wards off Bb7} Bxd6 {[%emt 0:04:14] The simplest solution. A draw is practically unavoidable now.} 29. Rxd6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Bb7 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 30. Rxe6 {[%emt 0:01:09]} Rc8 {[%emt 0:00:29] [#] Hoping for ...Rf2.} 31. Re1 $1 {[%emt 0:01:35]} Rf2 {[%emt 0:01:37]} 32. Bd2 {[%emt 0:01:43]} e4 {[%emt 0:02:00]} 33. h5 {[%emt 0:00:40] White is interested in liquidating all the kingside pawns.} Rg2 {[%emt 0:00:53]} 34. h6 {[%emt 0:01:16]} (34. c3 {seems wilder.} a5 35. h6 b4 36. hxg7 Bd5 37. Re5) 34... gxh6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} (34... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Rd5e6]} 35. Rxa6 Bc4 $14) 35. Rxh6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Rc6 {[%emt 0:00:06] ...e3! would be deadly.} 36. Rh5 {[%emt 0:01:05]} b4 {[%emt 0:00:51]} 37. b3 {[%emt 0:01:12]} Rc7 {[%emt 0:01:01]} 38. Reh1 {[%emt 0:01:09]} ({Trickier was} 38. Re3 $5 $14 {, but after ''} Rg1+ 39. Kb2 Rg2 40. Reh3 Rc8 {Black's position remains safe.}) 38... e3 $1 {[%emt 0:00:19] The position is equal.} 39. Rh8+ {[%emt 0:00:17]} (39. Bxe3 Rcxc2+ 40. Kd1 Bf3+ 41. Ke1 Rge2+ 42. Kf1 Bg2+ 43. Kg1 Re1+ 44. Kh2 Rxh1+ 45. Kg3 Rxh5 46. Bg1 Rh3+ 47. Kf4 Re2 48. Kg4 Kf7 49. Kf5 Re4) 39... Kf7 {[%emt 0:00:26]} 40. R8h7+ {[%emt 0:00:45]} (40. Bxe3 Rcxc2+ 41. Kd1 Bf3+ 42. Ke1 Rge2+ 43. Kf1 Bg2+ 44. Kg1 Re1+ 45. Kh2 Rxh1+ 46. Kg3 Rxh8 47. Kf4 Rh3 48. Bd4 Re2 49. Kf5 Rf3+ 50. Kg5 Re6) 40... Ke6 {[%emt 0:00:30]} (40... Rg7 41. Rf1+ (41. Bxb4 Bxh1 42. Rxh1 Rc8 $19) 41... Kg8 42. Rxg7+ Kxg7 43. Bxb4 $16 (43. Bxe3 Be4 $14)) 41. R1h6+ {[%emt 0:07:18]} Kf5 {[%emt 0:02:14]} (41... Ke5 $5 $11 42. Rxc7 (42. Bxe3 Rcxc2+ 43. Kd1 Bf3+ 44. Ke1 Rge2+ 45. Kf1 Bg2+ 46. Kg1 Re1+ 47. Kh2 Be4+) 42... exd2+ 43. Kb2 d1=Q 44. a4 bxa3+ {[%mdl 64] Deflection} 45. Kxa3 Qc1+ 46. Ka2 (46. Kb4 Qxh6 47. Re7+ Kd6 48. Re8 (48. Rf7 Rxc2 49. Ka5 Qh5+ 50. Kb6 Qxf7 51. Ka5 Qc7+ 52. Kb4 Qc5+ 53. Ka4 Bc6#) 48... Qd2+ 49. Ka3 Qxc2 50. Rd8+ Kc6 51. Rh8 Qb2+ 52. Ka4 Rg4+ 53. Ka5 Qe5#) 46... Qxh6 (46... Rxc2+ 47. Rxc2 Qxc2+ 48. Ka3 Qc1+ 49. Kb4 Qxh6 (49... Qf4+ 50. Ka3 Qxh6 51. Kb4 Qd2+ 52. Ka3 Bd5 53. Ka4 Qc3 54. b4 Qa1#) 50. Kc3 Be4 51. Kb4 Qd2+ 52. Ka4 Bd5 53. Ka3 a5 54. Ka4 Qb4#) 47. Kb2 Qd