1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Bb4 5. Nd5 e4 6. Nh4 {One of the sharpest lines in the Reversed Rossolimo.} O-O 7. a3 $5 {A rare move in this specific position, forcing Black to choose a square for the bishop. Instead: Exploring less charted territory. Erkundet wenig bekanntes Terrain.} (7. Bg2 {has been played in the vast majority of games.} d6 {and now:} 8. a3 {is less common here as well. Now:} (8. O-O {is the current mainline. Now} g5 9. d4 (9. a3 $2 {mixes up the move order} Ba5 10. d3 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nb8 12. dxe4 gxh4 {led to a win for Black in Nakamura,H (2787)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2690) Baku 2023 0-1 (33)}) 9... h6 10. Ne3 gxh4 11. a3 Ba5 12. b4 Bb6 13. c5 {which is analyzed in Caruana-Esipenko in the Archives}) (8. Nxb4 {avoids the sharp piece sacrifice, and now} Nxb4 9. a3 Na6 10. d3 {is the subject of Navara-Keymer in the Archives.}) 8... Ba5 {also works, in contrast to the main game, where the bishop is played here a move earlier.} (8... Bc5 9. O-O Re8 (9... g5 $2 {is well met by} 10. d4) 10. e3 g5 11. b4 {is covered in Nakamura-Anand in the Archives}) 9. b4 Bb6 10. Bb2 Bd4 11. Bxd4 Nxd4 12. e3 Nf5 {and Black is fine.}) 7... Ba5 $146 {Already a slight inaccuracy. Perhaps Black was confused by the tweaked move order with 7 a3. Black should prefer one of the alternatives:} ({Vorgänger:} 7... Bc5 {when:} 8. Nf5 $6 (8. Bg2 d6 9. O-O {transposes to Nakamura-Anand (see the note to White's 7th move above)}) 8... Ne5 9. Nfe3 (9. f4 exf3 10. d4 Nxd5 11. cxd5 d6 {also favours Black}) 9... c6 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Bg2 Nxc4 {and Black won a clean pawn in Cuadras Avellana,J (2282)-Riff,J (2489) Castell de Sant Ferran 2017 0-1 (50)} 12. O-O Nxe3 13. fxe3 Qe7 {0-1 Cuadras Avellana,J (2282)-Riff,J (2489) Miquel Mas op-A 18th 2017 (2)}) (7... Be7 8. Nf5 Nxd5 9. cxd5 d6 (9... Ne5 $2 {Hetul,S (1815)-Rihan,S Nagpur 2008 1-0 (32) 1-0 (32) can be met by} 10. Bg2 {winning the e4-pawn}) 10. Nh6+ gxh6 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Bg2 d5 13. d3 exd3 14. Qxd3 {with roughly balanced chances}) 8. b4 {[%emt 0:00:08] White gains extra space for free, since Black does not have ..Bc5-d4 available, which would be the case after 7...Bc5 b4} Bb6 9. Bb2 Bd4 10. Bxd4 Nxd4 11. e3 Nc6 12. Bg2 Ne5 {Alternatively:} (12... Re8 13. O-O d6 14. f3 {gives White a slight edge due to upcoming control of the f-file}) 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bxe4 Nxc4 15. O-O Nd6 16. Bg2 {White's central pawn majority give him the more pleasant game.} Nf5 {Black wants to free the d-pawn in order to complete development, but at the same time, trading knights seems to help White more than Black. Instead:} (16... a5 {aims to create queenside counterplay. A sample line runs} 17. Qb1 c6 18. Nf3 Re8 19. Rc1 axb4 20. Qxb4 Ne4 21. d3 Ng5 22. Nd2 d5 23. h4 Ne6 24. a4 {when White is slightly for choice, although Black remains solid.}) 17. Nxf5 Qxf5 18. d4 d5 19. Rc1 {White is aiming for a minority attack on the queenside. Another, perhaps more efficient, move order would be:} (19. b5 Bd7 20. Rb1 c6 21. bxc6 bxc6 (21... Bxc6 {leaves the bishop passively placed}) 22. Rb7 {and White is pressing.}) 19... c6 20. b5 Bd7 21. Qb3 h5 {Naturally trying for counterplay, although ironically, the h5-pawn becomes a weak point.} 22. h4 a6 23. bxc6 bxc6 24. Rc5 Rfb8 25. Qd1 Qh7 $6 {A strangely passive choice for posting the queen. After:} (25... Qg6 26. Bf3 (26. e4 dxe4 27. Rg5 {can be met by} Bg4) 26... Bg4 {and Black remains well in the game}) 26. e4 $1 {An alert response, taking advantage of the loose h5-pawn.} Bg4 {Or:} (26... dxe4 27. Rxh5 Qg6 28. Rg5 Qf6 29. Bxe4 {and White is simply a pawn up.}) 27. f3 {Loosening White's kingside. Instead:} (27. Qc2 {maintains control, the c6-pawn will soon fall.}) 27... Bd7 28. exd5 Qg6 29. dxc6 Bxc6 30. Kh2 Rb5 31. Qc1 Bb7 {After:} (31... Rxc5 32. dxc5 Re8 {Black is only slightly worse, in view of White's somewhat weakened king's cover.}) 32. Rd1 Qd6 33. a4 Rxc5 34. dxc5 Qc7 {Black is much more passively placed than in the previous note.} 35. Qg5 g6 36. Rd6 {Now White can start switching to attack.} Re8 {Or:} (36... Rc8 37. Qe5 Kh7 38. Qf6 {and Black is tied down.}) 37. Bf1 Bxf3 38. Bc4 Be4 39. Qf4 Re7 40. Bxf7+ {The decisive breakthrough.} Kh7 (40... Rxf7 41. Qxe4 Qxc5 42. Rxg6+ Kf8 43. Qa8+ Ke7 44. Rg5 {also wins for White}) 41. Bc4 Qxc5 42. Qf8 {Black can't survive for long, for example:} Rg7 $146 (42... Qxd6 43. Bg8+) 43. Bg8+ Kh8 44. Bd5+ Kh7 45. Bxe4 {with an extra piece and mate soon to follow. 1-0 (45) Maghsoodloo,P (2707)-Sadhwani,R (2641) Douglas 2023 Mega2023 Update 53 [David Cummings]} 1-0


