{B70: Sicilian Dragon: 6 g3 and 6 Be2 (without a later Be3)} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 g6 6. h4 $6 {I miss my good old Dragon days when the occasional opponent would try an offbeat approach like this. Actually the young Iranian GM clearly has a penchant for the unusual as this month he also tried} (6. h3 Bg7 7. g4 {in another game. Regular subscribers will know that we have scrutinised that approach before with} O-O 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. Nde2 {obviously being a fianchetto system but with White's g-pawn slightly more advanced!}) 6... h5 $146 ({One certainly couldn't argue with} 6... Nc6 {or} 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. Nde2 a6 9. f3 b5 10. Bb3 Qb6 (10... Bb7 11. Bg5 Na5 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Bh6 Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Qb6 {29. Other Systems:-6. h4,7 Other Systems}) 11. h5 Nxh5 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. g4 Nf6 14. Nxf6+ exf6 15. Qd5 Ne5 16. Qxa8 Nxf3+ 17. Kf1 O-O 18. Bf4 Qd7 19. Rd1 Qxg4 20. Qa7 Ng5 21. Qe3 Re8 {Ivanovic,B (2500)-Georgiev,K (2615) Jugoslavija 66/186 1996 CI1-130 [Georgiev,Kiril] 0-1 (51)}) (6... Bg7 {but I rather like the text, grasping the g4-square. Indeed I think that's why I'm not enamoured with White's 6th move which arguably shows his hand a little early. We see so many systems these days where Black flicks in an early ...h5 and doing it after White has committed themself to h2-h4 makes the advance super justified.}) ({RR} 6... Nc6 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. Nde2 a6 9. f3 b5 10. Bb3 Qb6 11. h5 Nxh5 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. g4 Nf6 14. Nxf6+ exf6 15. Qd5 Ne5 16. Qxa8 Nxf3+ 17. Kf1 O-O 18. Bf4 Qd7 19. Rd1 Qxg4 20. Qa7 Ng5 21. Qe3 {Ivanovic,B (2500)-Georgiev,K (2615) Budva 1996 0-1 (51)}) ({RR} 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. f3 h5 9. Be3 Bg7 10. Qd2 Ne5 11. Be2 Rc8 12. O-O-O Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. Kb1 Qc7 15. Nde2 a6 16. Bd4 Be6 17. Qe3 O-O 18. Nf4 Rc6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ncd5 Bxd5 21. Nxd5 {Maghsoodloo,P (2699)-Djokic,M (2194) Chess.com INT 2022 1-0 (48)}) 7. Bc4 {The downside is that Black is a little weaker around g6 and White immediately targets the base of that.} ({RR} 7. Bg5 Bg7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Bd3 Nxd4 10. O-O Ne6 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qd2 Bd7 13. f4 Ng4 14. Kh1 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Qb6 16. Qg3 Nc5 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Qg5 e6 19. Ne7+ Kh7 20. f5 exf5 21. exf5 Nxd3 {Mogirzan,M (2086)-Rodriguez Lopez,A (2002) Chess.com INT 2025 1-0}) 7... Bg7 8. Bb3 $146 ({RR} 8. Bg5 Nc6 9. Nde2 Qa5 10. Qd2 Bd7 11. O-O Rc8 12. Bb3 Ne5 13. Rad1 Qd8 14. Nf4 Rxc3 15. bxc3 Nxe4 16. Qe3 Nxg5 17. hxg5 Ng4 18. Qxa7 Be5 19. Nd5 Bh2+ 20. Kh1 h4 21. Rfe1 Kf8 22. Rxe7 h3 {Fauvet,E (2245)-Le Flao,P Toulon 1996 1-0 (40)}) ({RR} 8. Bg5 O-O 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. Nde2 Ne5 11. Bb3 Bg4 12. O-O-O Rc8 13. f3 Bd7 14. Kb1 Re8 15. Rhf1 Qa5 16. Bxf6 exf6 17. Qxd6 Red8 18. Rd5 b5 19. a3 Bc6 20. Qb4 Qxb4 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. axb4 Bf8 {Schneider,J (1906)-Gervinskas,V (1745) Bad Wiessee 2012 1-0 (41)}) 8... Nc6 {Black could just castle but instead is deliberately delaying doing so, confident that standard punishing tactics don't work here.} 9. Be3 ({For example then} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 {could happily be met by 10...Nh7 or even 10...Nd5 but here} Ng4 $1 {taking advantage of that post just looks good, especially in the case of} ({Note as in similar circumstances we've investigated recently not} 10... dxe5 {[%eval 70,18] 10...Ng4 0.08} 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bxf7 {as the bishop doesn't get trapped on f7 because the black h-pawn has moved leaving g6 loose.}) 11. exd6 O-O $1 12. dxe7 $2 {[%eval -289,25][%mdl 8192]} (12. Bg5 $11 {[%eval 4,17]} Qxd6 13. Qe2) 12... Qxe7+ $19 13. Qe2 {[#]} Re8 $1 {Okay so perhaps White's been a tad greedy but certainly} 14. Qxe7 Rxe7+ 15. Kf1 $4 {[%eval -700,24]} (15. Be3 $142 {[%eval -357,23]} Nxe3 16. fxe3) 15... Ba6+ $19 16. Kg1 Re1# {is nice work if you can get it!}) 9... Ng4 $1 {Anyone that has followed this site or read any of my Dragon books will know why this is such an appealing move. White can't afford to lose his dark-squared bishop for a knight.} 10. Nxc6 {White would rather not bring a black pawn to c6 to control d5 but this is the only real option open to him.} bxc6 11. Bg5 ({Yes although} 11. Bd4 {[%eval -52,20] 11.Bg5 -0.05} e5 12. Be3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bf6 {[%eval -47,21]} (13... Bg4 $17 {[%eval -79,20]} 14. Qd3 O-O) 14. g3 {might offer some f-file compensation, really this bishop needs to be preserved.}) 11... Ba6 ({Physically preventing castles although} 11... Qb6 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Rb6f2] feels natural too with} 12. O-O {[%eval -46,19]} (12. Qd2 $11 {[%eval 1,20]}) 12... Ba6 $15 13. Ne2 {(obviously this pin is a poor situation for White.)} Bxb2 14. Rb1 {simply bagging a pawn because of the cute} Qc5 $1 15. Rxb2 {[%eval -129,22]} ({White should play} 15. c4 {[%eval -87,18]}) 15... Qe5 {forking the rook and mate on h2.}) 12. Qd2 {White instead over=protects f2 and clears the path for the option of long castles.} Qb6 13. f3 Ne5 {Of course the game could go either way but for me Black has been for preference for a while.} 14. Na4 (14. O-O-O {would be met by} Rb8 {and so with the d5-square unavailable to the steed (a key point in my own preference) White tries something else.}) 14... Qb7 {(nor of course the c5-square)} 15. Rd1 (15. O-O-O {would pile a lot of pressure on the b3-bishop to remain in view of the protection required for b2.}) 15... Bb5 {I'm not a great fan of this and Black's next move which between them deserve a '?!'. Threatens to win with ...Bxa4.} (15... O-O {just looks good to me but the text does of course simply threaten to take the offside knight to facilitate a knight invasion on c4.}) (15... Rb8) 16. Nc3 Nc4 ({I'd far prefer keeping the tension say through} 16... a5 {rather than alleviating it through the text.}) 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 {Although this is an open board where the bishop pair should be attractive, the threat of the knight landing on c4 was awesome.} 18. b3 {[#]} Qb4 19. Nb1 (19. Ne2 {looked more natural but either way the queens are coming off.}) 19... Qxd2+ (19... a5 {is interesting.} 20. c3 Qb6 21. bxc4 Rb8) 20. Bxd2 Ba6 21. c4 {Not the usual type of Maroczy bind we get on the site but certainly fulfilling a job oof shutting out one of Black's pair.} f5 {[%eval 37,20]} (21... Bc8 $11 {[%eval -6,19] deserves consideration.}) 22. Bc3 $1 $14 {And halving that pair is the logical call as typically a bishop for knight advantage isn't as big as 2 bishops Vs bishop and knight.} O-O 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Nc3 {With the black bishop on a6 blocking a potential ...a5-a4 plan, now it is White who holds a small advantage.} fxe4 25. Nxe4 c5 26. Kf2 Bc8 ({Played in preference to} 26... Bb7 {in order to cover the hole on e6. Either way the ...a5-a4 plan is now on the menu.}) 27. Rhe1 a5 28. Ng5 (28. Re3 $5 {might have kept more options open with} Bf5 29. Nc3 Ra7 30. Rde1 {Strongly threatening Nb5.} Rf7 {and if} 31. Nd5 {[%cal Rd5e7] then} Kf8 {being a case of all hands to the pump!}) 28... Ra7 29. Re3 Rf4 {Correctly seeking some activity of his own.} 30. g3 Rd4 {Offering to mix things up a little with this is the point.} 31. Ke1 {[%eval -49,22]} ({Upon Better is} 31. Rxd4 $11 {[%eval 1,25]} cxd4 32. Re4 $1 {Black could support with} (32. Re1) 32... e5 {and stand just fine. However in the game Black is happy to trade a pair of rooks even without that central pawn structure being altered as of course he still has his main plan...}) 31... a4 $1 $15 32. f4 {[%eval -120,23]} (32. Rxd4 $15 {[%eval -45,21]} cxd4 33. Rd3) 32... axb3 33. axb3 Bf5 {[%eval -28,26] Black is once again for preference with suddenly him having the active pieces.} (33... Kf6 $17 {[%eval -78,23]}) 34. Rxd4 cxd4 35. Ne6+ Bxe6 36. Rxe6 {Endgame At the end of the day though we still have a rook and pawn ending and we all know that they're all drawn!? KR-KR} Rb7 {And now ...Kf7 would win.} 37. Re2 {[%eval -102,24]} (37. Re4 $15 {[%eval -37,26]}) 37... Kf6 {[%eval -53,24]} (37... Rxb3 $17 {[%eval -102,24]} 38. Rxe7+ Kf6) 38. Rb2 Kf5 39. b4 Ke4 {aiming for ...Kd3.} 40. Kd2 Rc7 41. Rc2 (41. b5 Rxc4 42. b6 Rc8 43. b7 Rb8 44. Rb5 e5 {would maybe be a more exciting route to a draw!}) 41... Rb7 42. Rb2 Rc7 43. Rc2 Rb7 44. b5 {The position is equal.} d5 45. c5 Rxb5 46. c6 {Although we're getting a similar scenario.} Rb8 47. c7 Rc8 48. Rc6 Kf3 49. Kd3 Kxg3 {Though less about connected passed pawns and more about volume!} 50. Kxd4 Kxf4 51. Kxd5 {Black must now prevent Ke6.} g5 52. Rc4+ Kf5 53. Kc6 gxh4 54. Kd7 Rxc7+ 55. Kxc7 $11 {KR-K3P} Kg5 56. Kc6 h3 57. Kd5 h2 58. Rc1 Kf4 59. Ke6 Kg3 60. Kxe7 Kg2 61. Rc2+ Kg1 62. Rc1+ Kg2 63. Rc2+ Kg3 64. Rc1 Kg2 {Fair enough! Weighted Error Value: White=0.07 (flawless) /Black=0.05 (flawless)} 1/2-1/2


