{[%evp 9,84,12,15,8,42,39,59,34,41,48,47,44,37,32,61,18,14,-17,-16,-14,-1,15,11,6,8,-5,0,8,12,0,49,-61,-54,-62,-10,-1,10,17,12,11,17,-1,-1,1,85,76,72,22,31,-6,12,1,10,1,41,16,32,21,27,26,34,17,1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-1,-294,-268,-272,-267,-306,-283,-420,-421] A13: English Opening: 1...e6} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 {[%cal Bd7d5,Bd5d4][%mdl 32]} 3. Bg2 d4 {With this move order, Black delays ...Ng8-f6, or indeed omits it entirely..} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Nh6 $146 {[%cal Bg8h6,Bh6f5,Bf5d6][%mdl 32] A fresh idea. The mainline arises after} (5... Bc5 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nbd2 {which is covered in Nepomniachtchi-Vidit, in this month's Update.} O-O (7... a5 8. Nb3 Be7 9. e3 dxe3 10. Bxe3 Ng4 11. Bc5 O-O 12. d4 a4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nc5 a3 15. bxa3 Rd8 16. Nb3 Nf6 17. Re1 Qxa3 18. Qe2 h6 19. h4 Bd7 20. Ne5 Be8 21. Qe3 Qb4 22. Reb1 {0-1 Panov Botvinnik Attack (2782)-Molina,R (2855) 17th Corsican Circuit Final 2013 (9)}) 8. Nb3 Be7 9. e3 (9. h3 a5 10. e3 e5 11. exd4 exd4 12. a4 Bb4 13. Bf4 Re8 14. g4 h5 15. g5 Nh7 16. Bd2 Bf5 17. Nc1 Qd7 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. h4 Nf8 20. Qd2 Ng6 21. Nb3 Bxd3 22. Nc5 Qg4 23. Nxd3 Nxd3 {0-1 Assmann,J (1877)-Boos,M (1758) corr OS-167 BdF-Schachserver 2011}) 9... dxe3 10. Bxe3 Ng4 11. Bc5 Rb8 12. d4 b6 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Qc2 Bb7 15. Rad1 Nf6 16. Rfe1 h6 17. Nc1 Qd6 18. Ne2 c5 19. b3 Rfd8 20. Qb2 Nf5 21. d5 exd5 22. cxd5 {1-0 Assaubayeva,B (2440)-Dzagnidze,N (2525) KAZ-World Blitz (Women) 2023 (6.3)}) 6. e3 {Fighting for the centre. Instead:} (6. d3 {didn't cause Black any problems after} Nf5 7. Na3 Bxa3 8. bxa3 O-O 9. Rb1 Rb8 10. e4 {[%eval -38,21]} (10. Nh4 $5 Nxh4 11. Bxc6 Ng6 12. Qa4 a6 $1 13. Bg2 Bd7 {is balanced}) (10. Nh4 $11 {[%eval 1,20]} Nxh4 11. Bxc6) 10... dxe3 $15 11. fxe3 e5 {and Black is already a bit better due to White's weakened pawn structure, Flores,D (2533)-Dubov,D (2716) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (43)}) ({RR} 6. d3 Nf5 7. Na3 Bxa3 8. bxa3 e5 9. Rb1 O-O 10. a4 Re8 11. Nd2 Nd6 12. Ba3 h5 13. h4 Nf5 14. Re1 Re6 15. Nf3 Rg6 16. Ng5 Rxg5 17. hxg5 Qxg5 18. Kh1 h4 19. g4 Ng3+ 20. fxg3 hxg3 {Carlsen,M (2837)-Xiong,J (2636) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1}) 6... Be7 $146 {A novelty. Black delays the ...Nh6-f5 jump until after White has captured with e3xd4. Earlier games saw:} (6... Nf5 7. e4 (7. d3 dxe3 8. fxe3 {[%eval -23,19]} (8. Bxe3 $142 {[%eval 13,21]} g6 9. Nc3) 8... h5 $1 $11 9. Nc3 h4 10. g4 h3 $1 {gave Black the initiative in Diermair,A (2465)-Horvath,D (2446) Playchess.com INT 2020 0-1 (38)}) 7... Nfe7 8. d3 (8. e5 $1 {White needs to seize a space advantage, or risk being worse.}) 8... Ng6 9. h4 h5 10. Nbd2 $6 {[%eval -86,21]} (10. b4 $5 {may be relatively best}) (10. b4 $11 {[%eval -8,22] keeps the balance.}) 10... e5 $17 11. Nh2 Be7 {and Black was positionally better in Van Wely,L (2644)-Fressinet,L (2652) Quenza 2023 �-� (56)}) ({RR} 6... Nf5 7. e4 Nfe7 8. e5 d3 9. b3 Qd7 10. Bb2 b6 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Re1 Nb4 13. Ng5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 h6 15. Qf3 Nec6 16. Nh3 Nc2 17. Nf4 Nxa1 18. Bxa1 O-O-O 19. Re3 Qe8 20. Nxd3 Kb8 21. Ne2 {Strybuk,A (2422)-Gholami Orimi,M (2509) Moscow 2025 0-1 (49)}) ({RR} 6... Nf5 7. e4 Nfe7 8. d3 Ng6 9. Na3 e5 10. Nc2 h5 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bd2 h4 13. Qe1 Be6 14. b4 Qd7 15. b5 Nd8 16. a4 Nf7 17. Qe2 Bg4 18. Rfc1 Be7 19. Qf1 a5 20. bxa6 Rxa6 21. a5 {Borhy,M (2390)-Aczel,G (2477) Hungary 2024 0-1 (48)}) 7. d3 O-O 8. exd4 {White is slightly better.} Nf5 {[#]} 9. d5 $1 {White wants to avoid being left with the backward d3-pawn.} exd5 10. Nc3 dxc4 11. dxc4 {With all of the central pawns gone, the focus turns to piece play.} Nd6 {A more efficient approach was:} (11... Ncd4 12. Nd5 Nxf3+ $1 13. Qxf3 Bd6 14. Rd1 {[%cal Oc4c5]} c6 {with a level game.}) 12. Qe2 {[%eval 18,21] The queen is a target here.} (12. Qa4 Bd7 13. Nd5 Re8 {[%cal Oc6d4]} 14. Bf4 {leaves White slightly for choice due to his more active setup.}) (12. Qa4 $1 $14 {[%eval 61,21]}) 12... Re8 13. Nd5 Bf8 14. Be3 Nf5 15. Rad1 Nxe3 16. fxe3 {[%cal Ob2b4] Accepting a weak e3-pawn in return for the open f-file.} (16. Nxe3 Qf6 {is equal}) 16... Bd7 17. Qf2 f6 {Prevents Ng5.} 18. Qc2 Qc8 $1 19. Nh4 Bg4 20. Rde1 {[%eval -61,22]} (20. Rc1 $1 $14 {[%eval 49,21]}) 20... Nb4 $15 21. Qb1 {[%cal Of1f6]} c6 {[%eval -10,22]} ({Black should play} 21... Nxd5 $15 {[%eval -62,21]} 22. Bxd5+ Kh8) 22. Nf4 $11 g5 $5 {[%csl LRf4,LRh4][%cal Bg7g5,Bg5f4][%mdl 32] A major escalation after which the position gets very messy.} 23. h3 $1 gxf4 24. hxg4 fxe3 25. a3 e2 {Both sides have a set of weaknesses and exposed kings.} 26. Rf4 {[%cal Og2e4]} (26. Rf5 Qd7 (26... Qc7 27. g5 $17) 27. axb4 Bxb4 $19) 26... Qd7 {[%eval 85,24] [#] An forceful alternative is:} 27. Be4 $1 $16 (27. axb4 Bxb4 28. Nf3 Qd6 $17) 27... Na6 {[%cal Bb4a6,Ba6c5,Bc5e6,Be6g5,Bg5f7,Bf7e5][%mdl 32] and ...Bh6 would now be decisive} 28. Rxe2 {[%eval 22,21]} (28. Bf5 $16 {[%eval 72,24]} Qc7 29. Kf2 (29. Qc2 Bd6 $15 {[%mdl 64] Skewer}) 29... Bc5+ 30. Kg2) 28... Nc5 $11 29. Nf5 {[%eval -6,24]} (29. Rxf6 $2 Qd4+ (29... Qxg4 30. Bxh7+ Kh8 31. Rh2 $18) 30. Rff2 Nxe4 $19) (29. Bf5 $14 {[%eval 31,21]} Qf7 30. Rh2) 29... Re5 30. b4 Ne6 31. Rff2 {The position is dynamically balanced, and both sides play well, until a blunder appears just before the time control.} a5 {[%eval 41,22]} (31... Ng5 $11 {[%eval 1,22] might be stronger.}) 32. c5 axb4 33. axb4 Ng5 34. Bg2 {Dodges Nh3+} Qe6 35. Qd3 Nf7 36. Rxe5 Nxe5 37. Qe4 Ra4 38. Qd4 Qc4 {This move loses the game for White.} 39. Rf4 $4 {[%eval -294,25] Dropping a vital pawn.} (39. Qd8 Nxg4 40. Qe8 {remains completely unclear.}) (39. Qd8 $11 {[%eval -1,23] and White stays safe.} Nxg4 40. Qe8) 39... Rxb4 $19 40. Nh6+ {Or:} (40. Qd8 {Threatening mate with Nh6+.} Qc1+ 41. Rf1 Qxc5+ 42. Kh1 Nxg4 {and everything falls apart for White.}) 40... Kg7 41. Nf5+ Kf7 42. Qd1 {[%eval -420,24]} (42. Qd2 $142 {[%eval -283,23]} Qxc5+ (42... Bxc5+ 43. Kh1 $19) 43. Kh2) {Weighted Error Value: White=0.27 (precise) /Black=0.09 (flawless)} 42... Qd3 $1 {Forcing the trade of the rooks and/or queens, after which it's an easy win for Black.} (42... Qxc5+ $2 43. Kh2 $19) 0-1


