1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bd3 Re8 {Nowadays more popular than 9...a6. Heutzutage beliebter als 9...a6.} 10. O-O Bf8 11. Ne5 c5 12. Bb5 $5 {This is a move we haven't considered before. The bishop will likely soon retreat back to d3, but by attacking the rook White hopes to disrupt Black's coordination.} (12. f4 Nc6 {is normal - see games in the archives.}) 12... Re7 (12... Re6 {is the more natural response, as it doesn't block the bishop.} 13. f4 a6 (13... Nc6 14. Be1 cxd4 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. exd4 Rc8 17. Bh4 $14 {favoured White in Bryakin,M-Holm,K/Novi Sad 2021}) 14. Bd3 Nc6 15. Bf5 (15. Ne2 {might be better, and} Ne4 16. Be1 f6 $2 17. Bxe4 fxe5 18. Bf5 $1 {is an example of White exploiting Black's rook move}) 15... Re8 16. Ne2 g6 17. Bb1 Rc8 {and White's bishop moves hadn't achieved anything useful, Shengelia,D-Bosman,M/Batumi 2018.}) (12... Nbd7 {looks strange, not only because of the self-pin but also because the knight usually far prefers the c6-square. However, after} 13. f4 a6 14. Bd3 (14. Bxd7 Nxd7 15. Na4) 14... b5 $1 15. Be1 b4 {Black utilises the time gained on the light-squared bishop to accelerate queenside counterplay.} 16. Na4 (16. Ne2) 16... c4 17. Bf5 a5 18. Qf3 Nb6 19. Nxb6 Qxb6 20. Bh4 a4 21. g4 Ne4 $1 {favoured Black in Eliseev,V-Khismatullin,D/ICCF email 2017.}) 13. f4 a6 14. Bd3 Nc6 {The result of White's idea is that Black has gained two moves: ...a6 and ...Ra7. While it could be argued that ...a6 is useful, ...Re7 is most certainly not!} 15. Ne2 $146 ({Predecessor:} 15. Be1 $5 cxd4 $1 16. Nxc6 (16. exd4 $1 Nxd4 17. Bh4 {with some compensation for White.}) 16... Bxc6 17. exd4 {(Harsha,B-Giri,A/Chess.com 2020) and now} Ne4 (17... Re8 18. Bh4 Qd6 {looks nice for Black}) 18. Bh4 f6 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. d5 Bb7 21. Re1 {0-1 Harsha,B (2509)-Giri,A (2764) Titled Tuesday intern op 15th Sept blitz 2020 (7)}) (15. Na4 $5 {is a possibility here and it's more appealing when ...a6 has left a slight weakness on b6.}) ({RR} 15. Be1 cxd4 16. exd4 Nxd4 17. Bh4 Re8 18. Bb1 Ne6 19. Qc2 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 Nf8 21. Rcd1 d4 22. b4 Bxb4 23. Qb3 Qc7 24. Ne2 Bc5 25. Nxd4 Nd5 26. Be4 Bxd4 27. Rxd4 Nxf4 28. Nxf7 N8e6 29. Nd8 Kh8 {Sandipan,C (2482)-Tudor,H (2396) Abu Dhabi 2025 1-0 (48)}) 15... Rc7 $1 {Making best use of the rook's situation.} (15... Re8 16. Be1 Ne4 $6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Nxf7 $1 {is a sacrifice we've seen before, and this is a favourable version for White:} Kxf7 $2 19. Qb3+ Kg6 20. f5+ {and White's attack is winning, e.g.} Kh6 21. Rf4 (21. Bg3) 21... Qd7 22. Rh4+ Kg5 23. Nf4 g6 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Qg8 Qg7 26. Qd5+ Ne5 27. Nh3+ Kf6 28. dxe5+ Rxe5 29. Rf4+ {1-0 Heimisson,H-Steingrimsson,H/Reykjavik 2022.}) 16. Be1 Ne4 $1 17. Nxc6 {Exchanging knights doesn't feel right, but it's not easy to suggest another active plan for White.} ({After} 17. Bxe4 dxe4 {the key difference to the previous note is that the rook covers the f7-pawn, so there's no sacrifice.}) 17... Rxc6 (17... Bxc6 {intends ...Bb5 and might be preferable, especially if White goes ahead with Bxe4 as in the game.}) 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Bc3 $1 Rac8 20. Qe1 $1 {White is ready for kingside action.} a5 $1 {Enabling ...Ba6 to gain much needed counterplay.} 21. Rd1 Qe8 $1 22. f5 Ba6 23. Rf4 Bd3 24. dxc5 Bxc5 (24... Rxc5 $1 {is stronger, intending} 25. Nd4 Bd6 $1 26. Rg4 Be5 $1 {when Black is control.}) 25. Nd4 Rh6 26. Qg3 Bf8 27. Rg4 g6 28. fxg6 hxg6 29. Rd2 (29. Rg5 $1 {prevents ...Rh5 and prepares Nf5.}) 29... Rh7 (29... b5 $1 {was a missed opportunity to chase the bishop.} 30. Ne2 (30. Nf5 $2 {can be met by} b4 $1 31. Nxh6+ Bxh6 {intending} 32. Bd4 Rc1+ 33. Kf2 Rf1#) 30... b4 31. Bd4 Bxe2 32. Rxe2 Qe6 {White's attack has been defused and Black has the advantage.}) 30. Rf2 (30. h4 $1) 30... Bg7 (30... b5 $1 {is still a good idea.}) 31. Rg5 $1 Rc5 $1 (31... b5 {no longer has the desired effect:} 32. h4 $1 b4 33. Bd2 {and h5 is coming.}) 32. Rxc5 bxc5 33. Nb3 Bxc3 34. bxc3 {Now the position is easier to play for White, especially in time pressure.} Rh5 35. Qc7 $1 Rd5 36. Nxc5 Bc4 37. h3 Rd1+ 38. Kh2 Qd8 $1 39. Qf4 f5 40. Rb2 Qd6 41. Qxd6 Rxd6 42. h4 Rd5 (42... Rd1 $1 $11) 43. Rb8+ Kf7 44. Rb7+ Kg8 45. Nd7 $1 $16 Rd3 46. Ne5 Rxc3 47. Rc7 Rxe3 48. Rxc4 Ra3 49. Nxg6 Kf7 50. h5 Rxa2 51. Rc7+ Kf6 52. h6 Rb2 53. h7 Rb8 54. h8=Q+ 1-0


