1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 (7... O-O 8. e3 Bf5 9. Qb3 {was Duda -- Vazquez, 1-0, 2021, check the archives.}) 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Ne5 $146 {A new move for our site and according to my database, a novelty. Normally 9.Qb3 enjoys the strongest popularity with the majority of games seeing that continuation. As we'll address the move is not particularly strong and in longer time controls will likely never be employed. Black can just play a thematic idea and be better so apart from in really short time controls like blitz, I don't see the value of such a venture.} (9. Qb3 Ba5 10. Be2 {was excellently analyzed by Illingworth in Kovalenko -- Wojtaszek, 1/2, 2016, check the archives.}) (9. Bd3 $6 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O c6 {was Devaev -- Bluebaum, 0-1, 2022. Granted it was Titled Tuesday. Weirdly enough in spite of 9.Bd3 only having been played in three games, this position has been reached several dozen times through transposition. Black's score is above 50% and it makes sense since he should have absolutely 0 problems in this Carlsbad with the light squared bishops traded. I believe he scores better than 50% since the White players who are playing Bd3 are clearly looking to vacuum off pieces and avoid a complex battle.}) ({RR} 9. Be2 c6 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. O-O Bd6 12. Bg3 Qxb3 13. axb3 {½-½ (13) Berkes,F (2681)-Brkic,A (2573) Schwarzach 2019}) ({RR} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c6 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Be7 13. b4 a6 14. Rfb1 b5 15. a4 Re8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. a5 Be7 18. Qc2 Bd6 19. Ne2 Rc8 20. Nc1 Nf6 21. Nd3 Ne4 22. Rb2 Bf8 23. Nc5 Nxc5 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2765)-Anand,V (2791) Shamkir 2015 ½-½ (47)}) ({RR} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c6 11. O-O O-O 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Ne5 Re8 14. f4 Qd6 15. Ne2 Ne4 16. Ng3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 f6 18. Ng6 Re4 19. a3 Ba5 20. b4 Bc7 21. Nh4 Qe6 22. Rf3 Re8 23. Kf2 g5 {Shaik,S (2317)-Svane,F (2651) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1}) ({RR} 9. Be2 c6 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Nd2 O-O 12. O-O Rae8 13. Bg3 c5 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 c4 16. Qa2 Qa5 17. Rfc1 b5 18. Bd1 Qb6 19. h3 Qc6 20. a4 a6 21. Qa3 {½-½ (21) Wunnink,M (2306)-Maatman,N (2364) Netherlands 2022}) 9... c6 $2 (9... g5 $1 10. Bg3 (10. Nxd7 $2 {just helps Black mobilize even quicker.} Qxd7 11. Bg3 Ne4) 10... Ne4 {Who would look at this position and take White!} 11. Nd3 (11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. Qb3 {the only move to hold on.} (12. bxc3 Bxc3+ $19) 12... Nxa2+ 13. Ke2 Be6 14. Qxa2 $17) (11. Qb3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 f6 14. Bg3 h5 $1 $15 {Is a dream position for every Ragozin player.}) 11... Bxc3+ {is the classic way to seize the initiative.} (11... Ba5 $5 12. Rc1 c6 13. Be2 Qe7 {In a way this might be better than 11...Bxc3+. The position is complex and while Stockfish insists on a precise path to equality the position seem much more uncomfortable. Black can consider rerouting the Bishop to c7 after an exchange on g3. Apparently White can go for} 14. O-O Nxg3 15. hxg3 h5 {and he has enough to survive this but playing this at the board would take an unwavering confidence. An important point is the bishop cannot immediately go to c7 on pain of Nxd5.} 16. b4 $1 {Initiating counterplay on the queenside as quickly as possible!} Bxb4 (16... Bb6 17. b5 Rh6 $1 $132 {It's unclear who's attacking whom.}) (16... Bc7 $4 17. Nxd5 $18) 17. Nxb4 Qxb4 18. Qd2 Qe7 19. Rfe1 $13) 12. bxc3 h5 $15 {is also uncomfortable for White.}) 10. Nxd7 {And he got away with it!} Bxd7 ({Interestingly Black can accept the hideous structure and maintain fine chances after} 10... Qxd7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Rc1 Rg8 13. a3 Bd6 14. Na4 Be4 {The computer insists White is slightly better but the lines it gives aren't human at all, so unclear seems like a fair assessment.}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Be7 13. Qb3 Qb6 14. Qc2 (14. Qxb6 axb6 15. a4 {was also interesting.} g5 16. Bg3 Ne8 $5 17. f3 h5 $13) 14... Rfe8 {The game is level and after a prolonged struggle, White went on to win.} 15. Rae1 Nh5 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. b4 a6 18. Na4 Qc7 19. Nc5 Rae8 20. Rc1 Nf6 21. h3 Bc8 22. a4 Qd6 23. Qb2 Nh7 24. b5 axb5 25. axb5 Ng5 26. h4 Ne4 27. bxc6 bxc6 28. Nxe4 dxe4 29. Be2 Qf6 30. h5 Bd7 31. Rc5 Qh4 32. Ra1 Re6 33. Ra7 Rf6 34. Bf1 Bf5 35. Raa5 Qxh5 36. Qb7 Qg6 37. Ra6 Kh7 38. Raxc6 Rxc6 39. Rxc6 Re6 40. Rc5 Rb6 41. Qc7 Rb1 42. Rc1 Rxc1 43. Qxc1 Qd6 44. Qd2 h5 45. Qa5 Bg6 46. Qg5 f6 47. Qb5 h4 48. Be2 f5 49. Qc5 Qf6 50. d5 Bf7 51. d6 Be6 52. Bb5 Qa1+ 53. Kh2 Qb2 54. d7 Qxf2 55. Qe5 h3 56. Kxh3 f4+ 57. Kh2 Qg3+ 58. Kg1 Qxe3+ 59. Kh1 Qe1+ 60. Kh2 Qh4+ 61. Kg1 Qe1+ 62. Bf1 Qe3+ 63. Kh1 1-0


