1. Nf3 {*} d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c5 4. c4 d4 5. e3 Nc6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. d3 e6 8. O-O h6 (8... Bd6 {can be considered the mainline. After} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nbd2 Qe7 {see for example Aronian-Robson in the Archives.}) (8... Be7 {places the bishop less actively, and now another plan for White is} 9. Re1 O-O 10. Na3 Nd7 11. Nc2 e5 12. b4 {which is covered in the archived game Fridman-Grabarczyk.}) (8... Bc5 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 $5 {was an unusual idea essayed by Keymer in an online game, Praggnanandhaa-Keymer from 2022, also in the Archives.}) 9. Re1 (9. Na3 Bxa3 {taking the knight in one go is an advantage of Black's move order. Now} 10. bxa3 O-O 11. Bf4 Ng4 12. Bd2 e5 {is examined in Vachier Lagrave-Anton Guijarro in the Archives.}) (9. Bf4 {is more critical. White is happy to trade the "problem" c1-bishop, and if Black doesn't offer the bishop trade, then it is harder to achieve the ...e6-e5 break. After} Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Nbd2 O-O {White has tried:} 12. Re1 (12. Rc1 {and now:} Qb4 $5 {probes White's queenside. If} (12... e5 {is a bit premature as Black's centre can now come under pressure:} 13. c5 Qc7 (13... Qe7 {can be met with} 14. Re1 {and the x-ray along the e-file causes Black problems}) 14. Nc4 {with an edge for White according to Kuljasevic}) (12... Rd8 13. a3 a5 14. c5 Qe7 15. Re1 (15. Qa4 $5 {stopping the a-pawn from advancing, and applying pressure on the queenside, looks like an improvement}) 15... a4 16. Nc4 Nd7 17. Nfe5 Ncxe5 18. Nxe5 {was played in Gombocz,F (2210)-Gavrilescu, D (2473) Pardubice 2019 1/2-1/2 (45) , and here} Ra5 {targeting the exposed c5-pawn is at least fine for Black.}) 13. Nb3 {then Black can now continue} e5 {and the b3-knight is sub-optimally placed, when compared to the note to 12...e5.}) 12... a5 {is analyzed in Kollars-Huschenbeth in the Archives}) 9... Bd6 10. Na3 O-O 11. Nc2 a5 12. a3 (12. Ncxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bb4 14. Be3 Bxe1 15. Qxe1 Ng4 {but White probably doesn't have quite enough for the sacrificed material, Seeman,T (2411)-Volodin,A (2457) Viljandi 2021 1-0 (45)}) 12... e5 13. Rb1 a4 14. Nb4 (14. b4 axb3 15. Rxb3 Nd7 {Black brings the knight to the ideal c5-square with tempo} 16. Nb4 Nc5 17. Rb1 Re8 18. Nh4 Bd7 {and Black is clearly better. It is true that White has control of the d5-square, but can't do much with it, Almeida Quintana,O (2539)-Fernandez de La Vara,A (2486) Villa Clara 2020 1-0 (67)}) (14. Bd2 Re8 15. Bb4 $6 {Trying to swap the bishop, but Black side-steps and leaves it oddly placed on the b4-square.} Bc7 16. Nd2 Bf5 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Qd7 19. Bxf5 Qxf5 20. Qe2 Rad8 {with strong central control for Black, Gorbatov,A (2375)-Fantinel,T (2382) San Sebastian 2016 0-1 (80)}) 14... Re8 15. c5 (15. Nd5 {- 151/7 could be the best try to hold the balance, and was played in Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2595)-Huschenbeth,N (2611) Chess.com INT 2022 1-0 (32), a game which White won, but Black can improve here with} Bg4 (15... Nxd5 {gives Black an edge according to the engine, but the lines look rather irrational}) 16. h3 Bd7 17. Nd2 Na5 {and Black is at least fine}) 15... Bc7 16. Nd2 Bg4 {Diagram [#]} 17. Bf3 $146 (17. Qc2 Qd7 18. Nc4 Bh3 19. Bh1 {Savchenko,B (2550)-Iljiushenok,I (2567) Sochi 2022 �-� (38), and now} Nxb4 20. axb4 Bf5 {is good for Black, since White can't grab with} 21. Bxb7 $2 {since after} Rab8 22. Bg2 e4 {Black crashes through in the centre.}) 17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Ra5 (18... Ba5 $1 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Qxc6 Qd7 $1 {for example} 21. Qxd7 Nxd7 22. c6 Nc5 {when Black will soon recover the sacrificed pawn, and White is tied up.}) 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Qxc6 (20. b4 axb3 21. Nxb3 {activates White's pieces, although after} Ra6 {remains better}) 20... Re6 21. Qf3 Rxc5 $15 22. b4 axb3 23. Nxb3 Rc3 24. Bd2 e4 {Black achieves the thematic breakthrough.} 25. Qd1 {A critical position for the outcome of the game.} exd3 $2 {Here:} (25... Rxd3 $1 {is very strong, for example} 26. Nc5 Rxd2 27. Qxd2 Re5 28. Rec1 d3 {with tremendous compensation for the exchange. Even if White later gives up the knight for Black's d- and e-pawns, then Black retains a rook (along with bishop and knight), which is a more favourable material balance than in the game.}) 26. Rxe6 {White frees his position by trading pieces.} fxe6 27. Nxd4 Qxd4 28. Bxc3 Qxc3 29. Rb3 Qc6 30. Qxd3 {After the dust has settled, White has rook and pawn fighting two minor pieces, but White also has an outside passed pawn, while Black's e6-pawn is isolated. The computer gives it the full 0.00 assessment.} Ne4 31. Qe2 Bd6 32. Re3 Nxf2 {Black decides to kill the game here.} 33. Kxf2 {½-½ (33) Maghsoodloo,P (2719)-Keymer,V (2696) Wijk aan Zee NED 2023 [David Cummings]} Bc5 $146 {and the resulting queen endgame is drawn.} 1/2-1/2


