1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 ({Otherwise,} 2. Bf4 f5 3. e3 Nf6 {transposes.}) 2... f5 3. Bf4 Nf6 4. e3 b6 ({In the past, several alternatives have been examined on this site:} 4... d5 {in Carlsen, M - Janaszak, D Titled Tuesday online blitz 2017}) (4... Be7 {Sjugirov, S - Gleizerov, E Bryansk rapid 2021}) ({and the} 4... g6 {of Andersen, M - Hauge, L Reykjavik 2022.}) 5. Be2 ({In the following, in response to} 5. Bc4 {Black opted for quite a notable plan:} Bb7 6. O-O h6 ({as an alternative, I would suggest} 6... Bd6 $5 {which works well in some analogous positions}) 7. Nc3 g5 $5 {(now we understand his previous move!)} 8. Bg3 d5 {(if the centre remains closed maybe he can better justify his kingside actions)} 9. Bd3 Bd6 10. Ne5 {Paravyan, D - Onischuk, Ai Krasnaya Polyana 2021, and now the best continuation would be the daring} h5 $1 $13 {with attacking chances.}) 5... Bb7 6. h3 ({With} 6. c4 {White takes space with a sort of Queen's Indian/Dutch/English Defence hybrid:} Bb4+ (6... Be7 {isn't silly, as it threatens ...Nh5, but after} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 Nh5 9. Ne5 Nxf4 10. exf4 d6 11. Bf3 {White keeps a pull, Hakobyan, A - Paravyan, D Tsaghkadzor 2017}) 7. Nbd2 O-O (7... Be7 $5 8. O-O Nh5 {looks a shade too slow:} 9. Ne5 Nxf4 10. exf4 O-O 11. Bf3 c6 12. d5 $14 {Carlsen, M - Vallejo Pons, F Berlin blitz 2015, and White had the initiative}) 8. O-O Bxd2 {(Black happily cedes the bishop pair without causing any damage to White's structure, but he does achieve comfortable development and the bishop pair aren't going to be easy to exploit)} 9. Nxd2 d6 10. h3 Nbd7 11. Bh2 Qe8 12. f3 e5 {+=/= Kamsky, G - Ladopoulos, D Titled Tuesday online blitz 2022, and Black had achieved a decent position.}) 6... Nc6 $146 {It's rare here, but Maghsoodloo has already played this manoeuvre before in an analogous position. I quite like the fact that it transfers the knight to somewhere potentially useful (straight away) and thus avoids a log-jam with his pieces (later).} ({If} 6... g6 {then} 7. c4 {makes sense (as now ...Bb4+ doesn't fit well with his previous move):} Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Bh2 Nbd7 11. Rc1 Qe7 12. b4 a5 13. a3 axb4 14. axb4 Ne4 {+=/= Kamsky, G - Williams, S Leon blitz 2020, White has some chances on the queenside, but Black's pieces are quite well placed to react.}) ({Also after} 6... Be7 {White can include c2-c4 in his plans:} 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 Ne4 9. Nfd2 $1 {(taking the opportunity to challenge for e4 sooner rather than later)} d6 ({surely the right way forwards is with} 9... Nxd2 $1 10. Qxd2 d6 11. Nc3 Nd7 12. b4 (12. Bh2 Qe8 13. b4 Qg6 14. f3 Bg5 {Baarslag, E - Westerweele, H Vlissingen 2022, with fair counterplay}) 12... a5 13. a3 Bg5 {Cuadrado Wentwort Hyde, G - Chaika, I e-mail 2015, with only a small space edge for White}) 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 (10... fxe4 11. Nc3 Qe8 12. Bh5 {(killing off Black's hopes of activating his queen)} g6 13. Bg4 Bf6 14. d5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Na6 16. b4 Bg7 17. b5 $18 {Grachev, B - Amin, B Titled Tuesday online blitz 2020}) 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Bf3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nd7 14. Rad1 a6 {Murphy, H - Walton, A British league 2017, and White will have the better chances with e3-e4 coming.}) ({RR} 6... Be7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. c3 Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 d6 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. c4 Nc6 16. Qd2 Rc8 17. Rfd1 e5 18. Bg3 Qc7 19. Ne1 Rcd8 20. Nc2 Rb8 21. b3 {Killmer,M (1488)-Engelhardt,E (1707) Binz 2013 0-1 (46)}) ({RR} 6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 h6 9. a4 g5 10. Bh2 d6 11. a5 Qe8 12. Ne1 Qg6 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nbd7 15. axb6 cxb6 16. Nd3 Rfc8 17. c3 a5 18. Qe2 h5 19. Rfe1 d5 20. Nf3 g4 21. Nfe5 {Nguyen,Q (2242)-Fedoseev,V (2678) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (39)}) ({RR} 6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 Ne4 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 d6 11. Rb1 Nc6 12. d5 Na5 13. Nd4 e5 14. Ne6 Qc8 15. Nxf8 Qxf8 16. Bh2 Bf6 17. Qc2 g6 18. Kh1 Ba6 19. f4 exf4 20. exf4 Re8 21. Rfe1 {Kislinsky,A (2350)-Lortkipanidze,N (2359) Chess.com INT 2025 1-0 (68)}) ({RR} 6... Be7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. O-O h6 9. Ne5 Qe8 10. c4 d6 11. Nef3 g5 12. Bh2 g4 13. hxg4 Nxg4 14. Bf4 Qg6 15. Ne1 Nd7 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Ndxf3 Kh7 18. Nh2 Nxh2 19. Bxh2 Rg8 20. Qf3 Nf6 21. Qh3 {Buciu,A (1755)-Mikkelsen,M (1883) Cammeray 2018 0-1 (32)}) 7. Bh2 (7. O-O g6 {(too sluggish)} ({I prefer} 7... Bd6 $1) 8. c4 Bg7 9. Nc3 Ne7 $2 {(more time is squandered)} 10. Nb5 d6 11. c5 $18 {Grachev, B - Morozevich, A Moscow blitz 2008, with very strong threats.}) (7. Nbd2 {has been played but this looks too routine as there is no pressure on the black camp e.g.} Ne7 $5 8. c4 Ng6 9. Bh2 Bb4 ({or} 9... Bd6 $5 {à la Maghsoodloo}) 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 d6 13. b4 {Milutinovic, D - Laketic, G Serbian league 2009, and I would suggest either 13...a5 or} e5 {with decent chances. The engine prefers White slightly because the bishop pair might potentially be an asset, but this needs to be proven.}) 7... Ne7 8. c4 Ng6 {The first time this position has occurred despite it looking reasonable enough. The knight manoeuvre across to g6 being a fairly rare occurence it seems.} 9. O-O Bd6 ({One could also centralize a knight with} 9... Ne4) 10. Bxd6 cxd6 11. Nc3 ({I think White should grab more space with} 11. d5 $5 $14 {against which I would be interested to find out what the Iranian No.1 intended.}) 11... d5 {A strange pawn structure indeed, but not bad as Black challenges for central squares.} 12. Rc1 O-O 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bc4 Ne7 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Ne5 d6 18. Nd3 ({Rather than} 18. Nc6 Qd7 {when the advanced knight could easily get stranded.}) 18... Qd7 $11 {The Iranian's opening seems to have worked a treat as he has no problems and a 'sitting pretty' knight.} 19. Qd2 a5 20. Rc2 Rfc8 21. Rfc1 Ne7 22. Kf1 Rxc2 23. Rxc2 Rc8 24. Qc1 Rxc2 25. Qxc2 {Now it's a question of seeking a win...with both colours. Even if your engine comes up with '0.00' in a high-level encounter, this doesn't mean that it's drawn!} h6 26. Ke2 g5 27. f3 Kf7 28. Kd2 Kg7 29. Qb3 b5 30. Qc3 Qa7 31. Qb3 Qd7 32. Qc3 b4 $5 {Maghsoodloo is looking for the full point, but advancing one's pawns on all fronts is fraught with danger.} 33. Qc4 Nd5 34. e4 Nf6 $2 ({Instead,} 34... fxe4 35. fxe4 Nf4 {keeps the balance.}) 35. e5 $1 dxe5 36. Nxe5 {Now it's White with the more imposing knight outpost.} Qd6 37. Qc5 $1 Qxc5 38. dxc5 Nd5 39. Nc4 {The a-pawn is put under pressure.} a4 40. Nb6 $1 Kf6 41. Nxd5+ {Simplest.} exd5 42. Kd3 Ke5 43. g3 f4 44. g4 {Black is run out of half-decent moves and finds himself in Zugzwang.} b3 45. axb3 axb3 46. Kc3 d4+ 47. Kxb3 Kd5 48. c6 Kxc6 49. Kc4 d3 50. Kxd3 Kc5 51. Kc3 Kb5 52. b4 Kb6 53. Kc4 Kc6 54. b5+ Kb6 55. Kb4 Kb7 56. Kc5 Kc7 57. b6+ Kb7 58. Kb5 Kb8 59. Kc6 Kc8 60. b7+ Kb8 61. Kb6 1-0


