{The World Champion worked hard to help his team in this event and in several rounds his wins proved crucial for the club. He tried a new and deep idea (a bit risky at times) against the Iranian #1, talented super GM Parham Maghsoodloo. Things seemed alright for Carlsen until the complications got to the champion himself. Luckily, the path to victory for White wasn't clear and the players split the point at the end. Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Magsodloo promised to become really top Worls player few years ago ,but it seems that he slowed down. But in this game World Champion was in troubles!'} 1. d4 {Schandorff, Lars Mikhalchishin,Adrian} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 {Diagram [#]} Ne8 $5 {I was aware of this move but I did not know how it is played out until I saw this game! Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Telling honestly, this Carlsbad system is not easy to handle with Black.So,Magnus wants to create some nonclassical set ups.'} (9... Re8 {Carlsen,Magnus 2863 - Firouzja,Alireza 2728, Stavanger 2020 - 146/141}) 10. Bg3 (10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qc2 Nd6 12. O-O (12. O-O-O $2 a5 $15 {is better for Black.}) 12... Nd7 13. Ng3 Qg5 $5 14. f4 Qd8 15. f5 Nf6 $13 {and Black seems to dismiss White's assault.}) 10... Nd6 $5 (10... Bd6 {This move has been employed in the correspondence games with relative success. I have a hard time wrapping my head around what this move actually does. So, I leave it here for your further investigation.} 11. O-O Bxg3 12. Nxg3 Be6 13. f3 (13. Nce2 Nd7 14. f3 Nd6 15. Qd2 Qb6 16. Rae1 Rac8 $13 {Riess,Bernhard - Laliga, Olivier, corr 2017/18}) 13... Nd7 14. Qd2 Nd6 15. Rae1 Rc8 16. e4 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Rd1 f6 $13 {Alan Rawlings - Gerald Hildebrand, corr. 2014/15}) 11. O-O Re8 12. Qc2 Bf8 13. Rae1 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'N!?' Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'New and interesting.' Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '.'} (13. Rad1 a5 14. a3 Nd7 15. h3 Nf6 16. Be5 Nfe4 17. Bxe4 (17. Na2 Be6 18. Rc1 Be7 $11) 17... dxe4 18. Ng3 f5 19. Nce2 Nf7 (19... a4 $5) 20. f3 exf3 21. Rxf3 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Qe7 23. Nxf5 Qxe5 24. Neg3 Bxf5 25. Nxf5 Rad8 26. Rdf1 Rd7 27. Qc4+ Kh7 28. Qc2 Kg8 29. Qc4+ Kh7 30. Qc2 {1/2 : 1/2 Nisipeanu,Liviu Dieter 2615 - Moussard,Jules 2686, Deutschland 2022}) ({Magnus had this position on the board.} 13. Bf4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} Be6 14. f3 Nd7 15. Rad1 b5 16. e4 Rc8 17. e5 Nc4 18. b3 Ncb6 19. Qd2 {½-½ (70) Grischuk,A (2764)-Carlsen,M (2856) Warsaw 2021}) 13... a5 {Diagram [#]} 14. Nf4 $146 {White has other options. Both a3 and h3 are good waiting moves. Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Novelty of Iranian Grandmaster.It was tried a bit different Knight transfer' Schandorff, Lars: 'This is a good positional move.'} (14. Nc1 Na6 15. a3 Be6 16. Nb3 Nc4 17. Ne2 a4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nd2 b5 20. e4 b4 21. Nxc4 Bxc4 22. Qxc4 Rxe4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'with tough game, Bogner,S (2573)-Fressinet,L (2630) Germany 2022'} 23. Be5 Qd5 24. Qc2 $14 {Bogner,Sebastian 2573 - Fressinet,Laurent 2630, Deutschland 2022}) ({RR} 14. Nd1 Na6 15. a3 Bd7 16. f3 Rc8 17. Nec3 c5 18. Qf2 Bc6 19. Bf4 b5 20. Ne2 Nc4 21. Qg3 h5 22. Qh3 g6 23. g4 Bd7 24. Qg2 h4 25. g5 Bg7 26. Kh1 Nd2 27. Rg1 c4 28. Bc2 b4 {Salem,A (2677)-Carlsen,M (2859) Chess.com INT 2022 0-1 (37)}) ({RR} 14. a3 Nd7 15. Nf4 b5 16. Nb1 Bb7 17. Nd2 Nc4 18. Rd1 Nf6 19. a4 Qb6 20. b3 Nd6 21. Ne2 Rac8 22. Rc1 Nde4 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Be5 c5 25. Qb1 Nd7 26. axb5 Qxb5 27. Nc4 cxd4 28. Nxd4 Qa6 {Maghsoodloo,P (2684)-Moussard,J (2587) Chess.com INT 2025 ½-½ (129)}) 14... Na6 15. a3 {Diagram [#]} Qf6 $146 {World #1 plays with fire. Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '?' Schandorff, Lars: '!?' Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Overoptimistic.Preferable was to transfer Knight to e6.' Schandorff, Lars: 'Looks a little risky to me. Easier is probably ...Bd7 followed by ...b5 like we have seen in other games. Here is an example where Black quickly got comfortable play:'} (15... Nc7 16. h3 Ne6 17. Na4 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 b5 19. Nc5 a4 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. e4 dxe4 22. Nxe4 Qd8 23. Qxc6 Bd7 24. Qc3 g6 $44 {Black has enough compensation with his bishop pair.}) (15... Bd7 $145 {Schandorff, Lars: '!'} 16. f3 b5 {Schandorff, Lars: ''} 17. Qf2 b4 18. axb4 Nxb4 19. Bb1 a4 20. e4 a3 21. bxa3 Rxa3 22. Rc1 Nc4 $13 {Lu,Shanglei 2605 - Li,Di 2539, China (ch) 2022} 23. Rfe1 {Schandorff, Lars} Rb3 24. exd5 Rb2 25. Rxe8 Bxe8 26. Qe1 cxd5 27. Ncxd5 Nxd5 28. Rxc4 Nxf4 29. Bxf4 Bb5 30. Rc1 Qxd4+ 31. Qe3 {½-½ (31) Lu,S (2605)-Li,D (2539) Xinghua 2022}) ({RR} 15... Bd7 16. f3 b5 17. Qf2 b4 18. axb4 Nxb4 19. Bb1 a4 20. e4 a3 21. bxa3 Rxa3 22. Rc1 Nc4 23. Rfe1 Rb3 24. exd5 Rb2 25. Rxe8 Bxe8 26. Qe1 cxd5 27. Ncxd5 Nxd5 28. Rxc4 Nxf4 29. Bxf4 Bb5 30. Rc1 {Lu,S (2605)-Li,D (2539) Xinghua 2022 ½-½ (31)}) ({RR} 15... b5 16. f3 Nc7 17. Qf2 b4 18. Na4 bxa3 19. bxa3 Bf5 20. Nc5 Bxd3 21. Nfxd3 Nc4 22. a4 Ne6 23. e4 Bxc5 24. Nxc5 Nxc5 25. dxc5 Qd7 26. Qd4 Rad8 27. h3 f6 28. Kh2 Qf7 29. exd5 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 {Sambuev,B (2414)-Migot,T (2344) Montreal 2025 1-0 (58)}) ({RR} 15... Nc7 16. f3 Nc4 17. e4 b5 18. Bf2 b4 19. axb4 axb4 20. Nd1 Ra1 21. exd5 Rxe1 22. Rxe1 Nxd5 23. Nxd5 cxd5 24. Bxc4 dxc4 25. Qxc4 Be6 26. Qd3 Be7 27. Ne3 Rxe1+ 28. Bxe1 Bc5 29. Kf2 Qxd4 30. Qxd4 {Maghsoodloo,P (2656)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2531) Almaty 2022 ½-½ (31)}) 16. f3 $6 ({Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'It was unexpected central strike here' Schandorff, Lars: 'The machine screams'} 16. e4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '!?' Schandorff, Lars: '!'} Qxd4 (16... dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Bg4 (18... Bd7 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} 19. Re3 Nc7 20. Rf3) 19. h3 Bd6 20. Qd2 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) 17. exd5 Bd7 {Schandorff, Lars: 'and Black seems to hold.'} 18. Qd1 (18. Rd1 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} Qb6 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Nfd5 Nc5 {and Black holds the position.}) 18... c5 19. Nfe2 Qf6 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Nb5 Bxb5 22. Bxb5 Red8 23. Bc4 $14 {White has a small but long lasting edge thanks to the d5 pawn and control over light squares on the queenside.}) ({Also} 16. Nh5 {Schandorff, Lars} Qg5 17. Bxd6 $1 Bxd6 18. Ng3 {intending f4 could put some pressure on Black.}) 16... b5 17. Bf2 {Schandorff, Lars: 'He has to defend d4 before he can play e4.'} ({It was possible to prepare programm e3-e4 a bit differently.} 17. Qf2 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} Nf5 $1 {Schandorff, Lars} 18. e4 Nxg3 19. hxg3 b4 $132) 17... Nc4 {Schandorff, Lars: 'Now Black has plenty of play.'} 18. g3 {Schandorff, Lars: 'Protecting the knight on f4.'} ({If White protects Knight differently,then Black equalise after} 18. Qc1 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian Schandorff, Lars: 'did the same, but with more flexibility.'} Nc7 19. a4 b4 20. Ne4 Qd8 21. Nd2 Nxd2 22. Qxd2 Ne6) 18... Qd8 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '?!'} ({Better was to bring Knight to the center} 18... Nc7 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} 19. e4 Ne6 20. e5 {Schandorff, Lars} Qe7 $13) 19. e4 {Schandorff, Lars: '!' Schandorff, Lars: 'Finally.'} b4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '[#]'} ({Magbus did not want to give up the center} 19... dxe4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} 20. fxe4 Nc7 21. e5 Ne6 22. Rd1 Nxf4 23. gxf4 Bg4 24. Rc1 {and Black still face problems, due to White powerful center.}) 20. exd5 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '!'} Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Nd6 $2 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: '?!'} ({Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Better would be'} 21... Nb6 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'after what White can hold the initiative ,sacrificing a piece'} 22. dxc6 bxc3 23. bxc3 Bxa3 24. Qb3 Bd6 25. Bb1 (25. Bg6 $1 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} Ra7 26. Bb1) 25... Bxf4 26. gxf4 Bh3 27. d5 $16 {The engine analysis are crazy but surely White has the upper hand. Egnines like this better for Black than what happened in the game. However, I did not find White's path to victory to be that easy in the game per se, so 21..Nd6 makes more sense to me although engines don't like it.}) 22. Na4 cxd5 23. Nxd5 {Schandorff, Lars: '' Schandorff, Lars: 'White won a pawn and is much better. However the WC is hard to beat...'} Rb8 {Diagram [#]} ({Strong pressure keeps White after} 23... Bb7 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} 24. Ndb6 Rb8 25. d5) 24. Nc5 $6 ({Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'and'} 24. Re5 Bb7 25. Nc5 {This seems totally dominant.} Bxd5 (25... bxa3 26. bxa3 Nc7 27. Nxb7 Rxb7 28. Nf4 $18 {and White is a pawn up.}) (25... Nc7 26. Nxb7 Rxb7 27. a4 $18 {Again, White is a solid pawn up.}) 26. Rxd5 Nc7 27. Re5 g6 {Diagram [#]} 28. a4 $1 Bg7 29. Re2 Nd5 30. Kg2 $18 {This is the best Black can get but I still doubt if there could be any practical chances for Black here. White seems to be cruising to victory.}) ({There were two other promising optios here} 24. Nf4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian}) 24... Nb5 25. Bxb5 $2 {Squanders most of the advantage.} (25. Re5 $16 {was still good to push for a win.}) 25... Rxb5 26. Qc4 ({White could keep extra pawn with} 26. Nf4 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian but Blacks Bishop pair would be some compensation for it.}) 26... Rb8 27. a4 $6 ({Magnus would keep compensation even after better} 27. Rd1 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} bxa3 (27... Nxc5 28. dxc5 Be6 29. Qe2 $1 bxa3 30. bxa3 Qc8 31. Nb6 Qc7 32. Qe3 Rd8) 28. bxa3 Qd6) 27... Nxc5 28. dxc5 Bb7 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian: 'Now starts forced variation ,where Magnus defends easily.'} 29. c6 Rc8 30. Bb6 Qd6 31. Bc7 Qc5+ ({Similar development would follow after} 31... Qxc6 {Mikhalchishin,Adrian} 32. Qxc6 Bxc6 33. Ne7+ Bxe7 34. Rxe7 Bxa4) 32. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 33. Kg2 Bxc6 $11 34. Rc1 Bxd5 35. Rxc5 Bb3 36. Bb6 Rxc5 37. Bxc5 Bxa4 38. Bb6 Bc6 39. Bxa5 b3 1/2-1/2


