1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bf5 5. f3 {A rare idea} h5 $5 {A fifth move novelty from the Indian star!} ({A few days earlier Maghsoodloo faced} 5... e6 {which is the main reply:} 6. g4 {(OK, White has tried other moves here but this is surely the only way to test Black's set-up)} Bg6 7. h4 h6 (7... h5 8. g5 Nfd7 9. Nge2 (9. Bd3 $6 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 g6 11. Nge2 {gave White nothing in Bellahcene, B - Bailet, P Aix-en-Provence 2022, so he offered a draw that was accepted}) 9... Bd6 10. b3 $5 $146 ({I prefer this to} 10. Qb3 Na6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. e4 {Galperin, P - Katz, A Merida 2022, which looks too loosening, for example, after} Nb4 {White will have to be careful not to just end up with weaknesses galore}) 10... O-O 11. Bh3 {with a tense struggle coming up where White has more space}) 8. Nge2 (8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 {(I don't think this exchange works that well once White has committed his kingside pawns)} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. Nge2 {Kozul, Z - Benitah, Y Aix-les-Bains 2011, and now vigorous play is required:} dxc4 $1 12. Qxc4 Rc8 {intending ...b5 with good counterplay in prospect}) 8... Bd6 9. Qb3 (9. Nf4 $5 {is interesting, when Black has to decide if he should capture or not, either way it's 'unclear'}) 9... b6 $6 ({Stockfish suggests} 9... dxc4 $3 10. Qxc4 (10. Qxb7 Nd5 {with murky play when the queen on b7 would get trapped if it captured on a8}) 10... b5 $132) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nf4 $5 Bh7 12. Bd2 g5 $6 {(a bit panicky, as now the h-file might become a problem)} 13. Nfe2 Qe7 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Bg2 Na6 16. e4 $1 {Maghsoodloo, P - Smirnov, A Chennai 2022, and Black was in trouble.}) ({After} 5... Nbd7 {White could create some action with} 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Nh3 {with Nf4 in mind. The knight on d7 feels misplaced so I prefer White.}) ({Following} 5... h6 6. Qb3 {in Perlovskiy, V - Polikushin, V Kolomna 2007, Black rather passively retreated his bishop to c8. Instead,} Qb6 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Bd2 Nc6 {looks perfectly fine to me. The inclusion of the 'supplementary pawn moves' f2-f3 and ...h7-h6 shouldn't harm Black's game.}) 6. Bd3 {A modest enough move, but Maghsoodloo hopes that the daring advance ...h7-h5 will prove to be out of place at a later date.} Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nge2 dxc4 ({If} 8... Nbd7 {then the capture} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 {would give Black three recaptures, each with its own pluses and minuses. Anyway, with the text move, Harikrishna seems to want to avoid this scenario.}) ({RR} 8... Nbd7 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. e4 dxe4 11. fxe4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Qb5+ Ned7 14. Bg5 Qb6 15. e5 Qxb5 16. Nxb5 Nd5 17. Nec3 N7b6 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. O-O-O a6 20. Rxd5 axb5 21. Rxb5 Rxa2 22. Kb1 Ra7 23. Be3 {Chen,Y (2237)-Kuznecova,M (2279) Durres 2025 1-0}) 9. Qxc4 Nbd7 $146 ({RR} 9... a6 10. Bd2 b5 11. Qb3 Nbd7 12. e4 c5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O c4 15. Qc2 e5 16. Rad1 Bd6 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nf4 Bc5 19. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Kh1 O-O 21. Ncd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Qe7 23. Nxh5 Nd3 24. Qd2 {Trost,E (2442)-Bharath,S (2482) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (80)}) 10. e4 {There's nothing wrong with gaining ground in the centre.} Rc8 11. a4 {Clearly a prophylactic move, but is it necessary?} ({If instead} 11. Be3 {any advance with ...b7-b5 might prove to be 'positionally risky' especially as Black has already advanced on the other wing.}) 11... Qa5 12. Bd2 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Rab1 $6 ({The engine preference is for} 14. Nf4 {with a tiny space edge. If then} c5 {, as it's well-supported, the d-pawn can safely advance:} 15. d5 $1) ({However, the routine move} 14. Rfd1 {can be happily met by} c5 {as then} 15. d5 $6 Ne5 {suits Black fine, as White's queen is awkwardly placed.}) 14... e5 $6 ({The right break seems to be} 14... c5 $1 {(creating some problems for White along the a7-g1 diagonal) as again} 15. d5 $6 {is well met by} Ne5 $15) 15. b4 $1 {This space-gaining advance seems to ensure that White obtains the easier game.} Qc7 16. Be3 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 exd4 {The engine is giving 0.00 around here, but I'd still take White (remember that the h-pawn is potentially 'out on a limb' on h5!).} 18. Nxd4 Ne5 19. Qe2 Ng6 20. Nf5 Rxd1+ 21. Qxd1 Bf8 22. a5 {Now there really is a threat of capturing on a7.} b6 23. axb6 axb6 24. b5 $1 {A minority attack approach.} Ne7 25. Nd4 c5 26. Nde2 Ng6 27. h3 {There is no particular hurry, as White has a solid game plus there are certain modest positional features (the d5-outpost, advanced h-pawn and the fixed pawn on b6) that might give prospects of a real advantage down the line. Meantime, Black has plenty of time to commit himself!} c4 $6 {Overplaying his hand. Maybe Harikrishna simply overlooked White's next move.} ({Instead, following} 27... Bd6 28. Qc2 h4 {Stockfish is happy with Black's chances, but with} 29. Bg5 {White's game still looks easier to me.}) 28. Na4 $1 {Oh! Suddenly the b6-pawn is problem.} Nd7 $6 ({Black should perhaps ditch the weakness with} 28... Rd8 {intending} 29. Qc2 ({the more subtle} 29. Qc1 $1 {might be best, but even so} Rd3 30. Bxb6 Qd7 {still looks tricky}) 29... Rd3 30. Bxb6 Qd7 {with decent practical chances.}) 29. Nec3 {Heading for the d5-square!} Bc5 {Desperately seeking activity, even at the cost of the queenside. The engine dismisses it as bad, but this is a game of chess between two humans. No-one plays perfectly.} 30. Bxc5 Nxc5 31. Nd5 Qg3 32. Naxb6 Rb8 33. Nxc4 $18 Nh4 {Time pressure makes even 'easy' wins into 'hard' work, so White has to be vigilant.} 34. Nce3 ({Simplest is} 34. Qe2 Ne6 35. Qf2 {avoiding any potential tricks.}) 34... Ne6 35. Ne7+ Kh7 36. N7f5 Qg5 37. Nxh4 $6 ({The engine gives} 37. Kh1 $1 g6 38. f4 {but I doubt many grandmasters would go for such a risky-looking idea just before move forty.}) 37... Qxe3+ 38. Kh1 g6 $1 {The knight is not happy on h4.} 39. Qd6 $6 ({A better version is} 39. Qd7 Kg7 40. Qd6 Rb6 41. Qe5+ {(with check!)} Kh7 42. Ra1 {but even then Black has decent drawing chances. After} Qd4 43. Qxd4 Nxd4 44. Ra4 Nxb5 45. Rb4 Rb7 {White will have to strive to win a 4 vs. 3 on the same side. Some books claim that a knight endgame with such a pawn disposition is winning, but I wouldn't be so sure. It looks like a classic 50-50 scenario to me, for example, going further with} 46. Kg1 Nd6 47. Rxb7 Nxb7 48. Kf2 Kg7 49. Ke3 Kf6 50. f4 Nc5 $16 {and I still wouldn't be sure of the most likely result.}) 39... Rb6 40. Qe5 ({It seems that} 40. Qe7 Kg7 41. Qa7 Qd3 42. Qxb6 Qxb1+ 43. Kh2 Qe1 {is no longer advantageous either.}) 40... Qd3 41. Qa1 Rxb5 42. Rxb5 Qxb5 43. Qf6 Qd7 {Now we have 4 vs. 3 with queens as well. This may offer White more winning chances, but only if he can expose the opposing king rather than his own!} 44. Kh2 Kg8 $6 {The first move that comes to mind, as it bolsters the defence of f7, but it turns out that his reduced grip on g6 is a more important issue.} ({Better is} 44... Nc5 $5 {intending to either shuffle back and forwards or hop to d3.}) 45. f4 Nd4 $2 {Missing the big point.} ({Naturally,} 45... Nf8 {is more solid.}) 46. Nxg6 $1 fxg6 47. Qxg6+ Kf8 48. Qxh5 {Four pawns versus a knight is clearly promising, with or without queens.} Qd6 49. e5 Qd5 50. Qg6 Ne6 51. h4 $5 Qc4 (51... Nxf4 $4 {fails to} 52. Qh6+) 52. Qh6+ Ng7 53. h5 Qe2 54. Kh3 Qd3+ $2 (54... Qf1 $1 $14 {holds back the tide....well, for now.}) 55. Kh4 $18 Qe4 56. g4 Kg8 57. Qf6 Qh1+ 58. Kg5 Qd5 59. Qg6 Kf8 60. Qd6+ 1-0


