1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $5 {An uncommon recapture, but one which Sam has already checked in the archives a couple of times. It's not without merit, as the Queen often ends up on the c-file and Black's light-squared Bishop can reach e6 in one move.} 7. Nc3 {This is White's most popular continuation.} (7. O-O {1/2-1/2 (59) Zelcic,R (2527)-Bosiocic,M (2625) chess24.com 2020 [Collins,Sam]}) 7... e5 8. Qd3 (8. Qb6 $5 {also received a test recently and looks promising.} Qc6 9. Nd5 Qxb6 10. Nxb6 Rb8 11. Be3 Nf6 12. Nd2 Be6 13. c4 Be7 14. f3 Nd7 15. Nd5 Bd8 (15... f5 $5 $132 {is a more active try for Black.}) 16. Ke2 $14 {I would rate White's chances as slightly higher as his pieces are well-placed to support his advance on the Queenside.} g6 17. a4 f5 18. a5 h5 19. b4 Nf6 20. Rhb1 fxe4 {1-0 (44) Svane,R (2615)-Cheparinov,I (2667) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021} 21. fxe4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f1,Gf1g1] maintains a solid presence for White in the centre and allows him to pursue his Queenside initiative unhindered.}) 8... Qc6 9. Nd5 {A new move for our site.} (9. O-O {1/2-1/2 (44) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780) -Carlsen,M (2872) London 2019 [Sam Collins]}) ({RR} 9. O-O Be6 10. Rd1 Rc8 11. a4 h6 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Nf1 Be7 14. Ne3 O-O 15. Ncd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qd7 17. Nf5 Kh8 18. c4 e4 19. Qh3 Nh7 20. b3 Bf6 21. Ra2 b5 22. axb5 axb5 23. cxb5 Ng5 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Carlsen,M (2872) London 2019 ½-½ (44)}) 9... Be6 (9... f5 $5 10. Nd2 (10. Qb3 $5 b5 11. exf5 {This is ok for Black as long as he avoids the natural recapture.} Ne7 $1 (11... Bxf5 $2 12. Ne3 Bd7 13. Ng5 Nh6 14. O-O $14 a5 15. Nd5 Rc8 16. Re1 $5 Qxc2 $6 17. Qa3 $1 $44) 12. Nc3 $1 Nxf5 13. O-O Be7 14. a4 Qc4 $1 15. axb5 Qxb3 16. cxb3 Bb7 $44) 10... Nf6 11. O-O (11. f3 $6 Nxd5 12. exd5 Qc7 $15 {looks pleasant for Black, with his two Bishops and mobile central majority, �-� (54) Zarubitski,V (2432)-Sivuk,V (2557) Moscow RUS 2020}) 11... fxe4 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Nxe4 f5 14. Nf6+ Kf7 15. Nd5 Rg8 $1 $11) (9... Ne7 $5 {is the engine preference.} 10. c4 {is met by either} f5 $5 $132 ({or} 10... b5 $5 $132)) ({RR} 9... Ne7 10. c4 b5 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Qxb5 Qxb5 13. Nc7+ Kd7 14. Nxb5 Ba6 15. Nc3 Nc6 16. Be3 Nb4 17. O-O-O Bc4 18. Nxe5+ {1-0 (18) Terry,R (2508)-Kleimenov,N (2198) Chess.com INT 2025}) 10. c4 Rc8 11. Nd2 $146 ({RR} 11. b3 f5 12. exf5 Bxd5 13. cxd5 Qxc1+ 14. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 15. Ke2 Rxh1 16. Qc4 Be7 17. Qc8+ Kf7 18. Qxb7 h6 19. Qc8 Ra1 20. a4 Ra2+ 21. Ke1 Ra1+ 22. Ke2 Ra2+ 23. Kf1 Ra1+ 24. Ne1 h5 25. h4 Rh6 {Terry,R (2508)-Pyrig,R (2414) Chess.com INT 2024 1-0 (41)}) ({RR} 11. b3 b5 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. O-O Be7 14. a4 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Qc2 16. Qxc2 Rxc2 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra8+ Bd8 19. Rd1 O-O 20. Ba3 Ra2 21. b4 Bb6 22. Ra6 Bd4 23. h3 h5 24. Ra5 Rc8 25. Rc1 Rxc1+ {Pastar,S (2361)-Rozen,E (2482) Petrovac 2024 0-1 (33)}) 11... f5 $6 {This is less good with the b-pawns still on the board.} (11... b5 $1 12. b3 f5 $5 {transposes to the previous note.} (12... Nf6 13. O-O Be7 14. Rd1 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qb7 16. a4 $14 {White has a strong initiative.}) 13. exf5 bxc4 14. bxc4 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Qb5 16. Qxb5+ axb5 17. Ne4 Rc4 18. f3 Be7 19. O-O Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Rb1 O-O 22. Rxb5 e4 $1 $44 {Black should have enough play to draw.}) 12. exf5 Bxd5 13. cxd5 Qb5 (13... Qc2 $5 14. Qxc2 Rxc2 15. b3 Ne7 16. Nc4 Nxf5 (16... Nxd5 $2 17. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Rc2] leaves the Black Rook trapped on c2.}) 17. Bd2 b5 18. Kd1 Nd4 19. Be3 $1 Rc3 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Nd2 Rc5 22. a4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh1e1,Ga4b5] White emerges with some initiative.}) 14. Qxb5+ axb5 15. Nf1 (15. Ne4 $5 {is more natural and perhaps more challenging.} Rc4 16. f3 Kd7 17. b3 $1 (17. Bd2 Ne7 18. b3 Rc7 19. Rd1 Nxd5 20. O-O b4 $11 {looks ok for Black.}) 17... Rc2 $1 (17... Rc7 $4 18. O-O Ne7 19. Ba3 $1 Nxf5 20. f4 $18 {gives White a crushing initiative.}) 18. Bd2 (18. O-O Ne7 $1 19. Bg5 {[%cal Re7f5,Rf3f4]} Nxd5 20. Rfd1 Nf4 21. Bxf4 exf4 22. f6 gxf6 23. Nxf6+ Ke6 24. Nh5 Rg8 25. Nxf4+ Kd7 $44 {[%cal Gf8g7] This isn't easy to judge but it looks like Black has enough play to draw here as well.}) 18... Ne7 19. Kd1 Rc8 20. a4 Nxd5 21. axb5 Be7 22. Ke2 g6 $5 23. fxg6 hxg6 $44 {Black is a pawn down but the position is still very unbalanced.}) (15. O-O $5 {is also possible.} Nf6 16. Rd1 Kd7 17. Nf1 Rc5 {should give Black enough play as well:} 18. Bg5 $5 Nxd5 19. Be3 Nxe3 20. Nxe3 Be7 $11) 15... Be7 $6 (15... Nf6 $1 {looks more precise, immediately attacking d5.} 16. Ne3 g6 $1 17. fxg6 hxg6 $44 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8h6,Gh6e3,Gc8c5] It's surprising how much compensation Black has here. The engine already rates it as 0.00. It's going to be very difficult for White to hang on to the d5-pawn.}) 16. Ke2 Bd8 17. Ne3 Bb6 18. a4 $5 (18. Bd2 $5 Ne7 19. Rac1 Kd7 20. a3 $5 Bxe3 21. fxe3 e4 $1 {is very precise, preparing to capture the f5-pawn. White doesn't really have a useful way to improve his position.} (21... Nxd5 $5 22. Kf3 h5 $11 {is also fine.}) (21... Nxf5 $4 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Rf1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf1f7]} Nh6 24. e4 $18) 22. Ba5 Nxf5 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Rf1 Rc2+ $1 25. Bd2 Ne7 $11 {[%csl Yb2]}) 18... Ne7 $1 19. axb5 Kd7 $1 $44 {Black shows excellent understanding of the position. He is in no hurry to regain the pawns and calmly completes his development.} 20. Ra4 Bxe3 {Natural, but there is a good alternative.} (20... Rc5 $1 {may be even more precise.} 21. Rb4 Rhc8 22. Bd2 Nxd5 $11 {looks good for Black.}) 21. fxe3 (21. Bxe3 Rc2+ 22. Kf3 Rxb2 $15 {Black takes over the initiative.}) 21... Rc2+ 22. Bd2 Nxd5 23. Rb1 h5 (23... Nf6 $1 {is even better, clearing the way for the d-pawn.} 24. Kd3 Rhc8 $11 {[%cal Ge5e4]}) 24. Kd3 $5 (24. e4 $1 Nf6 25. Kd3 Rc5 26. b6 Rc6 27. Be3 d5 $1 $44 {gives Black good counterplay.}) 24... Rc5 (24... Rhc8 $1 25. e4 $5 Nf4+ 26. Bxf4 exf4 27. Ra7 Rxg2 28. Rxb7+ Rc7 29. Rxc7+ Kxc7 $11 {Black will hold thanks to his active Rook.}) 25. b4 e4+ $1 (25... Rxb5 26. e4 Nf6 $132 {is still ok for Black as we've seen, but the game move is even clearer.} 27. Ra5 $1 Rb6 $1 28. b5 d5 $5 29. Ra7 $1 (29. exd5 Rd6 $1 $11 {equalises.}) 29... Nxe4 30. Ba5 Rhh6 $1 31. Ra8 $5 Ke7 $44 {Black appears to have enough even here, but there is plenty of play left.}) 26. Kxe4 (26. Kd4 Rc2 27. Kxd5 Rxd2+ 28. Kxe4 Re8+ 29. Kf3 Re5 30. e4 d5 $1 $11 {Black active Rooks secure an easy draw for him.}) 26... Nf6+ 27. Kf4 Rc4+ 28. Kf3 Ne4 29. Be1 Rf8 30. Ke2 Rxf5 $11 {Black has played very well and equalised, but the game isn't over yet!} 31. Ra5 Rg5 32. Kd3 d5 33. Ra2 Nd6 34. b6 Rc6 35. Bc3 Nb5 36. Ba1 Rxb6 37. Rf1 Nd6 38. Bc3 Ne4 39. Be1 Nd6 {Black shows that he's happy to repeat.} (39... Ke6 $5 $11 {is another good way to play.}) 40. Rf8 Rg4 41. h3 Re4 42. Raa8 d4 $5 {A very concrete solution that wasn't really necessary.} (42... Re6 43. Bc3 g6 $11) 43. Rfd8+ Kc7 44. Bd2 $5 {Showing some ambition.} (44. Rxd6 Rxe3+ 45. Kxd4 Rxe1 46. Rxb6 Kxb6 47. Ra5 g6 48. Rg5 Re6 $11 {is an immediate draw.}) 44... dxe3 45. Bxe3 Rb5 (45... Ra6 $5 {would have been cleaner, but perhaps Black didn't have time to evaluate the pawn ending correctly:} 46. Rxa6 bxa6 47. Rxd6 $5 (47. Rh8 Rxb4 48. Rxh5 Rb5 $11 {is probably a better practical choice for White.}) 47... Rxe3+ 48. Kxe3 Kxd6 {However, this is a very good practical chance for Black, as White only has one move that draws!} 49. h4 $3 (49. Kd4 $4 h4 {removes all of White's reserve tempi and wins the b4-pawn by force:} 50. Kc4 Kc6 51. Kc3 Kb5 52. Kb3 g6 $3 53. Kc3 Ka4 54. Kc4 g5 $1 55. Kc3 Ka3 56. Kc4 Kb2 57. Kd5 Kb3 58. Kc5 Kc3 $19) 49... Kd5 50. Kd3 Ke5 51. Ke3 $11) 46. Bc5 $1 Re6 47. Kc3 Kc6 48. Kb3 {The engine wants to sacrifice the exchange on c5 here but that is difficult for a human to voluntarily play!} Rg6 $2 (48... Rxc5 $5 49. bxc5 Kxc5 50. Rh8 g6 $44 {Black is able to hold this without too much trouble.}) (48... h4 $5 {is another solution.} 49. Bxd6 Rxd6 50. Rac8+ Kd5 $11) 49. Bxd6 $2 (49. Ra2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd8g8,Ga2c2,Gb3a4] would be good for White as Black's pieces are suddenly uncoordinated.}) 49... Rxd6 50. Rac8+ Kd5 51. Ka4 $5 {White goes for his last practical chance to win.} Rxd8 52. Rxd8+ Kc6 53. Rd6+ $5 Kxd6 54. Kxb5 {Black has two ways to hold the draw here.} Kc7 $4 (54... h4 $1 55. Kb6 Kd5 56. Kxb7 Kc4 57. Kc6 Kxb4 58. Kd5 Kc3 59. Ke4 Kd2 60. Kf4 Ke2 61. Kg5 Kf2 62. Kxh4 Kxg2 $11) (54... Kd5 $1 55. h4 Kd4 $3 {Black keeps the b-pawn in his sights.} (55... Ke4 $4 56. Kb6 $18 {wins for White.}) 56. Kb6 Kc4 57. Kxb7 Kxb4 58. Kc6 Kc4 59. Kd6 Kd4 60. Ke6 Ke4 61. Kf7 Kf4 62. Kxg7 Kg3 63. Kg6 Kxh4 $1 $11) 55. g4 $3 $18 {The only moves that wins and Black either missed this altogether or miss-evaluated it.} hxg4 56. hxg4 Kd7 57. Kb6 Kc8 58. g5 {Black will run out of good moves shortly.} Kd7 (58... g6 59. Ka7 $1 Kc7 60. b5 Kc8 61. b6 $18) 59. Kb5 (59. Kxb7 $18) 59... Kd6 {A slightly odd end to the game, so perhaps Black resigned a move earlier and this was the players analysing on the board after the game ended. Obviously, White could have captured the b-pawn on move 59 and won, but even the current position is still winning for White. A very hard fought game. Both sides have many interesting resources in the opening and the positions are unexplored and fascinating.} 1-0


[Event "Bundesliga 2021-22"]
[Site "Baden Baden GER"]
[Date "2022.05.29"]
[Round "10.3"]
[White "Maghsoodloo, Parham"]
[Black "Adams, Michael"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Kapnisis,S, TA"]
[ECO "D37"]
[WhiteElo "2701"]
[BlackElo "2698"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[EventDate "2022.03.05"]
