1. d4 {Nigel Davies Kuzmin, Alexey Kuzmin, Alexey} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 {[#]} 6. Bf4 $5 {Nigel Davies: 'This rare line has been played by Magnus Carlsen in a couple of games. Maghsoodloo has also used it, in both online and over the board games, so Adams would not have been surprised.' A rare line which has gained some attention mainly because Carlsen used it in a couple of cases. Maghsoodloo has used it in the past, both online and over the board games, so Adams shouldn't have been surprised.} c6 {Nigel Davies: 'Let's take a look at some plausible alternatives:'} ({Nigel Davies: 'a)'} 6... O-O 7. e3 c6 (7... Bf5 {Nigel Davies} 8. Qb3 Nc6 9. Qxb7 Nb4 10. Rc1 Nc2+ 11. Rxc2 Bxc2 12. Bxc7 {gives White more than enough for the sacrificed exchange.}) 8. Bd3 Re8 (8... Nh5 $5 9. Qc2 Nxf4 10. exf4 g6 11. h4 $13 {leads to sharp play} (11. O-O {(Nigel Davies) , with active play for the slightly compromised pawn structure. Nigel Davies: 'produces a structure I looked at in my November 2023 update, and a quite pleasant version for White. White's grip on e5 and easy play compensates him for his slightly weakened pawn structure.'})) 9. h3 Nbd7 10. Qc2 $14 {0-1 (31) Maghsoodloo,P (2699)-Gokerkan,C (2456) chess.com INT 2022 Nigel Davies: 'was better for White in Maghsoodloo, P (2699) - Gokerkan, C (2456), chess.com INT 2022.'}) ({Nigel Davies: 'b)'} 6... Bd6 {Nigel Davies: 'seems more attractive for White after'} 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 O-O 9. Qc2 $14 (9. Bd3 {Nigel Davies} Re8 10. h3 Nc6 11. O-O Ne4 12. Qb3 {etc.})) 7. e3 (7. Qc2 {The Carlsen way} g6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. h4 $5 a5 (11... Nb6 12. Ne5 Qc8 13. O-O-O Qe6 14. Kb1 Ne4 $13 {1/2 (51) Carlsen,M (2863)-Nakamura,H (2736) chess24.com INT 2020}) 12. Kf1 a4 13. a3 Qb6 14. Qc2 h5 15. Bg5 O-O 16. Ne5 Rfe8 $13 {0-1 (58) Carlsen,M (2863)-Aronian,L (2767) Stavanger NOR 2020}) 7... Bf5 {[#] Nigel Davies: 'Again let's see the alternatives:' Black grabs the chance to develop his bishop to f5 before white gets the chance to play Bd3. By the old standards black should be satisfied if he manages to develop his bishop to f5.} (7... Nh5 $5 8. h3 Nxf4 9. exf4 O-O 10. Bd3 Bd6 11. g3 $13 {[%cal Ye1f1,Yf1g2]}) ({b)} 7... Qb6 {(Nigel Davies) can be answered by the calm} 8. Qc2 {, for example} Bf5 9. Qxf5 Qxb2 10. Qc8+ Bd8 11. Rb1 Qxc3+ 12. Kd1 Ne4 13. Bg3 {leaves b7 under threat.}) 8. Nh4 $1 {Nigel Davies: 'The key move, which causes problems for Black.' White tries to remove black's bishop from the important b1-h7 diagonal.} Bg4 {Nigel Davies: 'There are other bishop moves here too, and all of them deserve further study:'} ({Nigel Davies: 'a)'} 8... Be4 9. Be2 Nbd7 (9... h6 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Nf5 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 g6 (12... O-O $2 13. Bd3 $18 {[%cal Yd1g4]}) 13. Ng3 $14) 10. O-O (10. f3 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bg3 O-O 13. O-O b5 {[%cal Ya7a6,Yc6c5] looks ok for black}) 10... O-O 11. h3 (11. f3 $5 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. e4 c5 $1 14. Kh1 cxd4 15. Qxd4 dxe4 16. Rad1 $5 $13 (16. fxe4 Bc5 17. Qd3 Qe7 $13)) 11... Re8 12. f3 Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. e4 c5 15. Nb5 $1 cxd4 16. Nc7 Bc5 {Nigel Davies: 'was Maghsoodloo, P (2701) - Oparin, G (2654), Toledo ESP 2021, and now'} 17. Kh1 (17. Bd3 $5 {Nigel Davies: 'was apparently White's best, with slightly the better of it.'}) 17... dxe4 18. Nxe8 Qxe8 19. fxe4 Ne5 $44 {1-0 (37) Maghsoodloo,P (2701)-Oparin,G (2654) Toledo ESP 2021}) ({Nigel Davies: 'b)'} 8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 (9. g4 $5 Nbd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. h4 $14) 9... hxg6 10. h4 (10. Be2 {Nigel Davies} Nh5 11. Be5 Nd7 12. O-O Nhf6 13. Bf4 Nh5 14. Bxh5 Rxh5 15. Rb1 {still leaves Black with some problems to solve because of his loss of castling rights.}) 10... Bd6 11. Qf3 {[%cal Yf1d3,Yg2g4] Appears to be quite pleasant for white}) ({Nigel Davies: 'c)'} 8... Be6 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. h3 $14 (10. Nf5 {(Nigel Davies) gets the bishop pair.})) 9. Qc2 {[#]} ({Nigel Davies: 'This is probably White's best, though'} 9. Be2 {Nigel Davies: 'is also playable as in Davies - Pal.'} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 g6 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. Bh6 Ng4 13. Bf4 Ngf6 14. O-O O-O 15. h3 Re8 $13 {1/2 (74) Yu Yangyi (2751)-Jakovenko,D (2719) Shenzhen CHN 2019}) 9... Nbd7 {Kuzmin, Alexey: 'After h3 the bishop will have to retreat on to е6, and the moves Qc2 and h3 are useful for White. That's why if Black does not play 9...Nh5, the manoeuvre 8...Bg4 will lose its sense. In this case playing 8...Be6 outright is more logically.'} ({Nigel Davies: 'There is a major alternative in'} 9... Nh5 {Nigel Davies: ', for example'} 10. h3 Be6 (10... Bc8 $5 {Might look strange but probably c8 is a better square than e6.}) 11. Nf3 Nxf4 12. exf4 g6 13. Bd3 Qd6 14. Ne2 (14. f5 $5) 14... Nd7 15. O-O {Nigel Davies: 'gave White compensation for his weakened pawns in Warmerdam, M (2613)-Michalik, P (2577) Prague CZE 2022.'} Nf6 $6 (15... O-O-O $1 {Castling long looks quite risky but probably the queenside is the safest place for the black king.} 16. b4 Kb8 17. a4 Nb6 $13) (15... O-O 16. f5 $16) 16. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (100) Warmerdam,M (2613)-Michalik,P (2577) Prague CZE 2022}) ({Nigel Davies: 'Another possibility is'} 9... g6 {Nigel Davies: 'for example'} 10. h3 Be6 11. Bd3 (11. Nf3 {Kuzmin, Alexey} Bf5 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. g4 $14) 11... O-O (11... Nh5 $5 12. Nf3 Nxf4 13. exf4 Bd6 14. g3 $13) 12. Nf3 {Kuzmin, Alexey: '' '' Kuzmin, Alexey: 'Maghsoodloo,P - Rychagov,A Blitz, Chess.com INT 2022'} Nbd7 13. O-O c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nd4 $14 {0-1 (51) Maghsoodloo,P (2716)-Rychagov,A (2549) chess.com INT 2022 Nigel Davies: 'was better for White at this stage in Maghsoodloo, P (2716) - Rychagov, A (2549), chess. com INT 2022.'}) (9... Ne4 {Kuzmin, Alexey Usually such a penetration is not good if Black can not reinforce the knight on е4.} 10. Nf3 (10. h3 $5 Bxh4 $6 (10... Be6 $14) 11. hxg4 Bxf2+ 12. Ke2 Bg3 13. Nxe4 Bxf4 14. exf4 dxe4 15. Qxe4+ Qe7 16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. Kf3 $16) 10... Nd6 (10... Qa5 $14) 11. Bd3 $16 {Smolik,J - Zhou,A Mamaia 2022}) 10. h3 Be6 (10... Bh5 $6 {Kuzmin, Alexey} 11. Bd3 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. O-O-O $16) 11. Nf3 {Nigel Davies: 'With Black's bishop having gone from the f5 square, White has a typical and rather pleasant version of this position type.' White has managed to kick black's bishop out of f5 and can probably claim a small advantage.} (11. Nf5 $6 {Kuzmin, Alexey Nigel Davies: 'seems less convincing after'} Bxf5 12. Qxf5 Ne4 $1 $132 13. Bd3 {Nigel Davies} g6 14. Qg4 Ndf6 15. Qe2 O-O 16. O-O Bd6 {, with an easy game for Black now.}) 11... Nf8 $6 {Nigel Davies: 'White has a good game after this move, but the alternatives don't look too attractive either:'} ({Nigel Davies: 'a)'} 11... O-O 12. Ng5 $14 h6 {Nigel Davies} 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Bd3 {gives White a useful pair of bishops.}) ({Nigel Davies: 'b)'} 11... h6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. a3 $14 {Nigel Davies: 'is a typical QGD Exchange, with White's choice of plans making life difficult for his opponent.'}) (11... Nh5 12. Bd3 (12. Bh2 g6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O a5 $1 {[%cal Yh5g7,Ye6f5] With a typical queen's gambit declined middlegame position} (14... Ng7 $6 15. b4 $1 Bxb4 16. Rfb1 $14)) 12... Nxf4 13. exf4 $14 {Nigel Davies: 'would again produce a structure I looked at in my November 2023 update, which looks especially awkward for Black because of his bishop on e6.'}) (11... g6 {Kuzmin, Alexey by analogy with the game Maghsoodloo - Kasimdzhanov was better.}) 12. Bd3 Ng6 13. Bh2 Nd7 $146 {Nigel Davies: 'Black hopes to make Nf3-e5 less attractive for White, whilst potentially bringing the knight to b6 and c4, should White start a minority attack with b2-b4. White seems to be better after other moves too, for example:' A move played in order to make Ne5 less attractive while the black knight is likely neading towards b6 in order to help against a possible minority attack.} ({Nigel Davies: 'a)'} 13... Bd6 14. Ne5 (14. O-O-O $5) (14. Ng5 {Nigel Davies} Bxh2 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bxg6+ hxg6 17. Qxg6+ Kf8 18. Rxh2 {wins a pawn for quite questionable compensation.}) 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. f4 Qh4+ 17. Qf2 Qxf2+ 18. Kxf2 {looks good for white}) ({Nigel Davies: 'b)'} 13... O-O 14. O-O Bd6 15. Ne5 {Kuzmin, Alexey: '' ''} Nd7 16. f4 {Nigel Davies: 'starts a typical Philidor type attack. None of this endears me to Black's position.'} f5 17. Kh1 {[%cal Yf1g1,Yg2g4] I like white's attacking potential.}) ({RR} 13... Bd6 14. Ne5 Ne7 15. f4 c5 16. f5 Bc8 17. Nb5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Ne4 19. Bxe4 Qa5+ 20. Qc3 Qxb5 21. Bd3 c4 22. f6 cxd3 23. fxe7 Be6 24. O-O Rc8 25. Qa3 Qc5 26. Qxd3 Qxe7 27. Qb5+ Qd7 28. Qb4 {Melnikov,F (2338)-Rychagov,A (2546) Sochi 2025 0-1 (61)}) 14. O-O O-O 15. Rab1 (15. Ne2 $5 {[%cal Ye2f4]}) 15... Re8 {[#]} (15... a5 {Nigel Davies: 'could be met by'} 16. a3 (16. Na4 {(Nigel Davies) , when} Nb6 {is good for White after} 17. Nc5 {.}) 16... Nb6 17. b4 $2 (17. Ne2 Bd6 $14) 17... axb4 18. axb4 Nc4 {is fine for black}) 16. b4 (16. Nd2 $5 {[%cal Yf2f4] is a way for white to take advantage of black's Re8. White's threat of f4 is quite annoying.} Ngf8 17. f4 (17. b4 $5) 17... f6 18. b4 $14) 16... Nb6 17. a4 {[#]} a6 $6 (17... Nc4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 {Nigel Davies: 'is unpleasant for Black but might have been his best shot. Now things start to get ugly.' Kuzmin, Alexey: 'was better although White had an advantage in this case too.'} 19. Rfd1 {is good for white but compared to what happenned in the game black can still fight back.}) 18. a5 $1 ({Nigel Davies: 'After'} 18. b5 $2 {Nigel Davies: 'Black has the typical'} cxb5 19. axb5 a5 $13 {Nigel Davies: ', with good counterplay.' Black is fine and the transfer of his knight to b6 makes perfect sense.}) 18... Nc8 {[#]} (18... Nc4 {Nigel Davies: 'would be met by'} 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. Na4 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5] Nigel Davies: ', though this might have been Black's best try.'}) 19. Na4 {Nigel Davies: 'A logical follow up to White's earlier play.' Although white's move is perfectly logical and gives white a substantial advantage there was a more concreet way to play.} ({Nigel Davies: 'Yet there was also a nice tactical shot with'} 19. b5 $1 {Kuzmin, Alexey: '!?' '!?' Nigel Davies: 'after which' Was a nice tactical shot to achieve the necessary breakthrough in the queenside.} {Nigel Davies: 'Or'} Qxa5 (19... cxb5 $6 20. Nxb5 axb5 21. Bc7 Qd7 22. Bxb5 $18 {[%csl Rd7]} Bf5 {Nigel Davies} 23. Bxd7 Bxc2 24. Rb2 {is simply winning for White.}) (19... axb5 20. Nxb5 $1 {Kuzmin, Alexey: '' ''} Nd6 21. Nxd6 Bxd6 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Rxb7 Rxa5 24. Rc1 $18 {Nigel Davies: ', and Black will struggle to defend his c6 pawn.'}) 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Na4 $18 {Nigel Davies: 'threatening Qxc6 for starters.'}) 19... Bd6 (19... Nd6 {Nigel Davies: 'would be met by'} 20. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Yf2f4]} (20. Nc5 {(Nigel Davies) , which is also very good for White.})) 20. Ne5 {Kuzmin, Alexey: '' '' Kuzmin, Alexey: 'White has a huge advantage.'} Nf8 {Nigel Davies: 'Preparing to play the logical ...f7-f6, but even this won't solve Black's problems.' Black tries to prepare f6 in order to kick white's knight out of e5 but this will not be enough to ease black's problems.} 21. Nc5 Rb8 22. Kh1 ({Nigel Davies: 'There was a case for the immediate'} 22. f4 $5 {Nigel Davies: 'for example'} f6 {[#]} 23. Bxa6 $1 fxe5 {Nigel Davies: 'is met by'} (23... Bxc5 24. bxc5 fxe5 25. f5 Bd7 26. dxe5 $18 {Nigel Davies: ', and Black has no answer to White's powerful pawn phalanx.'}) ({Nigel Davies: 'and'} 23... bxa6 {Nigel Davies: 'by'} 24. Nxc6 Qc7 25. Nxa6 $18 {Nigel Davies: ', both of which are winning for White.'}) 24. Nxb7 Qc7 25. Nxd6 (25. fxe5 {Nigel Davies}) 25... Nxd6 26. f5 $16) 22... Na7 $6 {Nigel Davies: 'Bringing the knight back to b5 should not have been Black's priority, but perhaps he underestimated the speed with White White's kingside play would develop.' Black should have kicked white's knight out of e5 before white gets the chance to play f4. Transfering black's knight to b5 shouldn't have been black's priority.} ({Nigel Davies: 'He had to kick back White's knights with'} 22... f6 {Nigel Davies: 'after which'} 23. Nxa6 $5 (23. Nf3 Bf7 $14 {Nigel Davies: 'gives Black a stable if inferior position.'}) 23... fxe5 24. Nxb8 e4 {Nigel Davies: 'is just rather murky.'} 25. Be2 Bxh2 26. Kxh2 Qc7+ 27. Kg1 Qxb8 28. b5 $16) 23. f4 f6 24. Nf3 Bf7 25. Rbe1 Nb5 {[#]} 26. g4 $1 $18 {Nigel Davies: '!' Nigel Davies: 'This simple kingside advance is impossible to meet because Black has no counterplay.' White's space advantage is enormous and makes it difficult for black to find squares for his pieces. Black has no counterplay and simply waits for white's final attack in the kingside in order to react.} Na3 (26... Bxc5 27. dxc5 {Nigel Davies: 'would not change anything.' Doesn't change much}) 27. Qc1 Nc4 {[#] Nigel Davies: 'Under normal circumstances this would be a great idea, but here it gives White the chance to push through with e3-e4.' Regrouping Nb5 to c4 is hardly better for black since white gets the chance to play e4} 28. e4 $1 Ne6 ({Nigel Davies: 'After'} 28... dxe4 {Nigel Davies: 'there follows'} 29. Bxc4 exf3 30. Bxf7+ Kxf7 31. Qc4+ {is game over} Kg6 {Nigel Davies} 32. f5+ Kh6 33. Rxe8 Qxe8 34. Bxd6 {etc.}) (28... b6 29. axb6 Qxb6 30. f5 $18) 29. Nxe6 (29. e5 $5 {Nigel Davies: 'would have been less convincing because of'} Bxc5 {Nigel Davies} 30. dxc5 fxe5 31. Nxe5 Nxe5 32. Rxe5 Rc8 {. Even this is good for White but not as convincing as the game.}) 29... Rxe6 {[#]} 30. e5 $1 {Nigel Davies: 'White correctly pushes his pawns in the kingside creating serious threats and pays no attention to what happens in the queenside.' White correctly pushes his pawns in the kingside creating serious threats and pays no attention to what happens in the queenside.} Bxb4 31. f5 Re7 32. Re2 Bxa5 {[#]} 33. g5 {Nigel Davies: 'One of several good moves.' White pawns dominate the kingside and the end is a matter of time.} (33. e6 $18 {Nigel Davies: 'was also winning for White.'}) 33... fxe5 34. dxe5 Bh5 35. e6 Bc7 36. f6 Bxh2 37. fxe7 Qxe7 38. Kxh2 Rf8 39. Kg2 1-0


