1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. exd5 Qxd5 (6... Nxd5 {is seen in this month's game Matlakov-Jumabayev.}) 7. Nb5 Na6 (7... Qd8 {was successful in the Archives game Vachier Lagrave-Caruana and hasn't been refuted at all, but hasn't been terribly popular since. Black's counterchances tend to be more limited than after 7...Na6.}) 8. Nc3 Qd8 ({The almost equally popular} 8... Qd6 {is seen in Draskovic-Meier and other Archives games. Kovalev himself tried} 9. a3 {(White's most successful move)} Bd7 10. Nc4 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 Nc5 12. Nc3 Na4 13. Nxa4 Bxa4 14. b3 Bd7 $5 (14... Bc6 $11) (14... Bb5 15. Nd6+ Bxd6 16. Bxb5+ Ke7 $11) 15. Bb2 O-O-O 16. Bd3 Nd5 17. O-O-O f6 18. Be4 $14 {Kovalev,V (2655)-Nisipeanu,L (2672) Dortmund 2018}) 9. a3 Bd7 {This is playable, but reduces control over d6 and I don't think it equalizes.} ({a)} 9... Be7 {is more commonly played, when one example is} 10. Qf3 Nc7 11. Bd3 Ncd5 12. Nxd5 (12. Nde4 $5) 12... exd5 (12... Qxd5 13. Ne4 Bd7) 13. O-O O-O 14. h3 Be6 (14... Bd6 15. Nb3 Re8) 15. Nb3 Nd7 16. Nd4 Nc5 17. c3 (17. Rd1 $1 Nxd3 18. Rxd3 $14) 17... Nxd3 18. Qxd3 {with approximate equality, Kollars,D (2607) -Meier,G (2628) Dortmund 2021}) ({b)} 9... Nc7 {has scored okay in a small sample space, but is a little passive and hasn't caught on.}) ({RR} 9... Be7 10. Qf3 O-O 11. Bxa6 {1-0 (11) Carlsen,M (2881)-Caruana,F (2791) Flor/Fjaere 2014}) 10. Nc4 ({RR} 10. Be2 Bc6 11. Bf3 Qc7 12. O-O Be7 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. Nc4 Rad8 16. Ne5 Qc8 17. Bg5 Nc7 18. Ng4 Nfd5 19. Bxe7 Nxe7 20. Rad1 Ng6 21. Qe3 a6 22. Ne5 Ne7 23. Qf3 f6 24. Nd3 Ncd5 {Kolosowski,M (2444)-Maghsoodloo,P (2701) Warsaw 2021 ½-½ (120)}) 10... Be7 $146 ({A previous Kovalev game went} 10... Bc6 11. Qxd8+ (11. Bf4 Be7 12. Ne5 $14) 11... Rxd8 12. Ne5 $14 Nb8 13. Be3 a6 {Kovalev,V (2648)-Erigaisi,A (2559) chess.com INT 2020 and now} 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Bd3 {leaves White with a small advantage due to the bishop pair.}) ({RR} 10... Bc6 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Ne5 Nb8 13. Be3 a6 14. Bb6 Rc8 15. Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 18. O-O-O Ke7 19. Be2 Rhc8 20. Bf3 R8c7 21. Rhe1 Nbd7 22. Re3 Ne5 23. Be2 g5 24. Rd4 h5 25. h3 {Kovalev,V (2648)-Erigaisi,A (2559) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (62)}) ({RR} 10... Qc7 11. Qf3 Bc6 12. Qg3 Qxg3 13. hxg3 Rd8 14. Na5 Nb8 15. Be3 a6 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Bd3 Ne5 18. Be2 Rc8 19. Bd4 Ned7 20. Bf3 Rc7 21. g4 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. g5 Ng8 24. b4 Nd7 25. Ne4 {Vaz,E (2430)-Viani,A (2378) Bengaluru 2025 1-0 (48)}) ({RR} 10... Nc5 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Qxd6 Qe7 13. Qe5 Bc6 14. Be3 Ncd7 15. Qg5 O-O 16. O-O-O Rfe8 17. f3 a6 18. h4 e5 19. h5 h6 20. Qg3 Kh8 21. Be2 Nc5 22. Bc4 Na4 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Bxd5 Nxd5 25. Rxd5 {Ivanchuk,V (2733)-Hambleton,A (2446) Edmonton 2015 ½-½ (37)}) 11. Nd6+ (11. Ne5 {also keeps a little pressure on Black, e.g.,} O-O 12. g3 {and Bg2.}) 11... Kf8 12. Be3 $5 (12. Bf4 Bc6 13. Ndb5 $14) 12... Bc6 13. Ndb5 (13. Nc4) 13... Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Bc5 $2 (14... Nc5 $1 {recentralizes, when} 15. Nd4 Na4 16. Nxa4 Bxa4 17. b3 Bd7 {is equal.}) 15. Nd4 Nc7 (15... Be8 $4 16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. Nxe6+ fxe6 18. Bxc5+) (15... Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Nc7 17. f3 $16) 16. Nxc6 Bxe3 17. Na5 {A strong move, but} (17. fxe3 $1 bxc6 18. Rd6 {is more one-sided:} Ncd5 19. Rxc6 Nxe3 20. Kd2 Nxf1+ 21. Rxf1 $16) 17... Bb6 $1 18. Nxb7 Rb8 (18... Ke7 $1 19. Nd6 Rhd8 20. Nc4 Bd4 {gives some counterplay.}) 19. Nd6 Ba5 $2 (19... Ke7) 20. b4 Rxb4 $2 {The point, but it falls short.} (20... Bb6 21. Na4 Rd8 22. Nxb6 (22. c4 $5 Bxf2+ $1 23. Kxf2 Rxd6 {, although} 24. Be2 $1 {is still quite good for White}) 22... axb6 23. Nb5 {and White has material and position in his favor.}) 21. axb4 Bxb4 22. Ndb5 $1 Nxb5 {Nothing else works:} (22... Nfd5 23. Rb1 $1 Nxb5 24. Rxb4 Nxb4 25. Bxb5 Nxc2+ 26. Kd2 $18) (22... Ncd5 23. Bc4 Nxc3 24. Rd8+ Ke7 25. Rxh8 Nxb5+ 26. Kf1 $18) 23. Rd8+ Ke7 24. Rxh8 Nxc3 25. Bd3 a5 26. O-O {White is too exchanges up, and can always give one back for the a-pawn. The rest of the game is fairly clear:} g6 27. Ra1 h5 28. Ra8 Nfd5 29. Ra7+ Kf6 30. g3 a4 31. R1xa4 Nxa4 32. Rxa4 Bc3 33. Ra7 Bd4 34. Rd7 Bc5 35. Kg2 Nc3 36. Rc7 Bd4 37. f4 Nd5 38. Rd7 Bc5 39. Kf3 Bg1 40. Be4 Ne7 41. h3 Bc5 42. Rc7 Bb6 43. Rb7 Bc5 44. Rb5 Bd6 45. c4 Nc8 46. c5 Bc7 47. Rb7 Ba5 48. Bc6 Ne7 49. Be8 e5 50. fxe5+ Ke6 51. Ke4 g5 52. g4 (52. Bd7# $1) 52... hxg4 53. hxg4 f6 54. exf6 Kxf6 55. Bd7 Ng6 56. Bf5 Ne5 57. Kd5 1-0


