1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Bd3 d5 {There are quite a few lines in the Nimzo-Indian where Black can transpose into the Botvinnik-Capablanca Variation, so if you're willing to play the positions it's a useful resource to have at hand. is another move-order.} (7... Nc6 {aims for the main line of the Saemisch.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne2 b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. f3 {Grischuk chooses the main line.} ({White can head for a different type of position with} 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. c4 {- see the notes to Rakhmanov,A-Sagar,S/Teplice 2015.}) 11... Re8 12. Ng3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Bb2 h5 (14... c4 {is the main alternative.} 15. Qe2 (15. Qd2 b5 16. Rae1 {- see the notes to Kryvoruchko, Y-Klekowski,M/Wroclaw 2017}) 15... b5 $1 (15... h5 16. Qf2 $1 {is promising for White, as we saw in Le Quang Liem-Aleksandrov,A/Khanty-Mansiysk 2019. It seems, however, that Black can allow e3-e4, as correspondence games have shown.}) 16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Nxe4 $1 {Without this idea, White would have an overwhelming positional advantage.} 18. Nxe4 Qd5 19. Rf4 (19. Rae1 f5 20. Qh5 Rxe4 21. Rxe4 Qxe4 22. Qxf5 Qxf5 23. Rxf5 a6 24. Bc1 Ne7 {and Black held in Amico,R-Catozzi,M/ICCF email 2019}) 19... f5 20. Nf6+ $1 gxf6 21. Qf2 Ne7 22. a4 Rab8 (22... a6 {is more natural but after} 23. Ba3 $1 {Black's position is getting stretched}) 23. Ba3 Qd7 $1 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25. Rxf5 bxa4 26. Rxf6 a3 $1 27. Rf1 Rb6 28. Rf5 Qe3 {(�-� Fuchs,J-Goreczny,G/LSS email 2019)} 29. Rf8+ (29. Rg5+ Rg6) 29... Rxf8 30. Qxe3 Rxf1+ 31. Kxf1 Rb1+ 32. Kf2 a2 {forces White to give perpetual check.}) 15. Rae1 (15. e4 {remains a critical alternative.} c4 {is another option for Black, and this has also held in correspondence games:} (15... h4 16. Nf5 {looks dangerous, but with precise defence Black is okay.} dxe4 17. fxe4 cxd4 ({as noted before,} 17... Rxe4 18. Nxg7 Ne5 19. Qh3 $1 {favours White}) 18. cxd4 Rxe4 19. Nh6+ (19. Nxg7 $5 Nxd4 20. Kh1 $1 h3 $1 (20... Rg4 $2 21. Rad1 $18) 21. Qxh3 Kxg7 22. Qg3+ Kf8 23. Qh3 (23. Rad1 $5) 23... Kg7 24. Qg3+ Kf8 {1/2-1/2 (24) Lafortune,P (2021)-Sileika,A (2086) ICCF email 2020}) 19... gxh6 20. Rxf6 Qxf6 $1 (20... Qd5 21. Rd6 Qxd6 22. Qxe4 Rd8 23. Qxh4 $16 {Kasabasic, D-Bourgoin,C/LSS email 2011}) 21. Qxe4 Qg6 $1 22. Qxh4 Re8 23. Qf2 Qh5 24. Qg3+ (24. Rc1 Re2) 24... Qg5 25. Qf3 Qe3+ 26. Qxe3 Rxe3 $11 {Depasse,J-Wosch,A/LSS email 2019.}) 16. Qc2 (16. Qe3 dxe4 17. fxe4 h4 18. Nf5 Nxe4 19. Qf3 Qf6 20. Rad1 Ng5 21. Qh5 Qg6 $1 $11 {Walther,J-Egoshin,G/ICCF email 2018}) 16... h4 17. Nf5 dxe4 18. fxe4 Nxe4 (18... Rxe4 $2 19. Nxg7 $1 Kxg7 20. Rxf6 $1 {favours White}) 19. Rf4 Nd6 20. Raf1 $1 (20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Rxh4 Qg6 $1 $11) (20. Rg4 Nxf5 21. Qxf5 Ne7 $1) 20... Ne7 $1 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. Rxf7 h3 ({or} 22... Qe6 23. Qf2 h3 24. Qg3 Ng6 25. R7f6 {�-� Wilkinson, J-Martins,E/ICCF email 2019}) 23. Bc1 Qe6 24. R7f3 Rf8 25. Qf2 Rxf3 26. Qxf3 Nd5 27. gxh3 Re8 $11 {Foulds,E-Ilyasov,A/ICCF email 2019.}) 15... h4 (15... g6 16. e4 $1 h4 17. Nh1 Nh5 18. Nf2 $1 {looks promising for White, as noted in the analysis of Gagarin,V-Romanov,E/Stockholm 2014.}) 16. Nf5 h3 $1 {We first looked at this move in the notes to Szabo,G-Paschall,W/Zalakaros 2016, and since then there have been quite a few new games reaching this position.} (16... Nh5 $6 17. e4 $1 {was good for White in Szabo,G-Paschall,W/Zalakaros 2016.}) 17. Re2 $146 {This is a novelty, but the idea of enabling a rook recapture on g2 is quite a natural one. Here's a summary of alternatives:} (17. e4 hxg2 18. Rf2 Ne7 19. e5 Nh5 20. Rxg2 Nxf5 21. Qxf5 Qh4 22. Rf1 g6 23. f4 Ng7 $11 {Ojeda,J-Roberts,A/ICCF email 2018.}) (17. gxh3 cxd4 18. cxd4 Ne7 $1 {looks perfectly okay for Black. After, for example,} 19. Ng3 Qd7 20. h4 Qh3 {Black gets good counterplay.}) (17. g4 Ne7 $1 18. Ng3 Rc8 (18... Ng6 $5 {planning ... Nh4 or} 19. e4 Nf4 20. Qd2 Ng2) 19. Bc1 (19. e4 $5) 19... Qd7 20. g5 Nh7 21. e4 cxd4 22. cxd4 Ng6 23. Be3 Nh4 $1 {and Black has managed to make it look like White has over-extended, Esipenko,A-Maghsoodloo,P/Chess.com 2020}) (17. Ng3 {has been played in numerous correspondence games. Retreating isn't the most obvious choice, but it's actually useful prophylaxis against ...Ne7, after which White usually retreats anyway as a knight exchange typically favours Black. Even so, Black has been holding okay. For example,} hxg2 18. Kxg2 Ne7 19. e4 Ng6 $1 20. Bc1 dxe4 21. fxe4 Qd7 22. Kg1 {(preparing Nf5)} (22. Rxf6 $5 gxf6 23. Nf5 Re5 $1 (23... cxd4 $2 24. Qh3 $1 {wins}) 24. Qh3 Rxf5 25. exf5 Qxf5 $1 26. Qxf5 Nh4+ 27. Kg3 Nxf5+ 28. Kg4 Ng7 29. d5 Rd8 30. Rd1 f5+ 31. Kf3 f6 $11 {Shaw,S-Wojcik,W/ICCF email 2018.}) (22. Nf5 cxd4 23. cxd4 Nxe4 $1 24. Rxe4 Qd5 25. Ng3 f5 $1 26. Rxf5 Nh4+ 27. Kg1 Nxf5 28. Rxe8+ Rxe8 29. Nxf5 Re6 {and White is unable to utilise his small material advantage, Schroeder,C-Fric, L/FICGS email 2019.}) 22... cxd4 23. cxd4 Rad8 24. Nf5 Ne7 25. Nxg7 $5 (25. Nxe7+ Qxe7 26. e5 Qe6 27. Rf4 Nd5 28. Rh4 Qg6+ 29. Qxg6 fxg6 30. Rg4 Nf6 31. Rxg6 Rxd4 $11 {Kulick,N-Germanes,R/FICGS email 2017}) 25... Kxg7 26. e5 Ng6 $1 (26... Nfd5 $2 27. Rxf7+ $1 Kxf7 28. e6+ Qxe6 29. Qh7+ Kf6 30. Qh6+ Ng6 31. Bg5+ $1 Kf5 32. Rxe6 Rxe6 33. Bxd8 {looks winning for White}) 27. exf6+ Kg8 {and White's open king offers Black enough counterplay.}) ({RR} 17. e4 hxg2 18. Kxg2 cxd4 19. cxd4 Ne7 20. Ng3 Ng6 21. Bc1 Rc8 22. Kh1 Nh7 23. e5 Nh4 24. f4 Qc7 25. Rf2 Nf6 26. f5 Ne4 27. Rff1 Qc2 28. Qxc2 Rxc2 29. Nxe4 dxe4 30. Rxe4 Nxf5 31. Bg5 g6 {Lazavik,D (2577)-Najer,E (2623) Sochi 2025 1-0 (40)}) ({RR} 17. g4 Ne7 18. Ng3 Rc8 19. Bc1 Qd7 20. g5 Nh7 21. e4 cxd4 22. cxd4 Ng6 23. Be3 Nh4 24. Rc1 Rxc1 25. Bxc1 Rc8 26. Bd2 Nf8 27. exd5 Qxd5 28. Qe4 Qa2 29. Qxh4 Qxd2 30. Qxh3 Rc2 31. Nf5 Ng6 {Esipenko,A (2682)-Maghsoodloo,P (2676) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (38)}) ({RR} 17. Ng3 hxg2 18. Kxg2 cxd4 19. cxd4 Rc8 20. e4 Na5 21. e5 Nh7 22. f4 Qd7 23. f5 Qa4 24. Re2 Qb3 25. Qa6 Rc2 26. Rff2 Rxe2 27. Rxe2 Ng5 28. Rf2 Ne4 29. Nxe4 dxe4 30. Qxa7 Nc4 31. Bc1 e3 {Shuvalov,E (2038)-Oro,F (2316) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (39)}) 17... Rc8 ({Clearly} 17... hxg2 $2 {is no longer desirable, because} 18. Rxg2 {activates the rook.}) ({However, there's no reason not to delay the typical ...Ne7 plan:} 17... cxd4 18. cxd4 Ne7 $1 19. Ng3 Rc8 {intending} 20. e4 Ng6 $1) ({Or} 17... Ne7) 18. e4 $1 {No further preparation is needed for this advance.} cxd4 19. cxd4 Ne7 $1 {There's no alternative. Black needs to deal with the positional threat of e4-e5.} 20. e5 (20. Nxe7+ $1 Qxe7 21. e5 Qe6 $1 (21... Nh5 22. f4 $1) 22. Ref2 $1 {Black is unable to blockade on the light squares.} Nh5 23. f4 Qg4 24. f5 $1 {favours White} ({whereas} 24. Qxh3 $2 Qxh3 25. gxh3 f5 $1 {favours Black!})) 20... Nxf5 21. Qxf5 Qd7 $1 {A crucial resource for Black, without which White simply plays Qxh3.} 22. g4 (22. Qxh3 Qxh3 23. gxh3 Nh5 $1 {is fine for Black. Notice that} 24. f4 {can be met very effectively by} f5 $1 $17 {fixing a weakness on f4.}) (22. Qd3 {is met by} Nh5 $1 23. f4 Qg4 $1 24. g3 (24. f5 $2 Nf4) 24... Rc6 ({or} 24... Nf6 25. f5 Ne4) 25. f5 Rec8 {with strong counterplay.}) (22. Qg5 Nh7 23. Qh5 Rc6 $1 {is also fine for Black, e.g.} 24. Qxh3 Qxh3 25. gxh3 Ng5 $1 26. Kg2 (26. h4 $2 Nh3+ 27. Kh1 Nf4) 26... Ne6 27. f4 f5 $1 28. exf6 $2 Nxf4+ $1) 22... Qxf5 23. gxf5 Nh5 24. f4 {We've reached a sharp endgame with imbalances but overall roughly level chances.} Rc4 25. Re3 $6 Rc2 (25... Nf6 $1 26. Rxh3 Ne4 {and Black's dominant knight is worth more than White's extra pawn. After Maghsoodloo's choice, the endgame remained easier for Black to play. Both sides' moves were likely affected by time pressure, and Maghsoodloo eventually prevailed.}) 26. Rxh3 g6 27. Bc1 Ng7 28. fxg6 fxg6 29. Be3 Nf5 30. Bf2 Rec8 31. Rd3 R8c3 32. Rfd1 Kf7 33. Kf1 Ke6 34. Ke1 Ng7 35. Rg3 Rxg3 36. hxg3 Kf5 37. Rd2 Rc3 38. Ra2 Ne6 39. Kd2 Rf3 40. Ke2 Ke4 41. a4 Rc3 42. a5 $2 b5 $1 43. a6 b4 44. Rb2 b3 45. Kd2 Rf3 46. Ke2 Rd3 47. Rd2 Rc3 48. Kd1 Kf3 (48... Rc6) 49. Be1 Re3 50. Bf2 Rc3 51. Be1 Ke4 52. Bf2 (52. Re2+ $1 Re3 53. Rxe3+ Kxe3 54. Kc1 $11) 52... g5 53. fxg5 Nxg5 54. Re2+ Kf3 (54... Kd3 $1 55. e6 Nxe6 56. Rxe6 b2 {wins.}) 55. Be1 Rd3+ 56. Rd2 Re3 57. Rf2+ Kxg3 58. Re2+ Kf3 59. Rxe3+ Kxe3 60. Bc3 Ne4 61. Bb2 Ng5 62. Kc1 Kd3 63. Kb1 Ne6 64. Ba1 Kc4 65. Kc1 (65. Bb2 $11) 65... Kb5 (65... Nc7 $1) 66. Kd2 (66. Bc3 $1 $11) 66... Kb4 67. Bb2 Nc7 $1 68. Kd3 Nxa6 69. e6 Nc7 70. e7 a5 71. Bc3+ Ka3 72. Bxa5 b2 0-1


