1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 {This is regarded as Black's most solid reply to the queen check. The resulting positions, in the mainline, don't give Black many hopes to play for a win, but in this game Tari confounds these expectations! We have also looked at Black's alternatives:} (5... c6 {- see Yu Yangyi - Di Li and earlier games in the Archives.}) (5... Nbd7 {is covered in Nepomniachtchi-Alekseenko and other games.}) 6. Qxc4 c5 7. Ne5 {White secures the bishop pair.} Qc8 {The best spot for the queen.} (7... Qc7 $6 {leaves the queen more exposed to White's pieces and after} 8. d4 Bd6 9. Na3 a6 10. Bf4 {White had pressure in Ponkratov-Inarkiev, which is analyzed in the Archives.}) 8. Qd3 Bc6 $5 {A rare choice, which has been tried in a few blitz/online games, but much less common than:} (8... Nc6 {Now after the typical moves} 9. Nxd7 Nxd7 10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. O-O Rd8 13. Nc3 Nf6 {the position is analyzed in Anton Guijarro-Adams in the Archives. Here we see an advantage of Tari's move order. Adams used two tempi on ...Nf6-d7-f6, while in the main game, Black avoids this loss of time for a net gain of one tempo  (if I'm counting correctly!).}) 9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10. Nc3 {The challenge for White is that, with routine development, he will be a tempo down on a line that is already extremely solid for Black. So the idea of doubling Black's c-pawns is, therefore, a critical test of Black's move order. Perhaps it is better to keep options open for the b1-knight, and instead go for:} (10. Qb5 {when Black can try:} h5 (10... Nd5 11. Nc3 Qd7 12. O-O Be7 {and now} 13. e3 $5 {looks interesting.} (13. b3 O-O 14. Nxd5 exd5 {was OK for Black in Donchenko,A (2624) -Bluebaum,M (2511) Playchess.com INT 2020 0-1 (70)}) 13... O-O 14. Rd1 {and after the sample line} a6 15. Qe2 Rad8 16. d4 cxd4 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. exd4 {White's bishop pair yield a slight pull.}) (10... Be7 11. Bxc6+ (11. Nc3 O-O {would transpose to the main game}) 11... bxc6 12. Qa4 e5 13. d3 O-O 14. O-O {is an improved version of the game for White, since the b1-knight can be developed via the d2-square and has a better perspective than in the game.}) 11. h4 {the insertion of the h-pawn moves appears to favour White. Now} Be7 12. d3 O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qc4 Ng4 15. Nd2 Rb8 16. Qc2 Bf6 17. Nc4 Ne5 18. Nd6 Qd8 19. Ne4 {and White has strong pressure on the doubled c-pawns, Donchenko,A (2658)-Nisipeanu,L (2657) Bad Wiessee 2020 1-0 (31). Again note the advantage of the Nb1-d2-e4 route, which White did not have available after 10 Nc3.}) 10... Be7 11. Qb5 {White decides to pursue the capture on c6. Instead:} (11. O-O O-O 12. b3 Rd8 13. Qb1 Nd5 14. Nxd5 (14. Bb2 {is similar to Anton-Adams - see the note to Black's 8th move.} Qd7) 14... exd5 15. Bb2 Qe6 16. e3 Bf6 17. Rc1 b6 {with equal chances, Nepomniachtchi,I (2792)-Aronian,L (2781) Paris 2021 1-0 (62)}) 11... O-O {would transpose to the main game} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qa4 e5 {Opening the path for Black's queen to press on the kingside light squares.} 14. d3 Rb8 $146 ({RR} 14... Nd5 15. O-O Nb6 16. Qa5 Qe6 17. b3 f5 18. Ba3 Nd7 19. Rac1 h5 20. Qa6 Nb6 21. Na4 f4 22. Bxc5 fxg3 23. hxg3 Bxc5 24. Nxc5 Qg4 25. Qb7 Nd5 26. Qd7 Rf5 27. e4 Ne3 28. Rce1 Nxf1 29. Qxf5 {Santos Latasa,J (2647)-Bluebaum,M (2670) Chess.com INT 2023 1-0 (72)}) ({RR} 14... Rd8 15. Be3 Rb8 16. Rb1 Rd4 17. Qxa7 Bf8 18. Qa3 c4 19. Qa4 Rb4 20. Qc2 cxd3 21. exd3 Rd8 22. O-O Qh3 23. f3 h5 24. Rfd1 Qf5 25. Qe2 Nd5 26. Nxd5 cxd5 27. b3 Rb7 28. Rbc1 d4 29. Bf2 {Deac,B (2700)-Gholami Orimi,M (2422) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (63)}) 15. Qc2 $6 {This move uses valuable time and looks passive. White should consider:} (15. O-O Nd5 16. Qc4 {with a roughly balanced position. Note that} Rb4 $2 {fails to} 17. Nxd5) 15... Qf5 {This is fine, but Black has more direct options:} (15... Qh3 {preventing short castling or}) (15... c4 $5 16. dxc4 Qh3 17. Bg5 Rfd8 {keeping White's king in the centre}) 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. dxe4 Qh3 {Now White has to evacuate the king and defend the weak kingside, while earlier thoughts of nice positional pressure on the doubled c-pawns are off the agenda for now.} 18. Bd2 Qg2 19. Rf1 Qxh2 20. O-O-O Qh3 {Black can save this tempo with another useful move such as:} (20... h6 21. Qc4 Rfd8 {and Black is for choice.}) 21. Qc4 Rfd8 22. Bc3 Qg2 23. Kc2 {A step in the wrong direction. White should seek activity with:} (23. Bxe5 {for example} Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Re8 (24... Rb4 $2 25. Qa6 {exposes Black's weak back rank}) 25. Rd7 Qxf2 26. Rxa7 {with an approximate balance.}) 23... Bf6 24. b3 $2 {Now White's kingside pawns start to drop.} (24. Rde1 {doesn't look pleasant, but holds the fort for now.}) 24... h5 {The immediate} (24... Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Qxf2 {as more accurate.}) 25. a4 (25. Rde1 {was again called for.}) 25... Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Qxf2 {Black is well on top, being a pawn up with the g3-pawn also weak.} 27. Rd7 Bg5 {Neatly defending the f7-pawn.} 28. Qd3 {Or:} (28. Bxe5 Rd8 29. Rxd8+ {trades rooks but after} Bxd8 30. Bd6 Bg5 31. Bxc5 Qxg3 32. Bxa7 Qf4 {should still win for Black.}) 28... Be3 29. Bxe5 Re8 30. Bb2 (30. Bc7 Qg1 {threatens mate and} 31. Qd1 Rxe4 {picks off another pawn}) 30... Qxg3 {Now the h-pawn runs through and can't be stopped.} 31. Rxa7 h4 32. Re7 Rxe7 33. Qd8+ Kh7 34. Qxe7 Qg4 35. Kd3 h3 36. Bxg7 Qxg7 37. Qh4+ Qh6 38. Qe7 Qh5 0-1


