{[%evp 9,51,13,22,2,8,4,0,-20,-8,-1,-1,-1,58,56,62,55,75,68,70,10,55,50,62,52,63,29,68,56,129,83,162,157,169,148,210,178,285,257,385,353,414,406,445,433] E46: Nimzo-Indian: Rubinstein: 4 e3 0-0 5 Ne2 without early Bd3} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 {[%cal Bc1d2,Bd2c3,Bc3d4][%mdl 32]} b6 (5... d5 6. a3 Be7 7. Nf3 c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qc2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Be7 12. Ng5 h6 13. h4 Qc7 14. Be2 Rd8 15. Rc1 Nf8 16. Nge4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Qxc2 18. Rxc2 Bd7 19. Bb4 Bxb4+ 20. axb4 {½-½ 6. Dingtermezzo!-** Game 14 Zwischenzug! A Comprehensive Guide to I 2023}) 6. Nge2 $146 {What's this? It looks like Maghsoodloo is taking the avoidance of doubled c-pawns to a new level, with a bizarre cocktail of Bd2 and Nge2. The justification, I guess, is that Nge2 is known to be quite effective in ...b6 lines, so it should always be a consideration after ...b6 even if White has already played Bd2 or Qc2.} (6. Bd3 Bb7 (6... d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nf3 c5 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 c4 11. Bc2 Bg4 12. Qb1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nc6 14. Ba4 Ne7 15. Rg1 a5 16. Ke2 Rb8 17. Qe1 Qd6 18. Bc2 Nc6 {4.e3,B  2021}) 7. Nf3 {reaches Bd2 main lines} c5 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Qe2 Nf6 12. a3 Be7 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. Rad1 a6 15. Rfe1 h6 16. Bf4 b5 17. Ne5 Nd5 18. Bd2 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Qd5 21. Qg3 Bd6 22. Qh3 {Nimzo Indian-9.ed4 d5 10.cd5 Survey 2020} f5 23. Be2 {Bandeira,M-Billot,D (ch) India 1988}) ({and} 6. Nf3 {is another common move order - see games in the archives.}) 6... Ba6 {This move is a novelty here, but the idea is well known from the line 4...b6 5 Nge2 Ba6.} (6... Bb7 7. a3 Be7 $1 {looks like a sensible option for Black. This looks like a favourable version, for Black, of the line 4...b6 5 Nge2 Bb7 6 a3 Be7, where the extra moves ...0-0 and Bd2 help Black more than White. For one thing, the thematic d4-d5 lacks the support of the queen here.} 8. Nf4 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 ({perhaps this is too ambitious and White should settle for} 10. Bd3 c5 11. O-O $11) 10... c5 $1 11. bxc5 bxc5 12. Rb1 Bc6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 {[%cal Od5d4]} 14. Bb5 d4 $1 {with active counterplay for Black,Tomescu,V-Gordon,S/Porto San Giorgio 2008.}) (6... d5 7. a3 Bd6 {is another logical response, reaching a common Reshevsky Variation position with the added Bd2 and ...b6. While ...b6 prevents the c4-c5 option, which is certainly a positive for Black, it's also worth noting that ...b6 isn't the most natural course for Black if White creates the Carlsbad structure with} 8. cxd5 exd5 {Even so, Black should be able to make this work, e.g.} 9. Rc1 a6 10. Ng3 Re8 11. Bd3 c5 12. O-O Nc6) ({RR} 6... Bb7 7. a3 Be7 8. Ng3 c5 9. Rc1 cxd4 10. exd4 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. Bg5 Nc6 14. Nce2 h6 15. Be3 Nd5 16. O-O f5 17. Nh5 Bd6 18. Bc4 Qh4 19. Nhf4 Bxf4 20. Nxf4 Nxf4 21. g3 {Maghsoodloo,P (2716)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2626) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1 (32)}) ({RR} 6... d5 7. a3 Be7 8. Ng3 c5 9. cxd5 cxd4 10. exd4 Nxd5 11. Be2 Nc6 12. Be3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Bg5 14. Qd3 Bb7 15. O-O Rc8 16. Rad1 Na5 17. Bf3 Bxf3 18. Rxf3 Nc4 19. Rb1 Ne5 20. Qe2 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 {Pham,L (2348)-Vokhidov,S (2645) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1 (55)}) ({RR} 6... Bb7 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Nxc3 c5 9. dxc5 bxc5 10. f3 d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Bb5 d4 14. exd4 cxd4 15. Ne2 Qb6 16. Qa4 Nc5 17. Qxd4 Rac8 18. Bb4 Rfd8 19. Qf2 Qxb5 20. Rxc5 Rxc5 21. Qxc5 {Maghsoodloo,P (2695)-Mitrabha,G (2515) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1 (46)}) 7. Ng3 (7. a3 Bxc3 $1 8. Nxc3 d5 {looks okay for Black.}) 7... d5 8. Qf3 $146 {The position is equal.} ({RR} 8. cxd5 Bxf1 9. Rxf1 exd5 10. Rc1 c5 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 c4 13. Qf3 Nc6 14. Kd2 a5 15. Qf4 b5 16. Ke2 b4 17. Bd2 Re8 18. f3 Qb6 19. Kf2 Re6 20. Nf5 Rae8 21. g4 g6 22. Nh6+ Kg7 {Badacsonyi,S (2298)-Vijayakumar,R (2172) Leamington Spa 2024 ½-½ (35)}) 8... c5 (8... c6 $1 {breaks the pin and enables Black to capture on c4.} 9. cxd5 {and Bxa6 should not be overlooked} Bxf1 10. Kxf1 Bxc3 $1 ({not falling for the trick} 10... cxd5 {[%eval 69,21] 10...Bxc3 -0.17} 11. Nxd5 $1) 11. Bxc3 cxd5 {looks perfectly reasonable for Black.}) (8... Bxc4 $2 9. Bxc4 a6 10. O-O $18) 9. a3 $1 {As usual in Bd2 lines, a2-a3 is a logical response to ...c5.} Bxc3 10. Bxc3 {[#]} cxd4 {[%eval 58,22]} ({It's not an obvious choice, but} 10... Bb7 $1 {prevents discovered attack ideas involving cxd5 and prepares ...Nc6 or ...Nbd7. This seems to be okay for Black, for example} 11. Rd1 (11. dxc5 {[%eval -40,19] 11.Qf4 0.02} d4 $1 {is the idea:} 12. Qxb7 dxc3 13. Rd1 {Wards off Qd2+} Nbd7 $1) (11. Qf4 cxd4 12. Qxd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4 Nc6) 11... Qe7) (10... Bb7 $11 {[%eval -1,21]}) 11. Bxd4 $14 Nbd7 {Naiditsch sacrifices a pawn to gain some activity, and this looks to be Black's best bet here.} 12. cxd5 {White is more active.} Bxf1 13. dxe6 $1 {This zwischenzug wins a pawn.} (13. Rxf1 Nxd5 14. e4 Ne7 $11) (13. Nxf1 e5 14. Bc3 Nc5 $11) (13. Kxf1 Nxd5 14. h4 Qc8 $11) 13... fxe6 14. Kxf1 {[%eval 10,22]} (14. Rxf1 $14 {[%eval 70,21]} Rc8 15. Rd1) 14... e5 {[%eval 55,20]} ({Pushing the e-pawn is the obvious choice, but Black has better chances of gaining enough play for the pawn with} 14... Nd5 15. Qe4 Qe8 {intending ...Qf7 and only later ...e5.}) (14... Nd5 $11 {[%eval 10,22]} 15. Qe4 Qe7) 15. Bc3 Nc5 {[%cal Of6e4] [#]} 16. Qe2 $1 (16. Bxe5 Nb3 (16... Nfe4 17. Qg4 $11) 17. Rd1 Nd2+ 18. Rxd2 Qxd2 $19) 16... Qd5 17. Kg1 ({Maghsoodloo's plan is a good one, but} 17. Rd1 $1 {first makes it stronger.}) 17... Rad8 {[%eval 68,21]} (17... Nfe4 $1 {forces White to be more accurate:} 18. Be1 $1 {keeps some advantage.} ({If} 18. Nxe4 $2 {[%eval -8,21] 18.Be1 0.62} Nxe4 19. Be1 Rac8 $1 20. f3 {[%eval -60,22] Black has} (20. Qd1 $11 {[%eval 1,20]} Qc4 21. h3) 20... Qb3 $1 $15 {Threatens to win with ...Rc2.} 21. fxe4 Rc2 22. Bd2 Rd8 23. Rd1 Qxb2)) (17... Rac8 $1 $11 {[%eval 29,21]}) 18. h3 $1 {Planning to connect the rooks with Kh2. It appears that Black can do nothing to exploit his temporary greater piece activity. In trying to do so, Naiditsch succeeds only in creating weaknesses in his own position.} Nd3 {[%eval 129,22]} (18... Nfe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Be1 $1) ({Black should try} 18... Nfe4 $14 {[%eval 56,20]} 19. Nxe4 Nxe4) 19. f3 $36 {[%eval 83,19][%mdl 2048] White is really pushing.} (19. Kh2 $142 {[%eval 129,22]}) 19... h5 {[%eval 162,21]} (19... e4 $16 {[%eval 83,19]}) 20. e4 $18 Qe6 21. Qe3 Nf4 {[%eval 210,20]} (21... h4 $16 {[%eval 148,18]} 22. Ne2 Nc5) 22. Ne2 g5 {[%eval 285,20]} (22... Nd7 $142 {[%eval 178,19]} 23. Kh2 Nc5) 23. Kh2 h4 {[%eval 385,21]} (23... Kh7 {[%eval 257,18] might work better.} 24. a4 Rg8 25. Nxf4 exf4) 24. Nxf4 exf4 25. Qe2 Kf7 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.11 (very precise) /Black=0.44} 26. Qb5 $1 {Inhibits Nd5.} 1-0


