1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 Be7 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 {Roiz,M: 'In my opinion this is the most challenging choice. Undoubtedly, having the doubled f-pawns isn't to everyone's taste.'} (11. e5 b4 12. exf6 bxc3 13. Qxc3 gxf6 {leads to very tense and double-edged play. See the notes to Ponkratov,P (2629)-Bacrot,E (2678) Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021 [Roiz,M]}) 11... gxf6 12. Kb1 b4 $5 (12... Qb6) 13. Ne2 Qb6 $6 {Roiz,M: 'I am surprised that this move is the most common choice - in my opinion, Black has to be careful because his k-side is unsafe.'} ({Roiz,M: 'Much safer is'} 13... h5 $1 {Roiz,M: ', as covered in Anand,V (2782)-Demchenko,A (2660) Riyadh KSA 2017 [Roiz,M]'} 14. f5 e5 15. Nc1 Qb6 16. Bc4 a5 (16... Rc8 17. Bd5 Na7 $1 18. Qd3 $16 (18. Nb3 $6 a5 $17)) 17. Qd5 Rh7 18. g4 hxg4 19. Rhg1 Rc8 20. Rxg4 Bf8 21. h4 $13) 14. f5 e5 {Roiz,M: 'This is practically forced - otherwise White will gain access to d5 for his knights.'} 15. Ng3 {Roiz,M: '?' Roiz,M: 'Even though this was played in most games, it is a serious mistake!'} ({The queen's activation} 15. Qh6 $1 {seems to pose Black huge problems:} O-O-O ({After} 15... Na5 16. Ng3 Bc6 {Genannt, R-Reichenbacher, G Germany 1986 White develops a decisive attack with} 17. Nh5 $1 Bxe4 18. Nd2 Bb7 19. Nxf6+ Kd8 20. Nde4 $18) (15... Na7 16. Ng3 Bb5) 16. Ng3 {It is hard to defend against an attack on the Pf6. For instance,} Na5 17. Nh5 Bc6 {Yeo,M - Hennigan,M Swansea 1995} 18. Nxf6 $1 Bxf6 19. Qxf6 Bxe4 20. Ng5 $18) 15... h5 {Roiz,M: '!' Roiz,M: 'This is the point! Black manages to consolidate and cover the weak spots on the k-side.'} 16. Bc4 Na5 $1 {Diagram [#] Roiz,M: 'A decent positional sacrifice.'} 17. Qd5 $146 {Roiz,M: 'This natural move is a novelty. White bravely accepts the challenge.'} ({Roiz,M: 'Hardly better is'} 17. Bd5 {- 150/(59)} Rc8 18. h4 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Rhe1 a5 {Black took over the initiative, but eventually lost. Asadli,V - Bok,B Chess.com INT 2021}) ({White also achieves nothing special with} 17. Bd3 Bf8 18. Qe2 Ke7 19. h4 Nc6 $132) ({RR} 17. Bd5 Rc8 18. Nf1 Bf8 19. Qe3 Qc7 20. Ne1 Bh6 21. Qe2 h4 22. Qh5 Ba4 23. b3 Bb5 24. Qxh4 Be2 25. Rd2 Bb5 26. Rd1 Ke7 27. Qh5 Be8 28. h4 Nc6 29. Qe2 Na7 30. a4 bxa3 31. c4 Rb8 {Gschnitzer,A (2433)-Warmerdam,M (2610) Dortmund 2022 0-1 (43)}) 17... Nxc4 $1 18. Qxa8+ (18. Qxc4 $2 a5 19. Nd2 Bb5 20. Qd5 Rc8 $17) 18... Bd8 {Roiz,M: 'The Qa8 is in big danger, so White's next move is forced.'} 19. Qd5 Ne3 {Roiz,M: 'Black partly regains the material.'} 20. Qxd6 ({The timid} 20. Qb3 {can be well met by} a5 $1 21. a4 Nxd1 22. Rxd1 {, and after} Bc6 $1 23. Rxd6 Qc5 $36 {Black's initiative outweighs the pawn.}) 20... Nxd1 21. Rxd1 {Roiz,M: '?' Roiz,M: 'Surprisingly, this natural recapture leads to a bad endgame, where White's drawing chances are miserable!'} ({Roiz,M: 'It was important to keep the queens on the board:'} 21. Qxd1 $1 h4 22. Ne2 a5 (22... Bc6 $145 23. Qd3 (23. Nd2 Qf2 24. Nc1 Qxg2 25. Nd3 Rg8 $36) 23... Ke7 24. Nd2 Bb5 25. Qf3 Qa7 $36 {Perunovic,Milos}) 23. Nc1 Be7 (23... a4 $44 {Black has full compensation, but White should be OK.}) 24. Nd3 a4 $13) 21... Qxd6 22. Rxd6 {Diagram [#]} Bb5 $1 {Roiz,M: 'Suddenly, it turns out that the bishop pair fully dominate the board. In particular, after ...h5-h4 the Ng3 is almost trapped!'} 23. Rd1 h4 24. Nf1 Bb6 {Roiz,M: 'What an illustrative situation: the mobility of White's knights is minimal!'} 25. N1d2 Bf2 {Roiz,M: '!'} 26. b3 {Roiz,M: '?' Roiz,M: 'Alas, Dmitry fails to put-up any resistance.'} ({Roiz,M: 'The only chance was'} 26. Rc1 $145 {Roiz,M: '!'} Rg8 27. g3 hxg3 28. hxg3 Rxg3 29. c4 Bc6 $17 {Perunovic, Milos} 30. Kc2 $17 {the limited material balance makes it tougher for Black to convert his huge positional advantage into a full point. Still, defending this position is a sort of suffering.}) 26... Rg8 27. Nc4 (27. g3 $145 hxg3 28. hxg3 Rxg3 $17 {Perunovic,Milos} 29. Rh1 Be3 $19) 27... Rxg2 28. Rd2 h3 {Roiz,M: '-+' Roiz,M: 'White's position collapses at once.'} 29. Kb2 Ke7 30. Rd3 Ba7 31. a4 bxa3+ 32. Kxa3 Rxc2 33. Kb4 Re2 0-1


