1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 a6 {There's nothing wrong with playing ...a6 as early as this, as long as Black is willing to play ...a6 lines in general, and it does prevent one or two options for White.} ({For example,} 6... g6 7. Bf4 (7. Qa4+) 7... a6 8. e4 ({or} 8. Nd2)) 7. a4 ({After} 7. e4 b5 8. Bf4 {Black could consider} Be7) 7... g6 8. e4 Bg7 ({It may well be that} 8... Bg4 $1 {a move we've seen on numerous occasions, is the most accurate move rather than just one option to reach a certain type of position.} 9. Be2 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 {- see many games in the archives.}) 9. Be2 O-O (9... Bg4 {here can be met favourably by} 10. Nd2 $1 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {- see the notes to Jones,G-Merry,A/London 2018. In particular, the absence of castling from both sides means that} Nbd7 12. Nc4 Nb6 {is met strongly by} 13. e5 $1) 10. Bg5 $1 {A rare choice in this position, but this looks like a good attempt to exploit the early insertion of ...a6 and a2-a4.} (10. O-O {is the overwhelmingly popular choice, after which} Bg4 ({and} 10... Re8 11. Nd2 Nbd7 {lead to main lines.})) 10... Bg4 (10... h6 11. Be3 $1 {is a position more likely to be reached via a King's Indian, Averbakh Variation. It's important to note here that without the insertion of ...a6 and a2-a4, Black would have the resource 10...b5!, offering good counterplay. - see the note to Black's 10th move.} (11. Bh4 g5 $1 12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Nd2 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Nd7 {is okay for Black}) 11... Bg4 (11... Ng4 12. Bf4) 12. Nd2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Nbd7 14. O-O Re8 15. a5 {with a pleasant edge for White.}) (10... Re8 11. Nd2 $1 Nbd7 12. O-O {is another typical position where the fact that the dark-squared bishop has managed to develop before Nd2 was played gives White a clear edge.}) 11. Nd2 $1 (11. O-O Bxf3 $1 (11... Nbd7 12. Nd2 $1 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 {transposes to the game}) 12. Bxf3 Nbd7 {is considerably more comfortable for Black than the game.}) 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nbd7 13. O-O {Without seemingly doing anything wrong, Black is already facing considerable difficulties. Such is the life for a Modern Benoni player! transposes to the game} Re8 14. f4 $5 {Maghsoodloo's plan is direct and very dangerous for Black.} ({RR} 14. Nc4 Ne5 15. Ne3 Qc7 16. Rad1 c4 17. f4 Nd3 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. e5 dxe5 20. Ne4 Bg7 21. f5 b5 22. Kh1 Rad8 23. Qf3 Nxb2 24. d6 Qa7 25. Rd5 Nd3 26. Ng4 Nf4 27. Nef6+ Bxf6 28. Nxf6+ Kg7 {Maghsoodloo,P (2701)-Mitrabha,G (2490) Chess.com INT 2022 1-0 (32)}) ({RR} 14. f3 Rb8 15. a5 h5 16. Kh1 Qe7 17. f4 Qf8 18. Qd3 Nh7 19. Bh4 Bf6 20. Bg3 h4 21. Bf2 Qh6 22. Qh3 Rbd8 23. Nc4 Ndf8 24. Rae1 Bxc3 25. bxc3 Qxf4 26. Bxh4 Rxe4 27. Rxf4 {1-0 (27) Korobov,A (2631)-Claverie,C (2290) Chess.com INT 2025}) ({RR} 14. Be3 Qc7 15. h3 Rab8 16. Rfe1 Ne5 17. Bf4 Nfd7 18. Bg3 c4 19. Red1 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra6 Nc5 22. Bxe5 Nxa6 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Nf3 b4 25. Nb1 c3 26. bxc3 bxc3 27. Rc1 c2 28. Na3 Nb4 {Maghsoodloo,P (2732)-Liu,Z (2401) Chess.com INT 2023 0-1}) 14... Qc7 15. Qf3 Rab8 (15... c4 16. Kh1 Rab8 17. e5 $1 dxe5 18. f5 $1 {is an older example of the same thematic pawn sacrifice.} Rf8 19. Nde4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 f6 21. Be3 Rf7 22. Qg4 Nf8 23. Bc5 Qd7 24. Nd6 b6 25. Bb4 gxf5 26. Qxc4 Qc7 27. Qxa6 Rd7 28. Rfc1 Qd8 29. Nxf5 $18 {and White won, Milos,G-Wiedenkeller,M/Copenhagen 1982.}) 16. Kh1 $146 ({RR} 16. a5 b5 17. b3 Nh5 18. Bh4 b4 19. Ne2 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 Nhf6 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. Ng3 Qe7 23. Rf1 Nd7 24. Nc4 Qf6 25. Qg4 Rbd8 26. Nf5 Rxe4 27. Ncxd6 Rd4 28. Nh6+ Kf8 29. Ndxf7 Ne5 30. Nxe5 R4xd5 {Alimov,A (1965)-Vorobyova,A (1993) Novokuznetsk 2012 1-0 (50)}) ({RR} 16. Rae1 h6 17. Bh4 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. e5 Nh7 20. e6 Ndf6 21. Nde4 b4 22. Nxf6+ Nxf6 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Ne4 Bxb2 25. f5 fxe6 26. dxe6 d5 27. fxg6 Rf8 28. Qe2 Bd4+ 29. Nf2 Qe7 30. Kh1 Bxf2 {Essing,A (2230)-Kubicka,A (2259) Chess.com INT 2024 0-1 (58)}) 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5 $1 dxe5 19. f5 $1 {Everyone who plays Modern Benoni positions should be aware of this idea!} e4 {This counter-sacrifice is also thematic, but it's not effective here.} ({After} 19... c4 20. Nde4 ({or} 20. Rad1 {White has tremendous compensation.})) 20. Ndxe4 Nxe4 (20... b4 21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 22. fxg6 hxg6 23. Bxf6 bxc3 24. bxc3 $16) 21. Nxe4 Qb6 (21... Ne5 22. Qg3 $1) 22. d6 $1 Qb7 23. Be7 $1 {More typical moves by Maghsoodloo, and White's attack is now irresistible.} Ne5 24. Qf4 gxf5 25. Nf6+ Bxf6 26. Bxf6 Qe4 27. Qg5+ Ng6 28. Qh6 {Though rarely played, Maghsoodloo's 10 Bg5 seems to take advantage of Black's failure to play ...Bg4 immediately after the ...a6 and a4.} 1-0


