1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 {In my opinion, the most principled variation. I always preferred to play this position for White. Usually, White has a choice between sacrificing a pawn long-term or trying to take the pawn back.} 5. O-O b5 {First, we will examine the most principled reaction for Black: to defend the pawn. Now White has no choice and should try to play for an initiative.} 6. a4 Bb7 7. d3 {This move changes everything. I believe White is on the driving seat in this line and we are not going to see 5...b5 very often.} (7. b3 {was the old theory} b4 8. bxc4 c5 {the position is quite acceptable for Black.}) ({RR} 7. b3 b4 8. bxc4 c5 9. d3 e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Nb3 a5 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. e3 O-O 14. d4 Qc7 15. Qe2 Ne4 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 17. Ne1 Nd6 18. e4 cxd4 19. c5 Ne8 20. Bxd4 Ne5 21. f4 Nc6 {Nakamura,H (2776)-Anand,V (2797) Zuerich 2015 1-0 (57)}) 7... cxd3 8. Ne5 {The point of White's idea} Qc7 (8... a6 9. Qxd3 (9. Nc3 e6 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 $16 {Gareyev won 6 moves later: 1-0 (18) Gareyev,T (2584)-Shetty,A (2431) Philadelphia 2019}) 9... Qxd3 10. Nxd3 $14 {Even without queens, Black's position is quite unpleasant. White has an initiative and an easy game. 1-0 (42) Zhigalko,A (2517)-Tsydypov, Z (2565) Kazan 2021}) ({RR} 8... b4 9. a5 a6 10. Qb3 e6 11. Nxd3 Qc8 12. Nxb4 c5 13. Qa4+ Nfd7 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. Nd3 Be7 16. Be3 O-O 17. Nd2 Rc8 18. Rfc1 Qb5 19. Nc4 Nc6 20. Qxb5 axb5 21. Nb6 Nxb6 22. axb6 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 {Van Liempt,M (2111)-Kleibeuker,M (2011) Hoorn 2025 1-0}) 9. Bf4 $146 {developing before everything. In those lines, White should be ready to sacrifice few pawns.} ({RR} 9. Nxd3 Nbd7 10. Nc3 e5 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Nxb5 Qb6 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Qa4 e4 15. Ne5 Be7 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Bg5 f6 18. Rfc1 O-O 19. Rc7 Qb6 20. Qc4+ Kh8 21. Be3 Ne5 22. Qd5 Rad8 23. Qxe5 {1-0 (23) Swapnil,S (2500)-Ashwath,R (2227) Abu Dhabi 2016}) ({RR} 9. Nxd3 e5 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. Nxe5 Be7 13. Qb3 O-O {½-½ (13) Stella,A (2447)-Banusz,T (2588) Fano 2013}) 9... Nh5 10. axb5 Nxf4 11. gxf4 $18 {Black could resign here.} f6 ({The main problem is that Black can't play} 11... cxb5 12. Qb3 {[%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b5]}) 12. bxc6 Nxc6 13. Nxd3 {White's king is quite much safer and Black can't complete the development. Parham easily convert his enormous advantage to a full point.} Rd8 14. Nc3 e6 15. Qb3 Be7 16. Rfc1 Qd7 17. Rd1 Qc8 18. Nb5 a6 19. Na7 Qa8 20. Qxb7 1-0


