{This was played in an early round of the Iranian Championship, in which Parham Maghsoodloo went on a rampage with a string of consecutive wins.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {See K.Goh Wei Ming - I. Salgado Lopez, Olympiad 2014 (0-1 in 40) in the Archives with Kevin's instructive notes.} Ng6 7. Be2 Be7 8. Be3 O-O 9. c4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 b6 11. Nc3 Bb7 {Clearly Black is not geared towards the standard breaks of ...b5 or .. . d5, but rather is looking for an opporunity to play ...f5 under good circumstances.} 12. Rfd1 {Basically the wrong rook, for a tactical reason which is difficult to explain, let alone spot.} ({In his white repertoire course on Chessable, Wesley So recommends} 12. Rad1 Bc6 13. Qd2 {when, if Black plays as in the game with} f5 14. exf5 Nh4 {, White prevails in the complications after} 15. fxe6 Nxg2 16. exd7 Kh8 17. Bg4 $1 {. By contrast to the note to White's 15th move, after} Nxe3 18. fxe3 $18 {the presence of the rook on f1 diametrically changes the evaluation of the position.}) ({RR} 12. Rad1 Bc6 13. f4 f5 14. g3 e5 15. fxe5 f4 16. gxf4 Nxf4 17. Qd2 Bc5 18. Kh1 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Qg5 20. Rf2 Qxe5 21. Rdf1 Nxe2 22. Rxf8+ Rxf8 23. Rxf8+ Kxf8 24. Qxe2 Qf4 25. Kg2 Ke7 26. Nd5+ Bxd5 {Ehlvest,J (2531)-Wartiovaara,O (2340) Tallinn 2025 0-1 (40)}) 12... Bc6 13. Qd2 (13. Rac1 f5 14. exf5 Nh4 {also led to excellent counterplay for Black in P.Leko - B.Gelfand, Hengshui 2019 (1/2-1/2 in 36).}) 13... f5 $146 ({RR} 13... Qb8 14. Bf1 Rd8 15. f3 Bc5 16. a3 a5 17. Qf2 Qe5 18. g3 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Qc5 20. Kf2 Ne5 21. Be2 f6 22. b3 Kf8 23. Rdb1 d6 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Qxe3+ 26. Kxe3 Rxa1 27. Rxa1 Ra8 28. Rxa8+ {Balogh,C (2632)-Rogozenco,D (2516) Germany 2013 ½-½ (46)}) ({RR} 13... Bc5 14. Bf1 f5 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. Bd3 Rh5 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Ne2 Qf6 20. Ng3 Rh4 21. Rac1 g5 22. Rc3 Rf8 23. Qe3 Qh6 24. Nf1 Rg4 25. Ng3 Rh4 26. Nf1 Rg4 27. Ng3 {½-½ (27) Balogh,C (1394)-Perunovic,M (2612) Hungary 2018}) 14. exf5 Nh4 $1 15. f3 ({Here} 15. fxe6 Nxg2 16. exd7 Kh8 $1 {would lead to an unclear position where White's material advantage is compensated by his weakened king.} 17. Bg4 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Bc5) 15... Rxf5 (15... Nxf5 $11 {is a safer recapture, when Black has no complaints from the opening.}) 16. Ne4 $1 Qe8 17. Ng3 Re5 18. Bf4 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 {Black's position looks critical but he finds a wonderful tactical resource.} Rxe2 $1 20. Qxe2 Nxf3 $3 {A stunning sacrifice to open the h1-a8 diagonal.} 21. Ne4 $1 (21. gxf3 $2 Qf7 {wins.}) 21... Nh4 22. Qg4 $6 ({After} 22. Bg3 $14 {White should retain some advantage, with a rook for a minor piece and pawn.}) 22... Be7 23. Bg3 $2 (23. Bd6 {was essential.}) 23... h5 ({The immediate} 23... Nf5 $1 {was even stronger, followed by ...h5.}) 24. Qe2 (24. Qh3 $15 {was the most tenacious defence.}) 24... Nf5 25. Be5 Qg6 26. Ng3 Nh4 27. Kg1 Rf8 28. Bd6 Bxd6 29. Rxd6 Nxg2 30. Qd3 ({White resigned in view of the inevitable} 30. Qd3 Nf4 $1 31. Qxg6 Nh3# {with a beautiful checkmate.}) 0-1


[Event "European Online CC Final"]
[Site "Tornelo INT"]
[Date "2021.03.31"]
