[Source "PGNMentor"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 Na6 7. Nf3 {comes to the same thing.} h6 {The most common reply, posing the big question immediately (i.e. before touching the 'c' or e-pawns).} 8. Bh4 ({After} 8. Be3 {the reply 8...Ng4 was chosen in both of Milov, V - Gallagher, J Switzerland 2000, and Burnier, D - Gallagher, J Neuchâtel 2002, (see the archives for details) but these days the standard choice at GM level is} e5 $1 {e.g.} 9. d5 (9. O-O Ng4 10. Bc1 c6 (10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Qf6 {(a 'dynamic' approach in typical Naiditsch-style)} 12. Nb3 Qh4 13. Bf4 Be5 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. h3 Nf6 16. Nd2 Rd8 {(most KID players would be happy with Black, but White can avoid serious difficulties with the game continuation...)} 17. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 18. cxd5 c6 19. Re1 cxd5 20. Bxa6 bxa6 21. Nf3 Qf6 $13 {Gelfand, B - Naiditsch, A Wijk aan Zee 2014}) 11. d5 (11. h3 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nf6 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bf3 Nh7 $1 {Burnier, D - Gallagher, J Neuchâtel 2002, which came about by transposition, see the archives}) 11... f5 12. g3 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nf6 14. Nh4 {(the idea behind 12.g3)} fxe4 ({maybe Black should trade a pair of knights to give more scope for his major pieces:} 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Nxg6 Rf7 $13) 15. Nxg6 Rf7 16. Be3 Bh3 17. Re1 Rc8 {with a complex struggle where the engines prefer White slightly, Mohota, N - Libiszewski, F Gibraltar 2020}) (9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Bf4 Nxe5 11. Nd4 Nc5 12. O-O Ne6 {(exchanging off a pair of knights tends to ease Black's development)} 13. Be3 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 c5 $1 {(the dynamic choice)} 15. Be3 Be6 $11 {L'Ami, E - Aguera Naredo, J Reykjavik 2012}) 9... Ng4 10. Bd2 f5 11. h3 (11. exf5 $6 Bxf5 12. h3 $2 Nxf2 $1 {(a nice shot!)} 13. Kxf2 e4 14. Kg3 exf3 15. gxf3 Nc5 16. Be3 Qe7 $19 {Drenchev, P - Cheparinov, I Plovdiv 2013}) 11... Nf6 ({here} 11... Nxf2 $2 {doesn't work:} 12. Kxf2 fxe4 13. Nxe4 Qh4+ 14. Ke3 Qf4+ 15. Kd3 $18 {Marn, J - Sychev, K Titled Tuesday online blitz 2021}) 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Qc1 f4 {with a decent game for Black. Noting that the sharp} 14. g3 $5 {should be met with} Nc5 15. gxf4 e4 16. Nd4 Nh5 $13 {Mesaros, F - Ritviz, P Porto Carras 2015.}) ({White could also withdraw the bishop to the 'artificial' d2-square i. e.} 8. Bd2 {but it's hard to believe that this has much bite e.g.} e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qc1 Kh7 11. O-O Nc5 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. Qc2 c6 14. Rab1 a5 $11 {John, H - Polzer, H correspondence 1999.}) 8... e5 ({The no-nonsense direct approach} 8... g5 9. Bg3 Nh5 10. Qd2 f5 {was the choice of a King's Indian specialist of many years:} 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. O-O c6 13. Rad1 Qd7 14. d5 Nxg3 15. hxg3 c5 16. Bd3 {Ivanov, S - Nunn, J World team seniors 2017. The engines prefer White slightly, but having seen many examples with a similar structure arising from the Leningrad Dutch, I suspect that Black should be fine. In essence, the weaknesses on the right-hand flank are not too difficult for him to protect.}) 9. O-O Qe8 10. d5 {It may have started as an Averbakh Variation, but it looks more like a Petrosian System now (for example, the plausible sequence 6.Nf3 0-0 7.d5 Na6 8.Bg5 h6 9.Bh4 Qe8 10.0-0 transposes)!} Nc5 {Although this looks like an obvious plan, White can meet it without discomfort, so I'm not a great fan, especially as the future b4-push will force the knight to move away with a loss of time.} ({I prefer} 10... Nh5 $1 {to exploit the move order, as there is no convenient way to keep the knight out of f4. Then} 11. Nd2 Nf4 12. f3 f5 13. Bf2 Qe7 14. Kh1 h5 15. Re1 Nc5 16. Nb3 b6 {Tan Zhongyi - Kashlinskaya, A Doha rapid 2016, was fine for Black.}) 11. Nd2 a5 12. b3 {Preparing the standard plan with an eventual b2-b4 to push back the knight.} Bd7 13. a3 Nh7 14. b4 {No messing about, the Iranian star dislodges the knight as soon as possible.} ({However it's possible to nurture this advance with some preparatory play:} 14. Qc2 f5 (14... h5 15. f3 Bh6 16. Rab1 {transposes to Giri, A - Ding Liren Wijk aan Zee 2015, which can be found in the archives again transposes to Giri, A - Ding Liren, Wijk aan Zee 2015, (see the archives) . Although this would seem to be a typical scenario in the Petrosian Variation, there is a slightly unusual feature: In such situations the knight usually stays on a6 rather than getting played early to c5. The main consequence here is that when b3-b4 comes, it's with tempo, so this feels like a superior version for White. Indeed David Vigorito (in his notes for ChessPublishing) does seem to indicate that White had chances for an edge.}) 15. f3 f4 16. b4 Na6 (16... Na4 17. Nb5 Bxb5 18. cxb5 axb4 19. axb4 Nb6 20. Qxc7 {Nikolov, M - Antonio, D Cappelle online blitz 2021, was catastrophic for Black}) 17. Rab1 h5 18. Bf2 g5 19. c5 g4 20. c6 bxc6 21. dxc6 Be6 {Ollier, P - Cornette, D Rochefort 2017, and White had already made great strides forwards on the queenside. So, for example, after} 22. b5 {the advantage would already have been nigh on decisive.}) 14... Na4 15. Qc2 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 f5 {In principle, White is well-placed to cope with the ...f5 'attempt at freedom' and has already made steady inroads on the queenside. So Guseinov hurries to get in the ...g4-advance in order to 'pump up' his chances of generating meaningful counterplay.} 17. f3 g5 18. Bf2 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 g4 $146 ({Black was soon in trouble after the slower} 20... f4 $6 21. c5 Qg6 22. cxd6 cxd6 23. Qc7 $18 {Dinckel, J - Kosztolanczi, G Budapest 2000.}) ({If instead} 20... Nf6 {(objectively best) then simplest would be} 21. Qc2 fxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. fxe4 $14 {keeping a space bind and calmly preparing to press on the queenside.}) ({RR} 20... f4 21. c5 Qg6 22. cxd6 cxd6 23. Qc7 Rf7 24. Qxb7 g4 25. Qa8+ Rf8 26. Qa7 gxf3 27. Bxf3 Nf6 28. Bh4 Rf7 29. Qb8+ Kh7 30. Bxf6 Bxf6 31. b5 Bg4 32. Ra7 Be7 33. Qe8 Bxf3 34. Nxf3 Qf6 35. b6 {Dinckel,J (2128)-Kosztolanczi,G (2196) Budapest 2000 1-0 (38)}) 21. fxg4 fxe4 $6 {Dodgy perhaps, but with the noble intention of seeking to create chinks on the kingside.} ({After} 21... fxg4 {White could continue with} 22. c5 $16 {etc.}) 22. h3 Qg6 23. Qe3 Nf6 24. Rf1 $6 {A little slow.} ({Instead, White should either play} 24. Bh4 $16 {immediately, or opt for}) (24. b5 $16 {to stymie any Black attempts of counterplay on the queenside. A strange idea, you might think, but here White can't be kept out of the kingside forever.}) 24... c6 $1 {White's plan is to round up the loose e-pawn (Bf2-h4xf6 and then Nxe4), so Black has to resort to thrashing about in order to try and complicate life.} 25. Bh4 (25. dxc6 bxc6 26. b5 cxb5 27. cxb5 d5 {wouldn't be so clear. A passed pawn can be a useful asset, but so could Black's new found central pawn mass.}) 25... cxd5 26. Bxf6 Rxf6 ({As Black is going to lose a pawn anyway, he should try and find the 'lesser evil' which, in this case, I estimate to be the following:} 26... Bxf6 $1 27. cxd5 Bg5 28. Qxe4 Rxf1+ 29. Bxf1 Be8 30. Qxg6+ Bxg6 31. Nc4 Be7 {with an endgame that could well be tenable.}) 27. cxd5 Rxf1+ 28. Bxf1 h5 $6 ({Trading queens is still the best chance:} 28... Qf7 29. Qxe4 Qf4 {as it can be tough to convert an extra pawn with B + N v 2Bs.}) 29. gxh5 Qxh5 30. Nxe4 Qg6 31. Bd3 Bf5 32. Qf3 Bxe4 33. Bxe4 Qg5 {Opposite bishops are not necessarily a 'drawish feature' when the stronger side has a pair of connected passed pawns.} 34. b5 b6 35. Kh2 Qf4+ 36. g3 $1 Qd2+ 37. Qg2 Qe1 38. h4 Bh6 39. Qf3 Qe3 {Accepting his fate. Black's king is too exposed to survive for long if the queens remain on the board, but the endgame is hopeless.} ({There is no joy for Black after} 39... Qd2+ {either:} 40. Kh3 Bg7 41. Qf5 Qh6 42. Qc8+ Bf8 43. Qc7 $18) 40. Qxe3 Bxe3 41. g4 Bf2 42. Kh3 Kg7 43. g5 Be1 44. h5 Bd2 45. Kg4 Be3 46. h6+ Kf7 47. Kh5 Bf4 48. g6+ 1-0


