{The following two examples are taken from my camp 1.d4 Nf6 - Practical Repertoire against the Sidelines. Both games feature a typical endgame with bishop pair arising from the Trompowsky Opening.} 1. d4 {Kharitonov,Andrei Y} Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 ({RR} 3. Nd2) 3... c5 4. Bxf6 gxf6 5. dxc5 ({RR} 5. Nc3 e6 6. Qf3 Bd7 7. O-O-O Nc6 8. Nge2 f5 9. Nf4 Qa5 10. Kb1 O-O-O) 5... e6 {Even though this is the most popular continuation, I find it slightly imprecise.} ({As pointed out in the introduction, our move order starts with} 5... Nc6 {with the idea of answering c2-c4 with ...d5-d4.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qxd8+ $2 {This is already a mistake. White should always avoid the exchange of the queens in this line.} ({A better idea would have been} 7. Nd2 {when after} Bxc5 8. Bxc4 Nc6 9. Ngf3 O-O 10. O-O {[%cal Gd1e2,Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gd2e4,Ge4g3,Gg3h5] we can see a typical position for this line. The computer insists that the position is completely equal. From a human perspective, however, the position is equal. White can follow with simple moves such as Qe2, Rfd1, and Rac1. Also, the manoeuvre Ne4-g3 comes into consideration. Given the fact that the black king is slightly vulnerable, he should handle the position with care. This type of position is the main reason why I suggest 5...Nc6 instead of 5...e6.}) ({RR} 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Qxc4 Qa5+) 7... Kxd8 8. Bxc4 Nd7 $146 {Black prefers taking the pawn with the knight since the dark-squared bishop can be developed on the long diagonal as well. Black is ready to answer} ({RR} 8... Bxc5 9. Nf3 Ke7 10. O-O b6 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Rac1 Nd7 13. a3 Rac8 14. b4 Bd6 15. Nd4 f5 16. Bb5 Rxc1 17. Rxc1 Nb8 18. Be2 a6 19. Nc4 Rc8 20. Rd1 Bc7 21. a4 Rd8 22. b5 axb5 23. axb5 {Vlachos,A (2435)-Ongut,T (2185) Porto Carras 2018 1-0 (48)}) ({RR} 8... Bxc5 9. Nf3 Ke7 10. Ke2 a6 11. Rc1 Bd6 12. Nc3 f5 13. e4 fxe4 14. Nxe4 Bf4 15. Rc3 Nd7 16. g3 Bh6 17. Rd1 Bg7 18. Rc2 Rd8 19. Bb3 Nf8 20. Rc7+ Rd7 21. Rdc1 Kd8 22. Rxd7+ Bxd7 23. Nfg5 {Martirosyan,H (2632)-Keymer,V (2591) Chess.com INT 2021 1-0 (43)}) ({RR} 8... Bxc5 9. Nc3 a6 10. O-O-O+ Kc7 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Nf3 Nc6 13. Kb1 b5 14. Bb3 Bb7 15. Rc1 Kb6 16. Rhd1 Rhd8 17. Ng3 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19. Rc1 Ne5 20. Nxe5 fxe5 21. e4 Bh4 22. f3 Rg8 23. Rh1 {Voitovich,V (2319)-Szajbely,Z (2283) Chess.com INT 2025 1-0 (81)}) ({RR} 8... Bxc5 9. Nc3 Ke7 10. Rc1 Bd7 11. Bb5 Rc8 ({RR} 11... Nc6 12. Nd5+ exd5 13. Rxc5 Kd6 14. Rc3) 12. Bxd7 Nxd7 13. Nge2 ({RR} 13. Nf3 Bb4 ({RR} 13... Nb6) 14. Ke2 Bxc3 15. Rxc3 Rxc3 16. bxc3 Rc8) 13... Ne5 14. O-O a6 15. Na4 Bd6 ({RR} 15... Ba7 16. Rxc8 Rxc8 17. Rc1 Rxc1+ 18. Nxc1 b5 19. Nc3 f5) 16. Rxc8 ({RR} 16. Nb6 Rxc1 17. Rxc1 Rd8 18. Nc8+ Ke8 19. Nxd6+ Rxd6 20. Nd4) 16... Rxc8 17. Rc1 Rd8 18. Nd4 ({RR} 18. Nb6 Nd3 19. Rb1 ({RR} 19. Nc8+ Kf8) 19... Bc5 20. Na4 Ba7) 18... Nd3 19. Rc3 Nb4 20. a3 Nd5 21. Rc1 f5 22. Nf3 ({RR} 22. g3) 22... b5 23. Nc5 {Lombardy,W-Ivkov,B Amsterdam 1974 MCL [Kharitonov,Andrei Y] 0-1 (49)} ({RR} 23. Nc3 Nxc3 24. Rxc3 Bxa3)) 9. c6 {with} Ne5 10. c7+ Kxc7 11. Be2 Bd7 {Finally the position has stabilized. Black has a serious advantage in view of his bishop pair and good central control. In this concrete position, the next move is going to be ...Bc6.} 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. f3 $2 {This is already a decisive mistake. Now, Black is going to achieve serious domination on the dark squares.} ({White should have played} 13. Nf3 {when a logical follow-up would have been} Rg8 14. Nxe5 fxe5 15. Bf3 {Trying to exchange one of the opponent's bishops is a classical way of fighting against a bishop pair. In this case, however, Black can transform his advantage by means of} Bb4 {[%cal Ge5e4] Besides the idea of spoiling White's queenside structure with ...Bxc3, Black is also threatening ...e5-e4.} 16. Bxc6 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Kxc6 18. g3 Rad8 19. Ke2 Rg4 $15 {[%cal Gg4a4] Black wants to transfer his rook to a4. White is still worse in view of his queenside weaknesses.}) 13... Rd8 14. Rd1 Bc5 15. e4 h5 {Always consider this move. The idea is to fix the g2-pawn by means of ...h5-h4. Remember that gaining space on the wings is a very important strategy when we have a bishop pair!} 16. Nh3 h4 17. a3 {White already struggles to find useful moves.} ({Probably the Iranian GM calculated that the idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops by means of} 17. Bb5 {does not work in view of} Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Bxb5 19. Nxb5+ Kc6 20. Nc3 Rg8 {when White does not have a comfortable way of defending the g2-pawn. For instance, after} 21. Nf4 Nc4 $19 {[%cal Gc4e3,Ge3g2,Gg8d8,Gd8d2] Black is already winning. White cannot parry all the threats.}) 17... a6 18. Nf4 Be3 19. Nd3 Nc4 $19 {Black has a decisive advantage because White cannot untangle.} 20. Bf1 Bb6 21. Rc1 Be3 22. Rc2 Bh6 23. Nd1 Ne5 ({Even simpler would have been} 23... Rd4 24. Nb4 Rhd8 25. Be2 Ba4 $19) 24. Nb4 Kb6 25. Nxc6 Nxc6 26. Nc3 Nd4 27. Rf2 Be3 28. Bc4 h3 29. g3 Rc8 30. Ba2 Rhd8 31. Rhf1 Ka7 32. f4 b5 33. Rf3 Nxf3+ 34. Rxf3 Bc1 35. Rf2 Bxb2 36. Rxb2 Rxc3 0-1


