1. c4 {ChessBase} e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 $5 {This is a playable move which is a hybrid between the Nimzo-Indian, the Queen's Indian, and the Ragozin. White can use this move by transposing to a good version of the Nimzo-Indian with e3.} 4. e3 $1 Nf6 5. a3 $1 Be7 {This will not solve Black's problems since White has gained an extra tempo.} (5... Bxc3+ {This move is far more common, taking the game into a Nimzo-Indian territory with a better version for White.} 6. bxc3 O-O (6... c5 7. cxd5 $1 exd5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2 $14) (6... c6 $5 {This is the only independent try for Black. In my opinion, White should undouble the pawns with cxd5 followed by an immediate c4! Check the games to see this idea in practice.} 7. cxd5 $1 cxd5 8. c4 $1 $14 b6 9. cxd5 $1 exd5 (9... Qxd5 10. f3 $14 (10. Ne2 $5 O-O 11. Nf4 Qd7 12. Bb2 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qe2 $14)) 10. Bb5+ $3 {This is a typical idea that disturbs the coordination of the Black pieces and it prevents Ba6 because it distracts either the knight or the bishop to d7.} Bd7 (10... Nbd7 11. a4 $16) 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Ne2 $1 $16) 7. cxd5 $1 exd5 8. Bd3 c5 9. Ne2 $14) ({RR} 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2 b6 10. a4 Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Qd3 c4 14. Qc2 Qd7 15. O-O) ({RR} 5... Bd6) 6. Nf3 O-O ({RR} 6... b6 7. Bd3 Bb7) 7. b4 {White took advantage of the extra move a3 to push b4 immediately.} ({RR} 7. Bd3 b6 {RR} 8. Qe2 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Rd1 cxd4 11. exd4 Ba6 12. Bg5 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Rc8 15. Qa6 Nd5 16. Bxe7 Ndxe7) 7... Nbd7 ({RR} 7... a5 8. b5 c5) ({RR} 7... c6 8. Bb2 b6 9. c5 a5 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O Ba6 12. Ne1 e5 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. b5 exd4 15. bxa6 dxc3 16. Bxc3 Nxc5 17. Qe2 Qa8 18. Rb1 Nfe4 19. Bd4 b5 20. a7 Ne6 21. Nf3 Bxa3 22. Qc2 {Caruana,F (2766)-Carlsen,M (2859) Chess.com INT 2022 ½-½ (72)}) ({RR} 7... b6 8. c5 a5 9. Bb2 bxc5 10. bxc5 Ba6 11. Bxa6 Rxa6 12. Qd3 Ra7 13. O-O Nc6 14. Rab1 Qa8 15. Ba1 Rd8 16. Qc2 h6 17. Rfd1 Ne8 18. Nb5 Ra6 19. Ne1 Qc8 20. Nd3 f5 21. f3 Bf6 22. Nf4 {Corbu,G (2115)-Pribelszky,B (2428) Arad 2025 ½-½ (57)}) ({RR} 7... b6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb2 a6 10. Bd3 Bd6 11. Ne5 c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. O-O c4 14. Bc2 Nbd7 15. f4 Rb8 16. Ra2 Nb6 17. Ba1 Qe7 18. e4 Bb7 19. exd5 Nbxd5 20. Qe1 Bxa3 21. Qh4 Ne3 22. Re1 {Indjic,A (2589)-Carlsen,M (2830) Samarkand 2023 0-1 (34)}) 8. Bb2 c6 ({RR} 8... a5 9. c5) 9. c5 $146 {This move is a good idea when White has some pieces developed and when the structure can be kept intact. Carlsen probably evaluated that Black isn't on time to play e5, or Black will manage to play e5 and will be worse.} ({RR} 9. Bd3 dxc4 ({RR} 9... Bd6 10. c5 ({RR} 10. O-O Qe7) 10... Bc7) 10. Bxc4 Bd6 ({RR} 10... Qc7 11. Rc1) ({RR} 10... a5 11. b5 c5 12. O-O Nb6 13. Bd3) 11. Ne2 ({RR} 11. Qc2 e5 12. Ba2 Qe7 13. Bb1) ({RR} 11. O-O e5 12. Qc2 exd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Ba2) 11... a5 ({RR} 11... Qc7 12. Ng3 e5 13. Nf5) 12. b5 Nb6 13. Bd3 cxb5 14. Bxb5 Bd7 15. Qb3 ({RR} 15. Qd3 Na4 16. Bc1) 15... a4 16. Qd3 Ra5 17. Nc3 ({RR} 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Bc3 Rb5 ({RR} 18... Qb5 19. Qb1 Qxb1+ 20. Rxb1 Ra6) 19. O-O Rc8) 17... Qe8 ({RR} 17... Nfd5 18. O-O) 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. O-O ({RR} 19. e4 Rc8 20. e5 Bxe5) 19... Rc8 20. e4 ({RR} 20. Nd2) ({RR} 20. Rfb1 Nc4 21. Bc1) 20... Nc4 21. Bc1 e5 22. Rd1 ({RR} 22. d5 b5 23. Nh4 b4 24. axb4 Bxb4) 22... exd4 23. Qxd4 Qe6 {Botvinnik,M-Reshevsky,S The Hague/Moscow 1948 MainBase [ChessBase] 1-0 (32)} ({RR} 23... Qc7)) ({RR} 9. Qc2) ({RR} 9. Qb3) ({RR} 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Bd3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 a5 12. b5 Nb6 13. Bd3 cxb5 14. Nxb5 Bd7 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. Qe2 Na4 17. O-O Qb6 18. Rab1 Nxb2 19. Rxb2 Red8 20. Rfb1 Be8 21. Qd2 a4 22. Na7 Qxa7 23. Rxb7 Qa8 {Botvinnik,M-Lipnitsky,I Moscow 1951 1-0 (41)}) 9... Qc7 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 e5 11. O-O e4 12. Nd2 {This position is objectively better for White because White's attack is faster on the queenside, although f3 can be also considered at some point, however, Black is not without chances too and should try to build up an attack against White's king which can be dangerous, especially in blitz.}) 10... e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qc2 $14 Qh5 14. Ne2 Ng4 15. h3 Ne5 16. Bxh7+ Qxh7 17. Qxh7+ Kxh7 18. Bxe5 {White won a pawn and went on to win the game.} b6 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. Ke2 Kg6 22. Rc3 f6 23. Bf4 b5 24. Bd6 Bd8 25. g4 a5 26. Kf3 axb4 27. axb4 Ra4 28. Rb3 Rca8 29. h4 Ra2 30. h5+ Kh7 31. Rhb1 R8a6 32. R3b2 R2a3 33. Kg3 f5 34. Nxf5 Bf6 35. Rd2 Bxf5 36. gxf5 1-0


