1. e4 {Postny,Evgeny} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {The Najdorf is one of Magnus's favourite weapons in his recent online tournament.} 6. h3 h6 $5 {A rare move, though in some cases it can transpose to major lines.} ({RR} 6... Nbd7 7. g4 h6 ({RR} 7... Nc5 8. Bg2 e5 9. Nf5 g6 10. Ne3) 8. f4 e5 9. Nf5 Nc5 10. Bg2 g6 11. Ng3 h5 ({RR} 11... exf4 12. Bxf4 Ne6 13. Be3 Bg7 14. Qd2 h5 ({RR} 14... Nd7 15. O-O-O Ne5 16. b3 Qa5 17. Nge2 Qa3+ 18. Kb1) 15. g5 Nd7 16. O-O-O ({RR} 16. Qxd6 Be5) 16... Be5 17. Nge2) 12. f5 ({RR} 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Rd1+ Ke8 16. O-O Ncd7 17. gxh5 Nxh5 18. Nxh5 Rxh5 ({RR} 18... Bxg5 19. Ng7+ Ke7 ({RR} 19... Kf8 20. Ne6+) 20. Nd5+) 19. Bxe7 Kxe7 20. Nd5+ Kf8 21. Rd3) 12... h4 13. Nge2 d5 ({RR} 13... b5 14. g5 Nh5 15. O-O Bb7 16. Nd5) ({RR} 13... Rg8 14. O-O Bd7 15. Be3 Bc6 16. Nd5) 14. fxg6 d4 ({RR} 14... fxg6 15. exd5) 15. gxf7+ Kxf7 16. O-O Kg6 17. Nd5 Bg7 ({RR} 17... Ncxe4 18. Qd3 Qxd5 19. Nc3 dxc3 20. Rxf6+ Kxf6 21. Qxd5) 18. b4 Ncd7 19. Qd3 Nb6 20. Nxd4 Bd7 21. Nf5 {Naiditsch,A (2686)-Sutovsky,E (2661) Poikovsky 2010 CBM 137 [Postny,Evgeny] 1-0 (36)} ({RR} 21. g5 Nh5 22. Qf3 Rf8 23. Nf5 Nxd5 24. Nxh4+ Kh7 25. Qxh5+)) ({RR} 6... e5 7. Nde2 h5 ({RR} 7... Be6 8. g4 d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Bg2 Bb4) 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. c3 Nd7 12. h4 Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Be7 14. g3 O-O 15. Bh3 Nf6 16. Qd3 b5) ({RR} 6... e6 7. g4 d5 ({RR} 7... b5 8. Bg2 Bb7) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nde2 Bb4 10. Bg2 O-O) 7. a4 $146 {This is already a novelty. The mix of the aggressive h2-h3 with the prophylactic a2-a4 makes a strange impression.} (7. g4 {is the most consistent reply, and then after} e6 ({Riskier is} 7... b5 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O e6 10. Re1 e5 11. Nf5 g6 12. Ne3 Nbd7 13. a4 b4 14. Ncd5 $14 {Carlsen,M - Gelfand,B Nice 2008}) 8. Bg2 {we are back on well-explored paths!}) ({RR} 7. g4 e5 8. Nde2 b5 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. a3 Nbd7 11. O-O Nc5 12. Ng3 g5 13. Nd5 Ne6 14. c4 Nf4 15. Be3 Bxd5 16. cxd5 Be7 17. a4 bxa4 18. Nf5 Qd7 19. Bxf4 gxf4 20. Rxa4 Qb5 21. Re1 Nd7 {Szajbely,Z (2187)-Kovacs,A (2074) Hungary 2014 1-0 (31)}) ({RR} 7. Be3 e6 8. Be2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. f4 Nc6 11. Bf3 Qc7 12. Qe1 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 e5 14. Be3 b5 15. Qg3 Kh7 16. a3 Bb7 17. Rad1 Rad8 18. Qf2 Qc4 19. Be2 Qc8 20. Nd5 Nxe4 21. Qf3 Nf6 {Ortiz Lopera,M (2010)-Velandia,W (1761) Manizales 2025 0-1 (58)}) ({RR} 7. Bd3 e5 8. Nde2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Ng3 Be6 11. f4 exf4 12. Bxf4 Nc6 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. Qxh6 Ne8 16. Nf5 Bg5 17. Qh5 Ng7 18. Qe2 Re8 19. Kh1 Rc8 20. Qf2 Ng6 21. Nd5 Bxd5 {Paravyan,D (2589)-Maghsoodloo,P (2695) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1 (31)}) ({RR} 7. f4 e5 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Be3 b5 10. a3 Bb7 11. Bd3 Be7 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. O-O-O exf4 14. Bxf4 Ne5 15. Nd4 g6 16. Rhf1 Nfd7 17. Kb1 Nc5 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 O-O-O 20. Bxe5 dxe5 21. Nc6 f5 {Ntagasigumwami,D (1720)-Naser Eldean,A (1906) Batumi 2018 0-1 (60)}) 7... e5 {Magnus prefers to fix the pawn structure.} ({Another decent option was} 7... e6 $5 8. Be3 Be7 9. a5 O-O 10. Bd3 {A complex, double-edged struggle is ahead.}) 8. Nde2 Be7 {I am not sure if this was the best moment to develop the dark-squared bishop.} ({Somewhat more flexible is} 8... Nc6 $5 9. g4 Be6 10. Bg2 Rc8 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 Ne7 $132 {White's setup on the k-side is somewhat exposed, so Black aims to transfer his knight to h4.}) 9. g3 {For some reason Parham deviates from the usual expansion on the k-side.} ({In my opinion,} 9. g4 $1 {was much better as the Ne2 can be successfully re-located:} Be6 10. Bg2 Nc6 11. Nd5 O-O 12. Ng3 $14) 9... b6 {On his turn Magnus also handles the position somewhat passively.} ({It was essential to play} 9... Nc6 $1 10. Bg2 Nb4 11. O-O Be6 $11 {the drawbacks of an early a2-a4 are becoming obvious: the Nb4 is very well placed, so ...d6-d5 is to follow soon.}) 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Nd5 {Parham decides to exchange his queen's knight in order to make its square vacant for the other.} ({As earlier, more promising was} 12. g4 $1 Nc5 13. Ng3 O-O 14. Be3 Rc8 15. Qd2 $14 {Black hardly has adequate compensation for his weak Pd6.}) 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 O-O 14. f4 (14. c4 {can be traditionally met by} a5 $1 15. Nc3 Nc5 $15) 14... b5 {A decent move - Black prevents White from extending on the q-side and isolates the Pd5.} 15. fxe5 dxe5 $5 {An ambitious and somewhat provocative choice.} (15... Nxe5 16. Nd4 Bg5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 $11 {would have kept the position equal.}) 16. d6 {Of course, White's main hopes are connected to a strong d-passer.} Bf6 {The position is still balanced, but the play is much sharper now.} (16... Bg5 17. Bxb7 Qb6+ 18. Kh2 Qxb7 19. Bxg5 hxg5 {is about equal as well.}) 17. Bxb7 Qb6+ 18. Kh2 Qxb7 19. Nc3 $1 {Eventually White manages to activate his knight.} Rac8 20. axb5 axb5 21. Nd5 {This aggressive choice doesn't really bother Black.} ({It made sense to develop the bishop and take control of the a7-square:} 21. Be3 $5 Qc6 22. Ra7 Rfd8 23. Qg4 h5 24. Qxh5 Qxd6 $11 {Still, Black should be fine here.}) 21... Rc5 $1 {This precise move practically forces White to sac the exchange.} 22. Nxf6+ Nxf6 23. Rxf6 gxf6 24. Qg4+ Kh8 (24... Kh7 25. Qf5+ Kg7 26. Qg4+ $11) 25. Qf5 $11 Qc8 {By making this move Carlsen avoids a repetition.} 26. Qxf6+ Kg8 27. c3 {Luckily for Parham, White can afford to spend a tempo on this quiet move.} Qe6 28. Qxe6 fxe6 29. Bxh6 Rd8 30. Ra6 (30. h4 Rxd6 31. Kh3 {is equally good. The k-side passers provide White with sufficient counterplay.}) 30... Rd5 31. h4 R8xd6 32. Ra8+ Rd8 33. Ra6 R8d6 (33... Kf7 $5) 34. Ra8+ Kh7 35. Bg5 e4 {Magnus continues to push for a win, but it's not realistic here.} (35... b4 36. cxb4 Rb6 37. Be7 $11) 36. Kh3 Rxg5 {The last try.} ({Black achieves nothing with} 36... Rd3 37. h5 R6d5 38. Kg4) 37. hxg5 e3 38. Ra1 Rd2 39. Re1 {White easily neutralizes the e-passer.} e2 40. b4 Kg6 41. Kg4 e5 {The further liquidation of material is unavoidable.} 42. Kf3 Rd3+ 43. Ke4 Rxc3 44. Rxe2 Rc4+ 45. Kxe5 Rxb4 46. Re4 Rxe4+ 47. Kxe4 Kxg5 48. Kd4 Kg4 49. Kc5 Kxg3 50. Kxb5 1/2-1/2


