1. d4 {Fischer,Johannes} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {So, Cheparinov sticks to his own recommendation from his new book (Cheparinov's 1.d4! Vol 1 King's Indian & Grünfeld)!} d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O Qd6 ({RR} 9... f5 10. e5 Nb4 11. Nh3 Qe8 12. Kb1 a5 13. Be2 c6 14. Rc1 Kh8 15. Ka1 Be6 16. Nf4 Qf7 17. h4 Bxa2 18. h5 Kg8 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. g4 Bb3 21. Bd1 a4 22. Qh2 Rfd8 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. d5) 10. Kb1 Rd8 11. Nb5 Qd7 12. d5 a6 13. Nc3 Na5 ({For the more popular} 13... Qe8 {see Ding Liren - Nepomniachtchi, I Carlsen Invitation Online rapid 2020, in the archives.}) ({I have already discussed the other knight leap} 13... Ne5 {in Wojtasezek, R - Areshchenko, A Polish league 2013, despite it being a rare choice. To counter this (instead of Wojtaszek's normal-looking choice of 14.Qc1) Cheparinov considers} 14. Bxb6 {to be very strong. It has been tested recently:} cxb6 15. f4 Ng4 16. h3 $1 ({less convincing is} 16. e5 {due to} Bh6 $1 17. h3 Nxe5 18. g3 Nc6 19. Qe3 Na7 20. Nf3 Qd6 $15 {Vrolijk, L -Salimova, N Kragero 2020, and the loss of the e-pawn weighs on White's chances}) 16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nf6 18. Bd3 {"Very difficult for Black to find counterplay" (Cheparinov), but the following forcing sequence needs further investigation:} Qa4 19. Bc2 Qa3 20. Ne2 Bd7 21. e5 Be6 $1 22. exf6 Rxd5 23. Qxd5 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 exf6 $14 {Wojnar, M - Falatowicz, P e-mail 2018, and Black held the game despite White having a fistful of wood for the queen.}) 14. Qc1 ({There are certain similarities between the game continuation and the following sequence:} 14. Bd4 Nbc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Qc1 b5 ({better seems to be} 16... Bxd4 $1 17. Rxd4 b5 18. Nge2 Qd6 19. h4 h5 20. Nd1 (20. g4 {is perhaps critical, but risky}) 20... Bd7 21. Ne3 Ne5 {Manninen, A - Rawlings, A e-mail 2016, with a certain solidity for Black}) 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. h4 {as in Onischuk, V - Bagi, M Zalakaros 2015, see the archives for the details, but White was in the driving seat there.}) 14... Nbc4 ({Gelfand chose} 14... Qd6 {here, whereupon} 15. h4 Qb4 ({if} 15... h5 {Cheparinov suggests the 'route one' approach} 16. g4 hxg4 17. h5) 16. h5 Nac4 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Nge2 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Qb6 {occurred in Giri, A - Gelfand, B Tromso 2014. Now the Bulgarian expert on this line gives} 21. Nd4 $146 e5 22. Nc2 Qxe3 23. Nxe3 $14 {. Two knights (plus a key pawn wedge on d5) versus two bishops is often an interesting imbalance. Frankly, this doesn't look like much to me (bearing in mind that there is a risk of things opening up later), but the engines do indeed lean towards Cheparinov's view that White is for preference.}) 15. Bd4 Bxd4 16. Rxd4 b5 17. Bxc4 {This capture is usually employed at some point, even if not immediately.} ({A couple of other seventeenth moves have been tried:} 17. h4 e5 18. Rd1 b4 $1 19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Nce2 Qb5 $132 21. h5 c6 {0.5-0.5 Lercel, M - Nasuta, G London 2016. It would have been nice to see a few extra moves, but this tense position is fairly balanced it seems. If White were then to invade with} 22. Qg5 Rd6 23. Qe7 cxd5 24. hxg6 {then Black saves himself with} Na3+ $1 25. Ka1 Nc2+ $11) (17. Rd1 Qd6 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Nge2 {(this is dubious in my opinion)} Qf6 {(a bit sluggish)} (19... b4 $1 $132 {(seems right as the attacked knight no longer has a retreat square)} 20. Na4 Bd7 $1 $15 {and now the queenside will be the scene of action}) 20. h4 e5 21. h5 Bb7 22. b3 Nb6 $14 {Plichta, K - Schmidt, W Poznan 2014. At the end, White has more chances of generating a quick attack, whereas Black will have to seek opening up the centre for counterplay.}) 17... Nxc4 {(and transposes back to the main game) has also occurred.} 18. Nge2 Qd6 ({I don't like the bishop's development} 18... Bb7 {so much:} 19. h4 ({Cheparinov prefers} 19. Rhd1 {which stops Black countering in the same way as in this example. In this case, another plan is required, maybe} Qd6 20. h4 h5 {but White has enhanced attacking chances with the black bishop 'out of play' on b7}) 19... e5 20. dxe6 (20. Rd3 b4 21. Nd1 Qb5 $13) 20... Qxe6 21. Rhd1 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Qe7 $11 {Lodici, L - Schmider, N Germany 2020, with ...Rd8 coming.}) 19. h4 Qf6 $146 {A novelty that aims to slow down any attempts to open up the kingside.} ({After} 19... h5 {the daring} 20. g4 $1 {seems to be dangerous to the human eye, although engines are not particularly impressed: is perhaps critical, but risky} Ne5 ({Cheparinov points out} 20... hxg4 21. f4 $1 $16 {claiming that "White's attack is unstoppable". Is this really true after} Kg7 {I wonder? Maybe, but he must be using more advanced technology than me!}) ({RR} 20... hxg4 21. f4 Kg7 22. h5 Rh8 23. Ng3 Bd7) 21. gxh5 b4 22. Na4 Nxf3 23. hxg6 fxg6 24. h5 $5 {Gunina, V - Muzychuk, M Batumi 2016, and Gunina's bloodthirsty attack was certainly become strong by now. Still, there might be ways to render Black's game palatable after 20...hxg4 etc. (if you spend lots of time on this line with your favourite engine).}) ({RR} 19... h5 20. g4 Ne5 21. gxh5 b4 22. Na4 Nxf3 23. hxg6 fxg6 24. h5 Nxd4 25. Nxd4 Qe5 ({RR} 25... Bd7 26. Rg1 Be8 27. Ne6) 26. Nc6 Qxe4+ 27. Ka1 Bf5 28. Nc5 Qc2 29. Qh6 Qg2 30. hxg6 Bxg6 31. Qh8+ Kf7 32. Ne5# {1-0 (32) Gunina,V (2497)-Muzychuk,M (2561) Batumi 2016 CBM 172 [Fischer,Johannes]}) 20. h5 g5 21. h6 Kh8 22. Rh5 Rg8 {The Iranian's novel defensive fortress looks like a clever way to frustrate his opponent. So with the kingside closed up for now, the Bulgarian turns his attention to the central arena.} 23. d6 $5 {Freeing up the d5-square whilst creating general mischief.} Be6 24. dxe7 $6 {Keeping life simple, but not really challenging the opponent that much.} ({It was instead possible to grab a pawn with} 24. dxc7 Rac8 25. Rd8 $1 {when a continuation such as} Rcxd8 26. cxd8=Q Rxd8 27. Qxg5 Qxg5 (27... Rd2 $6 {is risky after} 28. Qg3 $1) 28. Rxg5 Rd2 29. b3 Ne3 {is given by the engines as 'better for White'. Despite this assessment, Black's activity shouldn't be underestimated.}) 24... Qxe7 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. Rxd5 Rad8 $5 {Maghsoodloo hurries to activate even at the cost of a pawn.} ({The more straightforward} 26... f6 $11 {holds onto the g-pawn and any consequent time loss seems to be insignificant.}) 27. Rhxg5 Rxg5 28. Qxg5 Qxg5 29. Rxg5 Rd1+ ({The sloppy} 29... Rd2 $2 {is strongly met by} 30. Rd5 $1 {when Black has to accept a miserable knight endgame a pawn down.}) 30. Nc1 Rd2 31. b3 Na3+ 32. Ka1 Nc2+ 33. Kb2 $1 {Quite rightly avoiding the draw.} b4 ({After} 33... Ne1+ 34. Kb1 Nxg2 {White penetrates with} 35. Rg7 $16) 34. Rd5 $1 {This time the knight endgame isn't quite so bad for Black, but he still has to suffer to some extent.} Rxd5 35. exd5 Ne3 ({Maybe} 35... Ne1 $5 {to slow down the activation of both of White's pieces.}) 36. Nd3 Nxd5 37. Nc5 ({Another promising idea is} 37. Kc2 a5 38. Ne5 $16 {intending to rapidly activate the king.}) 37... a5 38. Nb7 f5 {The Iranian decides that he just has to get his king into play as soon as possible.} 39. Nxa5 Kg8 40. Nc6 Kf7 41. Kc2 Ke6 42. Kd3 Kd6 43. Nd4 Ke5 44. g3 {White has a clear pawn to the good, but there doesn't seem to be an easy way forward on either wing, that is as long as Black stays active.} f4 $5 45. g4 c5 46. Ne2 (46. Nc6+ $1 Kd6 47. Na5 $1 $18 {looks odd (placing the knight on the rim), but it enables the white king to then have access to c4 or e4 with excellent winning chances.}) 46... Ne3 $2 ({Waiting with} 46... Nb6 {would have been more prudent.}) 47. g5 $1 Nf5 (47... Kf5 $2 {loses to} 48. g6 $1) 48. Kc4 ({The nice break} 48. g6 $1 Nxh6 49. gxh7 Nf7 50. Kc4 $18 {would keep Black's knight occupied while the mopping up operation takes place.}) 48... Nh4 49. Kxc5 Kf5 50. Nd4+ Ke5 (50... Kxg5 51. Kxb4 $18) 51. Kxb4 $4 {A tempting idea when time is short, but it doesn't work at all.} ({An easy win was at hand after the patient move} 51. Kc4 $1 {(producing a mini-Zugzwang) e.g.} Ng6 52. Ne2 Kf5 53. Kxb4 {and then the connected passed a-pawns would indeed be decisive.}) 51... Kxd4 52. a4 Kd5 $2 ({The draw was a question of careful calculation:} 52... Nxf3 $1 53. g6 Ne5 $1 54. gxh7 (54. g7 $2 {even loses to} Nc6+ 55. Kb5 Ne7 $19) 54... Ng6 55. a5 f3 56. a6 f2 57. a7 f1=Q 58. a8=Q Qe1+ $11) 53. Kb5 Ke6 54. a5 Nxf3 55. g6 Ng5 56. g7 Kf7 57. Kc4 $6 ({A standard tempo-gaining theme wins i.e.} 57. a6 f3 58. a7 f2 59. g8=Q+ $1) 57... Ne6 58. b4 $2 ({Again} 58. a6 $1 f3 59. a7 f2 60. g8=Q+ $1 {was the way to success.}) 58... f3 59. Kd3 Nd4 60. Ke3 Nc2+ 61. Kxf3 Nxb4 62. Ke4 Kg8 63. Ke3 Na6 64. Kd4 Nb4 65. Kc4 Na6 66. Kb5 Nc7+ 67. Kb6 Nd5+ 68. Kb7 Nb4 69. a6 Nxa6 70. Kxa6 {Unfortunately for Cheparinov, the pawn endgame is only a draw.} Kf7 71. Kb6 Kg8 72. Kc6 Kf7 73. Kd6 Kg8 74. Ke7 1/2-1/2


