 White with an initiative.} {I would suggest} Rc2+ $1 {with nothing worse than a slightly clumsy version of a regular set-up} {The main alternative} 47. Kg1 {is equally popular, but that's another story. After} Nh3+ $1 48. Kh1 {there have been many games where Black can decide between 'ceding the bishop pair, but getting easy development' or 'losing some time by holding onto the light-squared bishop'. For the rare 12.e3 see Caruana, F - Vachier-Lagrave, M Online rapid 2020, in the recent archives.} Nf2+) 40. Rb5 $16 {would be easier for White to handle} ({I suspect that} 40. Rd1 $5 {is more challenging i. e.} Nf4+ 41. Ke1 {which looks slightly annoying at first (Black seems to have the wrong rook on d8, but he can probably live with this inconvenient situation), but after} Rxd1+ $5 {there aren't any tricks down the d-file. True, White can always opt for the 'advantage' of the bishop pair, but we've seen so often in such positions that it isn't a big issue. Anyway, see what you think, but I can't help feeling that Komodo's 'clear advantage for White' is exaggerated.} {More forcing, but perhaps not as precise is} 42. Kxd1 {e.g.} Rh3 $1 43. Nd2 Rxh2 44. b4 axb4 45. a5 Rh1+ {Thakur, A - Peled, S e-mail 2017, and now} 46. Kc2 $5 {[%cal Oa5a6] may not leave White with much to bite on.} {The less critical} Ra1 {was played in Sarana, A - Pogosyan, S Euro online rapid 2020 (see the archives).} {Otherwise} 47. Nc4 {is worth considering:} Ne6 $1 48. Rxb4 h5 49. Kb2 {(leads to a quick opening of the centre, but Black is soon able to get himself ably reorganized)} Rg1 50. a6 {[#] aiming for a7.} h4 $1 51. a7 {[#]} h3 $1 {(an important tempo gain)} 52. a8=Q h2) 40... Nf4+ 41. Kf2 {is 'at least a draw for White', but it seems that there is no more than that.} {If} Rd3 {[%eval -96,22] the g5-square is out of bounds for White's knight, but} (41... Rd6 $142 {[%eval -142,21] and ...Re6 would now be decisive} 42. Rxa5 Rd3) {Loses the game.} 42. Re5 $13 {[%eval -290,23] then has to be considered.} (42. Rxa5 $17 {[%eval -96,22]} Rh3 43. Kg1) {I suspect that} 42... Rc3 $1 $19 {was rejected because of} (42... Rh3 43. Re3 $11 {Black has easy development and White has the most evident weakness on c4.}) 43. Rxa5 Rh3 44. Rb5 $2 {[%eval -545,21] but this still seems favourable for Black after} (44. Kg1 {[%eval -285,23]}) 44... Rhxf3+ $1 {for example} 45. Kg1 Rc2 46. Rb6 Rff2 $1 $17 {Less combative is} 47. a5 $15 {the idea being to re-emerge via c2 sooner rather than later.} {Even better is} Rg2+ $1 {[%eval -774,5] avoiding White's next move.} (47... Nh3+ $142 {[%eval -32757,12]} 48. Kh1 Rg2 49. Nd2 Rgxd2 (49... Rcxd2 $2 {gets mated.} 50. Rg6+ Kxg6 51. Rf1 Rxh2#) 50. Rg6+ Kxg6 51. Rf1 Rxh2#) {Instead} 48. Kh1 $19 {rather helps Black's development, as after} {Weighted Error Value: White=0.55/Black=0.42} Nh3 0-1


