1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. e3 Bd7 $5 {This move is frowned upon by theory, but it's actually not so bad. Instead of the standard Ragozin plan of taking on c4 and preparing to counter in the center with ... e6-e5, Black instead aims for play on the queenside and along light-squares in particular} (6... O-O) 7. Qc2 O-O 8. a3 (8. Bd2 a6 $6 {Black should be careful not to mix up his plans, since including the move ...Bd7 slows down the standard ...dxc4 followed by ...e5 idea. Below are a couple of nice examples of how this can backfire for Black} (8... dxc4 $5 9. Bxc4 a6 10. a3 Bd6 $13) (8... Re8 $5 9. a3 Bf8 $13) 9. Rd1 (9. a3 Bd6 10. c5 Be7 11. b4 $14 {1-0 (83) Jovanic,O (2469)-Kovacevic,V (2512) Solin 2005}) 9... Qe7 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Ne4 12. Bd3 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Rfe8 14. O-O Rad8 15. b4 dxc4 16. Bxc4 e5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxe5 Rxe5 20. Rd2 $16 {1-0 (41) Mikhalchishin,A (2479) -Goessler,M (2209) Katowice 2017}) 8... Bxc3+ (8... Bd6 9. c5 Be7 10. b4 $14) 9. Qxc3 a5 10. b3 Ne4 $6 {A strange type of Stonewall position arises where Black has no dark-squared bishop and the knight on c6 is oddly placed} ({Black's standard treatment of this position consists of undermining White's light-squares on the queenside with} 10... a4 11. b4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Na7 13. Qd3 $5 {White should not allow the exchange of light-squared bishops without a fight. Black otherwise gets a pleasant position, as the variations below illustrate} (13. Bd3 $6 Bb5 14. e4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Nd7 16. O-O c6 17. Be3 Nb5 $13) (13. Ne5 $6 Bb5 14. Bb2 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Qd5 16. Qxd5 (16. Qxc7 $2 Rac8 $19) 16... exd5 17. Rc1 Nb5 $15 {0-1 (36) Blumin,B-Fine,R New York 1939}) (13. Qc2 Bb5 $11) 13... Nd5 (13... Qe8 $5 {[%cal Gd7b5]}) 14. O-O Nb6 $11) 11. Qc2 f5 12. Bd3 Be8 13. Bb2 Bg6 $6 {Black's idea is to provide additional support to the knight on e4 in order to enable the ...f5-f4 push. However, White can easily prevent this and even if he doesn't, it's not clear that this pawn break will favor Black at all} (13... Bh5 14. Nd2 (14. h3 Qf6 15. O-O-O $13) 14... Qg5 15. O-O Rf6 16. f4 Qh4 17. Nf3 $14) 14. O-O $1 (14. g3 Bh5 15. Nh4 Ng5 $13) ({The onyl case where Black's idea seems to work is after} 14. O-O-O $6 f4 $132) 14... f4 15. Rae1 Qe7 16. exf4 Rxf4 17. Nd2 $6 {A careless move that allows Black to trade into a strategically risky middlegame for White. Now White is under serious risk of being left with a "bad" bishop} (17. cxd5 $1 exd5 18. Nd2 Qd6 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Rxe4 21. Rxe4 dxe4 22. Qc4+ $1 (22. Qxe4 $14) 22... Kh8 23. d5 Ne7 24. Qd4 Rg8 25. Rd1 $16) 17... Nxd2 18. Qxd2 Bxd3 19. Qxf4 $6 (19. Qxd3 Qf7 20. f3 $13 {As long as White manages to keep the queens on the board, combined with the lack of a good outpost for the black knight, then he should be doing OK}) 19... Qf7 $146 ({RR} 19... Qd7 20. Qg4 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Rf8 22. Re1 Rf6 23. h4 Qd6 24. g3 Rf5 25. Qe2 Rf6 26. Qg4 Rg6 27. Qe2 Rf6 28. Qg4 Rg6 29. Qe2 {½-½ (30) Sammalvuo,T (2416)-Karttunen,M (2495) Finland 2023}) 20. Qxf7+ $2 {This is a serious strategic blunder. Without queens on the board, Black is free to start chipping away at White's light-squares, followed by the the knight maneuvers towards the outpost.} (20. Qe3 dxc4 21. f3 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 cxb3 23. Qxb3 Nd8 $15) (20. Qc1 a4 21. cxd5 exd5 22. b4 Na7 23. Re5 Rf8 24. f3 Bxf1 25. Qxf1 c6 $15) 20... Kxf7 21. cxd5 exd5 22. Re3 Bxf1 23. Kxf1 a4 24. b4 Na7 $17 {Black has a vicious clamp on the queenside. Now White must embark on a thankless defensive task} 25. Rf3+ Kg8 26. Rf5 Rd8 27. Re5 Kf7 28. Ke2 g6 29. Kd3 h5 30. Bc1 Rd6 31. f3 Nb5 32. h3 ({White's only hope is to mobilize the kingside pawn majority. One way of doing so would be after} 32. h4 c6 33. Re2 Re6 34. Rxe6 Kxe6 35. g4 $15) 32... c6 33. Re2 h4 34. Re1 (34. Bg5 Re6 (34... Nxa3 35. Re7+ $132) 35. Rxe6 Kxe6 36. Bxh4 Kf5 $1 {[%csl Rh4]} (36... Nxa3 37. Bg5 Nb5 38. Be3 a3 39. Kc2 $11 {and White should hold}) 37. Be1 Kf4 38. h4 Nxa3 39. Ke2 Nc4 40. g3+ Kf5 41. g4+ Kf6 $15 {Black's position is obviously better, but there is no clear win in sight}) 34... Re6 35. Rxe6 Kxe6 {An interesting endgame has arisen. At first sight it would seem White is completely busted, but we should not underestimate White's defensive chances. The lack of a second front (in fact, the h4-pawn is a liability for Black) makes it difficult for Black to make progress} 36. Ke3 Kf5 37. Kd3 Nc7 38. Ke2 g5 39. Kf2 b6 40. g4+ hxg3+ 41. Kxg3 Nb5 42. Bb2 Nd6 43. Bc1 Nc4 44. Kf2 Kg6 45. Kg3 Nd6 46. f4 Nf5+ 47. Kg4 gxf4 48. Bb2 f3 49. Kxf3 Kg5 50. Bc1+ Kh4 51. Kf4 $4 (51. Bb2 Kxh3 52. b5 $3 {Taking away the critical b5-square from the knight. Without it Black will be unable to prevent the invasion of the white king} (52. Kf4 Nd6 53. Bc1 (53. Ke5 Nc4+ $19) 53... Kg2 54. Ke5 Nb5 $19 {The black king is heading towards the queenside, while its white counterpart is unable to make progress}) 52... cxb5 53. Kf4 Nd6 54. Bc1 Nc4 55. Kf5 $11) 51... Nxd4 52. Ke5 Nb5 53. Ke6 Nxa3 $1 54. Kd6 (54. Bxa3 d4 55. Kd6 d3 56. Bc1 a3 $19) 54... Nc4+ 55. Kxc6 a3 56. Bxa3 Nxa3 57. Kxd5 b5 0-1


