1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 b5 6. e5 Nd5 7. Nxb5 Nb6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. Be3 (10. Na3 {is not particularly dangerous for Black.} Bxa3 {Black should be happy to spoil White's pawn structure while leaving White with the rather passive Bc1.} 11. bxa3 Bb7 12. Be3 Ne7 (12... Qd5 $5 13. Qc2 Ne7 14. Rfc1 Rb8 15. Ne1 Ba6 $13 {[%cal Ye8g8,Ye7f5]}) 13. Nd2 Nf5 $5 (13... Ned5 14. Bf3 $13 {1/2 (41) Gajewski,G (2599)-Wojtaszek,R (2750) Warsaw POL 2018} (14. Bxc4 $5 Nxe3 15. fxe3 O-O 16. Bd3 $5 Qg5 17. Qe2 c5 18. Be4 $14)) 14. Nxc4 O-O {White's extra pawn is of no significance in this position.}) (10. Qc2 a6 $1 {Putting immediate pressure on d4 is the easiest way to get a good game.} (10... O-O 11. Qe4 {0-1 (70) Abdusattorov,N (2594)-Maghsoodloo,P (2656) Abu Dhabi UAE 2019}) 11. Na3 (11. Nc3 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Bf3 Rb8 $132) 11... Bxa3 12. bxa3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Be3 (14. Bb2 Qc5 $13) 14... Qxe5 15. Bf3 Rb8 16. Rfe1 Qf6 $13) (10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Ba3 $6 {Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is not enough to prove an advantage.} (12. Qd2 Nd5 $13) 12... O-O $5 $13 (12... a6 {0-1 (91) Faizrakhmanov,R (2414)-Sarana,A (2510) Sochi 2017})) (10. Qd2 {(GM Robert Hungaski) was discussed in Zhang,Z (2432)-Sethuraman,S  (2638) Tianjin 2020 - see archive GM Robert Hungaski: 'was discussed in Zhang,Z (2432)-Sethuraman,S (2638) Tianjin 2020 - see archive'}) 10... O-O 11. Nc3 (11. Qd2 {(GM Robert Hungaski) was discussed in Wojtaszek-Duda, Polish Championship 2018 - see archive GM Robert Hungaski: 'was discussed in Wojtaszek-Duda, Polish Championship 2018 - see archive'}) 11... Rb8 {GM Robert Hungaski: 'This is Black's most flexible move. The rook will go to this square in the majority of cases, while it's not so clear that the bishop will always go to b7. As the following lines illustrate, we see the bishop developed to a6 in order to support the c4-pawn (especially in the cases where White plays with Na4)' GM Robert Hungaski: 'This is Black's most flexible move. The rook will go to this square in the majority of cases, while it's not so clear that the bishop will always go to b7. As the following lines illustrate, we see the bishop developed to a6 in order to support the c4-pawn (especially in the cases where White plays with Na4)' Keeps Black's options open} (11... Bb7 {is less accurate since Black should keep his options (b7 and a6) open for his bishop.} 12. Na4 {GM Robert Hungaski: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' makes more sense here than against 11...Rb8} (12. a3 Na5 13. Qc2 Nd5 14. Rad1 Nxe3 15. fxe3 c5 {GM Robert Hungaski: '⇆' '' '' '' GM Robert Hungaski: '1/2-1/2 (48) Keymer,V (2491)-Kovalev,V (2664) Douglas 2018'} 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. e4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qc8 20. Bxc4 (20. Nd2 $5) 20... Nxc4 21. Qxc4 Rb8 $11 {1/2 (48) Keymer,V (2491)-Kovalev,V (2664) Douglas ENG 2018} (21... a5 $5)) (12. Qb1 $5 {is an interesting idea that could be tested more.} a5 (12... Rb8 $5 13. Ne4 h6) (12... Nb4 $5 13. Rd1 {GM Robert Hungaski} Rb8 14. Ne4 (14. a3 $6 N4d5 15. Ne4 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Na4 $15) 14... Na4 15. Bxc4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nxb2 17. Rdc1 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 Qd5 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 $11) 13. Rd1 (13. Qe4 $5 {[%cal Ye4g4]}) 13... Nb4 14. Nd2 (14. Ne4 $5) 14... Ba6 15. a3 N4d5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Qc2 Bb5 18. f4 Rb8 $13 {1/2 (59) Hendri Sevano,R (1837)-De,G (2271) ICCF 2018}) (12. Qd2 {GM Robert Hungaski} Nb4 13. Rac1) 12... Na5 (12... Rc8 $5) (12... Nb4 {GM Robert Hungaski} 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Bxc4 $14) 13. Qd2 (13. Bd2 Bc6 (13... Nc6 $5) (13... Qe8 $5) 14. Bxa5 Bxa4 15. Qd2 Qd5 16. Bb4 Bxb4 17. Qxb4 $13 {1/2 (51) Sjugirov,S (2650)-Grachev,B (2654) Sochi RUS 2017} a5 {GM Robert Hungaski} 18. Qc3 Rfd8 19. Rfc1 Bb5 20. Qa3 h6 21. b3 c6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (51) Sjugirov,S  (2650)-Grachev,B (2654) Sochi 2017 GM Robert Hungaski: '1/2-1/2 (51) Sjugirov,S (2650)-Grachev,B (2654) Sochi 2017'}) (13. Nc5 $5 {GM Robert Hungaski}) 13... Nxa4 14. Qxa5 Nxb2 (14... Nb6 $5) 15. Rab1 c3 16. Qxc3 Na4 17. Qc2 Nb6 18. Rfc1 (18. Bd3) 18... Ba3 19. Ng5 g6 20. Rd1 Rb8 21. Ne4 (