he same manner as after 10.Bh4 g5 11.Bg3; however, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave plays differently.} 11. Bxa4 Bb7 12. Bc2 $1 Re8 13. f3 (13. d5) 13... Nb6 14. Nb3 Nh5 15. Na5 Qc8 {This position could have happened in Ding-Aronian, too - see above.} 16. g4 Nf6 $6 {Too humble.} 17. Be3 d5 18. dxe5 $16 {White's double pawns is an insufficient compensation for Black's material deficit although it requires a lot of work from White to convert his extra pawn.} Rxe5 19. Bd4 Re8 20. Bxb6 (20. Ng3) 20... cxb6 21. Nxb7 $1 {[%cal Yb1c3]} Qxb7 22. g5 Nh5 {An attempt to keep the position closed but almost all Black's pawns are now on light squares, which is a good news for White's light-squared bishop.} 23. exd5 (23. Bb3 dxe4 24. fxe4) 23... Rad8 (23... Qe7 $1 24. Be4 Qxg5+ 25. Kh1 Nf6) 24. Bb3 $5 (24. Be4) 24... Qe7 25. Rf2 $6 Qxg5+ $6 26. Kf1 $1 {White must create weaknesses in Black's camp.} a5 27. Ra4 Bf8 28. Rg4 Qe7 29. Re4 Qd7 30. Ng3 (30. Nd4) 30... Qh3+ $6 31. Ke2 (31. Rg2 Rxe4 32. fxe4 (32. Nxe4 Nf4 33. Ke1 Qxg2)) 31... Nxg3+ 32. hxg3 Qxg3 $2 {This move, weakening the c6 square, worsens Black's position.} 33. Qh1 (33. Qd3) 33... Bc5 34. Rh2 Rxe4+ {Black decides to wait but it doesn't help anymore.} 35. fxe4 Qe3+ 36. Kd1 {Probably premature.} Qd3+ 37. Ke1 Qb1+ (37... Bd6 {[%cal Rg7g6]} 38. Rh3 Bg3+ {[%cal Rg4g6]} 39. Rxg3 Qxg3+ $18 40. Kd1 $5 a4 $5) 38. Bd1 Re8 39. Re2 {[%cal Rd3f5]} Qd3 $6 {Another passive move.} (39... Bd6 40. Qf3 {[%cal Rb8a8] was much simpler.} b5) 40. Bc2 Qg3+ 41. Kd1 h5 42. Qe1 Qg4 43. Bd3 h4 44. Kc2 g5 (44... Bd6) 45. e5 Qa4+ 46. Kb1 b5 {Too late.} (46... Qf4) 47. Re4 b4 48. Qe2 Qd7 49. Bb5 Qe7 (49... Qd8 50. Qh5 bxc3 51. Bxe8 Qxd5 52. Bxf7+ (52. Qxg5+ Kf8 53. Bc6 (53. Qxh4 $18 Qd3+ 54. Ka2 Qd2 55. Qh8+ Ke7 56. Qf6+ Kxe8 57. Qc6+ Kd8) 53... Qd1+ (53... Qxc6 54. Rxh4 (54. Qxh4 Qb6 55. Qh8+ Ke7 $18 {or} 56. Qf6+ Qxf6 57. exf6+ $1 {(the key move, cutting off Black's king)} Kxf6) 54... Ke8 55. bxc3) 54. Ka2 c2) 52... Qxf7 53. Qxg5+ Qg7) 50. Bxe8 (50. d6 Qe6 51. Bxe8 Qxe8 52. Qg4) 50... Qxe8 51. Qh5 Qe7 52. e6 (52. cxb4 Bxb4 53. Re2) 52... f6 (52... Qf6 53. exf7+ Kg7) 53. Qg6+ Kf8 {[%mdl 4096]} (53... Kh8) 54. Qh6+ (54. Rc4 Qg7 55. Qh5) 54... Ke8 55. Qh8+ (55. cxb4 axb4 56. Rc4) 55... Qf8 56. Qh7 Qe7 57. Qg6+ (57. Qg8+ Qf8 58. Qg6+ Kd8 59. cxb4 axb4 (59... Bxb4 60. Rc4 Qd6 61. Qxf6+ Qe7 62. Qd4) 60. Rc4) 57... Kd8 (57... Kf8 58. Rc4 Qg7) 58. Qg8+ Qf8 59. e7+ Bxe7 60. Qe6 f5 (60... Bd6 61. Rc4 Bc5) 61. Rc4 Bc5 62. Qc6 Bd6 (62... Qd6 63. Rxc5 Qxc6 64. dxc6 {White wins the d5 pawn and the game, although it takes over 30 more moves.} (64. Rxc6 bxc3 65. Rf6 (65. Rxc3 g4) 65... f4) 64... h3 65. Rxf5 (65. Rxa5 g4 66. Ra8+ (66. cxb4 h2 67. Ra8+ Kc7) 66... Kc7) 65... g4) 63. Qc8+ {Under time pressure White fails to calculate} Ke7 64. Qe6+ Kd8 65. Rc8# 1-0


