{I've often wondered about the silly question: what is the best way to deal with the 'hippopotamus'? Iranian prodigy, Parham Maghsoodloo may have answered my question...} 1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. Bf4 ({RR} 6. O-O Ne7 7. Bg5 h6 8. Be3 b6 9. a4 a5 10. Qd2 Bb7 11. Ne1 f5 12. f3 Nf6 13. Bb5+ Bc6 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Ne7 17. c4 Kf7 18. Nd3 Qd7 19. Nxf6 Bxf6 20. Bxh6 Nc6 {Karpov,A (2720)-Spassky,B (2625) Hamburg 1982 1-0}) ({RR} 6. Be3 Ne7 7. Qd2 h6 8. h3 a6 9. O-O b6 10. Rfe1 Bb7 11. Rad1 f5 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Be3 Qf6 15. Nh2 Kh7 16. Bf3 d5 17. Ne2 {½-½ (17) Belin,A (1891)-Zweschper,E (1999) Germany 2024}) 6... Ne7 7. Qd2 h6 8. h4 b6 $146 ({RR} 8... a6 9. a4 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Rfe1 Kf8 12. Rad1 Kg8 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. e5 dxe5 15. dxe5 Nc5 16. Qe3 Qe7 17. Be4 a5 18. b3 Rf8 19. Rd2 f5 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Bxc6 Bxc6 22. Be5 Qe7 23. Bxg7 {Estrada Nieto,J (2329)-Tobar,J (2016) Cali 2010 1-0 (32)}) ({RR} 8... a6 9. a4 b6 10. e5 d5 11. Nd1 c5 12. c3 Nc6 13. Ne3 Bb7 14. Bd3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qe7 16. Nc2 Na5 17. Qe2 Rc8 18. O-O O-O 19. Qe3 Nc4 20. Qc1 Kh7 21. h5 Rc7 22. g4 Rfc8 23. Kg2 {Potkin,V (2552)-Azimi,R (2144) Warsaw 2005 1-0}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Rad1 a6 11. Rfe1 Qb8 $2 {It's astonishing that such dubious chess would feature in the classical portion of any of the World Cup matches. Black surely had better ways to play for a win than to play for a loss?!} (11... Kf8 $6 {is sometimes employed as a way to artificially castle. White may as well pre-empt this with} 12. Bd3 Kg8 13. Ne2 Kh7 14. h5 Rf8 15. hxg6+ fxg6 (15... Nxg6 $6 16. Ng3) 16. Bg3 {[%cal Ge2f4]} e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Qc3 $16 {Once the position opens up in the centre, Black is usually struggling.}) (11... Nf6 {is provocative, but perhaps best.} 12. e5 (12. Bd3 Nh5 {1-0 (57) Oliveira,D (2105)-Wallach,N (2165) WC-2017-Q-00001 2014} 13. Bh2 {is likely to transpose, albeit with even more shuffling.} O-O 14. Qe2 Nf6 15. e5 Ng4 16. Bf4 Nf5 17. h5 g5 18. Bc1) 12... Ng4 {Now logical is to shuffle the pieces around a little. Note that in closed positions, loss of tempi is not a huge deal.} 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Qe2 Nf5 15. h5 g5 16. Bc1 {Black now must go in for} Nxd4 $1 17. Nxd4 Nxe5 18. Be4 (18. Ne4 $36) 18... d5 19. Nf3 Nc6 (19... Nd7 20. Nxd5 $1 exd5 21. Bxd5 $18) 20. Bd3 Re8 21. Qd2 {when it is understandable that Black doesn't have quite enough compensation. Then again you can easily imagine the tables turning after} f5 {...Qf6, and so on.}) 12. a4 Qa7 {White has optimised his position. What next?} 13. e5 $1 {In light of White's forthcoming knight manoeuvre, this change in structure is favourable one.} d5 14. Bf1 Qb8 15. Ne2 c5 16. c3 c4 17. Ng3 Qc7 18. Nh2 $1 {The key manoeuvre in White's game plan, loading up several pieces against the weak h6-pawn.} Nf5 $6 {After this anti-positional move, Black's king was not safe on any part of the board.} ({The issue is that} 18... Nc6 19. Ng4 {also looks grim.}) (18... h5 {feels cooperative, although it was possibly the most tenacious out of Black's options.} 19. Bg5 Nc6 20. Ne2 {(hinting at g4 one day)} Nf8 $5 {and Black is still kicking as ...Nh7 will force the bishop off its desired course.}) 19. Nxf5 gxf5 20. Be2 O-O-O 21. Nf1 $18 {After having fulfilled its job on h2, the knight proceeds to eye-up the newly-created weakness on h5.} Rdg8 22. Ng3 Qd8 23. b3 $1 {My old coach used to assert that one should 'crack from both sides', particularly the case in closed positions.} cxb3 24. c4 {This should be close to winning and is definitely natural however my engine somewhat dislikes it.} (24. Rb1 $18) (24. Bh5) 24... dxc4 25. Bxc4 Kb8 (25... Bf8 26. d5 Nc5 27. d6 Rg4 28. Be2 (28. f3 Rxh4 29. Nxf5 Rxf4 30. Qxf4 Qg5 31. Qxg5 hxg5 32. Nd4 $16) 28... Rxh4 29. a5 $18) 26. d5 Nc5 27. Qe3 Qxh4 (27... exd5 28. Nxf5 Ne6 29. Bxb3 $18) 28. a5 Bf8 $6 (28... Rc8 29. axb6 h5 30. Be2 $16 {[%cal Ge2f3]}) 29. Nxf5 $1 Qg4 (29... exf5 30. e6+ Ka7 (30... Ka8 31. exf7 $18) 31. axb6+ Kxb6 32. Rb1 $18) 30. Ng3 b5 (30... h5 {is also hopeless:} 31. axb6 h4 32. dxe6 fxe6 33. Rd8+ Bc8 34. b7 Nxb7 35. Rxc8+ Kxc8 36. Bxa6 hxg3 37. Bxb7+ Kb8 38. Bf3 $18) 31. Be2 Qh4 32. d6 Na4 33. Rc1 $1 Rg4 34. Rc7 {Power play!} Rxf4 35. Rec1 Rc4 36. R1xc4 bxc4 37. Bf3 1-0


