{Finally, we will examine the plan after ...d5-d4 based on e2-e4, typically answered with ...dxe3. We usually reach this structure from the ...Nh6 systems with plenty of concrete examples. Now I will try to clarify the issue more abstractly, using a game from another line. GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Finally, we will examine the plan after ...d5-d4 based on e2-e4, typically answered with ...dxe3. We usually reach this structure from the ...Nh6 systems with plenty of concrete examples. Now I will try to clarify the issue more abstractly, using a game from another line. A03: Bird's Opening with 1...d5'} 1. f4 {GM Mihail Marin, MH} d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 c5 7. c3 d4 {[%eval 1,19]} (7... Nc6 $15 {[%eval -37,16] GM Mihail Marin, MH} 8. Na3 Qc7 9. Qc2 e5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Nb5 Qb6 12. fxe5 Ng4 13. Na3 Be6 14. Qb3 Qxb3 15. axb3 Nxe5 16. Nb5 Nc6 17. Bf4 a6 18. Nc7 Rad8 19. Be3 d4 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Bd2 {Bird's Opening-1 f4 d5 ChessPub Guide 2020 Flank Openings [ChessPublishing.com]}) ({RR} 7... b6 8. e4 dxe4 9. dxe4 Ba6 10. Re1 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nc6 12. e5 Ng4 13. Ng5 Rfd8 14. Re1 Rac8 15. Na3 h6 16. Ne4 h5 17. h3 Nh6 18. Be3 f6 19. exf6 exf6 20. Rad1 Nf5 21. Bf2 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 {Danielsen,H (2526)-Schandorff,L (2551) Reykjavik 2001 0-1 (55)}) 8. e4 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '='} dxe3 ({RR} 8... Nc6 9. Qe2 Ne8 10. cxd4 cxd4 11. Na3 f6 12. Bd2 Nd6 13. Rfc1 {½-½ (13) Dietz,J (2122)-Ahmels,V (2163) Germany 2024}) 9. Bxe3 {This is the aforementioned structure. With the pawn on f2 this would be a typical reversed King's Indian, but the extra tempo f2-f4 by itself is not enough to make the difference between a comfortable and a better position. We also need some sort of commitment by Black. ***In the systems from our repertoire, the slightly unnatural ...Nh6 does the work. If the knight stays there, White has h2-h3 and g3-g4 to keep it out of play. If it jumps to f5, White can gain time for his kingside attack with g3-g4 and f4-f5. ***In this position Black's main problem is his delayed queenside development. In the similar position with reversed colours White has the extra tempo Nc3, allowing him to react with b2-b3 or Qd3. But here Black has to make a concession.} Qc7 $6 {A curious mistake by such an experienced grandmaster. Moving with the queen in a moment when the whole queenside is undeveloped is a huge commitment. Black was probably dreaming of . ..b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7 and ...Nc6, reaching the most active setup, but this is impossible. GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'N' GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'A curious mistake by such an experienced grandmaster. Moving with the queen in a moment when the whole queenside is undeveloped is a huge commitment. Black was probably dreaming of . ..b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7 and ...Nc6, reaching the most active setup, but this is impossible. The position is equal.'} ({Safer was} 9... Nbd7 10. Na3 b6 {when White could think of starting a positional attack with} 11. Ng5 Rb8 12. f5) (9... Bf5 {GM Mihail Marin, MH} 10. Bxc5 Bxd3 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nd4 Bxb1 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Bxe7 {[%emt 0:00:07] Chapter 1-Game 7 Game}) 10. Na3 $146 ({RR} 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb6 13. Na3 Be6 14. Rc1 Qb8 15. b3 Nbd5 16. Bd2 Rc8 17. Qe2 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 a6 19. Rc5 Qd8 20. Kh1 Rc8 {½-½ (20) Tammela,K-Linqvist,G Tampere 1989}) ({RR} 10. Kh1 b6 11. Na3 Bb7 12. Qe2 Nc6 13. d4 cxd4 14. Nb5 d3 15. Qxd3 Rad8 16. Qxg6 hxg6 17. Nxc7 Ng4 18. Bg1 e5 19. h3 Nh6 20. fxe5 Nf5 21. Rfe1 Nxg3+ 22. Kh2 Nf5 23. e6 Nce7 24. exf7+ Rxf7 {David,A (2250)-Hoerstmann,R (2227) Germany 2018 1-0}) 10... e6 {[%eval 58,18]} ({The first concession provokes another one. Black spends another tempo on clearing the e7-square for the queen. If} 10... b6 {[%eval 97,20] he obviously did not like GM Mihail Marin, MH: '10...Rf8-d8 0.12 he obviously did not like'} 11. Nb5 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!'} Qd8 12. Ne5 {After GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'After. Prevents Nf6-g4.'} Nd5 {the least White can do is win an exchange with 13. Bxd5 Qxd5 14.Nc7, but he could also play for a lead in development if he is not too keen on weakening the long diagonal:} 13. Bf2 a6 14. Qb3 e6 15. Na3 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!' GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Threatens to win with c3-c4.'} Ra7 16. Rad1 {followed by d3-d4 soon. ***Black must have thought that his last move also takes measures against f4-f5, but he was wrong.}) (10... Be6 $11 {[%eval 15,18] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 11. Qe2 b6 $6 {Consistent but bad.} 12. f5 $3 {The only thing missing for a successful queen hunt was the dark-squared bishop's participation. By clearing the f4-square, White achieves that. GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!'} (12. Nb5 {[%eval 39,22] GM Mihail Marin, MH: '12.f4-f5 0.87'} Qe7 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!'} 13. d4 $14 {would also have been good.}) ({The "indifferent"} 12. Rad1 $6 {allows Black to reach the desired coordination:} Bb7 13. Nc4 {[%eval 1,20]} (13. d4 $14 {[%eval 57,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 13... Nc6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '='} 14. Rfe1 Rad8 {Both sides are doing fine here but in principle this would be a moral victory for Black.}) 12... exf5 ({Or if} 12... gxf5 {[%eval 142,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH: '12...e6xf5 1.04'} 13. Bf4 Qe7 {[%eval 393,22] GM Mihail Marin, MH: '?'} ({Black has to keep the queen on the seventh rank in order to allow ... Bb7 after the discovered attack along the long diagonal. But} 13... Qd7 {[%eval 436,21] runs into GM Mihail Marin, MH: '?' GM Mihail Marin, MH: '13...Qc7-d8 1.35 runs into'} 14. Ne5) (13... Qd8 $16 {[%eval 144,24] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 14. Nh4 $1 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '+-!' GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'And now Nh4xf5 would win.'} Bb7 {[%eval 618,22]} (14... Qd7 $142 {[%eval 419,20] GM Mihail Marin, MH} 15. Bxa8 Ba6) 15. Nxf5 $1 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '+-!'} Qd7 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Nxg7 Kxg7 18. Be5 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'White wants to mate with Qe2-g4+.'} Nbd7 19. Rxf6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Intending Qe2-g4+ and mate.'} Nxf6 20. Qg4+ {, mating soon.}) 13. Bf4 Qd8 {Sadly, e7 is not available anymore.} 14. Ne1 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '&Bianco is more active.'} Nd5 15. c4 {White won a piece and later the game. GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!'} Bb7 {[%eval 110,23]} (15... Nc7 16. Bxc7) 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Nb5 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Strongly threatening Nb5-c7.'} Nc6 18. Nf3 Qd7 19. Qd2 Rad8 20. Nc3 Bxf3 21. Rxf3 Ne5 22. Bxe5 Bxe5 23. Kh1 Bg7 24. Rd1 a6 {[%eval 135,21]} (24... Rde8 $142 {[%eval 103,22] GM Mihail Marin, MH} 25. b3 Re7) 25. Rff1 {[%eval 103,21]} ({White should play} 25. Rf2 {[%eval 135,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 25... h5 {[%eval 149,21]} (25... Qd4 $142 {[%eval 103,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 26. Qc2 Rfe8 27. Nd5 Re6 28. Nf4 {[%eval 76,21]} ({White should try} 28. Rde1 {[%eval 145,19] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 28... Rd6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: ''} 29. Rde1 {[%eval 41,22]} (29. Rf3 $16 {[%eval 78,20] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 29... Bh6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: ''} 30. Qc4 a5 31. b3 Rd4 32. Qa6 Qd6 33. Qb7 h4 34. Ne2 Rxd3 {[%eval 86,23]} (34... Rb4 $1 $14 {[%eval 45,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 35. gxh4 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: ''} Bd2 36. Rd1 Kg7 37. Ng1 Qf6 38. Nf3 Bf4 39. Rxd3 Rxd3 40. Qa6 (40. Ng5 $6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH} Bxg5 41. hxg5 Qd8 $11) 40... Re3 41. Qc4 Bc7 42. Qd5 {[%eval 62,21]} (42. Qc2 $16 {[%eval 108,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH}) 42... Re4 {[%eval 135,23]} (42... Qd6 $14 {[%eval 62,21] GM Mihail Marin, MH} 43. Qxd6 Bxd6) 43. h5 g5 {[%eval 238,24] GM Mihail Marin, MH: '[#]'} (43... Re3 $16 {[%eval 124,20] (GM Mihail Marin, MH) was worth a try.}) 44. Nxg5 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '+-!'} Qxg5 45. Bxe4 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Pin'} Qh4 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '[#]'} 46. h6+ {[%eval 125,24]} ({Resist} 46. Rg1+ $6 {GM Mihail Marin, MH} Kf8 47. Qd2 (47. Qa8+ Ke7 $17) 47... Qxe4+ 48. Qg2 Qe6 49. Qa8+ (49. h6 Qxh6 50. Qa8+ Ke7 $14) 49... Ke7) (46. Qd2 $1 $18 {[%eval 246,28] GM Mihail Marin, MH} Qxe4+ (46... fxe4 47. Rg1+) 47. Qg2+ Kf8 48. Qxe4 fxe4 49. Rf6) 46... Qxh6 {[%eval 561,25] GM Mihail Marin, MH: '?' GM Mihail Marin, MH: '[#] A mistake that costs the game.'} (46... Kf8 $16 {[%eval 125,24] (GM Mihail Marin, MH) is more resistant.} 47. Qd2 (47. Qa8+ Ke7 $11) 47... fxe4) 47. Rf2 {GM Mihail Marin, MH: '!' GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'White is clearly winning.'} Qc1+ (47... Bxh2 {GM Mihail Marin, MH} 48. Rxf5) 48. Kg2 Qg5+ 49. Kf1 Qc1+ 50. Ke2 Qb2+ 51. Kf3 fxe4+ 52. Kg2 Qe5 53. Qxf7+ {GM Mihail Marin, MH: 'Weighted Error Value: White=0.09 (flawless) /Black=0.32'} 1-0


