{Although Maghsoodloo is an extremely strong player, I've noticed that he is often not well-prepared theoretically. However, his deep tactical and strategic understanding often gives him the confidence to enter such positions. Very often, his opponents are not well-prepared enough to punish him.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 (6. c3 c5 {Even in this case, when the knight is not on c6, White can still capture on c5.} 7. dxc5 {This move can only be played if White has already played c3 earlier, and not now after 6.Be2.}) 6... c5 7. c3 Qb6 8. Qb3 Nc6 9. O-O Bf5 10. h3 h6 $2 {Simply very bad... As so often, neither White nor Black is well-prepared in the Torre with g6!} ({RR} 10... Rfe8 11. Bf4 Ne4 12. g4 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 Bc8 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Bc7 cxd4 16. exd4 e5 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 Rxe5 19. Rfe1 Be6 20. a3 d4 21. Nf3 Re4 22. Nxd4 Nxd4 23. cxd4 Rxd4 24. Rad1 Rad8 25. Rxd4 {Tomashevsky,E (2722)-Volokitin,A (2668) Novi Sad 2016 ½-½ (39)}) 11. Bh4 $146 (11. Bxf6 Bxf6 (11... Qxb3 12. Nxb3 (12. axb3 Bxf6 13. dxc5 {And even this is good. Black doesn't have sufficient compensation.} e5 14. b4 d4 {What should White play? In situations like this, White should avoid opening the center when Black has the pair of bishops.} (14... e4 15. Nd4) 15. e4 {This is the correct move.} Be6 16. Bc4 (16. b5 dxc3 17. bxc3 Ne7) 16... Bxc4 17. Nxc4 {After the exchange of bishops, Black has no counterplay and still remains a pawn down.}) 12... Bxf6 13. Nxc5 $18) 12. Qxd5 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxb2 14. a4 $3 Rfd8 15. Qb5 $16) (11. Bf4 {As we know, White can play his standard plan.} c4 ({Let's say Black plays a move like} 11... Rac8 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Nd4 {and if we're not sure about capturing on b7, we can even play this move instead.} (13. Qxb7) 13... Nxd4 14. exd4 Qc6 15. Rfe1 $14 {As we already know, this position is slightly better for White.}) 12. Qa3 Rfe8 13. b3) ({RR} 11. Bf4 c4 12. Qa3 Qd8 13. Ne5 g5 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Be5 Ne4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. b3 cxb3 19. axb3 Qd7 20. Qc5 Rfb8 21. b4 Rb7 22. Ra6 Rc7 23. f3 Bg6 24. e4 Rb8 25. Rfa1 Rbb7 {Gvanceladze,A (2182)-Agrest,I (2281) Iasi 2021 ½-½ (40)}) ({RR} 11. Bf4 Nd7 12. g4 Be6 13. Rfe1 Rac8 14. Bf1 f5 15. gxf5 gxf5 16. Bg2 Bf7 17. Kh2 Kh7 18. Rad1 Bf6 19. Bg3 Qxb3 20. axb3 a5 21. Ra1 b6 22. Bf1 e5 23. Ba6 Rce8 24. Bb5 Rc8 25. Bxc6 Rxc6 {Tristan,L (2527)-Fiorenza,B (1934) Buenos Aires 2024 1-0 (43)}) ({RR} 11. Bf4 g5 12. Bh2 c4 13. Qa3 Qd8 14. b3 b5 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Bd1 a6 17. Qb2 Bd3 18. Re1 Ne4 19. Be2 Qa5 20. Rac1 Qb5 21. Qa3 Qa5 22. Qb2 e5 23. Bxd3 cxd3 24. dxe5 Qb5 25. Qa3 Qa5 {Kumar,P (2040)-Blom,V (2325) Amsterdam 2022 ½-½ (53)}) 11... g5 12. Bg3 c4 13. Qa3 Qa5 14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Ne5 $14 (15. h4 $5) 15... Rac8 16. f4 e6 17. fxg5 hxg5 18. h4 g4 19. Rxf5 $6 {White sacrifices the rook and, after many complications, still manages to win the game.} (19. e4 $5) 19... exf5 20. Rf1 Nh5 21. Kh2 Nc6 22. Nxc6 bxc6 23. Bd6 Rfd8 24. Ba3 Bh6 25. Rxf5 Ng7 26. Rf6 g3+ 27. Kxg3 $17 Bxe3 28. Nf1 Bc1 29. Bg4 Re8 30. Kh2 Rb8 31. Rxc6 Rb6 32. Rxb6 axb6 33. Bf3 Nf5 34. Bxd5 b5 35. Kh3 Re1 36. Ng3 Ne3 37. Bf3 Nc2 38. Bc5 Bxb2 39. Ne4 b4 40. d5 Bxc3 41. Nxc3 bxc3 42. d6 Rb1 43. d7 Rb8 44. Be7 Ne3 45. Bg5 Nf5 46. d8=Q+ Rxd8 47. Bxd8 c2 48. Bg5 Nd4 49. a4 c3 50. Be4 f6 51. Be3 1-0


