1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. Qc2 b6 5. e3 Bb7 6. f3 c5 7. d5 $5 {The critical reaction.} (7. a3 {was examined in Harsha, B - Sandipan, C Kolkata 2018, see the archives.}) 7... exd5 ({There are alternatives, but they haven't been investigated very much:} 7... Na6 {(I can't see any problem with this)} 8. a3 ({after the} 8. e4 {of Dambacher, M - Froeyman, H Belgian league 2012, I suggest} Bd6 $1 {with dynamic play}) 8... Nc7 9. e4 Bd6 $1 {(a great square for the bishop)} 10. Bg5 h6 ({also promising is} 10... O-O {with a healthy lead in development}) 11. Bh4 Qe7 12. O-O-O g5 {Standke, W - Poljak, D e-mail 2016, with ...0-0-0 to follow shortly, Black is sitting pretty.}) ({Although} 7... Qe7 {gave Black a good position in the following, maybe it's just bluff:} 8. Nh3 (8. Nb5 $1 {looks like the biggest test, when the engine then goes for} Qd8 {hence my suspicion that 7...Qe7 isn't that great}) 8... exd5 9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Nf4 Bf7 11. Qxf5 g6 12. Qd3 Bg7 13. Nfd5 ({the calm} 13. Be2 {can be met by the annoying} c4 $5) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qe5 15. e4 O-O $15 {Goossens, E - Horvath, J Belgian league 2013, and Black had the easier development.}) 8. cxd5 ({I'm not sure what to make of White's queen moves in the following:} 8. Qxf5 dxc4 (8... d4 {is an engine suggestion}) 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. Nh3 Qe7 11. Nf4 Qe5 12. Qh3 {(is the queen happy here?)} O-O-O 13. Nd3 Qe8 $13 {Grover, S - Girinath, P Kottayam 2014. I quite like Black here as his development looks more convincing.}) 8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Qxf5 Be6 ({A recent novel try is artificial and won't get many followers:} 10... Qh4+ $2 11. g3 Qb4+ 12. Kf2 Be6 13. Qc2 {(the black queen is awkwardly placed, so it needs an escape route, hence Black's next move)} c4 14. Ne2 d5 15. Nf4 Qd6 16. b3 $16 {Atalik, E - Ovod, E Antalya 2019, and White had a significant advantage. Black's queen manoeuvre has just lost time and led to the compromising ...c4 advance.}) 11. Qe4 Nc6 12. Bc4 ({Previously} 12. Bb5 {had been played:} Rc8 ({alternatively the} 12... Qc7 13. Ne2 Bd6 $11 14. Bc4 {of Loginov, A - Driamin, D Saratov 1999, should be met with castling...either way!}) 13. Ne2 Qe7 14. Bd2 g6 (14... Bf7 $5) 15. Bc3 Bg7 16. Nf4 (16. Rd1 $1 $14 {keeps some pressure, as it's difficult for Black to liberate with ...d5 under satisfactory circumstances}) 16... Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Bf7 {Bernasek, J - Gleizerov, E Brno 2012, with near equality as the hole on d5 is hardly significant.}) 12... Qe7 13. Ne2 ({The double trade on e6 is inoffensive, so following} 13. Bxe6 Qxe6 14. Qxe6+ dxe6 15. Bd2 Be7 16. Bc3 Kf7 {Black has no problems, despite having more pawn islands.}) 13... Bg8 $5 {A curious-looking move, but it obliges 'not unfavourable' exchanges.} 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. Bxg8 Rxg8 16. Nc3 Bf6 17. Nd5 {White has an excellent knight on d5, but his other pieces are rather poor. So the young Iranian star plays on this fact.} Rc8 18. Ke2 Ne7 19. Rd1 c4 20. Rb1 Rc5 {The outpost on d5 is about to go, but White at least has a choice of what to do with his knight.} 21. Nxe7 ({After} 21. Nxf6+ gxf6 22. Kf1 ({worse is} 22. Kf2 Nc6) 22... Nc6 $13 {the knight is heading for d3.}) ({Keeping the tension with} 21. Nb4 $5 {is all very well, but what's the plan?}) 21... Kxe7 22. Bd2 Rb5 23. Bc3 {This ensures near equality, but there is still a great deal of work to do to earn a draw.} ({It might have been preferable to instead opt for} 23. Rdc1 Rc8 24. Bc3 $11 {when he can always recapture on c3 with a rook.}) 23... Bxc3 24. bxc3 Ra5 25. Rb2 Rc8 26. Rd4 Ra3 {The split queenside pawns mean that White is going to find himself on the defensive.} 27. Rc2 Rc5 {When the opponent isn't doing very much, there's rarely any harm in improving one's pieces!} 28. e4 Rca5 29. Rdd2 ({Correctly avoiding} 29. Rxc4 $2 Rxa2 $17) 29... b5 30. Kf2 Ra6 31. Rb2 Rb6 32. Rbc2 Rd6 $1 {An exchange of rooks emphasizes the passivity of White's game.} 33. Ke2 a5 34. h4 Rxd2+ 35. Kxd2 Kd6 36. Kc1 Kc5 37. Kb1 (37. Kb2 {just encourages} b4) 37... d6 {There is no rush!} 38. Rd2 $2 {Cracking too easily....but he wasn't yet at move forty!} ({He should have been more patient and continued defending the queenside whilst preparing for potential counterplay. So I would suggest} 38. h5 h6 39. Kb2 b4 40. Rc1 {and then temporizing with Rc1-c2-c1 until Black commits himself.}) 38... Rxc3 39. Rd5+ Kc6 40. Rg5 g6 41. h5 gxh5 42. Rxh5 Re3 43. a4 ({If} 43. Rxh7 {then} Re1+ 44. Kc2 Re2+ 45. Kb1 Rxg2) 43... Re1+ 44. Kc2 b4 $1 {Two connected passed pawns are so strong they don't require the king's support.} 45. Rxa5 b3+ 46. Kc3 Rc1+ 47. Kb2 Rc2+ 48. Kb1 Ra2 {The threat is ...c4-c3-c2 etc.} 49. Ra8 {After} Kc5 {it's of course hopeless:} 50. Rb8 $146 Rxg2 51. a5 Kd4 52. a6 Kc3 {and mate ends the game.} 0-1


