1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 Be7 10. Nf3 b5 11. a3 {A new move for our PGN Archive. Undoubtedly it was analyzed by GM Shankland in detail during his home preparation.} (11. e5 b4 12. exf6 bxc3 13. Qxc3 gxf6 {was covered on our site a long time ago in Heinemann,T (2468)-Chandler,M (2526) Solingen GER 2001 [John Fedorowicz]. Since then this complex position was deeply analyzed and tested at a high level, and still it seems acceptable for Black.}) ({The relatively rare} 11. Bd3 {yielded White a memorable victory in Shirov,A (2636) -Le Quang Liem (2715) Douglas ENG 2018 [Roiz,M], but objectively it doesn't set Black serious problems.}) ({The main} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Kb1 Qb6 {is covered in Zou,C (2440)-Sethuraman,S (2630) Changsha CHN 2019 [Roiz,M]}) 11... b4 {The most aggressive and common response. Black is trying to exploit the drawbacks of the early a2-a3 by opening the b-file.} ({Deserving serious attention is} 11... h6 $5 12. Bh4 ({After} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qxd6 Be7 14. Qd2 Qc7 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation for a pawn, to say the least.}) 12... Qa5 (12... b4 13. axb4 Nxb4 14. Kb1 {might transpose to text.}) 13. Kb1 ({Premature is} 13. e5 $2 b4 14. axb4 Nxb4 $40 {Antal,G - Toth,A Budapest 1998}) 13... Rd8 {This interesting position was only tested in 2 correspondence games so far. At the moment, it looks like Black's chances are not worse. For instance,} 14. e5 ({After} 14. Qe1 Rb8 15. e5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 b4 17. axb4 Qxb4 18. b3 Na5 $1 {Black gained the upper hand in Kroes,F - Ulasevich,S email 2010}) 14... dxe5 15. fxe5 Bc8 16. Bd3 {This was Laureles,R - Dehaybe,A LSS email 2009 Black should have played} Nd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd2 18. Nc7+ Kd7 19. Rxd2 Kxc7 $11) 12. axb4 Nxb4 13. Kb1 h6 {As the route of this game proves, this is insufficient to reach equality.} ({In my opinion, more challenging was} 13... Bc6 $5 14. Bc4 Rb8 ({But not} 14... O-O $6 15. e5 $1 ({Instead,} 15. Rhe1 Qc7 {was fine for Black in Vasiukov,E-Veid,R Moscow 1962}) 15... dxe5 16. Qxd8 Bxd8 17. Nxe5 {, and Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 15. Rhe1 ({White achieves nothing special after} 15. e5 dxe5 16. Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rxd8+ Bxd8 18. Nxe5 Bxg2 19. Rg1 Bh3 $13) 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. f5 O-O 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Bxe6+ Kh7 $44 {The powerful bishops provide Black decent compensation for a pawn.}) 14. Bh4 {might transpose to text.} Rb8 {This natural move is a novelty. However, most likely it was still covered by Sam before the game.} ({The only preceding correspondence game saw} 14... Qa5 15. Bc4 Bc6 16. Rhe1 ({Deserving of serious attention is} 16. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 17. Na2 Rb8 18. Qxd6 Rb6 19. Nxb4 Qxb4 20. Bb3 {, and Black struggles to show adequate compensation for a pawn.}) 16... O-O 17. f5 e5 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. g4 Rab8 $132 {Silva,M -Corti,H email 2012}) ({In comparison to the above-mentioned note, now} 14... Bc6 {seems less effective in view of} 15. f5 $1 Rb8 16. fxe6 fxe6 17. Bc4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Bxe7 Kxe7 20. Bb3 $36 {, and White's initiative overwhelms the pawn.}) 15. e5 dxe5 $6 {This natural move leads to a very unpleasant endgame.} ({The lesser evil was} 15... Nfd5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. exd6 Qxd6 19. Qe3+ Kf8 20. Bd3 $14 {, though then Black suffers from a weak isolated pawn.}) 16. Nxe5 $146 {The pressure along the d-file and the weak Pa6 makes Black's position difficult.} ({RR} 16. fxe5 Nfd5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Ne4 O-O 19. c4 Ba4 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. Nd6 Rc5 22. Nd4 Nc7 23. Qe3 Qg5 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. Re1 Ne8 26. h4 Nxd6 27. exd6 g4 28. Be2 Rd8 29. b3 Rxd6 30. Rd1 e5 {Jacobson,A (2276)-Sjugirov,S (2661) Chess.com INT 2021 ½-½ (62)}) 16... Rb7 (16... Bc6 17. Qxd8+ Bxd8 18. Nxc6 Nxc6 19. Bxa6 O-O 20. Bf2 $16) 17. Bc4 Bb5 $2 {Parham fails to stand the pressure.} ({The only way to put-up resistance was} 17... Qc7 18. Rhe1 (18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Qxd7+ Qxd7 20. Nxd7 Rxd7 21. Ne4 Rc7 $16) 18... Bc8 19. f5 O-O 20. fxe6 Bxe6 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Ng6 Nbd5 $1 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. Nxe7+ Nxe7 $16 {The e6 and a6 pawns are very weak, but Black still has some counterplay.}) 18. Qxd8+ Bxd8 19. Nxb5 axb5 20. Bxb5+ $1 {A simple, but beautiful tactical shot.} Rxb5 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. Nxf7+ Ke7 23. Nxh8 {White is 2 pawns up, while the Nh8 would soon be back in play.} g5 24. Ng6+ Kf7 25. Ne5+ Kg7 26. c4 1-0


