{[%evp 20,84,-3,-39,-32,-22,63,85,73,72,98,64,70,67,69,45,66,35,29,9,1,-78,81,71,103,91,94,49,52,41,42,39,75,72,91,82,99,76,107,72,130,119,136,-360,-360,-375,-363,-391,-391,-388,-351,-377,-346,-421,-347,-620,-399,-702,-694,-742,-687,-1056,-923,-1362,-1078,-29995,-29996] B68: Sicilian: Richter-Rauzer: 7...a6 8 0-0-0 Bd7 9 f4 Be7  Upon winning the Candidates Tournament in October of 1955, Olga was supposed to face the defending champion, Elisaveta Bykova. Instead, FIDE organized a triangular competition between the top 3 players of the world at that time. So, in addition to Olga and Bykova, former world champion Lyudmila Rudenko entered the arena. Their unusual tournament was held in Moscow in 1956 and involved 8-game mini-matches. These three ladies had several Moscow championships and Soviet championships under their belts. Just a few years earlier, Rudenko had bested both crowning herself world champion. Back then, Olga had been runner-up. Bykova, the youngest of the trio, had defeated Rudenko in a match and then successfully defended her title against a brilliant challenger, Kira Zvorykina. So Olga was likely the underdog, the only one of the three who had not clenched the world title. Olga eventually prevailed by scoring half a point more than Bykova in the overall table. The following game has our chapter's protagonist clashing with Rudenko, who was featured in the 3rd chapter of this course--see Lyudmila, the Second. [/course/102010/4]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 (9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. Qe1 h6 11. Bf4 Qb8 12. Nd5 Nd7 13. Kb1 b5 14. f3 Bb7 15. Ne3 Be7 16. h4 Qc7 17. Be2 Qc5 18. Rd3 Ne5 19. Rc3 Qb6 20. Bxe5 dxe5 21. Qg3 O-O 22. Ng4 b4 23. Rd3 Rac8 {1-0 Kaminski,V (2608)-Kurenny (2609) Sleipner International 1990}) 9... Be7 10. Nxc6 $146 (10. Nf3 Qa5 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 exd5 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Rxd5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 Rhd8 17. Rxd7+ Rxd7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. Bc4 f5 20. Re1 Re8 21. Rxe8 Kxe8 22. Bd5 Nd4 23. Kd2 b6 24. a4 Ke7 {1-0 5) Olga The Fourth-Rubtsova,O Queens of the Chess Board 2023}) 10... Bxc6 11. Bd3 {[%eval -39,18]} (11. Qe3 $11 {[%eval -3,17]}) ({RR} 11. Qe1 Qc7 12. Bd3 O-O-O 13. Kb1 Kb8 14. Rf1 Rhe8 15. h3 h6 16. Bh4 Nd7 17. Bf2 d5 18. exd5 exd5 19. Qd2 Nc5 20. Bd4 Ne6 21. Ne2 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Bf6 23. Qb4 Ka8 24. g3 Qe7 25. Nxc6 bxc6 {Corrales Jimenez,F (2536)-Mortimer,J (2820) Chess.com INT 2018 ½-½ (125)}) 11... h6 $15 ({RR} 11... O-O 12. Kb1 b5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. g4 Qb6 15. g5 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 d5 17. Rhe1 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 Rac8 20. Qd2 a5 21. Rd4 b4 22. h4 Qc5 23. h5 Qf5 24. h6 a4 25. hxg7 Kxg7 26. Rd3 {Yildiz,S (2208)-Aslanov,U (2324) Chess.com INT 2025 0-1 (34)}) 12. Bh4 Nd7 $146 {[%eval 63,20]} (12... b5 $11 {[%eval -22,16]}) ({RR} 12... Qc7 13. Qe3 b5 14. Kb1 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxh4 16. f5 e5 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Rc8 19. Qe4 Bf6 20. h4 h5 21. g3 Ke7 22. Rhf1 Qb6 23. Rd3 Rc5 24. Rfd1 a5 25. a3 Rhc8 26. R3d2 Qc7 27. Bb3 {Hracek,Z (2480)-Pulkkinen,K (2265) Mlada Boleslav 1992 1-0 (54)}) ({RR} 12... g5 13. fxg5 Ng4 14. Kb1 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Qe2 Ne5 17. Rd2 O-O-O 18. Rhd1 Qe7 19. Qf2 Kb8 20. Qd4 Nxd3 21. Rxd3 Rhg8 22. g3 Rg5 23. Qb4 Kc7 24. a4 b6 25. Ne2 a5 26. Qd4 Rc5 27. Nc3 {Silman,J (2310)-Christiansen,L (2400) San Francisco 1976 ½-½ (37)}) 13. Bxe7 $14 Qxe7 {White is better.} 14. Be2 Nf6 15. Bf3 {[%cal Oh1e1]} (15. Qxd6 {with more complications.} Bxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qd4) 15... O-O-O 16. Qe3 Qc7 17. Rd3 d5 18. e5 Nd7 {[%cal Og7g5]} 19. Ne2 g5 20. g3 {[%eval -78,19] [#]} (20. Re1 $11 {[%eval 1,20]}) 20... Kb8 $2 {[%eval 81,18]} (20... g4 $1 $17 {[%eval -78,19][%cal Rg4f3]} 21. Bg2 (21. Bxg4 d4 $17) 21... d4) 21. Nd4 $16 (21. fxg5 $2 Nxe5 (21... Qxe5 22. gxh6 Qxe3+ {[%mdl 64] Remove Defender} 23. Rxe3 $11) 22. Nd4 Nxd3+ 23. cxd3 Bd7+ 24. Kb1 hxg5 25. Qxg5 e5 $19) 21... Rc8 22. Rc3 $36 {[%mdl 2048] White is on the roll.} (22. fxg5 $6 hxg5 (22... Qxe5 23. gxh6 Qf6 24. h7 $11) 23. Qxg5 Nxe5 $11 (23... Qxe5 24. Qe3 $19)) 22... Qa5 23. Ra3 {[%eval 49,18]} ({White should play} 23. Kb1 $16 {[%eval 94,18]}) 23... Qc7 24. Rd1 Nb6 25. Be2 Ba4 {[%eval 75,17]} (25... Nc4 $14 {[%eval 39,18] is more appropriate.} 26. Bxc4 dxc4) 26. Rc3 (26. fxg5 Bxc2 27. Rc3 Nc4 28. Rxc4 (28. Kxc2 $2 Nxe3+ 29. Kd2 Qxe5 $19) 28... dxc4 29. Kxc2 (29. Nxc2 hxg5 30. Qc3 Rxh2 $15) 29... hxg5 $11) 26... Qe7 27. b3 Bd7 28. Kb1 gxf4 29. gxf4 (29. Rxc8+ {simplifies} Nxc8 30. Qxf4 Be8 31. h4) 29... Qa3 {[%eval 130,17]} ({Better is} 29... Rhg8 {[%eval 72,19]}) 30. Rxc8+ Rxc8 {[#]} {This costs White the game.} 31. Nf5 $2 {[%eval -360,22][%mdl 8192]} Rc5 $19 32. Qd4 (32. Nxh6 $2 {is the wrong capture.} Na4 33. Qd4 Nc3+ $19) 32... exf5 33. Rg1 Be6 34. Rg3 Rc6 35. Rh3 Qf8 36. a4 Nd7 37. Qf2 $2 {[%eval -620,18]} (37. Kb2 {[%eval -347,19]}) 37... Nc5 {[%cal Bd7c5,Bc5e4,Be4f2][%mdl 32]} 38. Qh4 $2 {[%eval -702,18]} (38. Kb2 {[%eval -399,22]}) 38... Ne4 39. Bd3 Qc5 40. Qxh6 Nf2 {[%cal Of2d3] White must now prevent ...Nxd3!.} 41. Qh8+ Rc8 42. Qh6 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.92/Black=0.51} Nxd3 {[%mdl 64] Remove Defender} 0-1


