1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 $5 {A novel idea that I hadn't seen before. Black has been playing this with some success recently and yet it is isn't mentioned by Avrukh!} 7. Qc2 Bg4 {White has scored woefully from this position. Is this because he has often been surprised and hasn't been able to find a good plan OTB, or is it that Black's idea is simply good!?} 8. h3 (8. Nge2) 8... Be6 (8... Bh5 9. f4) 9. Bd3 Nh5 $5 {New, but as this line is still in its early days Black has experimented with various ideas at this point:} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 $1 11. g4 Nf6 12. Nge2 Nbd7 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Ng3 (14. Na4) 14... Kb8 $11 {Black is comfortable and the asymmetric pawn structure offers him his share of the chances.} 15. Kb1 Nb6 16. f3 $146 {Premature, as White doesn't have the reserves in place to support this early advance.} ({RR} 16. Rhe1 h5 17. g5 Ne8 18. h4 Bg4 19. Be2 Bxe2 20. Ngxe2 Nd6 21. Nf4 g6 22. f3 Nf5 23. Qf2 Qd6 24. Nd3 Rhf8 25. Ne5 f6 26. Nxg6 Rg8 27. e4 Nxd4 28. Rxd4 Rxg6 29. f4 fxg5 30. hxg5 Rf8 {Moranda,W (2533)-Grabarczyk,M (2476) Lublin 2008 ½-½ (48)}) 16... Ne8 17. Rhe1 Nc7 (17... Nd6 18. e4) 18. Bf1 Rd7 {Keeping a careful eye on d6.} 19. f4 (19. e4 dxe4 20. fxe4 {Maghsoodloo is running his opponent out of any activity that he might aspire to.} Rhd8 21. Qf2 $1 {As it's on offer, why not?} Qb4) 19... f6 (19... Rdd8 20. f5 Bc8) 20. f5 (20. Bd3 Qd8) 20... Bf7 {White's e2-e4 advance has left him with a hole on d4. Rather than admit the error of his ways (and go back with his queen to d1 with a small disadvantage) he goes for a crazy idea that is easily rebuffed.} 21. e4 $2 dxe4 {Good, but there might be even better.} 22. Ngxe4 $2 Re8 $1 {The threat of ...d6 calls for drastic action.} 23. Qf2 Qd8 24. Nc5 Rde7 25. Rxe7 Qxe7 (25... Qxe7 26. N3e4 Nbd5 27. Qg3 {White has survived to a miserable pawn-down queenless middlegame.}) 0-1


