1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 b6 $5 {A novel idea that I hadn't seen before. Black has been playing this with some success recently and yet it is isn't mentioned by Avrukh!} ({Aditya had recently faced one of the main line options:} 6... d6 7. Bb2 Ne4 8. Nbd2 Nc6 {(now how to react, bearing in mind that Black is thinking about ...e5)} 9. c4 {(not the most challenging at this point)} ({Avrukh prefers} 9. Ne1 {after which Black has very different replies:} Ng5 $5 {(OK, the knight doesn't usually use this square in the Leningrad, but it will soon be neatly poised on f7)} (9... d5 {(an example of the Stonewall-Leningrad hybrid approach, against which White employs a typical knight dance that is worth noting...)} 10. Ndf3 f4 11. Nd3 fxg3 12. hxg3 Bf5 13. Rc1 Bh6 14. Rb1 Bg7 ({keeping with the 'rapid-piece deployment' mentality, I suggest} 14... Qd6 $5 15. c4 Rad8 {as more combative}) 15. c4 e6 16. Rc1 {and Avrukh prefers White}) 10. f4 Nf7 11. Nc4 e6 12. e3 Bd7 ({or} 12... Rb8 13. Nd3 Ne7 14. Qe2 b5 15. Nd2 Bb7 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 {Iturrizaga, E - Pruijssers, R Vlissingen 2017, and White failed to obtain any advantage at the time, but Avrukh suggests the direct} 17. e4) 13. Nd3 Rb8 14. Qe1 Re8 15. Rd1 b6 16. a4 Qe7 17. Ba3 Red8 {Bogner, S - Vovk, A Stroebeck 2015, Black had stayed solid but a little passive which (instead of agreeing a draw) White could have tried to exploit with} 18. Nde5 $5 $14) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qd5+ Kh8 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rad1 Rxd1 15. Rxd1 e4 $11 {Aditya, M - Petrosian, T Moscow 2019.}) 7. Bb2 ({Trying to get Black to show his hand with} 7. Ne5 $5 {might be more of a test:} d5 (7... c6 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. c4 Qc8 ({the alternative} 9... d6 10. Nd3 Qd7 11. Nc3 Na6 {doesn't look bad}) 10. Nd2 c5 11. d5 e6 12. e4 fxe4 13. dxe6 dxe6 14. Qe2 {Stella, A - David, Alb Cosenza 2017, looks somewhat preferable for White}) 8. c4 e6 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Bg5 c6 11. Rc1 Qe8 12. Qd2 Nbd7 {Hera, I - Lagarde, M French league 2018. Black's set-up looks slightly unusual, but there isn't anything really wrong with it.}) 7... Bb7 {White has scored woefully from this position. Is this because he has often been surprised and hasn't been able to find a good plan OTB, or is it that Black's idea is simply good!?} 8. c4 ({It's possible to try and do without c2-c4:} 8. Nbd2 e6 9. a4 a5 10. Ne5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 d6 12. Nd3 Nc6 13. e3 Qd7 14. Qe2 Rae8 15. Rad1 Qc8 $11 {Pile, R - Lagarde, M Cannes rapid 2018.}) 8... e6 9. Nc3 ({The knight is perhaps less influential on d2:} 9. Nbd2 a5 10. a3 Na6 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. Rad1 d6 13. Qb1 Rae8 14. Ba1 {(White has run out of ideas and is just waiting)} c5 $11 {Bindrich, F - Vallejo Pons, F Berlin Blitz 2015.}) 9... Na6 $5 {New, but as this line is still in its early days Black has experimented with various ideas at this point:} (9... Ne4 10. e3 d6 11. Qc2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Be4 13. Qb2 Nd7 14. Ne1 {Nie, Xinyang - Idani, P Qinhuangdao 2019, and now simplest would be} Bxg2 15. Nxg2 Qe7 $11) (9... Qe7 10. Qc2 a5 11. Rad1 d6 12. Rfe1 Na6 13. a3 Rad8 14. Ng5 (14. d5 e5 15. Nb5 h6 16. Na7 Qe8 $13 {Olafsson, H - Vallejo Pons, F Berlin rapid 2015}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 e5 16. e4 (16. d5 Nc5 17. b4 h6 $11) 16... f4 {Sasikiran, K - Vallejo Pons, F Berlin rapid 2015.}) (9... d5 10. e3 ({or the anti-Stonewall style idea} 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. Nd3 {e.g.} c6 12. e3 Re8 13. cxd5 exd5 14. b4 Ne4 $11 {Visakh, NR - Sandipan, C Mumbai 2019}) 10... Nbd7 11. Rc1 c6 12. Ne2 Qe7 13. Nf4 Ne4 14. h4 a5 $13 {Cvitan, O - Anton Guijarro, D German league 2017, with a decent-looking example of a Stonewall flavoured Leningrad.}) 10. a3 c5 $1 11. d5 $146 ({After} 11. dxc5 {Black could recapture either way, but in order to bring the knight into the game} Nxc5 $11 {looks simplest.}) ({RR} 11. Qc2 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc5 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. Ndb5 Rfc8 16. b4 Nb7 17. Qd3 a6 18. Nd4 Nd6 19. c5 bxc5 20. Nxe6 cxb4 21. Nd5 Qxe6 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Qxd6 Qxd6 25. Rxd6 b3 {Townsend,M (2145)-McDonald,N (2410) England 2023 ½-½ (47)}) 11... exd5 12. Nxd5 ({Certainly not} 12. cxd5 $2 Nxd5) 12... Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 ({Instead of this 'automatic' recapture, the flashy} 13... Ne3 $5 {has its points, but then} 14. Qd3 $1 Kxg7 15. Qxe3 {gives White less practical problems than the game.}) 14. cxd5 Qf6 $11 {Black is comfortable and the asymmetric pawn structure offers him his share of the chances.} 15. Nd2 Nc7 16. e4 $6 {Premature, as White doesn't have the reserves in place to support this early advance.} ({Correct is the Benoni-style} 16. Nc4 $11 {when Black would have to take risks to oust the knight from its outpost.}) 16... Nb5 ({Another line that promises good play is} 16... Ba6 17. Re1 Rae8 $15) 17. exf5 Qxf5 18. Nc4 Qf6 {Keeping a careful eye on d6.} 19. Qg4 Rad8 20. Rae1 Nd4 {White's e2-e4 advance has left him with a hole on d4. Rather than admit the error of his ways (and go back with his queen to d1 with a small disadvantage) he goes for a crazy idea that is easily rebuffed.} 21. Ne5 $2 h5 {Good, but there might be even better.} ({Black can win material with} 21... Ba6 {e.g.} 22. Nxd7 Qf5 23. Qxf5 Rxf5 24. Re7+ Rf7 25. Rxf7+ Kxf7 26. Ne5+ Kf6 27. Re1 Ne2+ {etc.}) 22. Qh3 $2 ({Black is also for preference following} 22. Qd1 Ba6 23. Nc4 b5 {but the text is even worse.}) 22... Bc8 $1 {The threat of ...d6 calls for drastic action.} 23. d6 Qxd6 24. g4 hxg4 ({He could also get greedy with} 24... Ba6) 25. Nxg4 Rh8 26. Qg3 Qxg3 27. fxg3 Rde8 {White has survived to a miserable pawn-down queenless middlegame.} 28. Bd5 Nf5 29. Rxe8 Rxe8 30. h4 Ba6 31. Rf4 Be2 {Maghsoodloo is running his opponent out of any activity that he might aspire to.} 32. Bf3 Nxg3 $1 {As it's on offer, why not?} 33. Kf2 Bxf3 34. Kxf3 Ne2 35. Rf6 Nd4+ 36. Kf2 Re4 {More carnage.} 37. Rd6 Rxg4 38. Rxd7+ Kh6 39. Rxa7 Rxh4 40. b4 cxb4 41. axb4 Nf5 42. b5 Rb4 0-1


