{The World Team was a tough experience for me personally, and this rather fortunate win was a rare bright spot. However, my teammates' excellent play meant that we collected the silver medals in the best result for the English team in many years.} 1. d4 {Adams, Michael} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 {I thought my opponent might look for a sharper option, but he sticks to his main opening repertoire.} h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. dxc5 ({RR} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Nxe7 10. e3 Nd7 11. Rd1 Qa5 12. Be2 Nd5 13. O-O Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Qxc3 15. bxc3 b6 16. Bb5 Nf6 17. Ne5 cxd4 18. cxd4 Bb7 19. Rc1 Rfc8 20. f3 Kf8 21. Kf2 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rc8 {Belke,F (2121)-Djordjic,D (1865) Belgrade 2023 ½-½ (63)}) 8... Na6 ({RR} 8... Qa5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 11. g3 Qxc5 12. Bg2 Nbc6 13. Rc1 e5 14. O-O Bf5 15. Qb3 Be6 16. Qa4 Qb6 17. Qa3 f6 18. Ne4 Rfd8 19. Nc5 Bf7 20. e3 Rab8 21. Bh3 Qb4 22. Qxb4 Nxb4 23. a3 {Gelfand,B (2733)-Jakovenko,D (2753) Odessa 2009 ½-½ (49)}) 9. e3 Nxc5 10. cxd5 $146 ({RR} 10. Be2 Nce4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. cxd5 Qb4+ 14. Nd2 exd5 15. a3 Qb6 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. O-O Bf5 18. b4 Rac8 19. Qb2 Rfd8 20. Rfd1 Qf6 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. g4 Be6 23. Kg2 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rc2 {Liang,A (2569)-Burke,J (2524) Saint Louis 2018 ½-½ (52)}) 10... Nxd5 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 (11... Qxe7 12. Nxd5 exd5 {would lead to a position my opponent had already reached in a couple of games with the Black pawn on h7. I wanted to avoid} 13. Be2 Bg4 14. O-O Rac8 15. Nd4 {, but here} Ne6 16. Qd2 Qg5 {as played once by Vladimir Kramnik, looks a good solution.}) 12. Be2 Bd7 ({Black's knight on c5 is a bit exposed, and his colleague on e7 is also not optimally placed.} 12... Qb6 {was probably best.}) ({The natural way to develop the bishop} 12... b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rfd1 {is a bit uncomfortable.}) 13. b4 Na6 14. Qb2 $1 ({A better try than} 14. a3 {which I had been anticipating.}) 14... Qb6 15. Rb1 Rfd8 ({I need to recycle the knight from a6, but my queen is awkwardly placed after} 15... Nc7 16. Ne5) 16. O-O Rac8 ({Now I didn't like} 16... Nc7 17. a4 Ncd5 ({but the stronger} 17... Ned5 $1 18. a5 Qd6 {gives my queen an escape route.}) 18. a5) 17. Rfc1 (17. a4 $5 {gives the option to look for mass liquidation} Qxb4 18. Qxb4 Nxb4 19. Rxb4 Rxc3 20. Rxb7 {although this still requires care.}) 17... Nc7 18. Ne5 Ncd5 19. Nc4 (19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. Nxd5 Rxc1+ 21. Rxc1 Nxd5 22. Rc8+ Rd8 {leads nowhere.}) 19... Qc7 20. Ne4 Qb8 21. b5 ({A good decision taking more space,} 21. Ned6 Rc6 22. e4 (22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23. Ne5+ Kg8 24. Nxc6 Nxc6 {is fine for Black.}) 22... Nb6 23. e5 Nxc4 24. Bxc4 Nc8 25. Ne4 Nb6 {swaps enough material to survive.}) 21... Be8 {White is a bit better, but as my last few moves were forced, this enabled me to catch up on the clock, and although my position is cramped it remains solid.} 22. a4 b6 23. g3 Nf5 24. Ned2 (24. Ne5 {is met by} Nc3 25. Rxc3 Qxe5 26. Rxc8) 24... Nf6 {Dodging the fork, and trying to manoeuvre the knight towards c5.} 25. Bf1 ({The calm} 25. Rc2 $1 {doubling rooks whilst keeping all options open looks best.}) 25... Nd6 ({Now} 25... Nd7 26. e4 $1 {is annoying.}) 26. Ne5 Nde4 27. Ndc4 ({After this my knights are better placed than my opponent's.} 27. Nxe4 $1 Nxe4 28. Bg2 {was the most testing aiming to land a minor piece on c6.} Nc3 $5 (28... Nc5 $6 29. Rc4 $16) (28... Rxc1+ 29. Rxc1 Nc5 30. Ra1 $14) 29. Nxf7 $1 (29. Rxc3 Qxe5 {equalises.}) 29... Nxa4 30. Qa3 Rxc1+ 31. Rxc1 Kxf7 32. Qxa4 a5 $1 {this still looks a bit shaky but the protected passed a-pawn may compensate for the other defects in my position.}) 27... Nd5 28. f3 $6 ({Finally both Black steeds have found good posts and} 28. Bg2 Nc5 {is nothing special. Now my opponent starts drifting, I don't like the game move weakening the kingside.}) 28... Nc5 29. e4 $6 ({Forcing matters is a sign White had not realised his edge has evaporated although} 29. Qa3 f6 {holds no fears for Black.}) 29... Nxa4 $1 {Seizing my chance.} 30. Qa3 Ndc3 31. Rxc3 Nxc3 32. Qxc3 Rc5 $1 {The point. I will win the pawn on b5 and the bishop on e8 has found a new lease of life.} 33. Nd3 $1 Rxb5 34. Rc1 {Although the rook on b5 isn't under immediate threat it doesn't have any clear escape route.} Rc8 35. Qa3 a5 36. Qa2 $5 ({This worked out well as we were both struggling to come to terms with the unusual nature of the position with little time to arrive at move 40.} 36. Be2 $1 {so that} a4 {can be met by} 37. Bd1 {was stronger.}) 36... Bd7 $6 ({Failing to understand that the queen move had freed the rook to find a better post. After} 36... a4 $5 37. Qxa4 Rb1 38. Qxe8+ Rxe8 39. Rxb1 b5 {White's loose king means the material balance is good for Black - especially in practice.} 40. Ne3 (40. Nf2 Rd8 41. Rb3 Rd4 42. Nb2 b4) 40... Rc8) ({The composed} 36... Rc7 $5 {preparing a4 is also a good idea.}) 37. Rd1 $1 Rd8 ({I had intended to follow my last move with} 37... e5 $2 {followed by Be6, but realised in time that} 38. Nf4 exf4 39. Rxd7 fxg3 40. Nd6 {is crushing.}) (37... Bc6 {maintains much better co-ordination, it's important for the bishop to eye the kingside as my rook is about to be banished there.}) 38. Na3 Rh5 39. g4 (39. e5 $1 {Cutting off the rook is logical , there is little choice but to play} b5 40. g4 Rh4 41. Qf2 g5 {which doesn't inspire confidence.}) 39... Rg5 40. h4 $2 (40. e5 Bc6 {was still best with all to play for. Attacking the rook looks logical but I managed to spot that the now unprotected g3 square was important.}) 40... Qg3+ 41. Bg2 (41. Qg2 Qxh4 42. Nf2 Rc5 {defends the rook on d8, and leaves White too much material behind.}) 41... Ba4 ({The most practical move, now all my pieces get active, but the mundane} 41... Qxh4 {was also pretty good.}) 42. Nc2 ({There is little hope for White. After} 42. Rd2 {I was tempted by} Rc5 (42... Qxh4 $19) 43. Nxc5 $2 Qe1+) (42. hxg5 Bxd1 43. Qf2 Qd6 $19) ({Or} 42. Rc1 Qxh4 43. Qf2 Qxf2+ 44. Nxf2 Rc5 {and there are too many pawns.}) 42... Bxc2 43. Qxc2 Qxh4 44. Rb1 (44. e5 $1 {is a better try, but after} h5 45. Qc7 Rg6 46. Qxb6 hxg4 47. f4 a4 48. Qa5 g3 49. Qxa4 Rg4 {the fact that only kingside pawns remain won't save White with g5 coming.}) 44... h5 45. gxh5 (45. Rxb6 hxg4 46. f4 Rh5 47. e5 Qg3 48. Rd6 Rb8 {is also hopeless.}) 45... Qxh5 46. Kf1 (46. Rxb6 Qxf3 $19) 46... b5 47. Rc1 Rxg2 $5 ({Simplifying the position, but after} 47... Qh2 $1 {White is so passively placed it is easy to nudge the pawns forward.}) 48. Kxg2 Qg5+ 49. Kh3 Rxd3 50. Qxd3 Qxc1 51. Qxb5 {My technique was far from impressive, but there isn't much hope here.} Qf4 52. Kg2 Qd2+ 53. Kh3 Qd8 54. Qc6 g6 55. Kg4 Qd2 56. Qb5 Qc3 57. f4 Kg7 58. e5 Qd2 59. Qa4 Qb4 60. Qd1 a4 61. Qd8 Qf8 62. Qa5 Qe8 $1 (62... a3 $6 63. Kg3 {leaves my queen awkwardly placed.}) 63. Qa7 Qc6 64. Kh4 ({After} 64. Qe7 Qa8 65. Kg5 a3 66. Qf6+ Kg8 {White doesn't have any threats.}) 64... Qe4 65. Kg4 Qf5+ 66. Kg3 Qd3+ 67. Kh4 a3 68. Qe7 a2 69. Qa7 Qd2 0-1


