1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 {The Romanishin Gambit (so called although White rarely "accepts" the gambit) - Black goes for quick queenside expansion and pressure against the c4-pawn.} 4. Bg2 {By far the main move, although several unusual alternatives are covered in the Archives:} Be7 5. Nf3 O-O {As White has developed quietly so far, Black has several pawn structure options. He can play with or without an early ...c7-c5. Black chooses the latter path in this game. Here:} 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 {Maghsoodloo varies from two of his games at the recent World Blitz Championship, where he played the rare alternative:} 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 $5 {White gains space with this temporary pawn sacrifice, and a Benoni-style structure soon arises. White has also played:} h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nc3 {The first new move. An earlier game instead continued:} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 c6 14. e3 (14. Qb3) 14... a5 15. b4 (15. h4) 15... axb4 {White's space advantage gives him the edge, but his next move lets the advantage slip away.} 16. Qxb4 $6 {The a4-knight was holding up Black's queenside play, while on the b2-square, the knight is just passively placed. Instead:} Ra7 $1 {Taking advantage of the reprieve, now Black always has ... a5-a4 and ..c5-c4 in the air.} (16... Qc7 17. Rfb1 Ra7 18. a5) 17. a5 Na6 (17... Nd7 18. Rfb1 Be7 19. Qc4) (17... Be7 18. Qb3 (18. Qb6 Qxb6 19. axb6 Ra3 20. Rxa3 Bxa3 21. Ne4 Nd7) (18. Qc4 Rxa5) 18... Na6 (18... Nd7 19. a6 (19. Rfb1 Qc7) 19... bxa6 20. Bxc6 Qc7 21. Be4 (21. Bg2 Rb8 22. Qc2 Bb4 23. Rfc1 Rc8 24. Qd3 Bxc3 25. Ra3) 21... Rb8 22. Qc2 Bb4 23. Rfc1 Rc8 24. Nb5) 19. Qb6 $6 (19. Ra4 Nc7 20. Rb1 Nd5 21. Nd1 Qd7 {is the subject of Giri-Bartel} (21... Qa8) 22. Nb2 Rfa8 23. Nc4 Bd8 24. Rba1 Bc7 25. R4a3 Qd8 26. Kg2 Bd6 27. R3a2 Bc7 28. Qb2) 19... Qa8 20. Rfb1 Nb8 {gave Black counterplay in Hakobyan,A (2545)-Maghsoodloo,P (2688) St Petersburg (blitz) 2018 0-1 (82)} 21. Na4 Nd7 22. Qb2 {is another popular line, see Ni-Cheng and earlier games in the Archives.} (22. Qb3 Bd8 23. a6 b5 {is analyzed in Bruzon Batista-Donchenko} 24. Nc3 Rxa6) 22... Bd6 (22... Bd8 23. a6 b5 24. Nc3 Rxa6 {can be found in the game Filippov-Korchnoi in the Archives.} 25. Nxb5) 23. Nb6 (23. a6 b5 24. Nc3 Rxa6 {led to a fixed centre in Damljanovic-Georgiev in the Archives.} 25. Nxb5 {is more rarely seen. Now} Rb8) (23. Nc3 Rb8) 23... Nxb6 24. axb6 Ra5) 18. Qb6 Qa8 19. Ne4 Bd8 {Black has neutralized White's initiative and now can target the weakened f5- and d5-pawns. Black is slightly better here.} 20. Qb2 Nb8 (20... Nc7 21. Nd6 Nb5 (21... Be7 22. Nc4) 22. Nxb5 cxb5 23. Qxb5 Rxa5 {and White is clearly better due to the weaknesses in Black's structure, Andreikin,D (2719)-Maghsoodloo,P (2688) St Petersburg 2018 1-0 (71)} 24. Rxa5 Qxa5 25. Qxb7) 21. Nd6 Bxa5 22. Nxb7 Qxb7 $146 (22... Rxb7 23. Rxa5 {is a similar idea to the main game, and is the sequence recommended by Adrien Demuth in his Reti repertoire book. Now} Rxb2 24. Rxa8 c5 25. dxc5 {and Black has:} Rc2 $1 26. Rb1 (26. Ra5 Nd7 (26... Rc8 27. Rb1) 27. c6 Nb8) 26... Nd7 27. Rxf8+ Kxf8 28. c6 {gives White an edge according to Demuth.} Ne5 29. Be4 (29. Rb8+ Ke7 30. Rb7+ {favours White - Demuth.} Ke8 31. Be4 Rc4 32. f4 Nxc6 (32... Rxe4 33. Rb8+ Ke7 34. c7)) 29... Rc4 30. Rb8+ Ke7 {was played in Bogosavljevic, B (2551)-Rajkovic,D (2453) Cetinje 2010 1-0 (65), and now} 31. Rb7+ $1 Kd6 32. f4 Rxe4 33. fxe5+ {would leave White clearly better.} Kxc6) ({RR} 22... Rxb7 23. Rxa5 Rxb2 24. Rxa8 c5 25. dxc5 Rc2 26. Rb1 Nd7 27. Rxf8+ Kxf8 28. c6 Ne5 29. Be4 Rc4 30. Rb8+ Ke7 31. Rb7+ Kd6 32. f4 Rxe4 33. fxe5+ Kxc6 34. Rxf7 Rxe3 35. Rxg7 Rxe5 36. Kf2 Rf5+ 37. Ke3 {Tkachiev,V (2644)-Bauer,C (2682) Pau 2012 ½-½ (46)}) 23. Qxb7 Rxb7 $5 {Black decides to try his luck in an endgame scenario.} 24. Rxa5 Rc8 25. Rc1 Rbc7 26. Ra8 Kf8 (26... g6 27. h4 h5 28. Rb1 Nd7 29. Rb7 {was played in Schlosser,P (2501)-Speelman,J (2493) Dresden 2018 1/2-1/2 (22), and now simplest is} Nf6 30. Rxc7 Rxa8 {and Black should be fine here.} 31. Rxc6) 27. h4 Ke7 {Black's advantage dissipates over the next few moves. Instead:} 28. h5 Kd6 29. e4 Ke7 (29... f6) 30. e5 {White has found a stable post for his knight and chances are roughly balanced.} Rd8 31. Kg2 Rb7 {More testing was:} 32. Rc4 f6 33. Be4 fxe5 34. dxe5 Rb2 35. Bg6 Nd7 36. Ra7 Re2 (36... Rf8 37. Bc2) 37. Re4 (37. Rxc6 Rxe5) (37. Be4 Kf8 38. Rd4 (38. Bf3 Rd2 39. Rxc6 Nxe5 {is a dream Benoni setup for White, Erdos, V (2658)-Zhigalko,S (2694) Warsaw 2013 1-0 (44). Black has no counterplay, and White can prepare to roll through the middle with e4-e5-e6.} 40. Rxe6 Nxf3 41. Kxf3) 38... c5 39. Rdxd7 Rxd7 40. Rxd7 Rxe4) (37. Rf4 Rxe5 38. Rf7+ Kd6 39. Rxg7 Re2 {is a quieter approach, which is analyzed in Ragger-Tomczak in the Archives.} 40. Rh7 Ne5) 37... Rxe4 (37... Rd2 38. Rf4 Rf8 {and White is for choice.} 39. Rxf8 Kxf8 40. Ra8+ Ke7 $6 {(too passive)} 41. Re8#) 38. Bxe4 Rc8 39. f4 Kd8 40. Kf3 c5 41. Ke3 {Black has enough resources to deal with this. Instead:} Rc7 (41... c4 {and Black's mobile queenside pawns give him the advantage.} 42. Kd4 {also looks promising for Black} c3 {among other moves, gives White a pleasant game, for example} 43. Bc2) 42. Ra8+ Rc8 43. Ra6 Ke7 44. Ra7 {Black is apparently in zugzwang since none of his pieces have good moves.} c4 $1 {The only move to avoid disaster, but Black gets enough counterplay despite his two pawn deficit.} (44... Kd8 45. Kd3) 45. Kd2 c3+ 46. Kc2 Kd8 47. Bd3 Rc5 48. Ra8+ Ke7 (48... Rc8 49. Rxc8+ Kxc8 50. Kxc3 {when it is Black asking the questions.} Kc7 $1 {keeps up the pressure, for example} 51. Bc4) 49. Ra7 Kd8 50. Ra3 Nb6 51. Rxc3 Rxc3+ 52. Kxc3 Nd5+ (52... Kc7 53. Kd4 Kc6 54. Bc4 Kd7 55. Bb5+ {but here White doesn't have enough to win.} Ke7 {is simpler} 56. Bc6) 53. Kd4 Ke7 54. Be4 Nb4 {Black will pick up at least one of White's pawns, and the draw becomes clear.} 55. Kc5 {looks scary since Black's king is almost caught in a mating net, but after} Na2 56. Kc4 Nc1 {(the only move)} 57. Bd3 1/2-1/2


