1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 {The Romanishin Gambit (so called although White rarely "accepts" the gambit) - Black goes for quick queenside expansion and pressure against the c4-pawn.} 4. Bg2 {By far the main move, although several unusual alternatives are covered in the Archives:} (4. d3 b5 5. e4 Bb7 6. e5 {is analyzed in Bruzon Batista-Donchenko}) (4. e3 d5 5. b3 Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Bg2 b5 {is the subject of Giri-Bartel}) 4... b5 5. b3 Bb7 {As White has developed quietly so far, Black has several pawn structure options. He can play with or without an early ...c7-c5. Black chooses the latter path in this game. Here:} (5... c5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. e4 d6 8. d4 Bb7 9. d5 e5 {led to a fixed centre in Damljanovic-Georgiev in the Archives.}) (5... d5 {is more rarely seen. Now} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. d4 c5 8. O-O Be6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {can be found in the game Filippov-Korchnoi in the Archives.}) 6. O-O Be7 (6... c5 7. Nc3 Qa5 {is another popular line, see Ni-Cheng and earlier games in the Archives.}) 7. Nc3 b4 {Maghsoodloo varies from two of his games at the recent World Blitz Championship, where he played the rare alternative:} (7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 O-O 10. Qc2 f5 11. a4 (11. d3 c5 12. Rad1 Ra7 13. d4 Be4 14. Qc1 bxc4 15. bxc4 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Rb7 17. Ne5 $6 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qc8 {gave Black counterplay in Hakobyan,A (2545)-Maghsoodloo,P (2688) St Petersburg (blitz) 2018 0-1 (82)}) 11... b4 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rad1 Bf6 14. d4 Be4 15. Qc1 Qe7 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Qf4 {and White is clearly better due to the weaknesses in Black's structure, Andreikin,D (2719)-Maghsoodloo,P (2688) St Petersburg 2018 1-0 (71)}) ({RR} 7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 O-O 10. Qc2 f5 11. a4 b4 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rad1 Bf6 14. d4 Be4 15. Qc1 Qe7 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Qf4 h6 19. h4 Rf8 20. Ne5 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Ra7 22. Rd3 {Andreikin,D (2719)-Maghsoodloo,P (2688) St Petersburg 2018 1-0 (71)}) 8. Na4 O-O 9. d4 d6 10. d5 $146 {White gains space with this temporary pawn sacrifice, and a Benoni-style structure soon arises. White has also played:} (10. a3 a5 11. Bb2 c5 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rfd1 {is a quieter approach, which is analyzed in Ragger-Tomczak in the Archives.}) (10. Ne1 Bxg2 11. Nxg2 Nbd7 12. f3 Nb6 13. Nxb6 cxb6 14. e4 b5 15. a3 {was played in Schlosser,P (2501)-Speelman,J (2493) Dresden 2018 1/2-1/2 (22), and now simplest is} bxc4 16. bxc4 a5 {and Black should be fine here.}) (10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. d5 {is a similar idea to the main game, and is the sequence recommended by Adrien Demuth in his Reti repertoire book. Now} exd5 12. Nh4 Ne4 13. cxd5 {and Black has:} Bxh4 $1 (13... Nec5 14. Qd4 Bf6 15. Qxb4 a5 {was played in Bogosavljevic, B (2551)-Rajkovic,D (2453) Cetinje 2010 1-0 (65), and now} 16. Qd2 $1 Nxa4 17. bxa4 Nc5 (17... Bxh4 18. gxh4 Qxh4 19. Rac1 {favours White - Demuth.}) 18. Nf5 {would leave White clearly better.}) 14. Bxe4 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Bg2 {gives White an edge according to Demuth.}) ({RR} 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Nd2 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 c5 13. Bb2 cxd4 14. Bxd4 Qc7 15. e4 Qc6 16. Qf3 Ne5 17. Qe2 Ng6 18. Rad1 Nd7 19. f3 Bf6 20. Nf1 Bxd4 21. Rxd4 Nc5 22. Nb2 e5 23. Rdd1 f5 24. exf5 Rxf5 {Svetlov,D (2314)-Bojarinov,V (2299) Nizhnij Novgorod 2008 0-1 (47)}) ({RR} 10. Bb2 Qc8 11. Rc1 Be4 12. d5 e5 13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Nbd7 15. e4 Re8 16. Qe2 Bf8 17. Nf3 Nb6 18. Nxb6 cxb6 19. Ne1 a5 20. Nd3 Nd7 21. f4 exf4 22. Rxf4 Nc5 23. Rcf1 Ra7 24. Qf3 f6 {Iskandarov,M (2530)-Zhao,C (2465) Bengbu 2025 ½-½ (41)}) ({RR} 10. a3 a5 11. Bb2 Re8 12. axb4 axb4 13. Qc2 Nbd7 14. Ne1 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 c5 16. e4 cxd4 17. Bxd4 Qc8 18. Rad1 Qc6 19. f3 Rec8 20. Qe2 h6 21. Ne3 Bf8 22. Rfe1 Ra5 23. Rd2 Rg5 24. Ng2 Ra5 {Moroni,L (2328)-Hernandez Camen,A (2046) Durban 2014 1-0 (36)}) 10... exd5 11. Nh4 c5 12. Nf5 {The first new move. An earlier game instead continued:} (12. cxd5 Re8 13. Re1 Bf8 $6 {(too passive)} 14. e4 Nbd7 15. Bb2 Qc7 16. Rc1 Rad8 17. Ba1 a5 18. Nb2 Ne5 19. f4 Ng6 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. Nc4 {is a dream Benoni setup for White, Erdos, V (2658)-Zhigalko,S (2694) Warsaw 2013 1-0 (44). Black has no counterplay, and White can prepare to roll through the middle with e4-e5-e6.}) 12... Re8 13. cxd5 Bf8 14. Re1 a5 15. e4 Nbd7 {White's space advantage gives him the edge, but his next move lets the advantage slip away.} 16. Nb2 $6 {The a4-knight was holding up Black's queenside play, while on the b2-square, the knight is just passively placed. Instead:} (16. Bf4 {among other moves, gives White a pleasant game, for example} Nb6 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. a3 {and White is for choice.}) 16... Nb6 $1 {Taking advantage of the reprieve, now Black always has ... a5-a4 and ..c5-c4 in the air.} 17. Bf4 Bc8 18. Qc2 Bxf5 19. exf5 Qd7 {Black has neutralized White's initiative and now can target the weakened f5- and d5-pawns. Black is slightly better here.} 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Rd1 g6 (21... a4 {also looks promising for Black}) 22. fxg6 hxg6 23. h3 Qf5 $5 {Black decides to try his luck in an endgame scenario.} 24. Qxf5 gxf5 25. Kf1 Ne4 26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Rd2 Kh7 {Black's advantage dissipates over the next few moves. Instead:} (27... a4 $1 {keeps up the pressure, for example} 28. bxa4 Ra8 29. Ke2 c4 {and Black's mobile queenside pawns give him the advantage.}) 28. Nd1 Bh6 29. Bxh6 Kxh6 30. Ne3 {White has found a stable post for his knight and chances are roughly balanced.} Kg6 31. g4 Kf6 {More testing was:} (31... Kg5 32. Nf5 Rd8 33. f3 Kf4 {when it is Black asking the questions.}) 32. h4 Ke5 33. h5 Rg8 (33... Kf4 {is simpler}) 34. Ke2 f5 35. gxf5 Rh8 36. h6 Kf4 37. Rd1 Rxh6 38. Rg1 Rf6 39. Rg6 Nd7 40. Rg4+ Ke5 41. Rg7 {Black has enough resources to deal with this. Instead:} (41. f3 {looks scary since Black's king is almost caught in a mating net, but after} exf3+ 42. Kxf3 Rxf5+ {(the only move)} 43. Nxf5 Kxf5 44. Rg7 Nb6 45. Ra7 Nxd5 46. Rxa5 {but here White doesn't have enough to win.}) 41... Nb6 42. Re7+ Kd4 43. Re6 Nd7 44. Kd2 {Black is apparently in zugzwang since none of his pieces have good moves.} c4 $1 {The only move to avoid disaster, but Black gets enough counterplay despite his two pawn deficit.} 45. bxc4 a4 46. Kc2 Kc5 47. Rxe4 Rh6 48. Ng4 Rh3 49. Re7 b3+ 50. axb3 axb3+ 51. Kb2 Nb6 52. Ne3 Nxc4+ 53. Kxb3 Nxe3 54. fxe3 Rf3 {Black will pick up at least one of White's pawns, and the draw becomes clear.} 1/2-1/2


