1. e4 {ChessBase II} c5 2. c3 e6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4 d5 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nbd2 {Of course this position could arise from a French Tarrasch (1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4.exd5 exd5 5.Ngf3 Nc6 6.Bb5 Bd6 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.0-0 Ne7) if White chose the non-critical 9.c3. That said, c3 is a useful move and the character of the position (an IQP where Black has reasonable chances to equalise with precise play) is the same in both cases.} O-O 10. Nb3 Bd6 ({We've discussed} 10... Bb6 {a couple of times in the Archives.}) 11. Bg5 (11. Bd3 {was White's choice in the battle of the chess sisters: N.Kosintseva - A. Muzychuk, Kasan FIDE GP (Women) 2012 (0-1 in 33), covered in the Archives.}) 11... Qc7 12. Re1 h6 13. Bh4 (13. Bxe7 Nxe7 {was defended a couple of times by the great Korchnoi.} 14. Nbd4 (14. h3 a6 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. Nfd4 g6 17. Qf3 Kg7 $11 {A.Rocha - V.Korchnoi, Sao Paulo 1979 (0-1 in 74).}) 14... a6 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. h3 $14 {R.Huebner - V.Korchnoi, Johannesburg 1981 (1-0 in 40).}) (13. Be3 Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Bc5 {S.Hansen - S.Krivoshey, Ubeda 1997 (1-0 in 51)} Rae8 $5) ({RR} 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Nbd4 a6 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. h3 Rfe8 17. Qb3 Bc5 18. Re2 Qb6 19. Ne5 Rad8 20. Nxd7 Rxd7 21. Qxb6 Bxb6 22. Nf5 Kf8 23. Rae1 d4 24. Bc2 Rc7 25. Nxd4 Bxd4 26. cxd4 Rd8 27. Rd1 Rcd7 {Huebner,R (2640)-Kortschnoj,V (2650) Johannesburg 1981 1-0 (40)}) ({RR} 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Nbd4 Bg4 15. h3 Bh5 16. Bd3 Bc5 17. Qd2 Qb6 18. Re5 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Bd6 20. Re2 Nc6 21. Rae1 Rad8 22. Bb1 Rd7 23. Qd3 g6 24. Qd2 Kg7 25. a3 Rfd8 26. Ba2 Bf8 27. Qf4 d4 {Wu,D (2232)-Goncharov,V (2077) Chess.com INT 2024 ½-½ (75)}) 13... Nf5 14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 {Black is, of course, very comfortable here.} Ne7 $146 ({RR} 15... a6 16. Be2 Ne7 17. Nfd4 Bd7 18. Bd3 Be5 19. Qh5 Bf6 20. Re2 Qc8 21. f3 a5 22. a4 ({RR} 22. Rae1 a4 23. Rxe7 Bxe7 24. Rxe7 axb3 25. axb3) 22... Qc7 23. Rae1 Bxa4 24. Nf5 ({RR} 24. Kh2) 24... Nxf5 25. Qxf5 Qb6+ 26. Kh2 g6 27. Qg4 Bxb3 28. Re6 Qd8 29. R1e5 Bxe5 30. Rxg6+ {Rogers,I (1865)-Chandler,M Wattignies 1976 EXT 2015 [ChessBase II] 0-1 (35)}) 16. Nfd4 g6 17. Qd2 Kg7 18. c4 dxc4 (18... a6 {leads to complicated and balanced play after} 19. Qc3 Kg8 20. c5 Be5 21. Be2 {followed by Bf3.}) 19. Rac1 {Now Black must play precisely to neutralise White's lead in development.} c3 20. Rxc3 Qb6 21. Rd3 a6 $6 ({White keeps some initiative after} 21... Bf5 22. Nxf5+ Nxf5 23. a4 {, but this seems to be the way to go for Black, for example} Rad8 (23... h5 {is also okay}) 24. g4 Ne7 25. Rd1 Nc8 {and a draw is very likely.}) 22. Nc2 $1 Bb8 $2 (22... Rd8 23. Bc4 Qc7 24. Qc3+ f6 25. Nbd4 $14 {looks unpleasant but this should have been tried.}) 23. Rxe7 (23. Bd7 $16 {is also good but I like Adhiban's choice.}) 23... axb5 24. Ne3 $18 {The attacking ratio on the kingside is intimidating. The Iranian talent grabs a pawn so as to have something to suffer for.} Rxa2 25. Nd5 Qc6 26. Rc3 Qd6 27. Qd4+ Kg8 28. Nf6+ Kh8 29. Rxf7 $1 {A lovely finish.} Rxf7 30. Rxc8+ Rf8 31. Nd7+ $1 1-0


