1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. e3 ({We find yet more strong players attracted to reversed Reti-like play, not the main line,} 5. c3 d6 6. e4 {.}) 5... d6 6. Bc4 $5 ({Played by the world champion, and a move which even sets a little trap. En route to triumphing at Gibraltar, rising star Vladislav Artemiev preferred} 6. c3 {and after} Nc6 $5 ({fairly rare, and a new move for us instead,} 6... Nbd7 7. Bd3 e5 8. O-O h6 9. Bh4 {can be found in Kramnik-Nepomniachtchi, Russian Team Championship, Sochi 2015, amongst other games in the Archive}) 7. Bc4 e5 8. O-O Qe7 9. b4 h6 10. Bh4 exd4 $5 ({a solid choice and presumably Vachier-Lagrave wasn't totally sure about} 10... e4 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Ne1 Bg7 13. f3 {, although this may not be so bad for Black after} Qg5) 11. exd4 Bf5 12. b5 (12. Re1 Qd7 13. Qb3 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 {also feels quite comfortable for Black}) 12... Na5 13. Re1 Qd7 14. Bf1 a6 $1 (14... g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 {was still possible, but Black would really prefer not to allow White a bit of queenside pressure with} 16. Nb3 Nxb3 17. axb3) 15. bxa6 bxa6 16. Nb3 Nxb3 17. axb3 a5 18. Nd2 g5 19. Bg3 Rfe8 {Black didn't have too many problems holding the draw in Artemiev-Vachier Lagrave, Gibraltar 2019.}) 6... Nbd7 ({Natural. The aforementioned trap is} 6... c5 7. c3 b6 $4 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Bd5 {, which poor Loek van Wely once fell for.}) 7. O-O Qe8 ({Etienne Bacrot did the same thing, but I still can't see too much wrong with} 7... e5 {followed by ...Qe7.}) 8. a4 a5 ({Contesting the queenside is new for us. Previously we analysed} 8... e5 9. a5 e4 10. Ne1 h6 11. Bh4 c6 12. Bb3 Nh5 13. f3 exf3 14. Qxf3 Ndf6 15. Nd3 Bg4 16. Qf2 Be6 {, which seemed OK for Black in Carlsen-Bacrot, Baden-Baden 2015.}) 9. e4 {Held up on the queenside, White has little better than to accept the tempo loss and expand in the centre.} e5 10. c3 h6 11. Bh4 Nh5 12. Re1 {Model play thus far from the world junior champion, and not such an easy set-up for Black to completely equalise against.} Ndf6 $146 ({Transferring a second knight to the kingside turns out to be new. Previously} 12... Kh8 13. Bb5 $5 {(probing)} f6 (13... c6 $6 14. Bf1 {was White's hope when d6 is quite tender}) 14. Nc4 Qe7 {had been seen in Ballmann-Cvitan, Pontresina 2000, and now} 15. Ne3 Nb6 16. Nd2 c6 17. Bf1 Be6 18. Ndc4 {feels like an edge.}) ({As such, perhaps} 12... Nb6 $5 {is Black's best move when White must avoid} 13. Bf1 $6 (13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Qc2 Nf4 {is fine too for Black}) 13... Bd7 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. b3 Be6 {and it's Black who controls the important c4-square.}) ({RR} 12... Kh8 13. Bb5 f6 14. Nc4 Qe7 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Ne3 c6 17. Bf1 Nc5 18. Nd2 Nf4 19. Qc2 h5 20. Ndc4 Qc7 21. Na3 Be6 22. Bc4 Bd7 23. Rad1 Rae8 24. f3 Bc8 25. Bf2 Qe7 26. Bf1 Be6 27. Bc4 {Ballmann,M (2413)-Cvitan,O (2541) Pontresina 2000 ½-½ (51)}) 13. Bf1 (13. Nf1 {was also possible, but I quite like Maghsoodloo's choice, adding a potential defender to the kingside while freeing c4 for the knight.}) 13... Nf4 ({The knight doesn't achieve a great amount here, so probably Black should have preferred to make a small improving move, as with} 13... Qe7 {.}) 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Nc4 N6h5 $5 ({Ambitious, but} 15... Nd7 16. Ne3 {also gives White a definite edge with potential holes on d5, f5 (after ...g5), and d6 (after ...c6) to aim at.}) 16. Nfd2 $1 {A second knight heads for the queenside, while Black's knights achieve little as he doesn't really want to create weaknesses with ...f5.} Bd7 17. f3 Bc6 ({Black is struggling for counterplay and} 17... f5 $2 {would not have been advisable:} 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Nxe5 $1 {just being very strong, and if} Bxe5 20. Nc4 Ng6 21. Nxe5 Nxe5 22. Qd5+ {.}) 18. Qc2 Kh8 19. b3 Ne6 20. Rad1 {Little by little Maghsoodloo continues to strength his position and Gordievsky now decides that he's had enough of the waiting game.} b5 $6 21. axb5 Bxb5 22. Ra1 a4 23. b4 $1 {Keeping lines closed and preparing to take over on the queenside after Nb1-a3.} Qb8 24. Bf2 Rd8 25. Nb1 Be8 $6 ({This isn't a good sign and} 25... c5 $5 26. bxc5 Bf8 {was likely a better try, even if White can retain the upper hand with} 27. Nba3 Bxc4 28. Nxc4 Nxc5 29. Rab1 Qc7 30. Nb6 Rab8 31. Nd5 {.}) 26. Nba3 Qc8 27. Nb2 ({Maghsoodloo decides it's time to bring the other knight to c4. He might also have continued to calmly improve his forces with} 27. Be3 {.}) 27... Nhf4 28. Nac4 Ng5 (28... Bb5 $5 {was possibly rejected on the grounds of} 29. Nxe5 Bxe5 30. Bxb5 {. However, after} Nxg2 $1 31. Kxg2 Ng5 32. Kh1 Qh3 {Black would have had some practical chances, even if} 33. Bd4 $1 Qxf3+ 34. Qg2 Bxd4 35. cxd4 Rxd4 36. Qxf3 Nxf3 37. Re3 {would maintain a clear advantage for White.}) 29. Be3 f5 30. h4 $5 {A possibly unexpected but effective upping of the tempo.} Nge6 $2 ({Now Black's position collapses, whereas} 30... Nf7 31. Bf2 fxe4 32. Qxe4 Qf5 33. Ra3 {wouldn't have seen him set to lose more than a pawn.}) 31. Bf2 fxe4 32. Qxe4 g5 $2 ({The immediate} 32... a3 {was a better try, even if} 33. Nxa3 Nd5 34. Rec1 {is just an extra pawn for White.}) 33. Nxe5 a3 34. Nbc4 a2 35. Ne3 Nf8 36. Nf5 {In the manoeuvring battle of the knights, I think we can safely say that Maghsoodloo was superior.} 1-0


