1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 {This setup gained popularity recently, since Nakamura began to use it both in quicker time-controls and in classical. It can be compared with the same 5th move with 3...Qd6 instead of 3...Qd8.} 6. Bc4 (6. Be2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 (8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Qd2 b6 10. Rad1 Bb7 11. Rfe1 e6 12. Bh6 Ne7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Ne5 Rc8 15. Qf4 a6 16. Rd3 b5 17. a3 Qd6 18. b4 {1-0 (60) Piorun,K (2612)-Nakamura,H (2763) Batumi 2018}) (8. Bg5 h6 9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Re1 b6 11. Bc4 Bb7 12. Ne5 {0-1 (46) Frolyanov,D (2517)-Nakamura,H (2746) St Petersburg 2018}) 8... Nc6 9. Be3 {1/2-1/2 (23) Giri,A (2783)-Nakamura,H (2746) St Petersburg 2018} (9. a3 e6 10. Bf4 b6 {0-1 (120) Yu,Y (2764)-Nakamura,H (2746) St Petersburg 2018}) 9... e6 {and Black will arrive at the same setup as in the game.}) (6. Bf4 $1 {seems to cause problems for Black in this line.} Bg7 7. Qd2 O-O (7... c6 {0-1 (34) Milov,L (2539)-Tiviakov,S (2684) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2009} 8. O-O-O Bf5 9. Bh6 O-O 10. h4 {and the attack is essentially the same as against 7...0-0.}) 8. Bh6 $1 c6 (8... c5 9. O-O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qb6 11. Bc4 $16) (8... Qd6 9. O-O-O Bf5 10. h4 {is equally dangerous.}) 9. h4 (9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. Be2 {0-1 (27) Gutsko,A (2177)-Antal,G (2565) Fagernes 2016}) 9... Bg4 10. h5 $1 Bxh5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Ne5 $1 {The main idea behind this is to enable f3, g4.} c5 (12... Nbd7 13. f3 $1 $18) 13. d5 Qc7 (13... Nbd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. f3 $18) (13... Qd6 14. Nc4 Qc7 15. Rh3 $1 {preparing f3 but taking the preventative measure against Qg3+.}) 14. Qe3 Rd8 15. Bc4 $16) 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 (8. Re1 Nc6 9. d5 Na5 10. Bf1 {1/2-1/2 (40) Amin,B (2704)-Nakamura,H (2761) Abidjan 2019} c6 $1 $11) 8... a6 (8... Nbd7 9. Re1 Nb6 10. Bb3 a5 11. a3 c6 12. Qe2 a4 13. Ba2 e6 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nd5 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bd2 b5 {1/2-1/2 (88) Ganguly,S (2647) -Dimakiling,O (2372) Bangkok 2016}) 9. a4 Nc6 $1 {Black's setup is now pretty much the same against anything: b6, Bb7 and re-routing the c6-knight in some active manoeuvre, e.g. e6, Ne7-d5 or f5.} 10. Re1 (10. Be3 e6 11. Qd2 Ne7 12. Bh6 b6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Ne5 Qd6 16. Rfe1 Rad8 17. Ne2 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bb3 c5 20. c3 Nc6 21. Qe3 c4 22. Bc2 Nd5 23. Qg3 Nce7 24. h4 f6 25. Ng4 Nf5 26. Qxd6 Rxd6 27. g3 Ra8 28. Ra1 Rda6 29. Rxa6 Rxa6 30. Nc1 Kf7 31. Nh2 b4 {0-1 (57) Vidit,S (2702)-Nakamura,H (2746) Kolkata 2018}) (10. Ne2 b6 $1 11. c3 Bb7 12. b4 Ne4 13. Bb3 e5 14. Qc2 {1-0 (46) Van Foreest,J (2600)-Admiraal,M (2447) Vlissingen 2017} Nxc3 $1 15. Qxc3 exd4 16. Qd2 d3 17. Nc3 Nxb4) 10... b6 ({RR} 10... e6 11. Bf4 Ne7 12. Qd2 b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Ne5 Nf5 15. Nxf7 Rxf7 16. Bxe6 Nd5 17. Ne4 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 Bd5 19. Bxf7+ Bxf7 20. c3 h6 21. d5 Qd7 22. d6 cxd6 23. Nxd6 Qc7 24. Qf3 Rf8 25. Nxf5 {Kovalev,V (2579)-Miton,K (2568) Chess.com INT 2024 0-1 (46)}) 11. b3 $146 (11. Be3 Bb7 12. Qe2 e6 13. Rad1 {1/2-1/2 (21) Neiksans,A (2566) -Rakhmanov,A (2647) Finland 2019} Qe7 14. Ne5 Qb4 $1 $11) ({RR} 11. d5 Na5 12. Ba2 c5 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Qd2 c4 15. Rad1 Rc8 16. Ne5 Rc5 17. Be3 Rc8 18. b4 cxb3 19. cxb3 Nd7 20. Nxd7 Bxc3 21. Nxf8 Bxd2 22. Rxd2 Kxf8 23. Bg5 f6 24. Bh6+ Kg8 25. Re4 b5 {Fromm,M (2454)-Spitzl,V (2365) Chess.com INT 2024 0-1 (38)}) ({RR} 11. Bf4 Bb7 12. Qd2 e6 13. Rad1 Ne7 14. Ne5 Ned5 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Bb3 c5 19. dxc5 bxc5 20. Bxd5 Rad8 21. Bxf7+ {1-0 (21) Carlsen,M (2862)-Maghsoodloo,P (2676) Chess.com INT 2020}) ({RR} 11. Bg5 Bb7 12. Bf1 h6 13. Bh4 e6 14. g4 Nb4 15. Bg2 Qc8 16. Qd2 c5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 Bg7 20. dxc5 bxc5 21. Ne5 Rd8 22. Qe2 Qc7 23. c3 Nd5 24. Nc4 Rab8 25. Qc2 Nf4 {Brankovic,D (2205)-Milanovic,D (2393) Novi Pazar 2025 ½-½ (38)}) 11... e6 12. Be3 Bb7 13. Qe2 Ne7 $11 (13... Nb4 {is good as well.}) 14. Rad1 Qd6 15. Bg5 Ned5 16. Bd2 Nf4 17. Bxf4 Qxf4 18. d5 exd5 (18... b5 $5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rd4 (20. Bxb5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 $15) 20... Qh6 21. Nxb5 exd5 22. Rh4 Nh5 $13) 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 c6 21. Qe7 Rab8 22. Bc4 b5 23. Bf1 c5 24. Qd6 Qf5 25. Bd3 Qc8 $6 {Black had played accurately up until this point.} (25... Qf6 $11) 26. Be4 (26. Ne5 $1 {probably would have obliged Black to part with his dark-squared bishop:} Rd8 27. Qe7 Bxe5 28. Qxe5) 26... bxa4 27. bxa4 a5 28. Bxb7 Rxb7 29. Ne5 c4 $2 (29... Qc7 $11) 30. Nd7 $2 (30. Nc6 {gives White a strong initiative, for example} Qc7 31. Qc5) 30... Rd8 31. Nf6+ Bxf6 32. Qxf6 Rbd7 (32... Rxd1 33. Rxd1 Rd7 $11) 33. Rxd7 Qxd7 34. Re4 Rc8 35. Re7 (35. Rf4 c3 $13) 35... Qd1+ 36. Kh2 Rf8 37. Qc3 Qd6+ 38. Qe5 Qb4 39. c3 Qxa4 40. f4 Qa3 $6 (40... Qa2 {was the most accurate, so that he could react to} 41. h4 {with the active} Qf2 42. Qf6 h5 $11) 41. h4 $1 h6 (41... h5 $2 42. f5 $16) 42. h5 g5 $2 {Finally, Maghsoodloo cracks under the pressure.} (42... gxh5 $1 43. Qf6 Kh7 44. Rc7 {[%cal Gc7c6]} (44. Rxf7+ Rxf7 45. Qxf7+ Kh8 46. Qxc4 Qe7 $11) 44... Qb2 $8 (44... Qb3 45. Rxf7+ Rxf7 46. Qxf7+ Kh8 47. Qf6+ Kh7 48. Qf5+ Kg7 49. Qxa5 $16) 45. Rc6 (45. Rxf7+ Rxf7 46. Qxf7+ Kh8 47. Qf6+ Kh7 48. Qf5+ Kg7 49. Qxa5 Qe2 $1 {In some sense, this ending illustrates why centralisation is so crucial. The evaluation is completely different when the queen is on b3, with no access to the central squares.}) 45... Qb5 46. Qxh6+ Kg8 {and the game continues.}) 43. fxg5 Qc1 44. gxh6 Qxh6 45. Ra7 $18 f5 46. Qd5+ Kh8 47. Qd4+ Kg8 48. Qxc4+ Kh8 49. Qd4+ Kg8 50. Kg1 Re8 51. Qd5+ Kh8 52. Qd4+ Kg8 53. Rxa5 Qxh5 54. Qd5+ Kh8 55. Qd4+ Kg8 56. Qd5+ Kh8 57. Qxf5 Qd1+ 58. Kh2 Qd6+ 59. g3 Qd2+ 60. Kh3 Qxc3 61. Qh5+ Kg7 62. Rg5+ Kf6 63. Rf5+ Ke6 64. Qf7+ Kd6 65. Rd5+ Kc6 66. Qd7+ Kb6 67. Rb5+ Ka6 68. Qb7# 1-0


