1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 c5 6. Nge2 Nc6 {We have reached an evergreen line of the Symmetrical English - White plays the Botvinnik system while Black uses a King's Indian setup with ...c7-c5. We have reached an evergreen line of the Symmetrical English - White plays the Botvinnik system while Black uses a King's Indian setup with ...c7-c5.} 7. O-O {Last year I analyzed a game where White tried for an early b2-b4: Last year I analyzed a game where White tried for an early b2-b4:} (7. Rb1 d6 8. a3 a5 9. d3 {is Nihal-Adhiban which can be found in the Archives. is Nihal-Adhiban which can be found in the Archives.}) 7... Rb8 {Black tries for an early ... b7-b5. His other main plan is to clamp down on the d4-square as soon as possible. An example of the latter approach is: Black tries for an early ...b7-b5. His other main plan is to clamp down on the d4-square as soon as possible. An example of the latter approach is:} (7... d6 8. d3 Ne8 9. Be3 Nd4 {which is analyzed in Ponomariov-Vachier Lagrave in the Archives}) 8. h3 d6 9. d3 a6 {We have also looked at:} (9... Ne8 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Rb1 Bd7 12. b4 b6 {in Short-Jones in the Archives.}) 10. a4 {White prevents ...b7-b5 at the cost of leaving a hole on the b4-square. In the game, as often happens, however, White manages to get in b2-b4 anyway, after Black has gone ...Nc6-d4. White prevents ...b7-b5 at the cost of leaving a hole on the b4-square. In the game, as often happens, however, White manages to get in b2-b4 anyway, after Black has gone ...Nc6-d4.} Ne8 11. Be3 Nd4 {Alternatives are:} (11... Bd7 {allows White to play the desirable break allows White to play the desirable break} 12. d4 {- see Bu Xiangzhi-Ye Jiangchuan in the Archives}) (11... e5 {clamps down on the dark squares, and is a pet system of GM Mark Hebden which is well worth studying. See Romero Holmes-Hebden, also in the Archives. clamps down on the dark squares, and is a pet system of GM Mark Hebden which is well worth studying. See Romero Holmes-Hebden, also in the Archives.}) 12. Rb1 Bd7 {Probably Black's most accurate. Instead:} (12... Nc7 13. b4 Nce6 (13... b6 {is less comfortable now because of the pin along the b-file}) ({ShashChess 19.2:} 13... b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. cxb5 Qd6 17. e5 Bxe5 18. Ne4 Qd8 19. Bh6 Re8 20. b6 Nd5 21. Nxc5 Rxb6 22. Rxb6 Qxb6 23. Nxd4 Nc3 24. Na4 Qxd4 25. Nxc3 Qxc3 26. Qa4 Rd8 27. Qa7 Qxd3 28. Qxe7 Be6 29. Qc5 Qd6 {[%eval 1,28]}) 14. bxc5 Nxe2+ 15. Nxe2 dxc5 16. f4 {gave White more space in Kosten-Bijaoui, in the archives. gave White more space in Kosten-Bijaoui, in the archives.}) 13. b4 b6 {Chopra erects a solid blockade on the dark squares. Instead: Chopra erects a solid blockade on the dark squares. Instead:} (13... Nxe2+ 14. Nxe2 cxb4 {opens the queenside where White has more firepower. Now opens the queenside where White has more firepower. Now} 15. Rxb4 b5 16. Qb3 Nc7 17. Rb1 bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rxb4 19. Rxb4 Qc8 20. Rb6 a5 21. Nf4 Re8 {was played in Vitouch, A (2254) -Vlcek,S (2286) Austria 2015 1/2-1/2 (24), and now was played in Vitouch, A (2254)-Vlcek,S (2286) Austria 2015 �-� (24), and now} 22. h4 {would leave White slightly better due to his more active pieces. would leave White slightly better due to his more active pieces.}) 14. f4 Nc7 ({RR} 14... e6 15. Bf2 Nc7 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Ne2 e5 18. fxe5 dxe5 19. Qc2 Ne6 20. Be1 h5 21. Kh2 Ng5 22. Ng1 Qe7 23. Qe2 Qe6 24. Bd2 Bf6 25. Qf2 Be7 26. h4 Nh7 27. Bh3 Qd6 28. Bh6 Bxh3 29. Nxh3 {Tirpan,C (2195)-Gaboyan,S (2165) Batumi 2025 0-1 (60)}) 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 f5 $146 ({RR} 16... Ra8 17. Bxd4 cxd4 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 Ra3 20. Kh2 Bf5 21. Rb3 Qa8 22. Nc1 Rxb3 23. Qxb3 Qa5 24. Rf2 Qe1 25. Qc2 Ra8 26. Re2 Qc3 27. g4 Ra1 28. Qxc3 dxc3 29. Rc2 Bd7 30. Na2 Rd1 31. Nxc3 {Grant,J (2275)-Arkell,K (2545) Walsall 1997 0-1 (60)}) ({RR} 16... Ra8 17. g4 Nce6 18. Ng3 Ra3 19. Nd5 Nc7 20. Nxc7 Qxc7 21. g5 d5 22. exd5 Bf5 23. Ne4 Qd7 24. Kh2 Bxe4 25. Bxe4 Nf5 26. Qg4 e6 27. Bg1 Re8 28. Rfe1 Ra2+ 29. Kh1 h5 30. gxh6 Nxh6 31. Qf3 {Melian,J (2247)-Garzon Zapatanga,C (2253) Florianopolis 2024 0-1 (51)}) 17. Qd2 {The first new move. An earlier game continued:} (17. Kh2 Nce6 (17... fxe4 18. dxe4 e5 {is more effective}) 18. Nd5 Nxe2 19. Qxe2 {and now} Nd4 $2 {lost quickly to} 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. exf5 Bxf5 22. Nxe7+ {in Miezis,N  (2542)-Maurer,F (2165) Triesen 2011 1-0 (22) in Miezis,N (2542)-Maurer,F (2165) Triesen 2011 1-0 (22)}) 17... Kh8 18. Kh2 e5 {The game has reached its state of maximum tension. Discerning the correct pawn exchanges in such situations are often key to outplaying an opponent. The game has reached its state of maximum tension. Discerning the correct pawn exchanges in such situations are often key to outplaying an opponent.} 19. Rf2 {White continues to build up, but here was a good time to play:} (19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Bg5 {pushing Black's queen around before he can get coordinated. After} Qe8 21. Nd5 {White is slightly for choice.}) 19... Be6 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Rbf1 Qd6 {In contrast to the previous note, Black can now double heavy pieces on the d-file, with pressure on the backward d3-pawn. In contrast to the previous note, Black can now double heavy pieces on the d-file, with pressure on the backward d3-pawn.} 22. h4 {Around here, White seems to lose the thread of what to aim for. The h-pawn move only serves to weaken White's control of the g4-square. Around here, White seems to lose the thread of what to aim for. The h-pawn move only serves to weaken White's control of the g4-square.} Rbd8 {More promising for Black was:} (22... Nxe2 23. Nxe2 (23. Qxe2 {is well met by} f4 {when} 24. gxf4 $2 exf4 25. Bxf4 Rxf4 26. Rxf4 Bxc3 {wins material for Black}) 23... Rbd8 {and Black is better due to his d-file pressure. and Black is better due to his d-file pressure.}) 23. Bxd4 $6 {Trading this bishop permanently weakens the dark squares. Trading this bishop permanently weakens the dark squares.} (23. Bg5 {was OK for White}) 23... exd4 24. Nb1 $2 {The knight is hopelessly out of play here.} (24. Nd5 {was called for. was called for.}) 24... Bc8 {Instead:} (24... Ne8 $1 {(either now or on the next move) creates the powerful threat of ...Ne8-f6-g4. White doesn't appear to have any good answer to this! (either now or on the next move) creates the powerful threat of ...Ne8-f6-g4. White doesn't appear to have any good answer to this!}) 25. Qe1 fxe4 (25... Ne8 $1) 26. Rxf8+ Rxf8 27. Rxf8+ Qxf8 28. Bxe4 Bh6 {After the rook exchanges, Black is still better, but the game continues. After the rook exchanges, Black is still better, but the game continues.} 29. Kg2 Ne8 30. Nd2 Nd6 31. Bd5 Bg4 $6 {Here:} (31... Qe7 {keeps White tied down to the defence of the two knights.}) 32. Ng1 Nf5 33. Nf1 {White has managed to unravel his pieces.} Ne3+ 34. Nxe3 Bxe3 35. Be4 Kg7 36. Nf3 Qe7 37. Qa1 Bc8 38. Qa8 Qd7 39. Ng1 {Chances are now equal, as Black has no way to break through. Chances are now equal, as Black has no way to break through.} Qg4 40. Qa7+ Kh6 $4 {Allowing Maghsoodloo to strike out of nowhere! Instead: Allowing Maghsoodloo to strike out of nowhere! Instead:} (40... Bd7 {holds because} 41. Qxb6 $4 {fails to} Qd1 {and Black mates.}) 41. Qf7 $1 {Amazingly, White has weaved a mating net.} Qd7 42. Qf6 {Here:} (42. Qf8+ Qg7 43. Qxc8 {is a simple win of a piece, although in the game Black doesn't have a good move either. is a simple win of a piece, although in the game Black doesn't have a good move either.}) 42... Bxg1 43. Kxg1 Qh3 44. Qf8+ Kh5 45. Bf3+ Bg4 46. Qf4 {Mate will follow in a few moves.} 1-0


