{[%evp 16,97,1,-6,1,-29,-3,-24,-8,-20,-23,-28,-9,-20,-9,-18,1,-1,1,-16,36,28,63,45,155,106,116,79,153,141,154,169,167,153,155,185,215,116,123,150,159,148,171,149,149,133,219,136,164,148,189,144,223,197,240,197,371,342,366,332,337,174,177,158,215,175,196,162,807,772,764,748,1179,1131,1296,1187,1819,1612,1793,1658,2012,1394,1879,1702] A34: Symmetrical English: 2 Nc3, lines with ...d5} 1. Nf3 {ChessBase II This game starts with a Reti move-order but transposes to the Rubinstein variation of the English, which is more often reached by the move order:} d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c5 (3... c6 4. O-O Bf5 5. d3 e6 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. Qe1 h6 8. e4 Bh7 9. Ne5 c5 10. f4 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Kh1 a5 13. Qe2 a4 14. a3 Qc7 15. g4 h5 16. g5 Ng4 17. Nf3 f6 18. exd5 {1-0 C 06/32 (2551)-Oliver,T (2525) FULL THEORY chess.com INT 2020 (9)}) 4. c4 $146 (4. b3 g6 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. c4 d4 7. b4 O-O 8. O-O Nfd7 9. d3 e5 10. bxc5 Nxc5 11. Nfd2 Re8 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Na6 14. Nd2 Bh3 15. Re1 Nc5 16. Bd5 Rc8 17. a4 Be6 18. Bg2 Qd7 {1-0 Nadrowski,J-Grabner,H EU/M/1097 corr ICCF 1995}) (4. O-O Nc6 (4... e6 5. d3 Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 Nbd7 8. e5 Ng4 9. Qe2 Qc7 10. Re1 b5 11. Nf1 Bb7 12. h3 Nh6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. N1h2 Kh8 15. Qd2 h5 16. Qh6 h4 17. Nxh4 Nxe5 18. N4f3 Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 {1-0 Ravisekhar,R (2325)-Miheso,C Thessaloniki ol (Men) 1988 (2)}) 5. d3 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. a3 O-O 8. Rb1 a5 9. Bg5 a4 10. Nd2 e6 11. e4 d4 12. Ne2 Qc7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. f4 Bg7 15. g4 f5 16. gxf5 exf5 17. e5 g5 18. fxg5 Nxe5 {Kovalenko,V (2350)-Kumar,N (2390) 80/575 Kalkata 2000}) 4... Nc6 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 {etc.} 7. O-O e5 8. b3 {An interesting try, although the mainline is:} (8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Nc4 {see for example Tomashevsky-Najer in the Archives}) (8. Ne1 {is also covered in several Archived games, and can sometimes transpose to the main game}) ({RR} 8. d3) 8... Be7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Ne1 {Going directly for the double-edged positional threat of 11 Bxc6. Instead:} (10. Rc1 f6 11. Ne1 Bd7 12. Nd3 Rc8 13. f4 {is the subject of Aronian-Svidler in the Archives}) ({RR} 10. Qc1 f6 11. Rd1 Bd7 12. d3 Rc8 13. Qd2 b6 14. e3 f5 15. Ne2 Bf6 16. d4 cxd4 17. exd4 e4 18. Ne5 Bg5 19. Nf4 Nd5 20. Bf1 Bxf4 21. gxf4 Be6 22. Rac1 Nxe5 23. dxe5 Qh4 24. Bc4 Qg4+ {Srijak,S (2019)-Mohota,N (2153) Guntur 2025 0-1}) 10... Be6 $146 {Black chooses to ignore the "threat". Black has also tried:} (10... Bg4 {which is a more active post for the bishop. After} 11. Rc1 Qd7 12. Na4 $6 {[%eval -61,23]} (12. Nd3 Qxd3 13. exd3 Bxd1 14. Nxd1 {is a better try.}) (12. Nd3 $11 {[%eval -15,20]}) 12... Ne6 {[%eval -3,22]} (12... b6 $1 13. Nd3 {[%cal Og2c6]} f6 {leaves White's knights offside}) (12... b6 $15 {[%eval -61,23]}) 13. Nd3 $11 Qxd3 $1 14. exd3 Bxd1 15. Rfxd1 Rad8 $6 {[%eval 71,24]} (15... Rac8 {is around equal}) (15... Rfc8 $11 {[%eval -2,22] remains equal.}) 16. Bxc6 $16 bxc6 {Glicenstein,A (2293)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2474) Deizisau 2005 1/2-1/2 (22), and now} 17. Bxe5 {gives White an edge}) (10... Bd7 {[%eval 22,20] 10...Qd7 -0.17 transposes to Reinderman-Bok, which favoured White after} 11. Nd3 f6 12. f4 ({RR} 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. f4) 12... exf4 ({RR} 12... exf4 13. Nxf4 Rb8 14. Rc1 b6 15. e3 Bd6 16. d4 Qe8 17. Ne4 Bxf4 18. exf4 cxd4 19. Re1 Qd8 20. Nd6 Ne7 21. Qxd4) 13. Nxf4 {etc., see the game in the Archives.}) ({RR} 10... Bf5 11. Ne4 f6 12. Nd3 Ne6 13. f4 exf4 14. gxf4 Qd7 15. Rc1 b6 16. Rc3 Rad8 17. Ng3 Ned4 18. Nxf5 Qxf5 19. Nf2 Qh5 20. Re1 Nb4 21. Rh3 Qf7 22. e3 Ne6 23. a3 Nd5 24. Qc2 f5 25. Nd3 {Le Quang,K (2268)-Van den Brande,W (2248) Belgium 2004 1-0 (61)}) ({RR} 10... Qd7 11. Nd3 b6 12. Bxc6 Qxc6 13. Nxe5 Qe6 14. Nd3 Bb7 15. Nf4 Qd7 16. d3 Rad8 17. f3 f5 18. Qd2 Bg5 19. Rad1 Ne6 20. e3 Rfe8 21. Nce2 Ba6 22. Nc1 Nc7 23. Qf2 Nd5 24. Rfe1 Qf7 25. a3 {Maghsoodloo,P (2679)-Esipenko,A (2584) Wijk aan Zee 2019 ½-½}) ({RR} 10... Bd7 11. Nd3 f6 12. f4 Bd6 13. Ne4 Qe7 14. Rc1 b6 15. b4 Nxb4 16. Nxb4 cxb4 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. fxe5 fxe5 19. Bxa8 Rxa8 20. Qb3+ Ne6 21. Qe3 Nd4 22. Bxd4 exd4 23. Qf3 Rd8 24. Qf7+ Kh8 25. Rc7 {Rotstein,A (2528)-Duquesnoy,J (2225) Cannes 2005 EXT 2022 [ChessBase II] 0-1 (32)}) 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {Black has an edge.} 12. Nf3 f6 13. d3 Bh3 14. Re1 Ne6 {A typically unbalanced scenario in this setup - White has a far superior pawn structure but his king is exposed due to the missing light-squared bishop.} 15. Rc1 Qe8 {[%cal Oc5c4]} 16. Na4 Rd8 {[#]} 17. Rc4 {A nice way to activate the rook, combining attack with defence, since the rook eyes the kingside.} Qg6 $6 {[%eval 36,21] After this, White piles the pressure on the c5-pawn. Black should go for activity, with for example:} (17... Nf4 $5 {[%eval 40,22] 17...Nd4 0.01 with one possible outcome being} 18. Nxc5 {[%eval -1,21]} (18. Bc1 $1 $14 {[%eval 40,22]}) 18... Ng2 $11 {[%cal Oe7c5]} 19. Rf1 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 {Kh1 would now be deadly.} Nf4 {[%cal Oe5e4] Threatens to win with ...e4!.} 21. Re1 {[%cal Od1c1]} Ng2 {with a draw by repetition!}) (17... Nd4 $11 {[%eval -16,21]}) 18. Ba3 $14 {[%cal Ra3c5]} Rd5 {[%cal Oe5e4]} 19. Qc1 {[%cal Ra3c5]} Bg4 {[%eval 155,22] The c5-pawn is doomed, but Black targets the d3-pawn in return.} ({Black should play} 19... Nf4 $14 {[%eval 45,20]}) 20. Bxc5 {[%eval 106,22] White goes for clarity.} (20. Nh4 {[%eval 114,23] 20.Nxc5 1.54 is also promising, for example} Qh5 21. f3 Bh3 22. Nxc5 {when Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn}) (20. Nxc5 $142 {[%eval 155,22]} Bxc5 21. Bxc5 Nxc5 22. Rxc5 Bxf3 23. exf3) 20... Nxc5 $16 21. Nxc5 Bxf3 {[%eval 153,22]} (21... Qh5 $142 {[%eval 79,20]}) 22. exf3 Bxc5 23. Rxc5 Qxd3 24. Kg2 {We have reached a major piece endgame, where White retains the advantage due to Black's weak c6-pawn.} (24. Rxc6 $6 Qxf3 25. Rc3 Qg4 $11) 24... Rxc5 25. Qxc5 {[%mdl 4096] Endgame KQR-KQR} Qa6 26. Qc2 {[%eval 116,22]} ({White should try} 26. a4 $18 {[%eval 215,23]}) 26... Rd8 27. Re3 h6 28. h4 Qb7 29. Rc3 Rd6 30. Rc5 {White is playing for two results, while Black has to defend passively and wait.} Qb6 {[%eval 219,24]} (30... Qd7 $16 {[%eval 133,24]} 31. h5 Kh8) 31. a4 Kh8 32. Rc4 a6 {[%eval 189,26]} (32... Qb7 $16 {[%eval 148,27]} 33. h5 Qc7) 33. Rc5 {[%eval 144,27]} (33. b4 $18 {[%eval 189,26]}) 33... Qb7 {[%eval 223,26]} (33... a5 $16 {[%eval 144,27]} 34. Qc3 Rd3 35. Rxc6 (35. Qxd3 Qxc5 36. Qe4 Kg8 $14) (35. Qxa5 Qxa5 36. Rxa5 Rxb3 $11) 35... Qxb3 36. Qxa5 Kh7) 34. h5 $18 {Fixing the light square weaknesses on the kingside. But does White have enough resources to break through?} Qb6 {[%eval 240,30]} (34... Qd7 {[%eval 197,30]} 35. Qc4 Qe8) 35. Qc3 Kh7 $2 {[%eval 371,30] [#]} (35... Qc7 {[%eval 197,27]} 36. Qc4 Qb6) 36. b4 Kh8 37. Qc4 Kh7 38. Qc2+ {[%eval 174,29]} (38. f4 {further opening the position, although the win is still far off.}) (38. f4 $142 {[%eval 337,29]}) 38... Kh8 39. Qc3 Kh7 {[%eval 215,26]} (39... Kg8 $16 {[%eval 158,28] is a better defense.} 40. Qc4+ Kh7) 40. Qc4 Kh8 41. Qf7 Kh7 $2 {[%eval 807,27] Black has been moving his king back and forth for the last 5-6 moves and finally misses a threat. Instead:} (41... Rd8 $142 {[%eval 162,23]} 42. Qe7 Rg8) 42. Qg6+ {White is clearly winning.} Kh8 43. Rxe5 {winning at least a pawn due to the pin on the 6th rank. Its all over.} fxe5 44. Qxd6 {KQ-KQ. White is a pawn up.} Kh7 45. Qxe5 Qxb4 46. Qe4+ Qxe4 47. fxe4 Kg8 48. Kf3 Kf7 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.25 (precise) /Black=0.68} 49. Ke3 {The pawn endgame is a simple win for White.} 1-0


