 the exchange on b6? What are the good and bad points of the black pawn moving from c7 to b6 as regards the pawn structure and possible plans resulting from it? White has an edge.} 14. Bc2 {ANSWER: The transfer of the black pawn to b6 means that the d6-pawn no longer has a defender. This could be of consequence if White manages to put a knight on f5 or (after deep preparation) engineers the pawn advance f2-f4, when the black centre structure comes under pressure. The disappearance of the c-pawn also means that Black no longer has the option of ...c7-c6 to stab at the d5-pawn and increase the scope of his bishop on b7. In fact this bishop is left staring at a brick wall on d5, unless Black manages to arrange ...f7-f5 in a favourable way to undermine the e4-pawn, when the white centre becomes shaky. If this isn't possible the bishop could well be rerouted to the more open c8-h3 diagonal. Thinking more positively for Black, the exchange on b6 has given his queen's rook the semi-open c-file where it can support the knight when it goes to c4.} ({It is worth considering if White's natural retreat of his bishop is inaccurate. After} 14. Nf1 {Nor would Black be entirely comfortable after} Bc8 (14... Nxb3 15. axb3 {White's pawns have been strengthened and Black has lost his counterplay based on ...Nc4.} (15. Z0 $2 {[%eval -538,22][%mdl 8192] 15.axb3 0.24})) ({Or} 14... Rc8 15. Ng3 Nc4 16. Qc1 {and White is ready to play 17 Nf5 and then whittle away at the black queenside with 18 a4.}) 15. a4 {[%eval 3,22]} (15. Ng3 $14 {[%eval 42,19]}) 15... Bd7 16. axb5 $1 Bxb5 {[%eval 62,23]} (16... axb5 $11 {[%eval 22,22]} 17. Bc2 Qc7) 17. Ng3 {etc. White has potential on both sides of the board typical of the Ruy Lopez.}) 14... Nc4 {Now the knight has a pleasant post in enemy territory. It can only be exchanged off at the cost of straightening out Black's pawns and leaving him with a queenside space advantage after 15 Nxc4?! bxc4.} 15. b4 $146 {[%eval -2,23] If White's previous move was 