where will the sacrifice take place, and how do you assess the position after it? (see the next two comments). ANSWER:} 25. Nxg7 $1 {[%mdl 64] Breaking up the defensive wall in front of the black king and clearing the way for the entrance of White's queen and second knight. Decoy} Kxg7 26. Nf5+ Kf8 27. Qh6+ Ke8 28. Qg7 $1 {ANSWER: The black king has been driven to the centre by the marauding white queen and knight. He will have to stay there for a while as 28...Kd7? 29 Qxf7+ forces mate. I like the quiet touch of White's last move which says to his opponent “it's your turn to move: how can you get out of this mess?” Nonetheless Black has adequate defensive resources to maintain equality. In other games in this book – for example those featuring Wei Yi, Koneru and Carlsen – we have seen a recipe in which the attacker sacrifices to chase the king towards the centre and then mates him there with a couple of deft strokes. Here it is not so easy. There is a clump of pawns, both white and black, blocking any frontal attack on the king. White has a fearsome queen and knight but they aren't deadly enough on their own to decide the game. They need the help of other pieces, and there are none that can join the attack for the moment.} Ra8 $1 {Clearing the c8-square as a flight square for his king.} (28... Nd2 29. Ra2 Nc4 (29... Nfxe4 30. Qg8+ {[%mdl 64] Deflection} Kd7 31. Qxf7+) (29... Ndxe4 30. Rxe4 Rxc3 31. Be2 $18) 30. g4 $16) 29. Be2 $1 {White plans to move his bishop to h3 where it can add weight to the attack by preventing the black king fleeing to d7, or else harass it on that square or c8.} Rca7 $2 {[%eval 504,24][%mdl 8192] QUESTION: This gives White the chance for some pawn power. Can you see the general idea, if not all the fine details?} ({After} 29... Kd7 $1 {White has nothing better than the forcing sequence} 30. Qxf7+ {[%eval -72,25]} (30. Bxc4 $1 $11 {[%eval -11,26] remains equal.} Bxc4 31. Qxf7+ Kc8 32. Qe6+ Kb8 33. f4 exf4 34. e5 Nxd5 35. exd6) 30... Kc8 $17