7 19. Bxf6+ Bxf6 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Rc6 22. b4 Ne6 23. c3 Qc7 24. Rd3) 11. Bg5 Bb7 12. O-O Rc8 13. h4 Rc7 14. Re1 Qa8 (14... O-O 15. Nc1 Rc4 16. Qe2 Qc7 17. Nb3 Rb4 18. Red1 Re8 19. Qd2 Rc4 20. Qe2 g6 21. Re1 Rb4 22. Rad1 Rc8 23. Bd2 Bf8 24. Bg5 a5 25. Rb1 Nh7 26. Bd2 Qb8 27. Rec1 Nhf6 28. Bg5 Qa8 29. Nd2 Nh7 30. Bh3 Nxg5 31. Bxd7 Rd8 32. hxg5 Rxd7 33. b3 Qd8 34. Nd5 Bxd5 35. exd5 Be7 36. Nc4 Bxg5 37. Rf1 Rc7 38. c3 Rcxc4 39. bxc4 Rxa4 40. c5 dxc5 41. Rfe1 Qxd5 42. Rxb6 e4 43. Qb5 Ra3 44. Qe8+ Kh7 45. Qxe4 Qxe4 46. Rxe4 Rxc3 47. Rc6 Bd2 48. Re2 Rc1+ 49. Kg2) 15. Rb1 O-O 16. Nc1 Re8 17. Nb3 Bf8 18. Qf3 Ng4 19. Rbc1 Rec8 20. Qd3 f6 21. Be3 f5 22. Nd2 Be7 23. Bg5 Nc5 24. Qe2 Bxg5 25. hxg5 f4 26. Bh3 Rf8 27. Bxg4 hxg4 28. Qxg4 Qe8 29. Kg2 Qg6 30. Nf3 fxg3 31. fxg3 Rcf7 32. Nh4 Rf2+ 33. Kg1 Qe6 34. Qxe6+ Nxe6 35. Ng6 R8f3 36. Nh4) (9... O-O 10. Be3 (10. g4 h4 11. a4 Be6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. f4 Rc8 14. Kh1 (14. f5 Bc4 15. Kh1 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. b3 Bxe2 18. Nxe2 Qc7 19. g5 Nh7 20. f6 gxf6 21. c4 fxg5 22. Nc3 Qd8 23. Nxb5 Nc5 24. Bd2 Ne6 25. Nc3 Ra8 26. Rxa8 Qxa8 27. Nd5 Qb7 28. Qh5 Kg7 29. Ne3 Nf6 30. Nf5+ Kg8 31. Qh6 Nh7 32. Qh5 Nf6 33. Qf3 Nf4 34. Bxf4 gxf4 35. Ra1 Bd8 36. Qd1 Qb4 37. Qxd6 Qxb3 38. Nh6+ Kg7 39. Nf5+ Kg8 40. Nh6+ Kg7 41. Nf5+ Kg8 42. Nh6+) 14... exf4 15. Bxf4 Bc4 16. Re1 Ne5 17. Nd4 Re8 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Qd2 Be6 20. Bg5 g6 21. Nd4 Be7 22. Bxh4 Nh7 23. Bxe7 Qxe7 24. Qf2 Kg7 25. Rad1 Ng5 26. Kg1 Rh8 27. Re3 Rh6 28. Rg3 Rch8 29. Qe3 Nc4 30. Nxe6+ Nxe6 31. Qe2 Nxb2 32. Rb1 Nf4 33. Qf1 Nxg2 34. Kxg2 Nxa4 35. g5 Rh5 36. Qf6+ Qxf6 37. gxf6+ Kxf6 38. Nxa4 b5 39. Nb6 Kg7 40. Nd5 Re5 41. Kf3 Rh4 42. Nf4 Rc5 43. Ng2 Rc3+ 44. Ne3 Kf6 45. Rd1 Ke6 46. Rd3 Rxd3 47. cxd3 a5 48. Ke2 Kd7 49. Kd2 Rh8 50. Rg5 Rb8 51. Nc2 a4 52. Kc3 Rc8+ 53. Kb2 Rc5 54. h4 Ke7 55. Ne3 Kf8 56. Nd5 Rc8 57. h5 Kg7 58. hxg6 fxg6 59. Rxg6+) 10... Nbd7 11. a4 Qc7 12. g4 hxg4 13. hxg4 Nb6 14. g5 Ng4 15. Qd3 Qd8 16. a5 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Nc4 18. Qg3 Bxg5 19. b3 Nxa5 20. Rxa5 Qxa5 21. Qxg5 Be6 22. Qh5 f6 23. Bf3) (9... Be6 10. a4 (10. Be3 Nbd7 11. O-O b5 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. a4 b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. Rfc1 a5 17. c3 b3 18. Re1 Nb6 19. Nc1 Nc4 20. Qe2 Bc2 21. Nd3 O-O 22. Bc1 h4 23. g4 Bg5 24. Be4) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Rc8 12. a5 h4 13. g4 Nh7 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Rc6 16. c3 O-O 17. f4 Qc7 18. Be3 exf4 19. Nxf4 Bg5 20. Kh1 Ne5 21. Qa2 Re8 22. Nd5 Qd7 23. Bd4 Kh8 24. Nb6) 10. Nd5 (10. a4 {or} b4 11. Nd5 {Sensibly guarding the a3-square as} Nxd5 12. Qxd5 $1 {leaves the c3-pawn in trouble e.g.} Ra7 13. Be3 {when} Be6 {allows} 14. Qd3 {.} {Instead} Rb7 $1 {planning 16 a4 would avoid weakening himself on the c-file.} {It is worth considering if White's natural retreat of his bishop is inaccurate. After} 15. f4 {Nor would Black be entirely comfortable after} Qc8 16. b3 a5 17. O-O-O Qc6 18. g4 {etc. White has potential on both sides of the board typical of the Ruy Lopez.} Na6 19. f5 {White's pawns have been strengthened and Black has lost his counterplay based on ...Nc4.} Bc8 {Or} 20. Ng3 h4 21. Nh5 Kf8 {and White is ready to play 17 Nf5 and then whittle away at the black queenside with 18 a4.} 22. Qd5 Rc7 23. Qxc6 Rxc6 24. Rd5) 10... Nxd5 (10... Nbd7 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 {, getting his rooks into the game, but} 12. Bg5 $1 {threatens to take on b6 and then give a killing check on c8. If this is stopped with} Bb7 {then} (12... Qe6 {and it's all over.} {or} 13. h4 O-O {and White wins the knight to start with} {A rook supports the attack down the d-file. If Black tries} 14. a3 {then White can utilise another pawn:} Bb7 15. Nc3 a5 $1 {. Again the black position falls apart for example} 16. Qe2 Ba6 17. Bh3 b4 $1 18. Nb5 Qe7 $1 19. O-O Nc5 20. a4 Rab8 21. b3 Ne6 {(neater than just taking the queen)} 22. Bxe6 Qxe6 {.} {After} 23. Bxf6 $1 {White has nothing better than the forcing sequence} Qxf6 24. Rfd1 Rfd8 25. Rd2 Qg6 26. Rad1 Rd7 27. Kh2 Rbd8 28. Qc4 Kh7 {with an unclear endgame in which he has three pawns for the piece.} {Not liking the dark square holes in his kingside after} 29. f3 Rc8 30. Qe2 Rc5 {. Nonetheless, as we saw in Chapter Three letting a white knight sit with impunity on f5 is seldom a happy state of affairs for Black in the Ruy Lopez. Maghsoodloo's queenside pieces are impressive, but no challenge has been made to the white centre with ...f7-f5. This gives Firouzja a freehand to prepare an attack on the kingside involving a dangerous piece offer. Objectively speaking the position is still dynamically balanced, but it's not much fun for Black.} {If} 31. Kh3 Qe6+ 32. Kg2 {Black escapes the trap with} Kg8 {attacking the white queen.} {ANSWER: I'm always impressed when I see a player dictate a game from the first rank in the style of Karpov. The bishop retreat not only defends f3 but has designs on the knight on h5 beyond it. Thus after} 33. Kf2 $2 Bxb5 34. axb5 Qh3 $1 {two black pieces are hanging.} {It was better to bolster the queenside with} 35. Qf1 $1 {.} {Again} Qh2+ {was consistent, though it requires a more vigorous response to} 36. Qg2 {:} Qxg2+ $1 37. Kxg2 Rxb5 38. Rxd6 Rc7 {and Black's massive centre gives him more than enough compensation for the slight material investment.} {Having been let off once, White should deter Black's ...f7-f5 advance with} 39. Kh3 {.} {It feels like Maghsoodloo's previous move prepared} Rbc5 $1 {but then he lost heart.} {while after} 40. R1d5 f6 41. Rd8+ Kf7 {White has to worry about the loose pawns on d5 and c3.} {This would have been a highly logical way to undermine the d5- and e4-pawns. Simply bad for White would then be} 42. R8d7+ $2 Kg6 {etc;}) 13. Nc3 {leaves the black king more exposed.} Qe6 (13... Rc8 14. h4 {ANSWER: But Firouzja could have cracked the defensive shell around the black king for a second time in the game with} O-O $1 {. We should use this exciting position as the chance to train our tactical flair. The key theme is getting a white rook into the attack. We could divide it into three sections:} {The rook crashes through along the f-file. Finally if} 15. a3 {(unlike the other black pawn moves this does no direct harm, but it is hardly inspiring if Black has no better use of a tempo)} Rfe8 16. O-O Nb6 17. a4 Rxc3 $1 18. bxc3 Nxa4 19. Qd2 Rc8 20. Rfd1 Nxc3 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 {(intending to crash through along the f-file after 38 Raf1)} 22. Rxd6 Ne2+ $1 23. Kf1 Rxc2 {and the endgame is dead lost for Black.} {or} 24. Rd8+ Kh7 {preparing 35 Rf1} {if} 25. Rd2 {Black has} Rxd2 {, a resource not available in the variation above after 30...a5 as the bishop on b5 would hang} {Breaking through with a rook along the e-file. After the helpful} 26. Bxd2 $2 {White smashes through with} Nd4 27. f3 Nd7 $1 28. Rc1 Nc6 29. Kf2 Kg8 30. Bh3 Nb6 31. Be3 g6 32. Bxb6) 14. h4) 11. Qxd5 Ra7 {Black has developed his pieces, established himself in the centre, and secured his king. His last move has introduced the idea of a discovered attack on the e4-pawn, so White closes the centre.} 12. Be3 Rb7 (12... Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Be6 14. Qd2 $1 Rc7 15. O-O Rc8 16. Rfd1 Nd7 17. Bf1 Nf6 18. a3 O-O 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with a draw by perpetual.} {if} 21. Bg5 Rc6 {or} 22. Bg2 Rfc8 $1 {and Black is busted as} 23. Rac1 Qc7 24. Bxf6 gxf6 {will mate on f7} {or} 25. c3 Kg7 {mates} {Rather than} 26. h4 {as Black wants a pawn on b2 to support a possible invasion with Ra1.} {It's too late to go back as after} a5 27. Bf3 $1 {(the pressure against c4 is stronger now that the bishop on b5 is no longer supported by a pawn on a6)} Bb3 28. Re1 b4 29. axb4 $1 {White has a decisive attack.} {However it was a good moment to evacuate the king from the centre with} axb4 30. Re3 Rh8 31. Kg2 Qb7 {. Then in order to keep essential dynamism once White is again compelled to use pawn power:} 32. Rd3 $1 Qa6 33. Qe3 Be6 {(menacing White with the threat of 36...Bd7 when his queen has no good square, so his next move is forced)} 34. Rd2 $1 Qb7 35. Qe2 bxc3 36. Rxc3 {. This is not as good for White as the sacrifice discussed in the previous note, as Black could force the exchange of queens with} Rxc3 37. bxc3 Qc6 {, though after}) (12... Be6 13. Qd2 Rb7 14. f4 Nd7 {the strong white centre pawns are enough for at least equality.} {not} 15. b3 Nf6 {when d5 is dropping} {In fact, there was still the chance to use pawn power with} 16. O-O-O $1 {when a sharp line is} Qa8 17. g4 Rc7 18. Ng3 O-O 19. f5 $1 h4 20. g5 Nh7 21. fxe6 hxg3 22. exf7+ Kxf7 23. Kb1 $1 Kg8 24. h4 {. QUESTION: How do you assess the position reached in this sharp variation? ANSWER: White has a massive centre of three passed pawns and a continuing initiative for a rook. His king being more or less safe is an important factor in his favour. Nonetheless positions of this kind with an unusual material imbalance are very hard to judge. Still 39...Ng6 40 Nc4! looks very much in White's favour. Black can try to improve with}) 13. Qd2 (13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Qd2 {with a draw by repetition.} {if} O-O 15. g4 {comes with check} {Upon} h4 {Black's queenside action is just enough to hold the balance:} 16. f4 $1) 13... Nd7 {QUESTION: Here for once is a positional question. How are we to interpret the exchange on b6? What are the good and bad points of the black pawn moving from c7 to b6 as regards the pawn structure and possible plans resulting from it?} 14. Nc3 {ANSWER: The transfer of the black pawn to b6 means that the d6-pawn no longer has a defender. This could be of consequence if White manages to put a knight on f5 or (after deep preparation) engineers the pawn advance f2-f4, when the black centre structure comes under pressure. The disappearance of the c-pawn also means that Black no longer has the option of ...c7-c6 to stab at the d5-pawn and increase the scope of his bishop on b7. In fact this bishop is left staring at a brick wall on d5, unless Black manages to arrange ...f7-f5 in a favourable way to undermine the e4-pawn, when the white centre becomes shaky. If this isn't possible the bishop could well be rerouted to the more open c8-h3 diagonal. Thinking more positively for Black, the exchange on b6 has given his queen's rook the semi-open c-file where it can support the knight when it goes to c4.} (14. b3) 14... Nf6 {Now the knight has a pleasant post in enemy territory. It can only be exchanged off at the cost of straightening out Black's pawns and leaving him with a queenside space advantage after 15 Nxc4?! bxc4.} (14... O-O $4 15. Nd5 Nf6 16. Nxe7+ {is mate.} {QUESTION: After} Qxe7 17. O-O Qe6 {how should the game finish? ANSWER: With the game move Black is playing with fire. Instead 36...b2! forces White to call it a draw with} 18. Bg5) 15. a3 $6 {If White's previous move was questionable this is definitely so.} a5 {Black has to be content with a backward pawn to attack.} 16. O-O Be6 (16... O-O 17. Qd3 Bd7 {and White can begin to free himself with} 18. Rfc1 Qc8 19. h4 {etc.} {The priority should be to neutralise Black's counterplay based on the passed pawn and White's vulnerable back rank. Correct was} Ng4 $1 20. Nd5 {(this is a scary move for White as it hits both b1 and e4, but f7 proves even more of a problem for Black)} Bd8 {(threatening mate)} 21. b4 Be6 22. Bd2 Qb8 $1 {(reintroducing the theme of mate on f7 after Bxg6)} 23. bxa5 Qa7 24. Rf1 Bxa5 25. Bxa5 Qxa5 26. Bf3 Kh7 27. Rab1 Ra8 {. The exchange of pieces has reduced the threats to Black's king though he is a little uncomfortable sitting in the centre. On the other hand White has regained his material and extinguished the danger emanating from the queenside. His king is now much safer and he can try to build up his initiative against its opposite number.} {The tempting} 28. Bxg4 {can be met by} hxg4 $1 {when Black should swap on f1 as}) 17. b4 {QUESTION: What should Black play to energise his game?} O-O (17... a4 18. Bg5 Qd7 {when the endgame offers little hope.} {White can hold on if he retreats his knight and then goes into an endgame:} 19. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 20. h4 O-O 21. Rfd1 {. Here we see the value of the knight on e3. It guards the f1-square so that Black can't win the white bishop with ...Ra1+ followed by ...Bf1+ and ...Bxh3. So play might continue} Rc8 22. Nd5) 18. Nd5 $146 (18. Bg5 {QUESTION: I know what move you are itching to play, but hold on! If you think for a little while you can win the game at once. ANSWER:} Qd7 $1 {. A sudden end to a crazily complicated battle. The white king is denied an escape square on g2 so there's no way to stop mate on the first rank.} {After} 19. bxa5 {winning the bishop is again the simplest way for Black:} Rc8 20. a4 b4 21. Nb5 Bxh3 {when he is a piece up and White has no more attack.} {Also good enough to win is} 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Qxb4 {.} {Because he wasted time with 39 Qg7 the f1-square proves fatally weak after} h4 24. Bxh3 Qxh3 25. Ra3 Be7) ({RR} 18. Kh2 axb4 19. axb4 Qc7 20. Rfc1 Rc8 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. exd5 Bd7 23. Ra6 Qc4 24. Bc5 dxc5 25. d6 e4 26. dxe7 Be8 27. Qd8 Rbb8 28. Qd6 cxb4 29. Qe5 Qc7 30. Qxe4 b3 31. Ra3 b2 32. Rb1 Rb6 {Aravindh,C (2749)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2757) Tashkent 2025 ½-½ (76)}) 18... axb4 19. Nxf6+ {Now White manages to stabilise his centre and can think about drumming up an initiative.} (19. axb4 Nxd5 20. exd5 Bd7 21. Ra6 h4 22. f4 exf4 23. Bxf4 hxg3 24. Bxg3 Rb6 25. Ra7 $2 {Perhaps in time trouble (after all it's been a hugely complex struggle) White becomes confused and makes a couple of useless moves with his queen.} Rb8 26. Be4 $2 {When the blood has been stirred by violent attacking blows it's hard to switch to a defensive posture.} Ra8 27. Rxa8 Qxa8 28. Qe2 {A last gamble.} f5) 19... Bxf6 (19... gxf6 $1 {ANSWER: The black king has been driven to the centre by the marauding white queen and knight. He will have to stay there for a while as 28...Kd7? 29 Qxf7+ forces mate. I like the quiet touch of White's last move which says to his opponent “it's your turn to move: how can you get out of this mess?” Nonetheless Black has adequate defensive resources to maintain equality. In other games in this book – for example those featuring Wei Yi, Koneru and Carlsen – we have seen a recipe in which the attacker sacrifices to chase the king towards the centre and then mates him there with a couple of deft strokes. Here it is not so easy. There is a clump of pawns, both white and black, blocking any frontal attack on the king. White has a fearsome queen and knight but they aren't deadly enough on their own to decide the game. They need the help of other pieces, and there are none that can join the attack for the moment.} 20. axb4 $1 {Clearing the c8-square as a flight square for his king.} Qc8 {White plans to move his bishop to h3 where it can add weight to the attack by preventing the black king fleeing to d7, or else harass it on that square or c8.} 21. Kh2 {QUESTION: This gives White the chance for some pawn power. Can you see the general idea, if not all the fine details?} Rd8 {The consistent move.} 22. Ra3 Rbd7 {Meeting the threat of 31...Nf3+ winning the exchange.} 23. Rfa1 {Maghsoodloo wants some pawn power of his own. He is willing to sacrifice back a piece to activate his rooks and create a passed pawn. Naturally he doesn't want to wait until White finally organises a central breakthrough.}) 20. axb4 Qc8 {The queen proves ineffective here and is soon withdrawn.} 21. h4 $1 Qc6 {QUESTION: What happens if Black tries 21...bxa4, hoping to exploit the fact that the bishop on d1 must stay guarding f3?} 22. Ra3 Rc7 23. Rc1 g6 24. c3 $1 {An important preparatory move which ensures White maintains a knight on f5 even after the looming sacrifice.} Bg7 {QUESTION: So where will the sacrifice take place, and how do you assess the position after it? (see the next two comments). ANSWER:} 25. Kh2 $1 {Breaking up the defensive wall in front of the black king and clearing the way for the entrance of White's queen and second knight.} Rfc8 26. Rca1 Kh7 27. Rc1 Rd7 0-1


