{This game occured in the 3rd round of the prestigious Asian Indoor Games, which happens every 4 years, between the top players of Iran and Vietnam.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. h3 O-O {This slightly worse Grünfeld has been used by a few super-GMs, notably Mamedyarov.} 8. Be3 (8. Be2 f5 $5 {the appeal of this line comes mainly from the simple plan of opening up the game with f7-f5, quickly pressuring the White centre and getting active piece play.} (8... Nc6 9. Be3 (9. d5 Na5 10. Bg5 c6 $132 {0-1 (41) Alsina Leal,D (2530)-Artemiev,V (2682) Minsk BLR 2017}) 9... f5 10. exf5 Bxf5 11. Qb3+ Kh8 12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {a typical scenario} 14. O-O e6 15. f4 Bg7 16. g4 Qh4 $1 17. Kh2 $2 {White cracks under pressure} (17. Rf3 $142 $1 Bxg4 {Kuzubov was probably scared of this and missed the intermmediate move} 18. Bf2 $1 Qh5 19. hxg4 Qxg4+ 20. Bg3 $16 {after which Black will struggle to prove sufficient compensation.}) 17... exd5 18. Bxb6 $6 (18. gxf5 d4 $40) 18... axb6 19. gxf5 Rae8 $40 {[%csl Re2,Rh2,Rh3][%cal Ge8e3] 0-1 (28) Kuzubov,Y (2558)-Mamedyarov,S (2646) Dubai 2005}) 9. O-O Nc6 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bh6 Rf7 13. f4 (13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bf3 Qd6 15. Re1 $14) 13... Bxc3 $1 14. bxc3 fxe4 15. c4 Qd6 16. Qd4 Bf5 (16... Na4 $5) 17. Rad1 Na4 $132 18. Kh1 $6 (18. g4 Bd7) 18... Qf6 $1 $36 {[%cal Ga4c5,Ga4c3] 0-1 (42) Fressinet,L (2700)-Mamedyarov,S (2764) Beijing 2012}) 8... Nc6 ({RR} 8... f5 9. Qc2 Nc6 10. O-O-O Kh8 11. a3 a5 12. Kb1 fxe4 13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Bd3 Nd5 15. Bd2 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Ng5 Ra6 18. Bxf5 gxf5 19. Rhe1 Qd7 20. Bc1 Bf6 21. Qc4 Rd6 22. Ka1 e5 23. g4 {Har Zvi,R (2513)-Mamedyarov,S (2770) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (44)}) 9. Bb5 f5 $146 {I think this is the most logical way to play this line, à la Mamedyarov!} ({Black has also tried other moves here:} 9... Bd7 10. O-O a6 11. Be2 Re8 12. Rc1 $16 {1-0 (41) Fridman,D (2629)-Smith,T (2193) Helmond 2013. And White is comfortable with his space and central control while Black is struggling to find counterplay.}) ({Or} 9... Na5 10. Qe2 a6 11. Bd3 Nc6 (11... f5 $5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. O-O Qd6 14. Rac1 Nc6 15. Be4 $14) 12. d5 {White has a 100% score in this position and it is practically difficult to play this for Black already.} Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {1-0 (29) Hebden,M (2523)-Rozycki,B (2085) London 2014, and now White could have played the simple and strong} 14. f4 $16 Bg7 15. O-O f5 $2 16. e5 $1 {with a strategically winning position.}) ({RR} 9... a6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qc1 c5 12. dxc5 Nc4 13. O-O Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Rb8 15. Rad1 Qe8 16. Rd2 Qc6 17. Rc1 f5 18. Nd5 Re8 19. Nd4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 e5 21. Qc4 Kh8 22. f3 a5 23. Qc3 Ra8 24. exf5 {Duhayon,Y (2263)-Van Weersel,A (2155) Brasschaat 2006 1-0 (32)}) ({RR} 9... Bd7 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Qb3 e6 12. Ne5 Qd6 13. Bf4 Qxd4 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Bxc7 Nc4 16. Rd1 Qc5 17. O-O Rfc8 18. Rd7 a5 19. Rfd1 Qb4 20. Na4 Qxb3 21. axb3 Nxb2 22. R1d6 Nxa4 23. bxa4 c5 24. Kf1 {Gritsayeva,O (2161)-Kirchei,V (2058) Sochi 2025 0-1 (42)}) ({RR} 9... Na5 10. Qe2 c6 11. Bd3 Be6 12. Rd1 h6 13. Ne5 Qd6 14. f4 Qb4 15. a3 Qb3 16. f5 gxf5 17. exf5 Bc4 18. Qg4 h5 19. Qxh5 f6 20. Bh6 Bxh6 21. Qxh6 fxe5 22. f6 Rxf6 23. Qg5+ Kf8 24. dxe5 {Zilberstein,D (2310)-Braylovsky,G New York 1998 1-0 (33)}) 10. Qb3+ $146 {Both a new and a logical continuation, which I think Liem came up with otb.} ({Another good way to increase the edge was} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O fxe4 12. Nxe4 Nd5 13. Qe2 Bf5 14. Nc5 Rb8 15. Rac1 Qd6 16. b3 $16 {1-0 (21) Verbesek,W-Yangibayev,R GER email 2008}) 10... Kh8 {A critical moment in the game, in which I remember seeing Liem thinking for a while before playing his next.} 11. Rd1 $5 ({One wonders what deterred Liem from ruining Black's pawn structure.} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. O-O f4 {It's possible that he was bothered by this idea} (12... fxe4 13. Ne5 $1 (13. Nxe4 Bxh3 $2 (13... Rxf3 $5 14. gxf3 Nd5 (14... Bxh3 $2 15. Ng5) 15. Kg2 Bf5 $44) 14. Neg5) 13... Qe8 14. Nxe4 $16) 13. Bd2 (13. Bc1 h6 $5 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gg5g4]} (13... Ba6 14. Rd1)) 13... Ba6 (13... Bxd4 14. Rfd1 e5 15. Ne2 c5 16. Bc3 $1 Qe7 17. Nfxd4 $3 cxd4 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. Bxd4+ Rf6 20. Qc3 Kg7 21. Rac1 $18) (13... h6 14. Rac1 g5 15. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Gd4,Rf4][%cal Gc1c6]}) 14. Rfd1 Bc4 {one can easily overestimate the activity of Black's pieces or his potential dynamic ideas but it is actually not enough to offset his weaknesses.} 15. Qc2 {[%csl Rc6,Re5,Re6][%cal Gc2c6,Gf3e5,Ge5c6]} h6 (15... Be6 16. Ne2) (15... Qd6 16. b3 Ba6 17. e5 (17. Bc1 $5) 17... Qe6 18. Ne4 Qf5 (18... Be2 19. Rdc1 Bxf3 20. Ng5 $16) 19. Rdc1 $16) 16. b3 Be6 17. Ne2 $16) 11... Na5 12. Qb4 a6 13. Qxa5 ({The more restrained move} 13. Be2 {can be met by} Nc6 (13... fxe4 {is met once again by the typical} 14. Ne5 $1 $14 {as in one of the lines examined earlier on move 11.}) 14. Qc5 f4 15. Bc1 Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gc6d4] a typical Grünfeld queen move, which here helps Black to achieve dynamic balance.} 16. Qxd6 (16. O-O $2 Nxd4 $1) (16. e5 Qxc5 17. dxc5 Nd7 18. Nd5 Ndxe5 19. Nxc7 Rb8 $132) 16... cxd6 17. O-O Bd7 $11) 13... axb5 14. Qxb5 fxe4 {This is another critical moment: Which square is better for the knight, e5 or g5?} 15. Ng5 $5 {Liem chooses the more logical way and easier position to play. His choice prevents Black from using the e6-square for his bishop.} ({The other choice may be slightly better, but White has to find a number of precise moves to obtain something special.} 15. Ne5 Be6 (15... c6 16. Qb3) 16. O-O (16. h4 $5 c6 17. Qe2 Nd5 18. Nxe4 Rxa2 19. h5 Bxe5 (19... Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Bxe5 $1 21. dxe5 Qa5+ 22. Nc3 gxh5 $11) 20. dxe5 Bf5 $13) (16. a3 c6 17. Qb4 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11) (16. d5) 16... c6 (16... Bxa2 17. b3 $1 (17. Nxa2 Rxa2 18. Qb3 Qd5 $15) 17... c6 18. Qb4 Nd5 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. Rd2 $1 $36) 17. Qb4 $1 Qc7 (17... Nd5 18. Qxb7 Rb8 19. Qxc6 Rb6 20. Qc5 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Rxb2 22. Rxf8+ Qxf8 23. Nxe4 $14) 18. Bg5 $1 Rae8 (18... Rfe8 19. Bf4) 19. Nxe4 Bxa2 20. Rfe1 $14 {and White has good pressure on Black's position.}) 15... c6 (15... Qe8 16. Qxe8 Rxe8 17. O-O Nc4 18. Bc1 $14 {White has better chances in this ending due to his superior pawn structure and his pieces will have better squares.}) 16. Qb3 Nd5 17. O-O {Surprisingly, it's already difficult to play Black's position.} Nxc3 $6 {It's hard to blame Parham for trying to relieve some pressure off his position.} (17... Nxe3 $4 18. fxe3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Rg5f7]}) (17... Bf5 18. Ngxe4 Nxe3 19. fxe3 e5 (19... Bh6 20. Rf3 $14) 20. dxe5 Qe7 $1 (20... Qh4 21. Qxb7 $1 Bxe4 22. Qb4 Qg3 23. Nxe4 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 $16) 21. Nd6 Bxe5 22. Nxf5 gxf5 23. Ne2 Qf7 $1 $132) 18. bxc3 Qd5 (18... Qe8 19. Rfe1 Bf5 20. Bf4 $16) 19. c4 Qa5 (19... Qf5 20. f3 $1 (20. g4 Qa5 21. Rd2 h5 22. gxh5 (22. c5 $6 hxg4 $1 23. Nf7+ (23. hxg4 Bxg4 24. Qxb7 Bf6 $13) 23... Kh7 24. hxg4 Bxg4 25. Ng5+ $1 (25. f4 $2 Bf6) (25. f3 Rxf7 $8 26. Qxf7 Qc3 $1 $132) 25... Kh8 26. f3 Bh5 $1 (26... Bxf3 27. Rxf3) (26... exf3 27. Rh2+ Bh5 28. Rxh5+ gxh5 29. Qd3 $18) 27. fxe4 Rxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Qa3 $11) 22... gxh5 23. Qd1 Qf5 24. Qxh5+ Kg8 25. Kh1 Be6 26. d5 cxd5 27. cxd5 Bf7 28. Qg4 Qxg4 29. hxg4 Rfd8 $14) 20... Qa5 (20... exf3 $2 21. Rxf3 Qa5 22. Nf7+ Kg8 23. Nh6+ Bxh6 24. c5+ Kh8 25. Bxh6 $18) 21. fxe4 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 h6 23. Nf7+ (23. Nf3 Qxa2 24. Qb4 Qa3 25. Qd2 Kh7 $14) 23... Kh7 24. Rf2 $14) 20. Rd2 {With this simple and solid move, White obtains a clear advantage as Black doesn't have any way of avoiding material loss.} h6 (20... Qf5 21. f3 $1 $16) (20... Bf5 21. c5 $16) 21. Nxe4 Bf5 22. Nc5 b6 23. Nd3 c5 $6 {Desperation to obtain compensation, but Black simply loses another pawn. Nevertheless, there's nothing good to recommend in Black's position all he can do is wait for an mistake from White.} (23... Rfd8 24. Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rc6]} Rac8 25. Rdd1 $16) 24. dxc5 bxc5 ({Maybe it's worth trying} 24... Bc3 $5 25. Rdd1 ({The engine's top recommendation is to sac a rook, but no way anyone will do this otb!} 25. Rc2 Bxd3 26. Rxc3 Bxf1 27. cxb6 {crazy computer...}) 25... bxc5 26. Bxh6 Rfd8 $16 {is still not enough compensation but at least Black is gaining piece coordination and making some counter-threats.}) 25. Nxc5 Rab8 {The rest of the game is a display of Liem's superb technique, one of the trademark qualities of a world-class player.} 26. Qa4 $1 Qc3 27. Nd7 $1 {The previous moves seek to simplify the position to an ending.} Rb4 28. Qa7 Rd8 29. Nf6 {Now, Liem uses small tactics put more pressure on his opponent, not giving him time to create any counter-threats!} Rbb8 30. Rfd1 {And again!} Rf8 31. Nd7 Ra8 32. Qb7 Bxd7 {Now Black finally gives in to the trade, after which Black's chances to complicate White's task vanishes.} (32... Rfe8 33. c5 $18 {[%cal Gc5c6,Gc6c7,Gd7b6]}) 33. Rxd7 Rxa2 34. Rxe7 Ra1 35. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 36. Kh2 h5 37. Qe4 Qf6 38. c5 {White has overwhelming material and positional advantages, therefore Black resigned. Impressive controlled play from Le Quang Liem!} 1-0


