{Summarizing, there is no doubt that the line with 5...exf6 is playable. Black must be prepared for a long hard grind, but he must also be ready for tactics. The line we are about to see represents the most critical test of the variation and brings us up to the present day. ---} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. Qc2 g6 {This looks as though it helps White, but Black intends to block the b1-h7 diagonal by playing a subsequent ...f6-f5.} 10. h4 Be6 {Black generally allows the h-pawn to advance.} 11. h5 f5 $1 {Black can play his knight to f8 via d7 and will develop counterplay on the queenside via ...Qa5 combined with the advance of his pawns. This is clearly going to produce a very sharp position as White has hardly any alternative other than to castle long. Savchenko has a novelty up his sleeve on move 14.} 12. Be3 (12. Qd2 Qf6 13. Qh6 {is met relatively comfortably by} Bf8 $1 {, as in R.Rapport-I.Salgado Lopez, Camarinas 2013, which continued} 14. Qf4 Nd7 15. Qg3 Bd5 16. Bf4 c5 $1 {(creating necessary counterplay)} 17. Bb5 Qb6 $1 18. hxg6 {White has straightened out the pawn structure to create a tactical melee;} ({Salgado is right on top of the complications as} 18. Bxd7 {is met by} Rxe2+ $1 19. Kxe2 Qxb2+) 18... fxg6 19. Qd3 Qe6 20. Qh3 Re7 21. Bg5 Rf7 22. O-O-O Bxa2 23. Nf4 Qb6 ({or} 23... Qe4 24. Bd3 Qc6 25. d5 Qd6) 24. c4 cxd4 25. Nd5 Qxb5 $1 {(a remarkable idea)} 26. cxb5 Rc8+ 27. Nc3 (27. Kd2 Bxd5 {leaves the white king very exposed}) 27... dxc3 28. bxc3 Nc5 29. Bh6 (29. Be3) 29... Ne4 30. Kb2 Nxf2 31. Qh4 Nxd1+ 32. Rxd1 Bxh6 33. Qxh6 Bc4 34. Qh4 Bxb5 35. Rd8+ Rxd8 36. Qxd8+ Kg7 37. Qd4+ Rf6 38. Qxa7 Bc6 39. g3 g5 40. Qc5 Kg6 41. Qc4 f4 {. The position is better for Black now, though Rapport drew in the end.}) ({RR} 12. Qd2 Qf6 13. Qh6 Bf8 14. Qf4 Nd7 15. Qg3 Bd5 16. Bf4 c5 17. Bb5 Qb6 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Qd3 Qe6 20. Qh3 Re7 21. Bg5 Rf7 22. O-O-O Bxa2 23. Nf4 Qb6 24. c4 cxd4 25. Nd5 Qxb5 26. cxb5 Rc8+ {Rapport,R (2676)-Salgado Lopez,I (2624) Camarinas 2013 ½-½ (62)}) 12... Qf6 ({I prefer} 12... Nd7 {here, keeping options open for the queen.}) ({RR} 12... Bd5 13. O-O-O b5 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. g4 Bxh1 16. Rxh1 Rxe3 17. fxe3 Nd7 18. gxf5 g5 19. e4 Kg7 20. e5 Bxe5 21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. Be4 Qb6 23. Nd4 Rh8 24. Qh2 Nf7 25. Qf2 Kf6 26. Qc2 c5 27. Ne6 {Sun,Y (1709)-Huang,Y (1515) Yancheng 2025 1-0 (41)}) ({RR} 12... Nd7 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. g4 f4 15. Bxg6 fxe3 16. Bxe8 exf2+ 17. Kf1 Nf6 18. g5 Bd5 19. gxf6 Bxh1 20. f7+ Kg7 21. Qf5 Qf6 22. Ng3 Bf3 23. Qxf6+ Kxf6 24. Kxf2 Bd5 25. Rf1 Bf8 26. Ke3+ Kg6 27. b3 {Mosadeghpour,M (2416)-Maghsoodloo,P (2447) Tehran 2015 1-0 (34)}) 13. O-O-O Nd7 $146 ({RR} 13... f4 14. Bd2 Nd7 15. g3 Bg4 16. Nxf4 Bxd1 17. Qxd1 Nf8 18. Qg4 Re7 19. Bc4 Bxf4 20. Bxf4 Rae8 21. hxg6 Nxg6 22. Be3 b5 23. Bd3 Rxe3 24. fxe3 Rxe3 25. Bf5 Qd6 26. Rg1 Qd5 27. Kb1 a5 28. Bc2 {Zwahr,P (2333)-Omoifo,O (2106) Caleta 2016 ½-½ (50)}) 14. c4 $5 {A new move, but does this encourage Black to play a move he wants to play anyway?} (14. Nf4 {is worth consideration, when} Bd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Kb1 Rab8 17. Rh3 b5 18. Rdh1 Re7 19. g3 {seems quite unclear to me, U.Atakisi-K.Delaney, European Cup, Rhodes 2013. Perhaps Black should try} b4 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. c4 h5 $5 {with ongoing complications.}) 14... b5 $1 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. c5 {White must close queenside lines.} Bc7 17. Rh6 Qg7 18. Rh4 {Sounding the retreat.} (18. Rdh1 Nf6 {leads nowhere for White, who faces ...Ng4.}) 18... Bd5 $6 (18... Qf6 19. Rdh1 Bd5 20. Nc3 Bxg2 {is a better way of doing things. After} 21. Rh8+ Qxh8 22. Rxh8+ Kxh8 23. Bxf5 Nf8 24. Be4 $1 Bxe4 25. Nxe4 Rad8 {, Black cannot be worse.}) 19. Nc3 Bxg2 20. Bxf5 $1 {A successful capture, which shows the thin line that Black often walks after 6 c3. As we know, with kings on opposite sides of the board, the relative speed of the attacks is everything.} b4 (20... gxf5 21. Qxf5 Nf6 22. Rg1 {is unthinkable for Black.}) 21. Nb5 $1 cxb5 22. Bxd7 Qf6 (22... Reb8 $2 {defends b5 but in all other respects is a poor move. White now has a free hand to attack; e.g.} 23. Rg1 Bd5 24. Rh5 $1 Bf3 25. Rf5 Rd8 26. Be6 $3 gxf5 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Qxf5+ Qf6 29. Qh7+ Ke6 30. Rg6 {, winning.}) 23. Bxe8 Rxe8 24. Rg4 Bd5 25. Rdg1 Kg7 26. Rg5 {Black is a clear exchange down and does not have enough in return.} b3 ({He cannot take on a2 as} 26... Bxa2 27. b3 Qa6 28. d5 {.}) 27. axb3 Be4 28. Qc3 Qa6 29. b4 Qa2 ({Or} 29... f6 30. R5g4 Bf5 31. d5 $1 Bxg4 32. Rxg4 Be5 33. Qa3 $1 {, winning.}) 30. d5+ f6 31. d6 Bd8 32. Kd2 {White refuses to be bluffed by the apparently active queen and converts easily.} a5 33. Qd4 Kf7 34. R5g4 Bf5 35. Rf4 Re5 36. Ke2 Rd5 37. Ra1 $1 Qxa1 38. Qxd5+ Be6 39. Qb7+ Kf8 40. Qa8 {. Nice control by Savchenko. It is unlikely that you will encounter this level of precision at club level.} 1-0


