{The Young Iranians by GM Ivan Sokolov Having taken on the job of coach to the Iranian national team, I already knew a lot about the players involved. The ‘Iranian Stars’ tournament, run on the Scheveningen system and fielding ten foreigners against the ten best Iranians, took place in July and, being one of the foreigners myself, I was able to gain first hand experience of the players I was later to coach. The Iranian team selection for Baku was based on the results of their latest individual national championship. And, as it turned out, their Olympiad side was to consist of the experienced Ehsan Ghaem Maghami, whom I placed on board one, and four youngsters, with an average age of only fifteen! Three of these youngsters had formed part of an Iranian team which won the gold medal at the World Teams U16 Championship, ahead of Russia, USA, India, China, etc. and I went to Tehran two weeks prior to the Olympiad to conduct a training camp with them. The fact that all these players were talented, ambitious and dedicated led me to feel optimistic that Iran’s final result would be considerably higher than their starting position. And so it was, seeded 46th, Iran finished 16th(!), ahead of many world chess powers! In this article I want to introduce these four young team members to the wider chess public, by presenting one game from each of them. Three of these games have annotations by the players themselves, to which I have added a few more comments where appropriate and indicated by (I.S.). * * * * * Parham Maghsoodloo has an unusual approach to the openings and tries to stay away from main lines and obtain his own kind of positions. In this way he is not looking for an opening advantage with White, but simply aiming for a playable game. In our training camp I tried to encourage him to study some mainstream theory but in the following game Parham decided to stick to his own personal way of playing. To my surprise he chose the move 8.Rd1, hardly seen in practice and which we agreed was not precise. Nevertheless, later in the game we see Parham’s main strength: he is good at practical streetfighting chess, strong in calculation and in handling complications. These qualities he already showed at the Iranian Stars tournament, played prior to the Olympiad and where he delivered a 2800+ performance. The comments to the game are by Parham, plus a few extra notes by me, which are marked (I.S. ). Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'The Young Iranians by GM Ivan Sokolov Having taken on the job of coach to the Iranian national team, I already knew a lot about the players involved. The ‘Iranian Stars’ tournament, run on the Scheveningen system and fielding ten foreigners against the ten best Iranians, took place in July and, being one of the foreigners myself, I was able to gain first hand experience of the players I was later to coach. The Iranian team selection for Baku was based on the results of their latest individual national championship. And, as it turned out, their Olympiad side was to consist of the experienced Ehsan Ghaem Maghami, whom I placed on board one, and four youngsters, with an average age of only fifteen! Three of these youngsters had formed part of an Iranian team which won the gold medal at the World Teams U16 Championship, ahead of Russia, USA, India, China, etc. and I went to Tehran two weeks prior to the Olympiad to conduct a training camp with them. The fact that all these players were talented, ambitious and dedicated led me to feel optimistic that Iran’s final result would be considerably higher than their starting position. And so it was, seeded 46th, Iran finished 16th(!), ahead of many world chess powers! In this article I want to introduce these four young team members to the wider chess public, by presenting one game from each of them. Three of these games have annotations by the players themselves, to which I have added a few more comments where appropriate and indicated by (I.S.). * * * * * Parham Maghsoodloo has an unusual approach to the openings and tries to stay away from main lines and obtain his own kind of positions. In this way he is not looking for an opening advantage with White, but simply aiming for a playable game. In our training camp I tried to encourage him to study some mainstream theory but in the following game Parham decided to stick to his own personal way of playing. To my surprise he chose the move 8.Rd1, hardly seen in practice and which we agreed was not precise. Nevertheless, later in the game we see Parham’s main strength: he is good at practical streetfighting chess, strong in calculation and in handling complications. These qualities he already showed at the Iranian Stars tournament, played prior to the Olympiad and where he delivered a 2800+ performance. The comments to the game are by Parham, plus a few extra notes by me, which are marked (I.S. ).''} 1. Nf3 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad'} d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 c6 7. Qb3 {I chose to play this variation after seeing the game Ivanchuk - Radjabov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'I chose to play this variation after seeing the game Ivanchuk - Radjabov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011.''} Qb6 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 8. Rd1 $146 {(I.S.) This rarely seen move came as a surprise, as we had already agreed during our Tehran training sessions that this move order was imprecise and offered Black easy equality. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '(I.S.) This rarely seen move came as a surprise, as we had already agreed during our Tehran training sessions that this move order was imprecise and offered Black easy equality.''} ({[(I.S.) Our analysis in training was focused on} 8. Nc3 {, which is what everyone plays here... [#] and then: Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '- 127/161'} Rd8 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad'} (8... Bf5 {can be met by Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '(Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad) can be met by'} 9. h3 $5 {a seemingly insignificant but nevertheless useful move, thought up by Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and which provides White with the possibility of a timely g3-g4 pawn push. An example of the latent power of this opening was seen in the following game:} Ne4 (9... Rd8 $145 {Dorfman,Josif D 2555 - Dolmatov, Sergey 2630, Polanica Zdroj 1993 - 58/503}) 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxb3 12. axb3 cxd5 13. Nd2 Rd8 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Na6 16. Be3 Be6 17. Rfc1 Bxb3 18. Rab1 Bd5 19. c4 Be6 20. d5 Bc8 21. c5 Kf8 22. d6 e6 23. Bg5 Rd7 24. c6 bxc6 25. Rxc6 Ke8 26. Nf6+ Bxf6 27. Bxf6 {1-0 Vachier-Lagrave,Maxime 2718 - Baron,Tal 2467, France 2013.}) 9. Rd1 ({we also analyzed} 9. Na4 {, a move favoured by Ding Liren; RR Ding,Liren 2755 - Adhiban,Baskaran 2646, Hyderabad 2015 - 124/ 152}) 9... Bf5 10. Ne1 {. The inclusion of 8.Nc3 Rd8, compared to the game, should clearly be in White’s favour. After} Na6 (10... dxc4 $145 {Jakovenko, Dmitrij 2738 - Grischuk,Alexander 2780, Khanty-Mansiysk 2015 - 124/153}) 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. a3 {White managed to convert his microscopic advantage to a win, due to Black’s doubled b-pawns, in Ivanchuk, Vassily 2768 - Radjabov,Teimour 2744, Khanty-Mansiysk (m/4-rapid) 2011}) ({RR} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Bf4 Bf5 12. Rfc1 e6 13. h3 h5 14. e3 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Bd6 Rfc8 17. Nd2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 e5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Rxc8+ Rxc8 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. Nf3 Bxb2 {Giri,A (2771)-Caruana,F (2808) Stavanger 2017 ½-½}) 8... Bf5 ({RR} 8... Rd8 9. Nc3 Be6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nbd7 12. b4 a6 13. h3 h6 14. g4 Ne4 15. Ne1 f5 16. gxf5 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Bxf5 18. f3 e5 19. e4 Be6 20. Be3 g5 21. Nd3 Re8 22. Nf2 Rad8 23. Rd2 {Maghsoodloo,P (2676)-Pechac,J (2519) Tornelo INT 2021 1-0 (59)}) 9. cxd5 $146 ({RR} 9. Na3 Na6 10. Nh4 Be6 11. c5 Qxb3 12. axb3 Nd7 13. Nc2 f6 14. b4 Nc7 15. Nf3 Bf7 16. Bh3 Be6 17. Bg2 a6 18. Bf4 Nb5 19. h4 Rfe8 20. Na3 Nxa3 21. Rxa3 Bg4 22. Bc7 Rac8 23. Ba5 e5 {Pioch,T (2007)-Richter,J (1851) Wiesbaden 2025 ½-½ (32)}) ({RR} 9. Na3 Nbd7 10. Bf4 Qxb3 11. axb3 h6 12. h4 a6 13. Rac1 Rac8 14. Ne5 Be6 15. Bf3 Rfd8 16. Nb1 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Ne8 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. e3 g5 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. cxd5 Bxd5 22. Nd2 Bxf3 23. Nxf3 f6 {Kuzubov,Y (2636)-Bacrot,E (2671) Linares 2019 ½-½ (32)}) 9... Qxb3 (9... cxd5 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. e3 Nb4 13. Ne1 $11) 10. axb3 {[#] I felt comfortable during the game because I had seen many examples of this type of position and knew White’s typical plans. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] I felt comfortable during the game because I had seen many examples of this type of position and knew White’s typical plans.''} cxd5 11. Ne1 Be4 (11... Ne4 12. Be3 Rd8 13. Nc3 $13) 12. f3 Bxb1 {After this move it is only White who can realistically play for a win. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'After this move it is only White who can realistically play for a win.''} 13. Rxb1 Nc6 14. e3 Na5 15. Rd3 Nc6 16. Rd1 Na5 17. Rd3 Nc6 {[#] Here I checked the positions of my teammates and realized that we needed a full point. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] Here I checked the positions of my teammates and realized that we needed a full point.''} 18. Bd2 e5 {(I.S.) The position is opening up and we will now see the strength of Parham’s dynamic calculating skills. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '(I.S.) The position is opening up and we will now see the strength of Parham’s dynamic calculating skills.''} 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Rd4 Nc6 21. Rd3 Ne5 22. Rd4 Nc6 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 23. Ra4 {As I said before, a draw wasn’t good enough, so I had to complicate matters a little. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'As I said before, a draw wasn’t good enough, so I had to complicate matters a little.''} Rfe8 24. Rd1 Nd7 25. Nd3 Rad8 26. Kf2 f5 27. Raa1 d4 28. Bf1 {Finally reaching a complex position in which I would be able to play for a win. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'Finally reaching a complex position in which I would be able to play for a win.''} Nb6 {[#] Diagram Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '[#] Diagram Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] Diagram''} 29. Nc5 $1 {After this move I gain dynamic play with many tactical possibilities. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'After this move I gain dynamic play with many tactical possibilities.''} Nd5 30. e4 {Achieving my ideal position! Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'Achieving my ideal position!''} Ne3 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 31. exf5 {I thought that the best way to proceed here was to sacrifice the exchange, for which White will get enough compensation and a comfortable game. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'I thought that the best way to proceed here was to sacrifice the exchange, for which White will get enough compensation and a comfortable game.''} Nxd1+ 32. Rxd1 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} d3 ({A smart move by Black because after Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'A smart move by Black because after''} 32... gxf5 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '?!' '?!'} 33. Nxb7 Rd7 (33... Rb8 34. Nd6 $16) 34. Bb5 {White would have had a clear advantage. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '' '' Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'White would have had a clear advantage.''}) 33. Ne6 Rd7 34. Nxg7 Kxg7 35. Bc3+ Kf8 36. fxg6 hxg6 37. Rxd3 {[#] White’s two bishops will kill Black in this position. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] White’s two bishops will kill Black in this position.''} Red8 38. Re3 Ne7 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]' Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]'} 39. Bb5 $1 Rc7 40. g4 Rd1 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 41. Rd3 ({(I.S.) I was not happy with this decision and thought that the clever thing to do was for White to keep his rook on the board, as it cooperates well with the bishop pair. But Parham had a different idea and decided to trade his rook. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '(I.S.) I was not happy with this decision and thought that the clever thing to do was for White to keep his rook on the board, as it cooperates well with the bishop pair. But Parham had a different idea and decided to trade his rook.''} 41. Bb4 {would have been my preferred choice here. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '' '' Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'would have been my preferred choice here.''}) 41... Rxd3 42. Bxd3 $14 {[#] Diagram Black is under pressure and White’s plan is simple: to push the kingside pawns. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] Diagram Black is under pressure and White’s plan is simple: to push the kingside pawns.''} Rd7 43. Ke2 Nd5 44. Bd2 {Now White is all ready to advance! Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'Now White is all ready to advance!''} Kf7 45. f4 a6 46. f5 Ne7 47. Bc4+ {[#] I played my last three moves very quickly. However, after this move I got a little worried because if Black plays 47...Ke8 it’s not so easy for me to win. But fortunately and to my relief he immediately played 47.. . Nd5. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] I played my last three moves very quickly. However, after this move I got a little worried because if Black plays 47...Ke8 it’s not so easy for me to win. But fortunately and to my relief he immediately played 47.. . Nd5.''} Nd5 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '?!' '?!'} (47... Kf6 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '?' '?'} 48. Bc3+ Kg5 49. f6 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '+-' '+-'}) (47... Ke8 48. f6 Nd5 49. g5 $14 {. (I.S.) It would have been a difficult decision to allow a protected passed pawn on f6 and it is easy to understand why Mchedlishvili avoided it. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '. (I.S.) It would have been a difficult decision to allow a protected passed pawn on f6 and it is easy to understand why Mchedlishvili avoided it.''}) 48. fxg6+ Kxg6 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 49. h4 {I knew that this position was winning for White and all I had to do was find the right plan. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'I knew that this position was winning for White and all I had to do was find the right plan.''} Kf6 50. h5 b5 {[#] (I.S.) There was huge time pressure here with both players literally on their 30 seconds increment. As pointed out by Parham in his comments, White had easier ways to victory. However, he never let the win slip. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] (I.S.) There was huge time pressure here with both players literally on their 30 seconds increment. As pointed out by Parham in his comments, White had easier ways to victory. However, he never let the win slip.''} 51. Bd3 Ke5 52. Bf5 Rd8 53. Kf3 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: '+-' '+-'} b4 {[#] Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#]''} 54. Bh6 (54. Bg5 Rh8 55. h6 a5 56. Kg3 Nf6 57. Bf4+ Kd5 58. g5 $18) 54... Kf6 {Here I realized that the winning plan is to take the a6 pawn and go for the b4 pawn with my king. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'Here I realized that the winning plan is to take the a6 pawn and go for the b4 pawn with my king.''} 55. Bd3 Nf4 56. Bxa6 Ne6 57. Be3 Ng5+ 58. Kf4 Rd1 59. Bc4 Nh3+ 60. Kf3 Ng5+ 61. Ke2 Rd8 {[#] Diagram Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] Diagram''} 62. Bd3 {Now I found the best way for my king to head for the b4 pawn. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'Now I found the best way for my king to head for the b4 pawn.''} Re8 {Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]' Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]'} 63. Bg6 $1 Rd8 64. Bf2 Kg7 65. Bg3 Rd5 66. Ke3 Kf6 67. Bh4 {We were both in time trouble, but White’s game is much easier to play in this position. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'We were both in time trouble, but White’s game is much easier to play in this position.''} Rd1 68. Be4 Rg1 69. Bf3 Rf1 70. Bg2 Rd1 71. Be4 Rg1 72. Bf5 Rf1 {[#] Diagram It is time for the king to do its job! Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] Diagram It is time for the king to do its job!''} 73. Kd3 Rc1 (73... Rh1 74. Bxg5+ Kxg5 75. Kc4 $18) 74. Kd4 Rh1 75. Bg3 (75. Bxg5+ Kxg5 76. Kc5 $18) 75... Nf3+ 76. Kc5 Rh3 77. Bf4 {[#] I didn’t have time to think, so I was just trying to somehow find a way to push the pawns. Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: '[#] I didn’t have time to think, so I was just trying to somehow find a way to push the pawns.''} Nh4 78. Bc2 Ng2 79. Bd2 Rh2 (79... Ne3 80. g5+ Kxg5 81. Kd4 $18) 80. Bg6 Nh4 81. Bf4 Rxb2 82. g5+ Ke7 83. Be4 Rxb3 84. Bd6+ Kd7 85. h6 Rc3+ 86. Kd5 Rc6 87. Be5 Rc8 88. h7 {and Black resigned. A great win for the Iranian team! Maghsoodloo,Parham;Asgarizadeh,A;Sokolov,Ivan: 'Maghsoodloo,Parham; Asgarizadeh,Ahmad: 'and Black resigned. A great win for the Iranian team!''} 1-0


