1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. Rc1 c6 7. e3 a6 8. Bd3 ({After the important alternative} 8. h3 {countering with} b5 {has been seen a few times:} ({I'm not sure that many will want to repeat the following alternative:} 8... Qa5 9. Qd2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Bb3 Qa7 {(a rarely used aspect of an early ...a6!)} 13. e4 Nc6 14. a3 e5 15. Be3 {Ankit, R-Bojkovic,S Novi Sad 2015, which clearly favoured White}) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Bd3 (10. b4 Nc6 11. Qb3 Bb7 12. a4 a5 $6 13. axb5 Nxb4 14. Be2 Ne4 15. Na4 Rc8 16. O-O Nd6 17. Nc5 {Riazantsev,A-Licznerski,L Wroclaw rapid 2014, with the same pawn structure as later on in the main game. Here however, on a crowded board, Black has problems to challenge White's bind.}) 10... Bb7 11. a4 b4 12. Na2 Nc6 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 a5 15. Rc7 Ba6 {(an effective plan)} 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 17. Qe2 Re6 $1 18. Rb7 Ne4 {Miladinovic,I-Savic,M Macedonian league 2014, and it turns out that Black's forces are the better deployed.}) ({Against} 8. Qb3 {Black could continue 'Meran-style' with} dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 {but it's still not easy to complete development e.g.} 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Nh5 12. Be5 $1 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 c5 $2 14. Nc6 Qe8 15. Nd5 {Dragun,K-Leenhouts,K Riga 2015, and Black loses at least a pawn and was already in trouble.}) ({RR} 8. c5 Nbd7 9. Be2 Re8 10. O-O h6 11. b4 Nh5 12. h3 Nxf4 13. exf4 Qc7 14. Qd2 h5 15. Ne5 Bh6 16. Qe3 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Be6 18. Rcd1 f6 19. Qg3 Kf7 20. f5 gxf5 21. Bxh5+ Kf8 22. Rfe1 Bg7 {Mamedyarov,S (2721)-Shivananda,B (2388) Kolkata 2009 1-0 (39)}) ({RR} 8. h3 Qa5 9. Qd2 Bf5 10. Be2 Qd8 11. O-O h6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. g4 Be6 14. Na4 Ne4 15. Qb4 b5 16. Bc7 Qe8 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. Qxc5 Nd7 19. Qc6 Nf6 20. Ne5 Bd7 21. Qb7 Qc8 22. Qxc8 Bxc8 {Trenner,R (2123)-Schunk,T (2103) Germany 2025 ½-½ (61)}) 8... b5 $5 {This seems to be a logical choice. White has to make a decision, but should be happy to open the c-file in view of his rapid development. From Black's point of view, it's easier to justify such a counter when White has played the slower h3 instead of Bd3.} ({I suppose Black could just try and ease his development problems by ceding the bishop pair:} 8... Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 dxc4 (10... e6 {(noting all the black pawns on light squares!)} 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rfd1 Qe7 {is solid but passive}) 11. Bxc4 Nbd7 12. O-O Qa5 13. Rfd1 e5 14. Bh2 exd4 15. exd4 Qb4 16. Bb3 a5 17. Na4 $6 {Shvartz,M-Tomczak,J German league 2011, keeps an edge for White. So the 8...Bg4 idea isn't that inspiring.} ({Instead, more incisive is} 17. d5 $1 {opening lines, looks even better, with a clear advantage to White})) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. O-O $146 ({RR} 10. Qb3 Bg4 11. Ne5 Be6 12. h3 Nfd7 13. Nf3 Nb6 14. O-O N8d7 15. Ng5 Nc4 16. Rfd1 Ndb6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Be2 Qd7 19. h4 Rac8 20. h5 Na5 21. Qb4 Nc6 {½-½ (21) Emuakpeje,O-Maduagwuna,E (2159) Lagos 2014}) 10... Bb7 11. Nd2 {Heading for c5.} ({The rapid reaction} 11. a4 {is a reasonable-looking try, when after} b4 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Ne8 {White could claim a small pull due to his more active forces.}) 11... e6 12. Nb3 ({A case could be made for the calm} 12. h3 {ensuring the survival of the dark-squared bishop, and thus retaining a strong influence along the b8-h2 diagonal.}) 12... Nh5 13. Nc5 $6 {This leads to a series of exchanges, including those of the light-squared bishops, which can't be a favourable ploy.} (13. Bxb8 Rxb8 14. Nc5 {is simpler and perhaps better.}) 13... Nxf4 14. Nxb7 Qe7 15. Nc5 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Nd7 17. b4 (17. Ne2 Rfc8 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 {is only equal. So Romain Edouard decides to take a positional risk.}) 17... Nb6 {Access to the c4-square is the basis of Black's counterplay.} 18. Rfe1 Rfd8 19. Ra1 Qe8 20. a4 {The only pawn break that makes any sense.} Nc4 21. Re2 bxa4 22. Rxa4 a5 $1 {Avoiding being saddled with a weakness on a6. Now, on a5, it's sufficiently well defended.} 23. b5 (23. bxa5 Rxa5 24. Rxa5 Nxa5 {just looks equal.}) 23... Bf8 24. Ra1 Rac8 25. e4 $5 {As the queenside play hasn't gone well, Edouard decides to try and complicate his opponent's life by opening another front.} Bxc5 $6 ({After} 25... Nb6 $1 {White's weaknesses aren't so easy to live with.}) 26. dxc5 Rxc5 27. exd5 Qf8 28. Qd4 $6 ({If} 28. Ne4 $1 {Black has the strong intermediate move} Qg7 $1 {gaining a tempo to cover f6. Then} 29. Rf1 Rdxd5 30. Qf3 Qd4 31. Nxc5 Qxc5 32. Qc3 Qxb5 {with two pawns for the exchange.}) 28... e5 29. Qd3 f5 30. Na4 Rdxd5 31. Qb3 Rc8 32. Rc2 Qb4 {Meeting all the immediate threats.} 33. Qxb4 $2 {This version of the ending proves to be tricky, but not tricky enough to trip up Maghsoodloo.} ({So White should keep the tension with} 33. Qa2 $1 {when (particularly in a time scramble) there would be practical difficulties for Black. Best play could then be} Rd2 34. Rxd2 Qxd2 35. Qxd2 Nxd2 36. b6 Kf7 37. h4 {with approximate equality according to Houdini. The implication being that the strong b-pawn offers enough compensation for the pawn deficit.}) 33... axb4 34. Nb2 Nb6 35. Rxc8+ Nxc8 36. Ra8 Rc5 37. Nd3 b3 $1 38. f4 ({Or} 38. Nxc5 b2 {and the promotion is coming.}) 38... e4 39. b6 ({After} 39. Nb2 Kf7 {White's position is 'played out'.}) 39... exd3 40. b7 d2 {Crazy-looking, but nevertheless completely hopeless for White.} 41. Ra1 Rc1+ 42. Kf2 b2 43. Rb1 d1=Q 0-1


