1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 (4. exf5 e4) 4... fxe4 (4... Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 {White could claim a small pull due to his more active forces. I suppose Black could just try and ease his development problems by ceding the bishop pair:} 6. exf5 O-O 7. Be3 Nd4 8. c3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3) 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Nxe4 (6... Bc5 $6 7. Qd3 Z0 (7... O-O 8. Qc4+) (7... d6 8. Qc4 Qe7 9. Nc3 Bd7 {Meeting all the immediate threats.} (9... Be6) 10. Nd5 $2 {This version of the ending proves to be tricky, but not tricky enough to trip up Maghsoodloo.} Nxd5 11. exd5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. a4 Z0 $1 (14... O-O 15. c3 Bc5 16. b4 Bb6 17. a5 {Crazy-looking, but nevertheless completely hopeless for White.}) (14... a6 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 O-O-O 17. Rf2 {After} Rdf8 18. Raf1 {White's position is 'played out'. Or} Qe7 19. Qe4 {and the promotion is coming. So White should keep the tension with} g6 $1 {when (particularly in a time scramble) there would be practical difficulties for Black. Best play could then be} 20. Rf3 Kb8 21. b3 Rxf3 22. Qxf3 Qg5))) (6... d6 {with approximate equality according to Houdini. The implication being that the strong b-pawn offers enough compensation for the pawn deficit. If} 7. Nc3 $1 {Black has the strong intermediate move} Be7 $1 {gaining a tempo to cover f6. Then} 8. Bc4 Na5 ({A case could be made for the calm} 8... Bg4 {ensuring the survival of the dark-squared bishop, and thus retaining a strong influence along the b8-h2 diagonal. The rapid reaction} 9. h3 {is a reasonable-looking try, when after} Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Ng5) 9. Qd3 Nxc4 10. Qxc4 c6 (10... Qd7 {just looks equal.} 11. Ng5 Rf8 12. Nd5 c6 {is only equal. So Romain Edouard decides to take a positional risk.} 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 14. Be3 {is simpler and perhaps better.}) 11. Bg5 Qd7 {with two pawns for the exchange. After} 12. Bxf6 $1 {White's weaknesses aren't so easy to live with.} Bxf6 13. Rad1 Qe6) ({RR} 6... Bd6 7. Bc4 Na5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. c4 Nc6 10. Nc3 Bc5 11. Na4 Be7 12. h3 Qe8 13. Nc3 Bc5 14. Na4 Be7 15. Nc3 Bc5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Nd4 18. Ng5 h6 19. Ne4 Be7 20. d6 cxd6 21. Nc3 {Tari,A (2618)-Christiansen,J (2610) chess24.com INT 2020 1-0 (43)}) ({RR} 6... Bd6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bg5 Qe8 9. Re1 a6 10. Bc4+ Kh8 11. Nd5 b5 12. Bb3 Na5 13. Nh4 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bb7 15. Nxf6 gxf6 16. Bh6 Rg8 17. Qf3 Qf7 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Rad1 Rg6 20. Qh3 Bc6 21. Bxf8 {Hardwick,H (1873)-Kadovic,T (1612) Reykjavik 2025 1-0 (36)}) 7. Nxe5 (7. Re1) 7... Nxe5 $146 ({RR} 7... Qf6 8. Ng4 Qg6 9. Re1 Be7 10. Qd5 Nd6 11. Bxc6 dxc6 12. Qg5 Qf7 13. h3 h6 14. Qf4 Bf5 15. Ne3 Be6 16. Qxf7+ Kxf7 17. Nc3 Rhf8 18. Ng4 Bxg4 19. hxg4 Bf6 20. Bf4 Nc4 21. Bxc7 Rfe8 22. Ne4 {Pritchett,C (2343)-Kuindzhy,A (2435) Rijeka 2011 ½-½ (48)}) 8. Re1 Nf6 $5 {This seems to be a logical choice. White has to make a decision, but should be happy to open the c-file in view of his rapid development. From Black's point of view, it's easier to justify such a counter when White has played the slower h3 instead of Bd3.} (8... Be7 $5 {As the queenside play hasn't gone well, Edouard decides to try and complicate his opponent's life by opening another front.} 9. Rxe4 $6 Nf7) (8... Qh4 9. Qd4) 9. f4 c6 10. fxe5 Qb6+ 11. Kh1 {Heading for c5.} Ne4 12. Rxe4 Qxb5 13. Nc3 $6 {This leads to a series of exchanges, including those of the light-squared bishops, which can't be a favourable ploy.} Qc5 14. Re1 Be7 15. Ne4 Qc4 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. exd6+ Kf8 {Access to the c4-square is the basis of Black's counterplay.} 18. Re7 h6 19. Qf3+ Kg8 20. Re8+ {The only pawn break that makes any sense.} Kh7 21. Qf5+ (21. Qf5+ g6 22. Re7+ $1 {Avoiding being saddled with a weakness on a6. Now, on a5, it's sufficiently well defended.} Kg8 23. Qxg6+ Kf8 24. Qg7#) 0-1


