7 33. Qe3 $1 Rd6 34. Rad1 Re6 35. Qd4 Rf6 36. Re2 Qh5 37. Re5 $15 Qf7 {1-0 (29) Kovalenko,I (2596)-Krasenkow,M (2643) Trzcianka 2013} 38. Re2 Qh5 39. Bc4 Qg6 40. Qe3 Qg4 41. Rd4 Qc8 42. Qe7 Qb8 43. Rg4 g6 44. Rh4 g5 45. Rd4 Rg6) 16... Qe7 17. a4 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rac8 19. a5 $1 {A very unpleasant move for Black. Black has made no obvious mistakes but his position is already strategically highly dubious.} Rc7 $6 {looks a bit naive} 20. axb6 {The plan that follows is quite straightforward and simple - to break through with g4.} axb6 $6 {A sub optimal move. Although It's not easy for Black to play maybe the best was to admit the mistake and play h5.} 21. Rfe1 (21. Ra7) 21... Rfc8 22. Qb2 {White just crashes through on the kingside. Black has no counterplay on the other flank and he won't be able to defend on the light squares either.} Rc3 23. Ra7 $6 {White is still much better but hg1 was just winning} Rxd3 24. Rxb7 Rdc3 25. Qxb6 Nxb6 26. Rxe7 R3c7 27. Rxc7 Rxc7 {Black tries to struggle for some counterplay. Black's g7-bishop has no squares, and White's king is safe as the light squares are still out of reach for Black's rooks...} 28. g4 f6 29. Rd1 Kf7 30. Nd2 $1 Na4 31. Kf1 Rc2 32. Nf3 Nc3 33. Re1 Kg6 34. g3 h5 35. gxh5+ Kxh5 36. e5 f5 37. d5 Ne4 (37... Nxd5 38. Nd4 Rd2 $36 39. Nxe6 {It seems a little dangerous to keep the a2-g8 diagonal exposed, especially with h4-h5 coming so swiftly.} Kg4 40. Nxg7 f4 {[%cal Gf1c4]} 41. gxf4 Kf3 42. Kg1 Rxf2 43. Rf1 Rxf1+ 44. Kxf1 Kxf4) 38. dxe6 Kg4 (38... Rxf2+ 39. Kg1 Ra2 ({But White still keeps the initiative with} 39... Rxf3 $1 40. e7) 40. e7 $18 {[%csl Rg7]} Ra8 41. Nd4 $18 Kg6 $1 {was much more powerful} 42. g4 Nc3 43. Re3 {I prematurely stopped my calculations here but after} Nd5 {Black has no defence!} 44. gxf5+ {I thought this was better, with the idea} Kf7 45. Rb3 $1 Nxe7 46. Rb7 {forcing White to play g5.}) 39. e7 Rxf2+ (39... Rc8 40. Nd4) 40. Kg1 Kxf3 41. Rf1 {c2 is defended, and g7 is doomed. A typical example of the strategic advantage White has in this position. Also, threats like a2-a1 are simply neutralised by b1.} Rxf1+ 42. Kxf1 $18 Nxg3+ 43. Ke1 {[%csl Rg7]} 1-0


